// AUTO-GENERATED by integrate_expansion.js — fact-checked question banks. Do not hand-edit.
module.exports = {"regents-alg1":[{"p":"Solve for x: 3(x - 4) = 2x + 5.","a":"x = 17","w":["x = 9","x = 7","x = -17"],"h":"Use the distributive property to clear the parentheses, then collect variable terms on one side.","e":"After distributing, 3x - 12 = 2x + 5; subtracting 2x and adding 12 to both sides isolates x = 17 (solving multi-step linear equations)."},{"p":"What is the slope of the line passing through the points (2, 3) and (6, 11)?","a":"2","w":["1/2","-2","4"],"h":"Slope is the change in y divided by the change in x between the two points.","e":"Using m = (y2 - y1)/(x2 - x1) = (11 - 3)/(6 - 2) = 8/4 = 2 (slope formula)."},{"p":"If f(x) = 2x^2 - 3x + 1, what is f(-2)?","a":"15","w":["3","-1","11"],"h":"Substitute -2 for every x, and be careful with the sign when squaring and multiplying negatives.","e":"f(-2) = 2(-2)^2 - 3(-2) + 1 = 2(4) + 6 + 1 = 15 (evaluating a function using correct order of operations with signed numbers)."},{"p":"Factor completely: x^2 + 7x + 12.","a":"(x + 3)(x + 4)","w":["(x + 2)(x + 6)","(x + 1)(x + 12)","(x - 3)(x - 4)"],"h":"Find two numbers whose product is the constant term and whose sum is the coefficient of x.","e":"3 and 4 multiply to 12 and add to 7, so the factorization is (x + 3)(x + 4) (factoring a trinomial with leading coefficient 1)."},{"p":"Solve for x: x^2 - 5x - 14 = 0.","a":"x = 7 or x = -2","w":["x = -7 or x = 2","x = 7 or x = 2","x = 14 or x = -1"],"h":"Factor into two binomials, then apply the zero product property to each factor.","e":"Since x^2 - 5x - 14 = (x - 7)(x + 2), setting each factor equal to zero gives x = 7 or x = -2 (zero product property)."},{"p":"Simplify: (3x^2y)^3.","a":"27x^6y^3","w":["9x^6y^3","27x^5y^3","3x^6y^3"],"h":"Raise every factor inside the parentheses, including the coefficient, to the third power.","e":"(3x^2y)^3 = 3^3 · x^(2·3) · y^3 = 27x^6y^3 (power of a product and power of a power rules)."},{"p":"Simplify: x^5 · x^3.","a":"x^8","w":["x^15","x^2","2x^8"],"h":"When multiplying powers with the same base, think about what happens to the exponents.","e":"By the product of powers rule, x^5 · x^3 = x^(5+3) = x^8 (exponents are added, not multiplied)."},{"p":"An arithmetic sequence begins 3, 7, 11, 15, .... What is the 10th term?","a":"39","w":["43","40","36"],"h":"Identify the common difference and count how many times it is added to the first term.","e":"With a1 = 3 and common difference d = 4, a10 = 3 + (10 - 1)(4) = 3 + 36 = 39 (explicit formula for an arithmetic sequence)."},{"p":"Solve the system: y = 2x + 1 and y = x + 4.","a":"(3, 7)","w":["(3, 4)","(7, 3)","(-3, -5)"],"h":"Since both equations are solved for y, set the two expressions equal to each other first.","e":"Setting 2x + 1 = x + 4 gives x = 3, and substituting back gives y = 7, so the solution is (3, 7) (solving a linear system by substitution)."},{"p":"What is the equation of the axis of symmetry of the parabola y = x^2 - 6x + 5?","a":"x = 3","w":["x = 6","x = -3","x = -6"],"h":"Use the formula involving the coefficients a and b from the standard form of the quadratic.","e":"The axis of symmetry is x = -b/(2a) = -(-6)/(2·1) = 3 (axis of symmetry of a parabola)."},{"p":"What is the slope of the line 2x + 3y = 12?","a":"-2/3","w":["2/3","3/2","-3/2"],"h":"Rewrite the equation in slope-intercept form y = mx + b to read off the slope.","e":"Solving for y gives y = -2/3 x + 4, so the slope is -2/3 (converting standard form to slope-intercept form)."},{"p":"What is the mean of the data set 4, 8, 10, 12, 16?","a":"10","w":["8","12","50"],"h":"Add all the values, then divide by how many values there are.","e":"The sum is 50 and there are 5 values, so the mean is 50/5 = 10 (arithmetic mean)."},{"p":"Solve the inequality: -2x + 3 < 11.","a":"x > -4","w":["x < -4","x > 4","x < 4"],"h":"Remember what must happen to the inequality symbol when you divide both sides by a negative number.","e":"Subtracting 3 gives -2x < 8, and dividing by -2 reverses the symbol to give x > -4 (reversing the inequality when dividing by a negative)."},{"p":"Solve for x: x^2 + 4x + 3 = 0.","a":"x = -1 or x = -3","w":["x = 1 or x = 3","x = -1 or x = 3","x = -4 or x = 3"],"h":"Factor the trinomial, then set each factor equal to zero.","e":"Since x^2 + 4x + 3 = (x + 1)(x + 3), the solutions are x = -1 or x = -3 (factoring and the zero product property)."},{"p":"If f(x) = 5x - 2, for what value of x does f(x) = 13?","a":"x = 3","w":["x = 13","x = 2.2","x = 15"],"h":"Set the function rule equal to 13 and solve the resulting linear equation for x.","e":"Solving 5x - 2 = 13 gives 5x = 15, so x = 3 (solving an equation from function notation)."},{"p":"A population of 200 bacteria grows by 5% each year. Which expression models the population after t years?","a":"200(1.05)^t","w":["200(0.05)^t","200(1.5)^t","200(1.005)^t"],"h":"For a percent increase, the growth factor is 1 plus the decimal form of the rate.","e":"A 5% annual increase gives a growth factor of 1 + 0.05 = 1.05, so the model is 200(1.05)^t (exponential growth model)."},{"p":"A scatter plot of two variables has a line of best fit with a correlation coefficient of r = 0.92. Which statement best describes the relationship?","a":"A strong positive linear correlation","w":["A strong negative linear correlation","A weak positive linear correlation","No linear correlation"],"h":"Consider both the sign of r and how close its absolute value is to 1.","e":"An r near +1 indicates a strong positive linear correlation, so r = 0.92 shows a strong positive relationship (interpreting the correlation coefficient)."},{"p":"Simplify the expression: 8x + 3(2x - 5).","a":"14x - 15","w":["11x - 15","14x + 15","10x - 5"],"h":"Distribute the 3 across both terms in the parentheses before combining like terms.","e":"Distributing gives 8x + 6x - 15, and combining like terms yields 14x - 15 (distributive property and combining like terms)."},{"p":"Solve for x using the quadratic formula: x^2 - 6x + 7 = 0.","a":"x = 3 ± √2","w":["x = 3 ± 2√2","x = -3 ± √2","x = 6 ± √2"],"h":"Substitute a = 1, b = -6, c = 7 into the quadratic formula and simplify the discriminant before dividing by 2a.","e":"The discriminant is b^2 - 4ac = 36 - 28 = 8, so √8 = 2√2, and (6 ± 2√2)/2 simplifies to 3 ± √2."},{"p":"Solve the system using elimination: 2x + 3y = 12 and 4x - 3y = 6.","a":"(3, 2)","w":["(2, 3)","(3, -2)","(-3, 2)"],"h":"Notice that the y-terms are opposites; add the two equations to eliminate y first.","e":"Adding the equations gives 6x = 18, so x = 3; substituting back yields 6 + 3y = 12, so y = 2 — the elimination method."},{"p":"What is the average rate of change of f(x) = x^2 over the interval 1 ≤ x ≤ 4?","a":"5","w":["8.5","15","3"],"h":"Average rate of change equals the change in output divided by the change in input over the interval.","e":"Average rate of change = (f(4) - f(1))/(4 - 1) = (16 - 1)/3 = 5, the slope of the secant line."},{"p":"A car worth $24,000 depreciates 15% each year. To the nearest dollar, what is its value after 3 years?","a":"$14,739","w":["$17,340","$20,400","$13,200"],"h":"Each year the car keeps 85% of its previous value; apply that factor once per year.","e":"Exponential decay: 24000(0.85)^3 = 24000(0.614125) ≈ $14,739, since retaining 85% means multiplying by 0.85 each year."},{"p":"The first three terms of a geometric sequence are 5, 15, 45, .... What is the 6th term?","a":"1215","w":["405","3645","3125"],"h":"Find the common ratio, then use a_n = a_1 · r^(n-1) with n = 6.","e":"The common ratio is r = 3, so a_6 = 5 · 3^5 = 5 · 243 = 1215, using the geometric sequence formula."},{"p":"Factor completely: 2x^2 - 18.","a":"2(x - 3)(x + 3)","w":["2(x^2 - 9)","2(x - 3)^2","(x - 3)(x + 3)"],"h":"Factor out the greatest common factor first, then check whether the remaining binomial is a difference of two squares.","e":"Factoring the GCF gives 2(x^2 - 9), and x^2 - 9 is a difference of squares, so the complete factorization is 2(x - 3)(x + 3); dropping the factor of 2 or stopping early leaves it not fully factored."},{"p":"What is the minimum value of the function f(x) = x^2 - 8x + 10?","a":"-6","w":["4","10","-26"],"h":"The minimum occurs at the vertex; find the x-coordinate with x = -b/(2a), then evaluate the function there.","e":"The vertex is at x = -(-8)/(2·1) = 4, and f(4) = 16 - 32 + 10 = -6, which is the minimum value of the upward-opening parabola."},{"p":"Solve for all values of x: x^2 + 6x = 16.","a":"x = 2 or x = -8","w":["x = -2 or x = 8","x = 4 or x = -4","x = -2 or x = -8"],"h":"Set the equation equal to zero first, then factor into two binomials.","e":"Rewriting as x^2 + 6x - 16 = 0 factors to (x + 8)(x - 2) = 0, so by the zero-product property x = -8 or x = 2."},{"p":"Simplify: (12x^5y^3) / (4x^2y).","a":"3x^3y^2","w":["3x^7y^4","8x^3y^2","3x^3y^3"],"h":"Divide the coefficients, then subtract exponents of like bases using the quotient rule.","e":"By the quotient rule for exponents, 12/4 = 3, x^(5-2) = x^3, and y^(3-1) = y^2, giving 3x^3y^2."},{"p":"A phone plan costs $30 per month plus $0.10 per text message. If Maria can spend at most $50 per month, what is the greatest number of texts she can send?","a":"200","w":["500","800","230"],"h":"Write an inequality with the fixed cost plus the per-text cost being less than or equal to the budget, then solve for the number of texts.","e":"Solving 30 + 0.10t ≤ 50 gives 0.10t ≤ 20, so t ≤ 200, the maximum number of texts within the budget."},{"p":"Two data sets have the same mean of 5. Set A is {5, 5, 5, 5, 5} and Set B is {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}. Which statement correctly compares their standard deviations?","a":"Set B has the greater standard deviation because its values vary more from the mean","w":["Set A has the greater standard deviation because it has five identical values","The two sets have equal standard deviations because their means are equal","The standard deviation cannot be determined without more data points"],"h":"Standard deviation measures how spread out data values are from the mean, not the value of the mean itself.","e":"Set A has no spread (standard deviation 0), while Set B's values differ from the mean, so Set B has the greater standard deviation."},{"p":"The function f(x) = 2x - 1 is defined only for the domain {1, 2, 3}. What is its range?","a":"{1, 3, 5}","w":["{1, 2, 3}","{2, 4, 6}","{0, 1, 2}"],"h":"Substitute each element of the domain into the function to find the corresponding output values.","e":"Evaluating gives f(1) = 1, f(2) = 3, and f(3) = 5, so the range (set of outputs) is {1, 3, 5}."},{"p":"What are the zeros of the function f(x) = (x - 3)(2x + 5)?","a":"x = 3 and x = -5/2","w":["x = -3 and x = 5/2","x = 3 and x = 5/2","x = -3 and x = -5/2"],"h":"Set each factor equal to zero and solve; the zeros are where the function equals 0.","e":"By the zero-product property, x - 3 = 0 gives x = 3 and 2x + 5 = 0 gives x = -5/2."},{"p":"Write the equation, in slope-intercept form, of the line that passes through the point (2, -1) with slope 3.","a":"y = 3x - 7","w":["y = 3x + 7","y = 3x - 1","y = 3x + 5"],"h":"Substitute the slope and the point's coordinates into y = mx + b to solve for the y-intercept b.","e":"Using -1 = 3(2) + b gives b = -7, so the equation is y = 3x - 7."},{"p":"A sequence is defined recursively by a_1 = 2 and a_n = 3a_(n-1) - 1. What is a_3?","a":"14","w":["17","5","44"],"h":"Find the second term first, then apply the rule again using that result to reach the third term.","e":"a_2 = 3(2) - 1 = 5, then a_3 = 3(5) - 1 = 14, following the recursive definition step by step."},{"p":"For a certain value of x, a line of best fit predicts a y-value of 42, but the actual observed data value is 39. What is the residual for this point?","a":"-3","w":["3","81","1.08"],"h":"A residual is the observed value minus the predicted value.","e":"Residual = observed - predicted = 39 - 42 = -3, and a negative residual means the model overpredicted."},{"p":"The simple interest formula is I = Prt. Solve this formula for r.","a":"r = I / (Pt)","w":["r = IPt","r = Pt / I","r = I - Pt"],"h":"Isolate r by using the inverse operation on the factors multiplied by it.","e":"Since P and t are multiplied by r, dividing both sides of I = Prt by Pt gives r = I/(Pt)."},{"p":"Which ordered pair is a solution to the system of inequalities y > 2x - 3 and y ≤ -x + 4?","a":"(0, 0)","w":["(3, 2)","(5, 0)","(-1, 6)"],"h":"Substitute each ordered pair into both inequalities; a solution must make both true at the same time.","e":"At (0, 0): 0 > 2(0) - 3 = -3 is true and 0 ≤ -(0) + 4 = 4 is true, so it satisfies both inequalities."},{"p":"Rewrite the function f(x) = x^2 + 10x + 21 in vertex form.","a":"f(x) = (x + 5)^2 - 4","w":["f(x) = (x + 5)^2 + 4","f(x) = (x - 5)^2 - 4","f(x) = (x + 10)^2 - 79"],"h":"Complete the square: take half of the coefficient of x, square it, and adjust the constant.","e":"Completing the square, half of 10 is 5 and 5^2 = 25, so x^2 + 10x + 21 = (x + 5)^2 - 25 + 21 = (x + 5)^2 - 4."},{"p":"Solve the linear-quadratic system: y = x^2 - 4x + 3 and y = x - 1.","a":"(1, 0) and (4, 3)","w":["(0, -1) and (4, 3)","(1, 0) and (3, 2)","(-1, -2) and (4, 3)"],"h":"Set the two expressions for y equal and solve the resulting quadratic equation, then find each y-value.","e":"Substitution gives x^2 - 4x + 3 = x - 1, so x^2 - 5x + 4 = 0 and (x - 1)(x - 4) = 0; the solutions x = 1 and x = 4 give the points (1, 0) and (4, 3)."},{"p":"A 60 mg dose of medication leaves a patient's bloodstream so that 20% of the amount present is eliminated each hour. To the nearest tenth, how much remains after 4 hours?","a":"About 24.6 mg","w":["About 30.7 mg","About 48.0 mg","About 12.0 mg"],"h":"Losing 20% each hour means 80% remains each hour; apply the decay factor once per hour.","e":"This is exponential decay with factor 0.8, so the amount is 60(0.8)^4 = 60(0.4096) ≈ 24.6 mg; subtracting a fixed 12 mg each hour would be an incorrect linear model."},{"p":"What is the domain of the function f(x) = sqrt(x + 4)?","a":"x ≥ -4","w":["x ≥ 4","x ≤ -4","x > -4"],"h":"A square root is defined in the real numbers only when the expression under the radical is not negative.","e":"The radicand must satisfy x + 4 ≥ 0, so the domain is x ≥ -4; equality is included because the square root of 0 is defined."},{"p":"Read: \"A market researcher surveyed 200 shoppers about roast preference. Of the 120 shoppers who were adults, 90 preferred dark roast.\" What is the relative frequency of preferring dark roast among the adults surveyed?","a":"75%","w":["45%","60%","30%"],"h":"A conditional relative frequency uses only the subgroup named in the question as its denominator.","e":"Restricting to adults, the conditional relative frequency is 90/120 = 0.75 = 75%; dividing by the total 200 would answer a different question."},{"p":"Factor completely: 3x^3 - 12x^2 + 12x.","a":"3x(x - 2)^2","w":["3x(x + 2)^2","3x(x - 2)(x + 2)","3x(x^2 - 4x + 4)"],"h":"First remove the greatest common monomial factor, then factor the remaining trinomial.","e":"Factoring out 3x gives 3x(x^2 - 4x + 4), and the trinomial is the perfect-square trinomial (x - 2)^2, so the complete factorization is 3x(x - 2)^2."},{"p":"Read: \"A table of a function shows the ordered pairs (0, 5), (1, 15), (2, 45), and (3, 135).\" Which function models the data?","a":"f(x) = 5(3)^x","w":["f(x) = 3(5)^x","f(x) = 5 + 10x","f(x) = 5x^2 + 10"],"h":"Check whether successive outputs grow by a common difference (linear) or a common ratio (exponential).","e":"Each output is 3 times the previous one and the value at x = 0 is 5, indicating exponential growth of the form f(x) = 5(3)^x."},{"p":"In the arithmetic sequence 5, 8, 11, 14, ..., which term is equal to 92?","a":"The 30th term","w":["The 29th term","The 31st term","The 27th term"],"h":"Use the explicit formula a_n = a_1 + (n - 1)d and solve for n.","e":"With a_1 = 5 and d = 3, a_n = 5 + 3(n - 1) = 3n + 2; setting 3n + 2 = 92 gives n = 30, so 92 is the 30th term."},{"p":"A ball is launched so that its height in feet after t seconds is h(t) = -16t^2 + 64t + 5. What is the maximum height the ball reaches?","a":"69 feet","w":["64 feet","5 feet","2 feet"],"h":"The maximum of a downward parabola occurs at the vertex; find the t-value with -b/(2a), then evaluate the height.","e":"The vertex occurs at t = -64/(2·-16) = 2 seconds, and h(2) = -16(4) + 64(2) + 5 = 69 feet, the maximum height."},{"p":"Simplify: (6x^-2)(2x^5).","a":"12x^3","w":["12x^7","12x^-10","8x^3"],"h":"Multiply the coefficients, then add the exponents on the like base.","e":"By the product rule for exponents, coefficients multiply to 12 and exponents add: -2 + 5 = 3, giving 12x^3."},{"p":"Read: \"A researcher finds a strong positive correlation between a city's monthly ice cream sales and its number of drownings.\" Which conclusion is best supported?","a":"The correlation does not establish causation; a third variable such as hot weather may influence both.","w":["Buying ice cream causes people to drown more often.","Increases in drownings cause people to buy more ice cream.","There is no real relationship between the two variables."],"h":"A correlation measures association, not cause; consider whether an outside factor could drive both variables.","e":"Correlation does not imply causation; a lurking (confounding) variable like warm weather can raise both quantities simultaneously."},{"p":"The area of a trapezoid is given by A = (1/2)(b_1 + b_2)h. Solve this formula for b_1.","a":"b_1 = (2A/h) - b_2","w":["b_1 = (2A/h) + b_2","b_1 = 2A - (b_2/h)","b_1 = (A/h) - b_2"],"h":"Undo the operations in reverse: clear the fraction, divide by h, then isolate b_1.","e":"Multiplying both sides by 2 gives 2A = (b_1 + b_2)h; dividing by h and subtracting b_2 yields b_1 = 2A/h - b_2."},{"p":"A rectangular garden has a length that is 3 feet more than its width, and its area is 40 square feet. What are its dimensions?","a":"5 feet by 8 feet","w":["4 feet by 10 feet","5 feet by 15 feet","8 feet by 11 feet"],"h":"Let the width be w, write the length in terms of w, and set the product equal to the area.","e":"With width w, the equation w(w + 3) = 40 gives w^2 + 3w - 40 = 0, so (w + 8)(w - 5) = 0 and w = 5, making the dimensions 5 ft by 8 ft."},{"p":"Read: \"A concession stand sells hot dogs for $3 and drinks for $2. The manager needs revenue of at least $30 and can prepare at most 12 items total.\" If x is hot dogs and y is drinks, which combination satisfies both 3x + 2y ≥ 30 and x + y ≤ 12?","a":"8 hot dogs and 4 drinks","w":["10 hot dogs and 4 drinks","4 hot dogs and 6 drinks","2 hot dogs and 8 drinks"],"h":"Substitute each pair into both inequalities and keep only the pair that makes both statements true.","e":"For (8, 4): 3(8) + 2(4) = 32 ≥ 30 and 8 + 4 = 12 ≤ 12, so both constraints are satisfied; the others violate at least one inequality."},{"p":"Find the interquartile range (IQR) of the data set: 3, 7, 7, 8, 12, 14, 19, 21, 25.","a":"13","w":["22","12","20"],"h":"Find the median, then find the medians of the lower and upper halves; the IQR is their difference.","e":"The median is 12; Q1 (median of 3, 7, 7, 8) is 7 and Q3 (median of 14, 19, 21, 25) is 20, so IQR = 20 - 7 = 13."},{"p":"An investment is modeled by A = 1500(1.045)^t, where t is in years. What is the annual interest rate?","a":"4.5%","w":["45%","1.045%","0.45%"],"h":"In an exponential growth model, the base equals 1 plus the rate written as a decimal.","e":"Since the growth factor is 1 + r = 1.045, the rate r = 0.045 = 4.5% per year."},{"p":"Which form of a quadratic function most directly reveals the coordinates of the parabola's vertex?","a":"Vertex form, f(x) = a(x - h)^2 + k","w":["Standard form, f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c","Factored form, f(x) = a(x - r_1)(x - r_2)","Slope-intercept form, f(x) = mx + b"],"h":"Think about which algebraic form displays a turning point (h, k) without further calculation.","e":"Vertex form a(x - h)^2 + k directly shows the vertex (h, k); factored form reveals zeros and standard form reveals the y-intercept."},{"p":"Read: \"Gym Plan A costs a $100 one-time fee plus $20 per month, and Plan B costs $40 per month with no fee.\" After how many months do the two plans cost the same total amount?","a":"5 months","w":["2.5 months","10 months","4 months"],"h":"Write an expression for each plan's total cost after m months and set them equal.","e":"Setting 100 + 20m = 40m gives 100 = 20m, so m = 5 months, when both plans cost $200."}],"regents-geo":[{"p":"Which of the following transformations is NOT an isometry (i.e., does not preserve distance)?","a":"A dilation with scale factor 3 centered at the origin","w":["A translation 4 units right and 2 units down","A reflection over the line y = x","A rotation of 90° about the origin"],"h":"An isometry (rigid motion) preserves every length and angle measure.","e":"Translations, reflections, and rotations are rigid motions, but a dilation with a scale factor other than 1 enlarges or reduces distances, so it is not an isometry."},{"p":"Point P(3, −5) is reflected over the x-axis. What are the coordinates of its image?","a":"(3, 5)","w":["(−3, −5)","(−3, 5)","(−5, 3)"],"h":"Reflecting over the x-axis fixes the x-coordinate and changes the sign of the y-coordinate.","e":"A reflection over the x-axis follows the rule (x, y) → (x, −y), giving (3, 5)."},{"p":"Point P(4, −1) is rotated 90° counterclockwise about the origin. What are the coordinates of its image?","a":"(1, 4)","w":["(−1, −4)","(−4, 1)","(1, −4)"],"h":"A 90° counterclockwise rotation about the origin uses the rule (x, y) → (−y, x).","e":"Applying (x, y) → (−y, x) to (4, −1) gives (−(−1), 4) = (1, 4)."},{"p":"The point P(2, −5) is dilated by a scale factor of 3 centered at the origin. What is the image of P?","a":"(6, −15)","w":["(5, −2)","(2/3, −5/3)","(−6, 15)"],"h":"A dilation centered at the origin multiplies each coordinate by the scale factor.","e":"A dilation centered at the origin follows (x, y) → (kx, ky); with k = 3 this gives (6, −15)."},{"p":"What are the coordinates of the midpoint of the segment with endpoints A(−2, 6) and B(4, −2)?","a":"(1, 2)","w":["(2, 4)","(3, −4)","(6, −8)"],"h":"The midpoint is the average of the x-coordinates and the average of the y-coordinates.","e":"By the midpoint formula ((x₁+x₂)/2, (y₁+y₂)/2) = ((−2+4)/2, (6+(−2))/2) = (1, 2)."},{"p":"What is the distance between the points (1, 2) and (4, 6)?","a":"5","w":["7","25","√7"],"h":"Use the distance formula, which is built from the Pythagorean Theorem.","e":"The distance formula gives √((4−1)² + (6−2)²) = √(9 + 16) = √25 = 5."},{"p":"A right triangle has legs of length 9 and 12. What is the length of the hypotenuse?","a":"15","w":["21","√63","225"],"h":"The Pythagorean Theorem relates the two legs to the hypotenuse.","e":"By the Pythagorean Theorem, c = √(9² + 12²) = √(81 + 144) = √225 = 15."},{"p":"In right triangle ABC, the side adjacent to angle A measures 8, the opposite side measures 15, and the hypotenuse measures 17. What is cos A?","a":"8/17","w":["15/17","8/15","15/8"],"h":"Cosine is the ratio of the adjacent side to the hypotenuse (SOH-CAH-TOA).","e":"By the definition of cosine, cos A = adjacent/hypotenuse = 8/17."},{"p":"In a 45°-45°-90° right triangle, each leg measures 6. What is the length of the hypotenuse?","a":"6√2","w":["12","6√3","3√2"],"h":"In an isosceles right triangle the hypotenuse relates to a leg by a fixed radical factor.","e":"In a 45°-45°-90° triangle the hypotenuse equals a leg times √2, so it is 6√2."},{"p":"In a 30°-60°-90° right triangle, the hypotenuse measures 10. What is the length of the longer leg (the side opposite the 60° angle)?","a":"5√3","w":["5","10√3","5√2"],"h":"In a 30°-60°-90° triangle the sides are in the ratio 1 : √3 : 2 (short leg : long leg : hypotenuse).","e":"The short leg is half the hypotenuse (5), and the long leg is the short leg times √3, giving 5√3."},{"p":"What is the area of a circle with a radius of 7?","a":"49π","w":["14π","49","196π"],"h":"The area of a circle depends on the square of the radius.","e":"Using A = πr², the area is π(7²) = 49π."},{"p":"What is the circumference of a circle with a radius of 5?","a":"10π","w":["25π","5π","100π"],"h":"Circumference uses the radius (or diameter) to the first power, not squared.","e":"Using C = 2πr, the circumference is 2π(5) = 10π."},{"p":"In a circle, a central angle intercepts an arc measuring 100°. What is the measure of an inscribed angle that intercepts the same arc?","a":"50°","w":["100°","200°","25°"],"h":"An inscribed angle and a central angle intercepting the same arc are related by a factor of one half.","e":"By the Inscribed Angle Theorem, an inscribed angle equals half the intercepted arc, so it measures 50°."},{"p":"What is the equation of a circle with center (2, −3) and radius 5?","a":"(x − 2)² + (y + 3)² = 25","w":["(x + 2)² + (y − 3)² = 25","(x − 2)² + (y + 3)² = 5","(x − 2)² + (y − 3)² = 25"],"h":"In (x − h)² + (y − k)² = r², the signs of h and k are opposite the center's coordinates, and the right side is r squared.","e":"The standard form (x − h)² + (y − k)² = r² with center (2, −3) and r = 5 gives (x − 2)² + (y + 3)² = 25."},{"p":"What is the volume of a cylinder with radius 3 and height 10?","a":"90π","w":["30π","900π","60π"],"h":"The volume of a cylinder is the area of the circular base times the height.","e":"Using V = πr²h, the volume is π(3²)(10) = 90π."},{"p":"What is the volume of a sphere with radius 3?","a":"36π","w":["108π","27π","72π"],"h":"The volume of a sphere depends on the cube of the radius and includes a factor of 4/3.","e":"Using V = (4/3)πr³, the volume is (4/3)π(3³) = (4/3)π(27) = 36π."},{"p":"In a triangle, the two remote interior angles measure 50° and 70°. What is the measure of the exterior angle at the third vertex?","a":"120°","w":["60°","110°","130°"],"h":"An exterior angle equals the sum of the two remote (nonadjacent) interior angles.","e":"By the Exterior Angle Theorem, the exterior angle equals the sum of the remote interior angles: 50° + 70° = 120°."},{"p":"Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF with AB corresponding to DE. If AB = 6, DE = 9, and BC = 8, what is the length of EF?","a":"12","w":["5","11","5.33"],"h":"Corresponding sides of similar triangles are proportional; find the scale factor first.","e":"The scale factor from ABC to DEF is 9/6 = 3/2, so EF = 8 × 3/2 = 12."},{"p":"Triangle ABC is similar to triangle PQR with a scale factor of 3 : 5. If the area of triangle ABC is 18 square units, what is the area of triangle PQR?","a":"50 square units","w":["30 square units","45 square units","90 square units"],"h":"Compare how a length scale factor relates to an area scale factor for similar figures.","e":"For similar figures the ratio of areas equals the square of the ratio of corresponding sides, so the area ratio is (5/3)² = 25/9 and 18 × 25/9 = 50."},{"p":"Point P(−3, 4) is reflected over the line y = x. What are the coordinates of its image?","a":"(4, −3)","w":["(−4, 3)","(3, −4)","(−3, −4)"],"h":"Recall how a reflection over the line y = x affects the coordinates of a point.","e":"A reflection over y = x maps (x, y) to (y, x), so P(−3, 4) becomes (4, −3)."},{"p":"Point P(−2, 5) is rotated 180° about the origin. What are the coordinates of its image?","a":"(2, −5)","w":["(−5, −2)","(5, 2)","(−2, −5)"],"h":"Think about how a half-turn about the origin changes each coordinate's sign.","e":"A 180° rotation about the origin maps (x, y) to (−x, −y), so P(−2, 5) becomes (2, −5)."},{"p":"Point A(6, −8) is dilated by a scale factor of 1/2 centered at the origin. What is the image of A?","a":"(3, −4)","w":["(12, −16)","(3, 4)","(−3, −4)"],"h":"A dilation centered at the origin multiplies each coordinate by the scale factor.","e":"A dilation about the origin maps (x, y) to (kx, ky); with k = 1/2, A(6, −8) maps to (3, −4)."},{"p":"Quadrilateral ABCD is inscribed in a circle. If angle A measures 110°, what is the measure of angle C?","a":"70°","w":["110°","55°","250°"],"h":"Consider the relationship between opposite angles of a quadrilateral inscribed in a circle.","e":"In a cyclic (inscribed) quadrilateral, opposite angles are supplementary, so angle C = 180° − 110° = 70°."},{"p":"Two chords AB and CD intersect inside a circle at point E. If AE = 4, EB = 6, and CE = 3, what is the length of ED?","a":"8","w":["4.5","2","18"],"h":"Use the relationship between the products of the segment lengths formed by two intersecting chords.","e":"By the Intersecting Chords Theorem, AE · EB = CE · ED, so 4 · 6 = 3 · ED, giving ED = 8."},{"p":"In a circle with radius 6, a central angle measures 60°. What is the length of the arc it intercepts?","a":"2π","w":["6π","12π","π"],"h":"The arc length is the fraction of the full circumference determined by the central angle.","e":"Arc length = (central angle/360°) · 2πr = (60/360)(12π) = 2π."},{"p":"In a circle with radius 10, a sector has a central angle of 72°. What is the area of the sector?","a":"20π","w":["40π","4π","100π"],"h":"A sector's area is the corresponding fraction of the whole circle's area.","e":"Sector area = (central angle/360°) · πr² = (72/360)(100π) = 20π."},{"p":"A circle is defined by the equation x² + y² − 6x + 8y − 11 = 0. What are its center and radius?","a":"Center (3, −4), radius 6","w":["Center (−3, 4), radius 6","Center (3, −4), radius 36","Center (6, −8), radius 6"],"h":"Complete the square in both x and y to rewrite the equation in standard form.","e":"Completing the square gives (x − 3)² + (y + 4)² = 36, so the center is (3, −4) and the radius is √36 = 6."},{"p":"A line passes through the points (1, 2) and (4, 8). What is the slope of any line perpendicular to it?","a":"−1/2","w":["2","1/2","−2"],"h":"First find the given line's slope, then apply the perpendicular-slope relationship.","e":"The given slope is (8 − 2)/(4 − 1) = 2, and perpendicular slopes are negative reciprocals, so the answer is −1/2."},{"p":"Point A is (1, 2) and point B is (9, 10). What are the coordinates of the point that partitions segment AB in the ratio 1 : 3 from A to B?","a":"(3, 4)","w":["(5, 6)","(7, 8)","(6, 7)"],"h":"Move the appropriate fraction of the way from A toward B in each coordinate.","e":"A 1 : 3 partition places the point 1/4 of the way from A to B: (1 + ¼·8, 2 + ¼·8) = (3, 4)."},{"p":"A 20-foot ladder leans against a wall, making a 65° angle with the ground. How high up the wall does the ladder reach, to the nearest tenth of a foot?","a":"18.1 ft","w":["8.5 ft","42.9 ft","9.3 ft"],"h":"Identify which side of the right triangle is opposite the 65° angle relative to the hypotenuse.","e":"The height is opposite the angle and the ladder is the hypotenuse, so height = 20 · sin 65° ≈ 18.1 ft."},{"p":"From an external point P, a tangent is drawn to a circle, touching it at point T. The radius of the circle is 8, and the distance from the center O to P is 17. What is the length of PT?","a":"15","w":["√353","9","25"],"h":"A tangent line is perpendicular to the radius at the point of tangency, forming a right triangle.","e":"Since OT ⊥ PT, triangle OTP is right-angled, so PT = √(17² − 8²) = √225 = 15."},{"p":"What is the volume of a cone with radius 6 and height 10?","a":"120π","w":["360π","20π","480π"],"h":"Recall how the cone volume formula compares to that of a cylinder with the same base and height.","e":"Volume of a cone = (1/3)πr²h = (1/3)π(36)(10) = 120π."},{"p":"A triangular prism has a base that is a right triangle with legs 3 and 4, and the prism's length is 10. What is its volume?","a":"60","w":["120","20","30"],"h":"The volume of a prism is the area of its triangular base times its length.","e":"The base area is ½(3)(4) = 6, so the volume is 6 · 10 = 60 cubic units."},{"p":"A cylinder has radius 4 and height 5. What is its total surface area?","a":"72π","w":["40π","56π","144π"],"h":"Total surface area includes both circular bases as well as the curved lateral surface.","e":"Total surface area = 2πr² + 2πrh = 2π(16) + 2π(20) = 32π + 40π = 72π."},{"p":"In triangle ABC, D is the midpoint of AB and E is the midpoint of AC. If BC = 17, what is the length of DE?","a":"8.5","w":["17","34","4.25"],"h":"Consider the relationship between a segment joining two midpoints and the third side.","e":"By the Triangle Midsegment Theorem, DE is parallel to BC and half its length, so DE = 17/2 = 8.5."},{"p":"In a triangle, the three medians intersect at the centroid. If one median has a total length of 18, what is the distance from the vertex to the centroid along that median?","a":"12","w":["6","9","36"],"h":"The centroid divides each median into two parts with a fixed ratio.","e":"The centroid divides each median in a 2 : 1 ratio from the vertex, so the vertex-to-centroid distance is (2/3)(18) = 12."},{"p":"A surveyor stands 50 feet from the base of a tree on level ground. The angle of elevation from the surveyor's instrument to the top of the tree is 42°. To the nearest tenth of a foot, how tall is the tree (assume the instrument is at ground level)?","a":"45.0 ft","w":["33.5 ft","37.2 ft","55.5 ft"],"h":"The known side (50 ft) is adjacent to the 42° angle, and the unknown height is opposite it. Which trig ratio relates opposite and adjacent?","e":"Using the tangent ratio, tan 42° = height/50, so height = 50 tan 42° ≈ 45.0 ft."},{"p":"A figure is reflected over line m, and its image is then reflected over line n, where m ∥ n and the distance between the two lines is 4 units. The composition of these two reflections is equivalent to which single transformation?","a":"A translation of 8 units","w":["A translation of 4 units","A translation of 2 units","A rotation of 180°"],"h":"A composition of reflections over two parallel lines produces one specific type of isometry. Think about how the total shift compares to the gap between the lines.","e":"The composition of two reflections over parallel lines is a translation whose distance is twice the distance between the lines: 2 × 4 = 8 units."},{"p":"A 6-foot-tall person standing near a flagpole casts a 4-foot shadow at the same time the flagpole casts a 30-foot shadow. Using similar triangles, how tall is the flagpole?","a":"45 ft","w":["20 ft","32 ft","27 ft"],"h":"The person and the flagpole form similar right triangles with the sun's rays. Set up a proportion of height to shadow length.","e":"By AA similarity, height/shadow is constant: 6/4 = h/30, so h = (6 × 30)/4 = 45 ft."},{"p":"In a right triangle, the altitude drawn to the hypotenuse divides the hypotenuse into two segments of lengths 4 and 9. What is the length of that altitude?","a":"6","w":["6.5","13","36"],"h":"The altitude to the hypotenuse is the geometric mean of the two segments it creates, not their average or sum.","e":"By the geometric mean (altitude) theorem, the altitude equals √(4 × 9) = √36 = 6."},{"p":"Two similar cylinders have radii in the ratio 2 : 3. The smaller cylinder has a volume of 40 cubic units. What is the volume of the larger cylinder?","a":"135 cubic units","w":["60 cubic units","90 cubic units","120 cubic units"],"h":"For similar solids, the ratio of volumes is not the same as the ratio of lengths. Consider what power the scale factor is raised to for volume.","e":"For similar solids, the volume ratio equals the cube of the linear scale factor: (3/2)³ = 27/8, so 40 × 27/8 = 135 cubic units."},{"p":"A rectangular gold bar measures 6 cm by 4 cm by 2 cm. Gold has a density of 19.3 grams per cubic centimeter. What is the mass of the bar?","a":"926.4 g","w":["48 g","88 g","231.6 g"],"h":"Density is mass per unit volume, so first find the volume of the bar, then apply the density relationship.","e":"Volume = 6 × 4 × 2 = 48 cm³; using density = mass/volume, mass = 48 × 19.3 = 926.4 g."},{"p":"From an external point P, two secants are drawn to a circle. They intercept a far arc of 80° and a near arc of 30°. What is the measure of the angle formed at P?","a":"25°","w":["55°","50°","110°"],"h":"An angle formed by two secants from a point outside the circle depends on the difference of the intercepted arcs, then a division.","e":"By the two-secant (exterior) angle theorem, the angle equals half the positive difference of the intercepted arcs: (80° − 30°)/2 = 25°."},{"p":"A circle has the equation (x − 1)² + (y + 2)² = 16. Which of the following points lies ON the circle?","a":"(5, −2)","w":["(5, 2)","(4, 2)","(1, 4)"],"h":"The center is (1, −2) and the radius is 4. A point is on the circle when it satisfies the equation exactly.","e":"Substituting (5, −2): (5 − 1)² + (−2 + 2)² = 16 + 0 = 16, so the point lies on the circle of radius 4."},{"p":"Quadrilateral ABCD has vertices A(0, 0), B(4, 0), C(5, 3), and D(1, 3). Based on its side slopes and lengths, what is the most specific classification of ABCD?","a":"Parallelogram","w":["Rectangle","Rhombus","Trapezoid"],"h":"Check the slopes of all four sides to find parallel pairs, then compare side lengths and check for right angles.","e":"Both pairs of opposite sides are parallel (slopes 0 and 3), so it is a parallelogram; adjacent sides are neither congruent nor perpendicular, so it is nothing more specific."},{"p":"For what value of x is the equation sin(2x + 10)° = cos(3x − 30)° true, using the cofunction relationship?","a":"22","w":["40","16","20"],"h":"Sine and cosine are cofunctions, so the equation holds when the two angle expressions are complementary.","e":"By the cofunction identity, sin θ = cos(90° − θ), so (2x + 10) + (3x − 30) = 90, giving 5x − 20 = 90 and x = 22."},{"p":"Each interior angle of a regular polygon measures 150°. How many sides does the polygon have?","a":"12","w":["10","15","24"],"h":"It is often easier to work with the exterior angle, which is supplementary to the interior angle, and remember the exterior angles sum to 360°.","e":"The exterior angle is 180° − 150° = 30°, and since exterior angles sum to 360°, n = 360/30 = 12 sides."},{"p":"A dilation is centered at point C(2, 3) with a scale factor of 2. What is the image of the point P(5, 7) under this dilation?","a":"(8, 11)","w":["(10, 14)","(6, 8)","(3, 4)"],"h":"For a dilation not centered at the origin, scale the vector from the center to the point, then measure from the center again.","e":"The image is C + 2(P − C) = (2, 3) + 2(3, 4) = (2 + 6, 3 + 8) = (8, 11)."},{"p":"Which statement best describes Cavalieri's Principle as it applies to volume?","a":"Two solids of equal height whose cross-sections have equal area at every level have equal volumes","w":["Two solids with equal surface areas must have equal volumes","Two solids with congruent bases must have equal volumes","Two similar solids always have equal volumes"],"h":"The principle compares solids level by level using cross-sections, not their outer surfaces or overall shape.","e":"Cavalieri's Principle states that solids of the same height with equal-area cross-sections at every corresponding level have equal volumes, which justifies volume formulas for oblique solids."},{"p":"A pyramid has a square base with edge length 6 and a height of 10. What is its volume?","a":"120 cubic units","w":["360 cubic units","240 cubic units","60 cubic units"],"h":"A pyramid's volume includes a fractional factor that a prism with the same base and height does not.","e":"Volume of a pyramid = (1/3)(base area)(height) = (1/3)(36)(10) = 120 cubic units."},{"p":"What is the smallest angle of rotation about its center that maps a regular hexagon onto itself?","a":"60°","w":["45°","72°","120°"],"h":"Divide a full turn by the number of times the shape looks identical during that turn, which equals its number of sides.","e":"A regular hexagon has 6-fold rotational symmetry, so the smallest mapping rotation is 360°/6 = 60°."},{"p":"In the coordinate plane, which line consists of all points equidistant from A(2, 0) and B(8, 0)?","a":"x = 5","w":["y = 5","x = 3","y = x"],"h":"The set of points equidistant from two given points is the perpendicular bisector of the segment joining them.","e":"The perpendicular bisector of AB passes through the midpoint (5, 0) and is perpendicular to the horizontal segment, giving the vertical line x = 5."},{"p":"A wheelchair ramp rises 5 feet over a horizontal run of 12 feet. To the nearest degree, what angle does the ramp make with the horizontal?","a":"23°","w":["67°","25°","20°"],"h":"The rise is opposite the angle and the run is adjacent, so use an inverse trig ratio to solve for the angle.","e":"tan θ = opposite/adjacent = 5/12, so θ = tan⁻¹(5/12) ≈ 22.6°, which rounds to 23°."},{"p":"From an external point P, two secants are drawn to a circle. The first secant has an external segment of 6 and an internal chord of 4. The second secant has an internal chord of 7. What is the length of the external segment of the second secant?","a":"5","w":["4","6","8"],"h":"Apply the two-secant power-of-a-point relationship, using each secant's external segment times its whole length.","e":"By the two-secant power theorem, 6(6 + 4) = x(x + 7), so x² + 7x − 60 = 0, which factors to (x − 5)(x + 12) = 0, giving x = 5."}],"regents-alg2":[{"p":"Express the sum (3 + 5i) + (6 − 2i) in standard form a + bi.","a":"9 + 3i","w":["9 − 3i","9 + 7i","9 − 7i"],"h":"Combine the real parts together and the imaginary parts together, just like combining like terms.","e":"Adding complex numbers means adding real parts (3 + 6) and imaginary parts (5i − 2i) separately, giving 9 + 3i."},{"p":"Simplify the power of i: i^22.","a":"−1","w":["1","i","−i"],"h":"Powers of i cycle every four: i, −1, −i, 1. Divide the exponent by 4 and use the remainder.","e":"Since 22 ÷ 4 leaves remainder 2, i^22 = i^2 = −1, using the cyclic (period-4) behavior of powers of i."},{"p":"Multiply and write the product in standard form: (4 + i)(2 − 3i).","a":"11 − 10i","w":["5 − 10i","11 + 10i","8 − 10i"],"h":"Use the distributive property (FOIL), then replace i^2 with −1 before combining terms.","e":"FOIL gives 8 − 12i + 2i − 3i^2; since i^2 = −1, the −3i^2 becomes +3, yielding 11 − 10i."},{"p":"Solve for all values of x: x^2 − 4x + 13 = 0.","a":"2 ± 3i","w":["2 ± 3","−2 ± 3i","3 ± 2i"],"h":"Compute the discriminant b^2 − 4ac first; a negative value signals complex solutions. Then apply the quadratic formula.","e":"The discriminant 16 − 52 = −36 gives √(−36) = 6i, so the quadratic formula yields x = (4 ± 6i)/2 = 2 ± 3i (complex conjugate roots)."},{"p":"What are all the real zeros of the polynomial p(x) = x^3 − 4x?","a":"−2, 0, 2","w":["0, 4, −4","0, 2","2, −2"],"h":"Factor out the greatest common factor first, then factor the remaining difference of two squares.","e":"Factoring gives x(x − 2)(x + 2), so by the Zero Product Property the zeros are x = 0, 2, and −2."},{"p":"Use the Remainder Theorem to find the remainder when p(x) = x^3 − 2x^2 + 3x − 5 is divided by (x − 2).","a":"1","w":["−1","5","−5"],"h":"The Remainder Theorem says the remainder equals the polynomial evaluated at the value that makes the divisor zero.","e":"By the Remainder Theorem, the remainder is p(2) = 8 − 8 + 6 − 5 = 1."},{"p":"Simplify the rational expression completely: (x^2 − 9)/(x^2 − x − 6).","a":"(x + 3)/(x + 2)","w":["(x − 3)/(x + 2)","(x + 3)/(x − 2)","(x − 3)/(x − 2)"],"h":"Factor the numerator (difference of squares) and denominator (trinomial), then cancel the common factor.","e":"Factoring gives (x − 3)(x + 3)/[(x − 3)(x + 2)]; canceling the common (x − 3) leaves (x + 3)/(x + 2)."},{"p":"Solve for x: √(2x + 3) = 5.","a":"11","w":["1","14","22"],"h":"Isolate the radical (already done), then square both sides to eliminate the square root.","e":"Squaring gives 2x + 3 = 25, so 2x = 22 and x = 11; squaring both sides is the standard method for radical equations."},{"p":"Solve √(x + 6) = x and identify the valid solution(s), rejecting any extraneous root.","a":"x = 3","w":["x = −2","x = 3 or x = −2","x = 6"],"h":"Square both sides to form a quadratic, then check each candidate in the original equation for extraneous solutions.","e":"Squaring gives x^2 − x − 6 = 0 → (x − 3)(x + 2) = 0; x = −2 fails the original equation, so only x = 3 is valid."},{"p":"Solve for x: 3^(2x) = 81.","a":"2","w":["4","3","1"],"h":"Rewrite 81 as a power of 3 so both sides share the same base, then set the exponents equal.","e":"Since 81 = 3^4, the equation becomes 2x = 4, so x = 2 by equating exponents of the common base."},{"p":"Evaluate the logarithm: log_2(1/8).","a":"−3","w":["3","−4","−8"],"h":"Ask: 2 raised to what power gives 1/8? Remember that a reciprocal produces a negative exponent.","e":"Because 2^(−3) = 1/8, the definition of a logarithm gives log_2(1/8) = −3."},{"p":"Which expression is equivalent to log_b(x^2/y)?","a":"2 log_b x − log_b y","w":["2 log_b x + log_b y","log_b x − 2 log_b y","(2 log_b x)/(log_b y)"],"h":"Apply the quotient rule to split the division into subtraction, then the power rule to bring down the exponent.","e":"The quotient and power rules give log_b(x^2) − log_b y = 2 log_b x − log_b y."},{"p":"A population of 500 bacteria increases by 3% each hour. Which function models the population after t hours?","a":"500(1.03)^t","w":["500(0.03)^t","500(1.3)^t","500(0.97)^t"],"h":"For exponential growth, the base equals 1 plus the decimal growth rate.","e":"Growth by 3% uses base 1 + 0.03 = 1.03, giving the exponential growth model A = 500(1.03)^t."},{"p":"In the arithmetic sequence with first term a₁ = 7 and common difference d = 4, find the 10th term.","a":"43","w":["47","39","36"],"h":"Use aₙ = a₁ + (n − 1)d; be careful to multiply the difference by (n − 1), not n.","e":"Applying aₙ = a₁ + (n − 1)d gives a₁₀ = 7 + (10 − 1)(4) = 7 + 36 = 43."},{"p":"Find the 6th term of the geometric sequence 3, 6, 12, 24, … .","a":"96","w":["192","48","64"],"h":"Use aₙ = a₁·r^(n − 1) with common ratio r = 2; the exponent is n − 1, not n.","e":"With a₁ = 3 and r = 2, a₆ = 3·2^(6 − 1) = 3·32 = 96 by the geometric sequence formula."},{"p":"What is the period of the function y = 2 sin(3x)?","a":"2π/3","w":["3","2π","π/3"],"h":"For y = a sin(bx), the period is 2π divided by b; the coefficient a affects amplitude, not period.","e":"The period of a sine function is 2π/|b|, so with b = 3 the period is 2π/3."},{"p":"Using the unit circle, evaluate cos(2π/3).","a":"−1/2","w":["1/2","−√3/2","√3/2"],"h":"The angle 2π/3 lies in Quadrant II, where cosine is negative; its reference angle is π/3.","e":"With reference angle π/3 in Quadrant II, cos(2π/3) = −cos(π/3) = −1/2, since cosine is negative in Quadrant II."},{"p":"Events A and B are independent with P(A) = 0.4 and P(B) = 0.5. Find P(A and B).","a":"0.2","w":["0.9","0.45","0.5"],"h":"For independent events, the probability of both occurring is the product of their individual probabilities.","e":"Independence means P(A and B) = P(A)·P(B) = 0.4 × 0.5 = 0.2 by the multiplication rule for independent events."},{"p":"Express the quotient (2 + 3i)/(1 − i) in standard form a + bi.","a":"−1/2 + 5/2 i","w":["5/2 − 1/2 i","−1/2 − 5/2 i","1/2 + 5/2 i"],"h":"Multiply the numerator and denominator by the complex conjugate of the denominator, then use i² = −1.","e":"Dividing complex numbers requires multiplying by the conjugate of the denominator: (2+3i)(1+i)/[(1−i)(1+i)] = (−1+5i)/2."},{"p":"A polynomial with real coefficients has 2 − i as one of its roots. Which value must also be a root of the polynomial?","a":"2 + i","w":["−2 + i","−2 − i","1 − 2i"],"h":"For polynomials with real coefficients, nonreal roots occur in a particular paired form.","e":"By the Complex Conjugate Root Theorem, nonreal roots of a real-coefficient polynomial come in conjugate pairs, so 2 + i must also be a root."},{"p":"Which quadratic equation has roots 3 + 2i and 3 − 2i?","a":"x² − 6x + 13 = 0","w":["x² + 6x + 13 = 0","x² − 6x − 13 = 0","x² − 6x + 5 = 0"],"h":"Use the fact that the sum of the roots equals −b/a and the product equals c/a.","e":"The sum of the conjugate roots is 6 and their product is 3² + 2² = 13, giving x² − (sum)x + (product) = x² − 6x + 13."},{"p":"Simplify the expression: (27x⁶)^(2/3), where x > 0.","a":"9x⁴","w":["18x⁴","9x⁹","3x⁴"],"h":"Apply the rational exponent to each factor: take the cube root first, then square.","e":"Using rational exponents, 27^(2/3) = (∛27)² = 9 and (x⁶)^(2/3) = x⁴, giving 9x⁴."},{"p":"Solve for x to the nearest hundredth: 5^x = 20.","a":"x ≈ 1.86","w":["x ≈ 1.30","x ≈ 2.90","x ≈ 4.00"],"h":"Take the logarithm of both sides and apply the power rule to bring the exponent down.","e":"Taking logs gives x = log 20 / log 5 ≈ 1.86, using the logarithm power property to solve the exponential equation."},{"p":"Solve for x: log(x) + log(x − 3) = 1 (base 10).","a":"x = 5","w":["x = −2","x = 5 and x = −2","x = 10"],"h":"Condense the left side with the product rule, rewrite in exponential form, then check the domain.","e":"By the product rule, log[x(x−3)] = 1 gives x² − 3x − 10 = 0, so x = 5 or x = −2; x = −2 is rejected because logarithms require positive arguments."},{"p":"Evaluate the logarithm: log₄(32).","a":"5/2","w":["2","8","3/2"],"h":"Rewrite 4 and 32 as powers of the same base and apply the change-of-base or power relationship.","e":"Since 4 = 2² and 32 = 2⁵, log₄(32) = log₂(2⁵)/log₂(2²) = 5/2 by the change-of-base property."},{"p":"A radioactive substance has a half-life of 12 years. If the initial amount is A₀, which function gives the amount remaining after t years?","a":"A(t) = A₀(1/2)^(t/12)","w":["A(t) = A₀(1/2)^(12t)","A(t) = A₀(2)^(t/12)","A(t) = A₀(1/2)^t · 12"],"h":"The exponent should represent the number of half-lives that have elapsed after t years.","e":"For exponential decay with a half-life, the base is 1/2 and the exponent is t divided by the half-life: A₀(1/2)^(t/12)."},{"p":"Find the sum of the first 20 terms of the arithmetic sequence with first term a₁ = 3 and common difference d = 5.","a":"1010","w":["1000","2020","970"],"h":"Use the arithmetic series formula Sₙ = (n/2)(2a₁ + (n − 1)d).","e":"Applying Sₙ = (n/2)[2a₁ + (n−1)d] gives S₂₀ = 10(6 + 95) = 1010."},{"p":"Find the sum of the first 6 terms of the geometric sequence 2, 6, 18, 54, … .","a":"728","w":["1458","486","364"],"h":"Identify the common ratio, then use Sₙ = a₁(rⁿ − 1)/(r − 1).","e":"With a₁ = 2 and r = 3, S₆ = 2(3⁶ − 1)/(3 − 1) = 2(728)/2 = 728 by the finite geometric series formula."},{"p":"Evaluate the sum of the infinite geometric series 16 + 12 + 9 + … .","a":"64","w":["48","21.75","No finite sum exists"],"h":"First confirm the common ratio satisfies |r| < 1, then apply the infinite sum formula.","e":"The ratio r = 3/4 has |r| < 1, so the series converges to S = a₁/(1 − r) = 16/(1/4) = 64."},{"p":"Which sinusoidal function has an amplitude of 3, a period of 4π, and a midline of y = 5?","a":"y = 3 sin(½x) + 5","w":["y = 3 sin(2x) + 5","y = 5 sin(½x) + 3","y = ½ sin(3x) + 5"],"h":"The period equals 2π divided by the coefficient of x, and the midline is the vertical shift.","e":"Period 4π requires b = 2π/4π = ½, amplitude 3 is the leading coefficient, and midline y = 5 is the added constant: y = 3 sin(½x) + 5."},{"p":"Using the unit circle, evaluate sin(7π/6).","a":"−1/2","w":["1/2","−√3/2","√3/2"],"h":"Determine the quadrant of the angle and its reference angle before assigning a sign.","e":"The angle 7π/6 lies in Quadrant III with reference angle π/6, where sine is negative, so sin(7π/6) = −1/2."},{"p":"If sin θ = 3/5 and θ terminates in Quadrant II, what is the value of cos θ?","a":"−4/5","w":["4/5","−3/5","−3/4"],"h":"Use the Pythagorean identity sin²θ + cos²θ = 1, then choose the sign based on the quadrant.","e":"From sin²θ + cos²θ = 1, cos θ = ±4/5; since cosine is negative in Quadrant II, cos θ = −4/5."},{"p":"In a school, the probability a randomly chosen student passed math is 0.7, and the probability a student passed both math and science is 0.42. What is the probability that a student passed science given that they passed math?","a":"0.6","w":["0.42","0.7","0.3"],"h":"Apply the conditional probability formula P(A | B) = P(A and B)/P(B).","e":"Using P(science | math) = P(science and math)/P(math) = 0.42/0.7 = 0.6, the definition of conditional probability."},{"p":"Test scores are normally distributed with a mean of 100 and a standard deviation of 15. Approximately what percent of scores fall between 85 and 115?","a":"About 68%","w":["About 34%","About 95%","About 99.7%"],"h":"Note how many standard deviations the interval endpoints are from the mean, then use the empirical rule.","e":"The interval 85 to 115 spans one standard deviation on each side of the mean, and by the empirical rule about 68% of data lies within ±1 standard deviation."},{"p":"A study computes a linear regression and reports a correlation coefficient of r = −0.87. Which statement best describes the relationship between the variables?","a":"A strong negative linear correlation","w":["A weak negative linear correlation","A strong positive linear correlation","No linear correlation"],"h":"Consider both the sign and how close the magnitude of r is to 1.","e":"A correlation coefficient near −1 indicates a strong negative linear association; r = −0.87 is close to −1 with a negative sign."},{"p":"The impedance of an AC circuit is given by Z = 8 + 6i ohms. The magnitude of the impedance is |Z|. What is |Z|?","a":"10 ohms","w":["14 ohms","√14 ohms","100 ohms"],"h":"The modulus of a complex number a + bi is found with a Pythagorean-type formula, not by adding a and b.","e":"The modulus is |a + bi| = √(a² + b²) = √(64 + 36) = √100 = 10, representing the magnitude of the complex impedance."},{"p":"What is the sum of the roots of the quadratic equation 2x² − 9x + 4 = 0?","a":"9/2","w":["2","−9/2","4"],"h":"There is a relationship between the coefficients of a quadratic and the sum of its roots that avoids solving the equation.","e":"By Vieta's formulas, the sum of the roots equals −b/a = −(−9)/2 = 9/2 (while the product equals c/a = 2)."},{"p":"Which binomial is a factor of the polynomial p(x) = x³ + 2x² − 5x − 6?","a":"(x − 2)","w":["(x + 2)","(x − 3)","(x − 1)"],"h":"By the Factor Theorem, (x − c) is a factor exactly when substituting that c makes the polynomial equal zero.","e":"By the Factor Theorem, (x − 2) is a factor because p(2) = 8 + 8 − 10 − 6 = 0; the other candidates give nonzero values."},{"p":"Solve for x: 1/(x − 2) + 1/(x + 2) = 4/(x² − 4).","a":"No solution","w":["x = 2","x = −2","x = 0"],"h":"After clearing denominators, always check the candidate against the values that would make any original denominator zero.","e":"Clearing denominators gives (x + 2) + (x − 2) = 4, so x = 2; but x = 2 makes the denominators zero, so it is an extraneous root and there is no solution."},{"p":"Solve for x: (x − 1)^(3/2) = 8.","a":"x = 5","w":["x = 3","x = 17","x = 65"],"h":"Undo a 3/2 power by raising both sides to its reciprocal exponent, then interpret that fractional power as a root and a power.","e":"Raising both sides to the 2/3 power gives x − 1 = 8^(2/3) = (∛8)² = 4, so x = 5."},{"p":"An account of $2000 earns 4% annual interest compounded continuously. Which function gives the balance A after t years?","a":"A = 2000e^(0.04t)","w":["A = 2000(1.04)^t","A = 2000e^(4t)","A = 2000(0.04)^t"],"h":"Continuous compounding uses the base e with the decimal form of the annual rate in the exponent.","e":"Continuous compound interest is modeled by A = Pe^(rt); here P = 2000 and r = 0.04, giving A = 2000e^(0.04t)."},{"p":"On the Richter scale, an earthquake's magnitude is M = log(I/I₀), where I₀ is a reference intensity. If an earthquake has intensity 1000 times I₀, what is its magnitude M?","a":"3","w":["6","100","1000"],"h":"Substitute the intensity ratio into the formula and evaluate a base-10 logarithm of a power of ten.","e":"M = log(1000·I₀ / I₀) = log(1000) = log(10³) = 3, using the base-10 logarithm that defines the Richter scale."},{"p":"Evaluate the logarithm: log₉(27).","a":"3/2","w":["3","2/3","1/3"],"h":"Write both 9 and 27 as powers of the same prime base, then compare exponents.","e":"Since 9 = 3² and 27 = 3³, log₉(27) = log₉(9^(3/2)) = 3/2."},{"p":"Describe the horizontal phase shift of the function y = 3 cos(2x − π).","a":"π/2 units to the right","w":["π units to the right","π/2 units to the left","π/4 units to the right"],"h":"Factor the coefficient of x out of the argument so the expression reads b(x − h); the value of h is the shift.","e":"Factoring gives y = 3 cos(2(x − π/2)), so the phase shift is π/2 units to the right."},{"p":"Solve 2 sin θ − 1 = 0 for all θ in the interval 0 ≤ θ < 2π.","a":"θ = π/6 and 5π/6","w":["θ = π/6 only","θ = π/6 and 7π/6","θ = π/3 and 2π/3"],"h":"Isolate sin θ, then use the unit circle to find every angle in the interval with that sine value, remembering sine is positive in two quadrants.","e":"Solving gives sin θ = 1/2, which occurs at the reference angle π/6 in Quadrants I and II, so θ = π/6 and 5π/6."},{"p":"Evaluate the sum written in sigma notation: Σ (from k = 1 to 4) of (2k + 1).","a":"24","w":["20","26","16"],"h":"Substitute k = 1, 2, 3, 4 into the expression 2k + 1 and add all four resulting terms, including the constant each time.","e":"The terms are 3 + 5 + 7 + 9 = 24; forgetting the +1 in each term is a common error."},{"p":"A fair coin is flipped 5 times. What is the probability of getting exactly 3 heads?","a":"5/16","w":["3/5","1/8","5/8"],"h":"This is a binomial situation; count the arrangements of the desired outcome and multiply by the probability of each specific sequence.","e":"Using the binomial formula, P = C(5,3)(1/2)³(1/2)² = 10/32 = 5/16."},{"p":"Read: \"A survey of 200 students found that 120 own a laptop. Of those laptop owners, 90 also own a tablet.\" Based on this survey, what is the probability that a student owns a tablet given that the student owns a laptop?","a":"0.75","w":["0.45","0.60","0.69"],"h":"A conditional probability restricts the sample space to the given group; divide by the size of that group, not the whole survey.","e":"P(tablet | laptop) = 90/120 = 0.75, since the condition restricts attention to the 120 laptop owners."},{"p":"Adult male heights are normally distributed with a mean of 68 inches and a standard deviation of 3 inches. Using the empirical rule, approximately what percent of men are taller than 74 inches?","a":"About 2.5%","w":["About 5%","About 16%","About 0.15%"],"h":"Find how many standard deviations 74 is above the mean, then use the empirical rule for the tail beyond that point.","e":"74 inches is 2 standard deviations above the mean; the empirical rule leaves about 5% outside ±2 SD, so about 2.5% lie in the upper tail."},{"p":"For the polynomial p(x) = 2(x + 3)²(x − 1)³(x − 4), at which zero does the graph touch the x-axis but not cross it?","a":"x = −3","w":["x = 1","x = 4","x = 0"],"h":"The behavior at a zero depends on whether its multiplicity (the exponent of its factor) is even or odd.","e":"A zero with even multiplicity produces a graph that touches but does not cross; x = −3 has multiplicity 2, while the others have odd multiplicity and cross."},{"p":"What is the horizontal asymptote of the rational function f(x) = (2x² + 3)/(x² − 4)?","a":"y = 2","w":["y = 0","y = −4","x = 2"],"h":"Compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator; when they are equal, the asymptote depends on the leading coefficients.","e":"Because the numerator and denominator have equal degree, the horizontal asymptote is the ratio of leading coefficients, y = 2/1 = 2."},{"p":"If f(x) = (x − 3)/2, what is the inverse function f⁻¹(x)?","a":"f⁻¹(x) = 2x + 3","w":["f⁻¹(x) = 2x − 3","f⁻¹(x) = (x + 3)/2","f⁻¹(x) = 2/(x − 3)"],"h":"To find an inverse, swap x and y and solve for y, undoing each operation in reverse order.","e":"Swapping variables in x = (y − 3)/2 and solving gives y = 2x + 3, so f⁻¹(x) = 2x + 3."}],"regents-earth":[{"p":"At a divergent plate boundary in the middle of an ocean, two oceanic plates move apart. What geologic feature forms primarily along this boundary?","a":"A mid-ocean ridge where new basaltic crust is created","w":["A deep-sea trench where old crust is destroyed","A folded mountain range of continental rock","A chain of volcanic islands above a subduction zone"],"h":"Think about what happens to magma that rises to fill the gap as plates separate.","e":"Divergent boundaries produce mid-ocean ridges, where upwelling magma solidifies into new basaltic oceanic crust (sea-floor spreading)."},{"p":"Where on the ocean floor is the youngest igneous bedrock generally found?","a":"At the mid-ocean ridges","w":["Along the deep-sea trenches","Adjacent to the continental margins","Evenly distributed across the entire ocean floor"],"h":"Consider where sea-floor spreading is actively adding new material.","e":"Sea-floor spreading makes bedrock youngest at the mid-ocean ridge and progressively older with distance from it."},{"p":"A geologist rubs an unknown mineral across an unglazed porcelain plate and observes the color of the powder left behind. Which mineral property is being tested?","a":"Streak","w":["Cleavage","Luster","Hardness"],"h":"The test involves the color of a mineral in powdered form, not the color of the solid sample.","e":"Streak is the color of a mineral's powder and is often more reliable for identification than the surface color of the sample."},{"p":"An igneous rock is defined by the way it forms. Which process produces an igneous rock?","a":"The cooling and solidification of magma or lava","w":["The compaction and cementation of sediments","The heat and pressure altering an existing rock in the solid state","The evaporation of a mineral-rich solution"],"h":"The word igneous relates to fire; focus on molten material.","e":"Igneous rocks form by the crystallization (solidification) of molten magma or lava, as shown on the rock cycle."},{"p":"Which of the following is an example of chemical weathering?","a":"Feldspar reacting with water and carbon dioxide to form clay minerals","w":["Water freezing in a crack and splitting a boulder apart","Wind-blown sand abrading and smoothing a rock surface","Tree roots growing into joints and prying a rock apart"],"h":"Chemical weathering changes the actual mineral composition of the rock, not just its size.","e":"Chemical weathering alters mineral composition through reactions such as hydrolysis; the other choices are physical (mechanical) weathering."},{"p":"A stream carrying sand, pebbles, and cobbles flows into a calm lake and its velocity suddenly drops. Which sediment is deposited first?","a":"The cobbles (largest particles)","w":["The sand (smallest particles)","The pebbles (medium particles)","All particles settle out at exactly the same time"],"h":"Larger, heavier particles require more energy to keep moving.","e":"When water velocity decreases, the largest and densest particles are deposited first (settling by particle size)."},{"p":"Along a cold front, how does the cold air mass interact with the warm air mass it meets?","a":"The dense cold air wedges beneath the warm air, forcing it to rise steeply","w":["The warm air slides gently up over the top of the cold air","The two air masses mix evenly with no vertical motion","The cold air rides up over the warm air and cools it"],"h":"Cold air is denser than warm air, so consider which mass stays near the ground.","e":"At a cold front the denser cold air pushes under and lifts the warm air abruptly, often producing tall cumulonimbus clouds and heavy precipitation."},{"p":"What is the primary cause of the seasons on Earth?","a":"The tilt of Earth's axis as Earth revolves around the Sun","w":["The changing distance between Earth and the Sun","The variation in the Sun's energy output during the year","The rotation of Earth on its axis every 24 hours"],"h":"Consider why the Northern and Southern Hemispheres have opposite seasons at the same time.","e":"Seasons result from the 23.5 degree tilt of Earth's axis, which changes the angle of insolation and length of daylight as Earth orbits the Sun."},{"p":"In a sequence of undisturbed sedimentary rock layers, which layer is the oldest?","a":"The bottom layer","w":["The top layer","The middle layer","All layers are the same age"],"h":"Sediments accumulate one layer on top of another over time.","e":"By the Law of Superposition, in undisturbed strata the oldest layer is at the bottom and each layer above it is younger."},{"p":"On a topographic map, what do closely spaced contour lines indicate about the land surface?","a":"A steep slope","w":["A gentle slope","A flat plain","A depression or basin"],"h":"Contour lines connect points of equal elevation; think about how quickly elevation changes when lines are packed together.","e":"Closely spaced contour lines mean elevation changes rapidly over a short horizontal distance, indicating a steep slope; widely spaced lines indicate a gentle slope."},{"p":"According to the rock cycle, sediments are turned into sedimentary rock mainly by which process?","a":"Compaction and cementation","w":["Melting and solidification","Heat and pressure without melting","Weathering and erosion"],"h":"Think about loose particles being pressed together and glued by dissolved minerals.","e":"Sediments become sedimentary rock through compaction (pressure from overlying material) and cementation (mineral glue), a process called lithification."},{"p":"During an earthquake, seismic S-waves (secondary waves) behave differently from P-waves. Which statement about S-waves is correct?","a":"S-waves cannot travel through liquids such as the outer core","w":["S-waves arrive at a seismic station before P-waves","S-waves travel through both solids and liquids equally well","S-waves travel faster than P-waves through the mantle"],"h":"Recall which wave type creates the shadow zone that reveals a liquid layer inside Earth.","e":"S-waves are transverse and cannot pass through liquids, so their absence beyond the S-wave shadow zone shows the outer core is liquid; P-waves are faster and arrive first."},{"p":"A student measures the density of a mineral sample, then breaks it into a smaller piece and measures the density again. What happens to the density?","a":"It stays the same because density does not depend on sample size","w":["It decreases because there is less mass","It increases because the piece is more compact","It doubles if the sample is broken exactly in half"],"h":"Density is a ratio of mass to volume; consider how both change when a sample is broken.","e":"Density is an intensive property; when a sample is divided, mass and volume decrease proportionally, so density remains constant for a given material."},{"p":"Two soil samples have equal porosity, but water flows much faster through Sample A than Sample B. Which property differs between them?","a":"Permeability","w":["Porosity","Capillarity","Density"],"h":"Porosity is the amount of pore space; this property describes how easily water moves through the connected pores.","e":"Permeability is the ability of a material to transmit water through connected pore spaces; larger, well-connected particles increase permeability even when porosity is equal."},{"p":"During which moon phase is the Moon positioned between Earth and the Sun?","a":"New moon","w":["Full moon","First-quarter moon","Third-quarter moon"],"h":"Consider the phase in which the side of the Moon facing Earth receives no direct sunlight.","e":"At new moon the Moon lies between Earth and the Sun, so its sunlit side faces away from Earth and it appears dark; a full moon occurs when Earth is between the Sun and Moon."},{"p":"On the Sun and other stars, what does the color of a star primarily indicate?","a":"Its surface temperature","w":["Its distance from Earth","Its total age in years","Its chemical composition only"],"h":"Think about how a heated metal glows red when cooler and blue-white when hotter.","e":"A star's color reflects its surface temperature: blue stars are hottest and red stars are coolest, a relationship shown on the Hertzsprung-Russell (luminosity vs. temperature) diagram."},{"p":"A planet travels in an elliptical orbit around the Sun. At which point in its orbit does the planet move fastest?","a":"When it is closest to the Sun (perihelion)","w":["When it is farthest from the Sun (aphelion)","At the two points midway between closest and farthest","Its speed is constant throughout the entire orbit"],"h":"Recall Kepler's law relating orbital speed to the area swept out in equal times.","e":"By Kepler's law of equal areas, a planet sweeps out equal areas in equal times, so it moves fastest at perihelion (closest to the Sun) and slowest at aphelion."},{"p":"A metamorphic rock forms from an existing rock. Which conditions produce a metamorphic rock?","a":"Heat and pressure that change the rock while it remains solid","w":["Complete melting followed by slow cooling","Compaction and cementation of loose sediments","Chemical weathering at Earth's surface"],"h":"The rock is transformed but never becomes molten or breaks down into sediment.","e":"Metamorphic rocks form when heat and pressure alter the texture and/or mineral composition of a pre-existing rock in the solid state (recrystallization without melting)."},{"p":"Read: \"A river deposits its sediment where it flows into the ocean, building up a fan-shaped landform of sand and silt at its mouth.\" What is this depositional landform called?","a":"A delta","w":["A moraine","A sand dune","A meander"],"h":"The landform is built by flowing water losing energy as it enters a standing body of water.","e":"A delta is a depositional feature formed where a river's velocity drops upon entering a lake or ocean, causing sediment to accumulate at the mouth."},{"p":"Which agent of erosion is primarily responsible for creating rounded, sorted sediments and V-shaped valleys in humid climates?","a":"Running water (streams and rivers)","w":["Moving glacial ice","Blowing wind","Ocean wave action"],"h":"Consider the most common erosional agent in regions with abundant rainfall, and the shape of valley it carves.","e":"Running water is the dominant agent of erosion in humid climates; it rounds and sorts sediments and carves V-shaped valleys, whereas glaciers carve U-shaped valleys."},{"p":"An oceanic plate converges with a continental plate. Which pair of features forms as a direct result of this collision?","a":"An ocean trench and a chain of volcanic mountains on the continent","w":["A mid-ocean ridge and new oceanic crust","A transform fault and shallow-only earthquakes","A rift valley and diverging continental crust"],"h":"Think about which plate is denser and therefore subducts, and what happens to it as it sinks.","e":"At an oceanic-continental convergent boundary the denser oceanic plate subducts, creating a deep trench, while melting above the descending plate feeds volcanic mountains (e.g., the Andes)."},{"p":"An unknown mineral scratches glass (hardness ~5.5) but is itself scratched by a piece of quartz (hardness 7). Which is the best estimate of the mineral's hardness on the Mohs scale?","a":"Between 5.5 and 7","w":["Less than 5.5","Exactly 7","Greater than 7"],"h":"A mineral can scratch anything softer than itself and is scratched by anything harder.","e":"On the Mohs hardness scale, a mineral's hardness lies above whatever it can scratch and below whatever scratches it, placing this sample between 5.5 and 7."},{"p":"Two igneous rocks form from the same magma. Rock A has large, visible interlocking crystals; Rock B is fine-grained and glassy. What best explains the large crystals in Rock A?","a":"Rock A cooled slowly deep beneath the surface, allowing crystals time to grow","w":["Rock A cooled quickly at Earth's surface after a volcanic eruption","Rock A is older, so its crystals had more time to erode into large grains","Rock A formed from sediments compacted under great pressure"],"h":"Crystal size in igneous rock reflects how much time atoms had to arrange into crystals as the melt solidified.","e":"Slow cooling in an intrusive (plutonic) environment gives ions time to form large crystals, while rapid cooling at the surface (extrusive) produces fine-grained or glassy textures."},{"p":"In which climate is frost (ice) wedging expected to be the MOST effective agent of physical weathering?","a":"A cool, moist climate where temperatures repeatedly cross the freezing point","w":["A hot, dry desert climate that stays well above freezing","A consistently frozen polar climate that stays far below freezing","A warm, humid tropical climate with heavy rainfall"],"h":"Frost wedging depends on liquid water repeatedly freezing and thawing inside cracks.","e":"Ice wedging requires both available water and frequent freeze-thaw cycles, so it is most active where temperatures oscillate above and below 0 degrees Celsius."},{"p":"At 3 p.m. the air temperature is 24 degrees Celsius and the dewpoint is 24 degrees Celsius. What is the relative humidity, and what is likely occurring?","a":"100 percent, and condensation (dew, fog, or clouds) is likely forming","w":["0 percent, and the air is completely dry","50 percent, and evaporation is rapidly increasing","100 percent, and the air can still hold much more moisture"],"h":"Relative humidity compares the air's moisture to the maximum it can hold; consider what it means when temperature equals dewpoint.","e":"When air temperature equals the dewpoint, the air is saturated (relative humidity 100 percent) and further cooling forces condensation."},{"p":"On a topographic map, one hilltop is at 800 meters and a point 30 kilometers away is at 200 meters. What is the gradient of the slope between these two points?","a":"20 meters per kilometer","w":["600 meters per kilometer","30 meters per kilometer","1000 meters per kilometer"],"h":"Gradient equals the change in field value divided by the distance between the two points.","e":"Gradient = change in elevation / distance = (800 - 200) m / 30 km = 20 m/km."},{"p":"A radioactive isotope has a half-life of 5,700 years. A rock sample now contains one-eighth of its original amount of that isotope. Approximately how old is the sample?","a":"17,100 years","w":["11,400 years","5,700 years","45,600 years"],"h":"Each half-life reduces the parent isotope by half; work out how many halvings give one-eighth.","e":"One-eighth remaining means three half-lives have passed (1/2 to 1/4 to 1/8), so age = 3 x 5,700 = 17,100 years."},{"p":"Which combination of characteristics makes a fossil a good index fossil for correlating rock layers?","a":"The organism was geographically widespread and existed for only a short span of geologic time","w":["The organism lived in one small area for a very long span of geologic time","The organism is still alive today and found on every continent","The organism was large and had hard body parts that resist weathering"],"h":"A useful marker must appear in many places yet pinpoint a narrow time interval.","e":"Ideal index fossils are widespread (so layers in different regions can be matched) and short-lived (so they mark a specific, narrow time period)."},{"p":"At solar noon in the Northern Hemisphere, why does the ground heat up more than it does in early morning, even on a clear day?","a":"The Sun's rays strike the surface at a higher angle, concentrating energy over a smaller area","w":["The Sun is physically much closer to Earth at noon","The atmosphere is thinner at noon, so less energy is absorbed","The Earth rotates faster at noon, generating frictional heat"],"h":"Consider how the angle at which sunlight hits a surface affects how spread out that energy becomes.","e":"A higher angle of insolation concentrates solar energy over a smaller area, increasing heating; low-angle rays spread the same energy over a larger area."},{"p":"A large mass of air moves northward across the United States. Because of the Coriolis effect, its path appears to:","a":"Curve to the right (to the east) relative to Earth's surface","w":["Curve to the left (to the west) relative to Earth's surface","Continue in a perfectly straight north-south line","Reverse direction and travel back southward"],"h":"Earth's rotation deflects free-moving objects, and the direction of deflection depends on the hemisphere.","e":"The Coriolis effect deflects moving objects to the right in the Northern Hemisphere, curving winds and currents eastward as they travel north."},{"p":"Along the San Andreas Fault, two plates grind horizontally past each other without creating or destroying crust. This is an example of which boundary, and what hazard is most associated with it?","a":"A transform boundary, associated with frequent, often shallow earthquakes","w":["A divergent boundary, associated with new crust and mid-ocean ridges","A convergent boundary, associated with deep ocean trenches","A hotspot, associated with a chain of shield volcanoes"],"h":"Focus on the motion (sliding past) rather than plates moving together or apart.","e":"At a transform boundary plates slide laterally past one another, building up stress that releases as earthquakes without producing or consuming crust."},{"p":"Astronomers measure the tiny apparent shift in a nearby star's position as Earth orbits the Sun. This technique is used primarily to determine the star's:","a":"Distance from Earth","w":["Surface temperature","Chemical composition","Age in billions of years"],"h":"The measured shift depends on viewing the star from opposite sides of Earth's orbit.","e":"Stellar parallax uses the apparent shift of a nearby star against distant background stars to calculate its distance from Earth."},{"p":"Light from distant galaxies is shifted toward the red (longer-wavelength) end of the spectrum, and more distant galaxies show greater shifts. What does this observation best support?","a":"The universe is expanding, with galaxies moving away from us","w":["The universe is contracting toward a single point","Distant galaxies are made mostly of red-colored stars","Earth is located at the exact center of the universe"],"h":"A shift toward longer wavelengths indicates motion away from the observer, like a receding sound source.","e":"The redshift of galaxy light (a Doppler effect) increasing with distance is key evidence for an expanding universe consistent with the Big Bang theory."},{"p":"Ocean tides on Earth are caused mainly by the gravitational pull of the Moon. Most coastlines experience about how many high tides in a 24-hour period?","a":"Two high tides and two low tides","w":["One high tide and one low tide","Four high tides and four low tides","No regular tides, only random changes"],"h":"A bulge of water forms on the side facing the Moon and on the opposite side; think about Earth's daily rotation through them.","e":"The Moon's gravity produces two tidal bulges, so a rotating point on Earth passes through roughly two high and two low tides each day."},{"p":"In a sequence of rock layers, horizontal sedimentary beds lie directly on top of tilted, eroded older layers. This buried, uneven contact surface is called a(n):","a":"Unconformity, which represents a gap in the geologic rock record","w":["Fault, which represents a fracture with movement","Intrusion, which represents magma injected into older rock","Index bed, which represents a single instant in time"],"h":"The surface marks a period when rock was eroded or not deposited before newer layers formed above it.","e":"An unconformity is a buried erosional or non-depositional surface indicating missing time (a gap) in the rock record."},{"p":"A metamorphic rock shows minerals aligned into parallel bands (foliation). This banded texture indicates the rock formed under conditions of:","a":"Directed pressure, which flattens and aligns mineral grains","w":["Rapid cooling of magma at Earth's surface","Cementation of loose sediment grains","Evaporation of mineral-rich seawater"],"h":"Consider what force could line up mineral grains into layers rather than leaving them randomly arranged.","e":"Foliation results from regional metamorphism under directed (differential) pressure, which aligns platy minerals into bands perpendicular to the pressure."},{"p":"A student maps a stream valley and notices the contour lines crossing the stream bend into a V shape. In which direction does the V of the contour lines point relative to the stream's flow?","a":"The V points upstream, in the direction opposite to the water flow","w":["The V points downstream, in the same direction the water flows","The V always points due north regardless of flow","The V points toward the steepest nearby hilltop"],"h":"Contour lines bend upslope as they cross a valley cut by the stream.","e":"By the rule of Vs, contour lines crossing a stream bend upstream (upslope), so the V points opposite to the direction of water flow."},{"p":"A student draws an ellipse using two pins (foci) placed 4.0 cm apart and finds the length of the major axis is 10.0 cm. What is the eccentricity of this ellipse?","a":"0.40","w":["2.5","0.04","0.25"],"h":"Eccentricity equals the distance between the foci divided by the length of the major axis; check which value goes on top.","e":"Eccentricity = distance between foci / length of major axis = 4.0/10.0 = 0.40, the formula given in the Earth Science Reference Tables."},{"p":"Read: \"Moist air from the Pacific is forced upward as it crosses a coastal mountain range. Heavy rain falls on the western slope, but the valley just east of the peaks is a near-desert.\" Which term best describes the dry eastern region and why is it dry?","a":"A rain shadow, because the air descends, is compressed, and warms after losing its moisture crossing the peaks","w":["A rain shadow, because descending air rises, expands, and cools on the eastern side","A leeward highland, because the descending air gains moisture as it warms","A windward desert, because air rising on the eastern slope releases its moisture there"],"h":"Think about what happens to air's temperature and moisture capacity as it sinks down the far (leeward) side of a mountain.","e":"On the leeward side, air that already lost moisture descends, compresses, and warms adiabatically, lowering its relative humidity and producing a dry rain shadow."},{"p":"Because Earth rotates on its axis, the stars appear to move in circular paths around Polaris. Approximately how many degrees do the stars appear to move each hour?","a":"15 degrees per hour","w":["1 degree per hour","23.5 degrees per hour","360 degrees per hour"],"h":"Earth turns a full 360 degrees in about 24 hours; divide to find the hourly rate.","e":"Earth rotates 360 degrees in 24 hours, so celestial objects appear to move 360/24 = 15 degrees per hour."},{"p":"An observer in the Northern Hemisphere measures the altitude of Polaris (the North Star) above the horizon to be 41 degrees. What is the observer's approximate latitude?","a":"41 degrees North","w":["41 degrees South","49 degrees North","23.5 degrees North"],"h":"There is a direct one-to-one relationship between the altitude of Polaris and one specific coordinate of the observer.","e":"The altitude of Polaris above the northern horizon is approximately equal to the observer's latitude, so 41 degrees altitude indicates 41 degrees N."},{"p":"A seismologist wants to pinpoint the location of an earthquake's epicenter using the difference in P-wave and S-wave arrival times. What is the minimum number of seismograph stations needed to determine the exact epicenter location?","a":"Three stations","w":["One station","Two stations","Five stations"],"h":"Each station gives a distance (a circle) to the epicenter; think about how many circles must intersect at a single point.","e":"Each station's P-minus-S time gives a distance circle; three circles are required to intersect at one unique point, fixing the epicenter."},{"p":"According to the Earth Science Reference Tables, how much heat energy is required to melt 1.0 gram of ice at 0 degrees Celsius into liquid water at 0 degrees Celsius?","a":"334 joules","w":["2260 joules","4.18 joules","2.11 joules"],"h":"You need the latent heat of fusion, not the heat of vaporization or a specific heat value.","e":"The heat of fusion of water is 334 J/g; energy absorbed during melting breaks bonds without changing temperature (latent heat)."},{"p":"Two cities lie at the same latitude, but one is on an ocean coast and the other is far inland. The coastal city has cooler summers and milder winters. Which property of water best explains this difference?","a":"Water has a high specific heat, so it warms and cools more slowly than land","w":["Water has a low specific heat, so it changes temperature faster than land","Water is more transparent, so it reflects most incoming insolation","Water has a lower density than land, so it stores less energy overall"],"h":"Consider which substance requires more energy to change its temperature by the same amount.","e":"Water's high specific heat (4.18 J/g/degC) lets it absorb and release large amounts of energy with little temperature change, moderating coastal climates."},{"p":"Four igneous rock samples are tested for density. Which of the following igneous rocks would be expected to have the GREATEST density?","a":"Basalt","w":["Granite","Rhyolite","Pumice"],"h":"Density increases with iron- and magnesium-rich (mafic) composition and decreases with trapped gas; recall which rock is dark and mafic.","e":"Basalt is mafic, rich in dense iron and magnesium minerals, so it has a higher density than felsic granite, rhyolite, or gas-filled pumice."},{"p":"In an experiment, dry soils made of different-sized particles are placed in tubes standing in water. In which soil will capillary action raise the water the HIGHEST?","a":"The soil with the smallest particles","w":["The soil with the largest particles","The soil with the most rounded particles","The soil with the best-sorted particles"],"h":"Capillary rise depends on pore size; smaller openings pull water upward more strongly.","e":"Capillarity increases as particle size (and pore size) decreases, so fine-grained soils like clay lift water highest through narrow pore spaces."},{"p":"Read: \"The Hawaiian Islands form a chain across the Pacific. The islands become progressively older and more eroded toward the northwest, ending in submerged seamounts.\" Which statement best explains this age pattern?","a":"The Pacific plate moved northwest over a stationary mantle hot spot","w":["The mantle hot spot migrated northwest beneath a stationary plate","The islands all erupted at once and eroded at different rates","The islands formed along a northwest-trending divergent plate boundary"],"h":"Consider what stays fixed and what moves when a chain of volcanoes shows a steady age progression.","e":"A stationary mantle hot spot melts through a moving plate; as the Pacific plate drifts northwest, older volcanoes are carried away, producing the age progression."},{"p":"An astronomer observes that the dark absorption lines in a distant star's spectrum are shifted toward the blue (shorter-wavelength) end compared with a laboratory reference. What does this blueshift indicate about the star?","a":"The star is moving toward Earth","w":["The star is moving away from Earth","The star is stationary relative to Earth","The star is cooling and contracting"],"h":"Apply the Doppler effect: shorter observed wavelengths correspond to a source approaching the observer.","e":"A blueshift (compression toward shorter wavelengths) indicates the source is approaching, the opposite of the redshift seen in receding objects."},{"p":"On a Hertzsprung-Russell diagram, a certain star is plotted as very luminous but relatively cool (reddish) in surface temperature. What can be concluded about this star?","a":"It must be very large in size (a giant or supergiant)","w":["It must be very small in size (a white dwarf)","It must be an average main-sequence star like the Sun","It must be extremely hot despite its red color"],"h":"For a cool surface to still emit enormous total energy, something about the star's surface area must compensate.","e":"A cool star can only be highly luminous if it has a very large radius (surface area), placing it among the giants and supergiants on the H-R diagram."},{"p":"On June 21 (the summer solstice), the Sun's rays strike Earth's surface at a 90-degree angle (directly overhead) at solar noon along which line of latitude?","a":"The Tropic of Cancer (23.5 degrees North)","w":["The Equator (0 degrees)","The Tropic of Capricorn (23.5 degrees South)","The Arctic Circle (66.5 degrees North)"],"h":"On the summer solstice the vertical rays reach their northernmost position; recall the boundary of the tropics.","e":"Because Earth's axis is tilted 23.5 degrees, the Sun is directly overhead at the Tropic of Cancer at noon on the June solstice."},{"p":"A student measures the density of a mineral as 2.5 g/cm3, but the accepted value is 2.7 g/cm3. Which expression correctly gives the student's percent deviation (percent error)?","a":"(|2.5 - 2.7| / 2.7) x 100","w":["(|2.5 - 2.7| / 2.5) x 100","(|2.5 - 2.7| / (2.5 + 2.7)) x 100","(2.7 / |2.5 - 2.7|) x 100"],"h":"Percent deviation divides the size of the difference by the accepted value, not the measured value.","e":"The Reference Tables define percent deviation as (difference from accepted value / accepted value) x 100, so the accepted 2.7 g/cm3 goes in the denominator."},{"p":"As a parcel of humid air is lifted upward through the atmosphere, a cloud eventually forms. Which sequence of changes best explains why the cloud forms?","a":"The air expands, cools to its dewpoint, and water vapor condenses","w":["The air is compressed, warms to its dewpoint, and water vapor condenses","The air expands, warms above its dewpoint, and water vapor evaporates","The air is compressed, cools below its dewpoint, and water vapor freezes directly"],"h":"Rising air encounters lower pressure; think about volume, temperature, and the level where condensation begins.","e":"Rising air expands under lower pressure and cools adiabatically; when it reaches the dewpoint, water vapor condenses onto particles, forming a cloud."},{"p":"Unlike the troposphere, the stratosphere shows air temperature INCREASING with altitude. What is the primary cause of this temperature increase?","a":"Ozone in the stratosphere absorbs ultraviolet radiation from the Sun","w":["The stratosphere is closer to the Sun, so it receives more radiation","Greenhouse gases trap infrared radiation rising from Earth's surface","Friction from high-speed jet stream winds heats the upper air"],"h":"Consider which gas concentrated in this layer directly absorbs high-energy solar radiation.","e":"The ozone layer in the stratosphere absorbs ultraviolet radiation, warming that layer and causing temperature to rise with altitude, a reversal of the troposphere's pattern."},{"p":"A hydrogeologist digs a well and notes that below a certain depth all pore spaces in the rock and soil are completely filled with water. What is the name of the upper surface of this fully saturated zone?","a":"The water table","w":["The capillary fringe","The zone of aeration","The permeability front"],"h":"It is the boundary marking the top of the region where every pore space is filled with groundwater.","e":"The water table is the top of the zone of saturation, below which all pore spaces are filled with groundwater; above it lies the unsaturated zone of aeration."},{"p":"On a summer afternoon, a region's surface air becomes strongly heated by the Sun. All else being equal, how does this heating tend to affect the air pressure at that location, and why?","a":"Air pressure tends to decrease, because warm air is less dense and rises","w":["Air pressure tends to increase, because warm air is more dense and sinks","Air pressure tends to increase, because warming adds molecules to the air","Air pressure tends to decrease, because warm air holds less water vapor and contracts"],"h":"Warming makes air molecules spread out; think about how changing density affects whether air rises or sinks.","e":"Heated air expands, becomes less dense, and rises, reducing the weight of air pressing down and producing lower surface pressure (a thermal low)."}],"regents-chem":[{"p":"Which subatomic particle has a negative charge and is located outside the nucleus of an atom?","a":"Electron","w":["Proton","Neutron","Positron"],"h":"Think about which particle occupies the region around the nucleus in the electron cloud.","e":"Electrons carry a -1 charge and occupy the orbitals (electron cloud) surrounding the nucleus, while protons and neutrons are in the nucleus."},{"p":"What is the total number of neutrons in an atom of the isotope carbon-14 (atomic number 6)?","a":"8","w":["6","14","20"],"h":"Neutrons equal the mass number minus the atomic number.","e":"The number of neutrons equals mass number minus atomic number: 14 - 6 = 8, applying the definition of mass number."},{"p":"As the elements in Period 3 are considered from left to right (Na to Cl), the atomic radius generally","a":"decreases","w":["increases","remains the same","increases then decreases"],"h":"Consider how nuclear charge changes across a period while electrons fill the same principal energy level.","e":"Across a period, increasing nuclear charge pulls the electrons in the same shell closer, so atomic radius decreases (periodic trend)."},{"p":"Which type of bond is formed when electrons are transferred from a metal atom to a nonmetal atom?","a":"Ionic bond","w":["Nonpolar covalent bond","Polar covalent bond","Metallic bond"],"h":"Focus on the difference between transferring electrons and sharing them.","e":"An ionic bond forms by the transfer of electrons from a metal to a nonmetal, producing oppositely charged ions held by electrostatic attraction."},{"p":"What is the gram-formula mass of CaCO3? (Ca = 40, C = 12, O = 16)","a":"100 g/mol","w":["68 g/mol","84 g/mol","116 g/mol"],"h":"Add the molar masses of every atom, remembering there are three oxygen atoms.","e":"Gram-formula mass = 40 + 12 + 3(16) = 100 g/mol, summing the atomic masses of each atom in the formula unit."},{"p":"How many moles of water are present in a 36.0 gram sample? (gram-formula mass of H2O = 18.0 g/mol)","a":"2.0 mol","w":["0.50 mol","18.0 mol","36.0 mol"],"h":"Divide the given mass by the gram-formula mass.","e":"Moles = mass / gram-formula mass = 36.0 g / 18.0 g/mol = 2.0 mol, applying the mole definition."},{"p":"In the balanced equation N2 + 3H2 -> 2NH3, how many moles of hydrogen gas are required to completely react with 1 mole of nitrogen gas?","a":"3 moles","w":["1 mole","2 moles","6 moles"],"h":"Use the coefficients in the balanced equation as a mole ratio.","e":"The balanced equation gives a mole ratio of 1 N2 to 3 H2, so 1 mole of N2 reacts with 3 moles of H2 (stoichiometry)."},{"p":"According to collision theory, increasing the temperature of a reaction increases the reaction rate mainly because the reactant particles","a":"collide more frequently and with greater energy","w":["decrease in average kinetic energy","form a stronger activated complex","require a higher activation energy"],"h":"Recall how temperature affects the kinetic energy and motion of particles.","e":"Higher temperature raises average kinetic energy, so particles collide more often and with enough energy to react, increasing rate per collision theory."},{"p":"For the equilibrium N2(g) + 3H2(g) <-> 2NH3(g), what happens to the equilibrium when the pressure on the system is increased at constant temperature?","a":"The equilibrium shifts toward the side with fewer moles of gas (products)","w":["The equilibrium shifts toward the side with more moles of gas (reactants)","The equilibrium does not shift at all","The value of the equilibrium constant increases"],"h":"Apply Le Chatelier's principle and compare the total moles of gas on each side.","e":"By Le Chatelier's principle, increasing pressure shifts equilibrium toward the side with fewer gas moles; here 2 moles of product versus 4 moles of reactant."},{"p":"According to the Arrhenius theory, what ion is produced in greater concentration when an acid is dissolved in water?","a":"Hydrogen ion, H+","w":["Hydroxide ion, OH-","Ammonium ion, NH4+","Oxide ion, O2-"],"h":"Recall what distinguishes an Arrhenius acid from an Arrhenius base in aqueous solution.","e":"An Arrhenius acid ionizes in water to yield H+ (hydronium) as the only positive ion, which defines acidic behavior."},{"p":"A solution has a pH of 3. Compared to a solution with a pH of 5, the solution with pH 3 has a hydrogen ion concentration that is","a":"100 times greater","w":["2 times greater","10 times greater","100 times smaller"],"h":"Each unit of pH change corresponds to a tenfold change in H+ concentration.","e":"pH is a logarithmic scale, so a change of 2 pH units equals a 10^2 = 100-fold difference in [H+], with lower pH being more acidic."},{"p":"In the reaction Zn + Cu2+ -> Zn2+ + Cu, which species is oxidized?","a":"Zn","w":["Cu2+","Zn2+","Cu"],"h":"Oxidation is the loss of electrons; track which species increases in oxidation number.","e":"Zn goes from 0 to +2, losing electrons, so it is oxidized (LEO: Loss of Electrons is Oxidation)."},{"p":"What is the oxidation number of sulfur in the compound H2SO4? (H = +1, O = -2)","a":"+6","w":["-2","+2","+4"],"h":"The oxidation numbers of all atoms in a neutral compound must sum to zero.","e":"With 2(+1) for H and 4(-2) for O, sulfur must be +6 so the total equals zero: +2 + S + (-8) = 0."},{"p":"Which compound is a saturated hydrocarbon?","a":"C3H8","w":["C3H6","C3H4","C2H2"],"h":"Saturated hydrocarbons contain only single bonds and fit the general formula CnH2n+2.","e":"C3H8 (propane) is an alkane fitting CnH2n+2 with only single carbon-carbon bonds, making it saturated."},{"p":"What is the name of the organic compound with the condensed structural formula CH3CH2OH?","a":"Ethanol","w":["Ethanoic acid","Methanol","Ethane"],"h":"Identify the functional group (-OH) and the number of carbon atoms in the chain.","e":"A two-carbon chain with a hydroxyl (-OH) group is ethanol, an alcohol named with the -ol suffix."},{"p":"Which type of nuclear reaction involves splitting a heavy nucleus into two lighter nuclei, releasing energy?","a":"Fission","w":["Fusion","Transmutation by decay","Oxidation"],"h":"Consider whether the heavy nucleus is being broken apart or combined.","e":"Nuclear fission is the splitting of a large nucleus into smaller nuclei with the release of energy, as occurs in nuclear reactors."},{"p":"An atom in the ground state has the electron configuration 2-8-1. To which group (family) on the Periodic Table does this element belong?","a":"Group 1","w":["Group 8","Group 11","Group 18"],"h":"The number of electrons in the outermost occupied shell indicates the group for main-group elements.","e":"With one valence electron (the last number, 1), the element belongs to Group 1, the alkali metals."},{"p":"Which change of phase is exothermic (releases energy)?","a":"Gas condensing to a liquid","w":["Solid melting to a liquid","Liquid boiling to a gas","Solid subliming to a gas"],"h":"Exothermic phase changes involve particles moving to a more ordered state and releasing energy.","e":"Condensation releases energy as gas particles slow and become more ordered; melting, boiling, and sublimation all absorb energy (endothermic)."},{"p":"An element consists of two naturally occurring isotopes: 69.0% with a mass of 63.0 atomic mass units and 31.0% with a mass of 65.0 atomic mass units. What is the average atomic mass of this element?","a":"63.6 atomic mass units","w":["64.0 atomic mass units","63.0 atomic mass units","65.0 atomic mass units"],"h":"The average is weighted according to how abundant each isotope is, not a simple average.","e":"Average atomic mass = Σ(fractional abundance × isotopic mass) = (0.690)(63.0) + (0.310)(65.0) ≈ 63.6 amu."},{"p":"As the elements of Group 1 are considered in order from lithium (Li) to cesium (Cs), the first ionization energy generally","a":"decreases","w":["increases","remains the same","increases, then decreases"],"h":"Consider how the distance of the outermost electron from the nucleus changes as you move down a group.","e":"First ionization energy decreases down a group because the valence electron lies farther from the nucleus and is more shielded, so less energy is needed to remove it."},{"p":"What is the percent by mass of nitrogen in ammonia, NH3? (N = 14, H = 1)","a":"82.4%","w":["17.6%","46.7%","25.0%"],"h":"Divide the total mass of the nitrogen by the gram-formula mass of the entire compound, then multiply by 100.","e":"Percent composition = (mass of element / gram-formula mass) × 100 = (14 / 17) × 100 ≈ 82.4%."},{"p":"Given the balanced equation 2 Mg + O2 -> 2 MgO, how many grams of magnesium oxide are produced when 48 grams of magnesium react completely? (Mg = 24, O = 16)","a":"80 grams","w":["40 grams","64 grams","96 grams"],"h":"Convert grams of Mg to moles, apply the mole ratio from the equation, then convert product moles to grams.","e":"48 g Mg = 2 mol; the 2:2 mole ratio gives 2 mol MgO × 40 g/mol = 80 g."},{"p":"A radioactive isotope has a half-life of 5.0 years. What fraction of an original sample remains unchanged after 15 years?","a":"1/8","w":["1/16","1/6","1/3"],"h":"First determine how many half-life periods fit into the total elapsed time.","e":"15 years is 3 half-lives, so the fraction remaining = (1/2)^3 = 1/8."},{"p":"What volume of 0.50 M NaOH is required to exactly neutralize 25.0 milliliters of 1.0 M HCl?","a":"50. mL","w":["12.5 mL","25. mL","100. mL"],"h":"At the neutralization point the moles of acid equal the moles of base (MaVa = MbVb).","e":"Using MaVa = MbVb: (1.0)(25.0) = (0.50)(V), so V = 50. mL."},{"p":"What is the molarity of a solution that contains 0.50 mole of solute dissolved in enough water to make 250. milliliters of solution?","a":"2.0 M","w":["0.50 M","0.125 M","1.0 M"],"h":"Molarity is moles of solute per liter of solution—convert milliliters to liters before dividing.","e":"M = mol/L = 0.50 mol / 0.250 L = 2.0 M."},{"p":"How many joules of heat are absorbed when 50.0 grams of water is heated from 20.0°C to 30.0°C? (specific heat of water = 4.18 J/g·K)","a":"2090 J","w":["1050 J","4180 J","6270 J"],"h":"Apply q = mCΔT, where ΔT is the difference between the final and initial temperatures.","e":"q = mCΔT = (50.0)(4.18)(10.0) = 2090 J."},{"p":"In the balanced reaction 2 Al + 3 Cl2 -> 2 AlCl3, what is the total number of moles of electrons transferred when 2 moles of aluminum react?","a":"6 moles","w":["2 moles","3 moles","8 moles"],"h":"Find the change in oxidation number for one aluminum atom, then account for all the atoms reacting.","e":"Each Al is oxidized from 0 to +3, losing 3 electrons; 2 Al × 3 e- = 6 moles of electrons transferred."},{"p":"Normal butane and 2-methylpropane both have the molecular formula C4H10 but different structural arrangements. These two compounds are best classified as","a":"isomers","w":["isotopes","allotropes","polymers"],"h":"Focus on the term for compounds that share a molecular formula but differ in structure.","e":"Isomers are compounds with the same molecular formula but different structural formulas."},{"p":"When an atom of uranium-238 (atomic number 92) undergoes alpha decay, what is the atomic number of the resulting nucleus?","a":"90","w":["92","91","94"],"h":"An alpha particle carries away two protons and two neutrons from the nucleus.","e":"Alpha decay emits a helium nucleus (2 protons, 2 neutrons), so the atomic number decreases by 2 (92 → 90)."},{"p":"A sample of gas occupies 22.4 liters at 273 K and 1.0 atmosphere. If the temperature is increased to 546 K at constant pressure, what volume will the gas occupy?","a":"44.8 L","w":["11.2 L","22.4 L","273 L"],"h":"At constant pressure, volume and Kelvin temperature are directly proportional.","e":"By Charles's law (V1/T1 = V2/T2), doubling the Kelvin temperature doubles the volume to 44.8 L."},{"p":"Which molecule contains polar covalent bonds but is itself nonpolar because of its symmetrical shape?","a":"CO2","w":["H2O","HCl","NH3"],"h":"Ask whether the individual bond dipoles cancel out given the overall geometry of the molecule.","e":"CO2 is linear and symmetrical, so its two polar bond dipoles cancel, making the whole molecule nonpolar."},{"p":"An atom of sodium has 11 electrons. Which electron configuration represents this atom in an excited state?","a":"2-7-2","w":["2-8-1","2-8-3","2-8"],"h":"The ground state fills the lowest energy levels first; an excited state has an electron promoted higher while keeping the same total number of electrons.","e":"2-8-1 is the ground state of sodium; 2-7-2 has the same 11 electrons but one promoted to a higher level, so it is an excited state."},{"p":"Adding a catalyst to a chemical reaction increases the reaction rate because the catalyst","a":"provides a reaction pathway with a lower activation energy","w":["increases the activation energy of the reaction","raises the temperature of the reactants","increases the concentration of the reactants"],"h":"Think about how a catalyst affects the energy barrier reactant particles must overcome.","e":"A catalyst speeds a reaction by providing an alternative pathway with a lower activation energy, without being consumed."},{"p":"Given the exothermic equilibrium 2 SO2(g) + O2(g) <-> 2 SO3(g) + heat, how does increasing the temperature affect the system?","a":"the equilibrium shifts to the left, decreasing the concentration of SO3","w":["the equilibrium shifts to the right, increasing the concentration of SO3","the equilibrium shifts to the right, decreasing the concentration of SO2","the equilibrium remains unchanged, since temperature does not affect equilibrium"],"h":"Treat the released heat as a product and apply Le Chatelier's principle to the added stress.","e":"For an exothermic reaction, added heat behaves as a product, so raising the temperature shifts the equilibrium toward the reactants (left)."},{"p":"Energy is emitted in the form of light when an electron in an excited atom","a":"falls from a higher energy level to a lower energy level","w":["jumps from a lower energy level to a higher energy level","moves within the same energy level","is removed completely from the atom"],"h":"Emission of light corresponds to the electron losing, not gaining, energy.","e":"When an electron drops from a higher to a lower energy level, the energy difference is released as a photon of light, producing bright-line spectra."},{"p":"How many joules of heat are required to melt 25.0 grams of ice at its melting point? (heat of fusion of water = 334 J/g)","a":"8350 J","w":["13.4 J","334 J","104,500 J"],"h":"Use q = mHf; remember that the temperature stays constant during a phase change.","e":"q = mHf = (25.0 g)(334 J/g) = 8350 J, since melting occurs at constant temperature."},{"p":"A student views the light emitted by several vaporized elements through a spectroscope and notices that each element produces its own unique pattern of colored lines. Which statement best explains why each element produces a characteristic bright-line spectrum?","a":"Electrons emit photons of specific energies as they fall from higher to lower energy levels.","w":["Protons in the nucleus release light of specific wavelengths as they rearrange.","Electrons absorb fixed amounts of energy as they move to higher energy levels.","Neutrons convert into protons, emitting light of characteristic colors."],"h":"Think about what happens to an electron's energy when it returns from an excited state toward the ground state.","e":"Each element's electrons occupy unique energy levels, so photons emitted during electron transitions have specific energies (wavelengths), producing a characteristic bright-line emission spectrum."},{"p":"A compound is found to contain 40.0% carbon, 6.7% hydrogen, and 53.3% oxygen by mass. What is its empirical formula? (C = 12, H = 1, O = 16)","a":"CH2O","w":["C2H4O2","CH4O","CHO2"],"h":"Divide each element's percent by its atomic mass to get moles, then reduce to the smallest whole-number ratio.","e":"Moles: C = 40.0/12 = 3.33, H = 6.7/1 = 6.7, O = 53.3/16 = 3.33, giving a 1:2:1 ratio and the empirical formula CH2O."},{"p":"At STP, what volume is occupied by 0.50 mole of oxygen gas, O2? (molar volume of a gas at STP = 22.4 L/mol)","a":"11.2 L","w":["22.4 L","44.8 L","5.60 L"],"h":"At STP one mole of any ideal gas occupies the same volume; multiply moles by that molar volume.","e":"Volume = moles x molar volume = 0.50 mol x 22.4 L/mol = 11.2 L; by Avogadro's hypothesis the identity of the gas does not matter at STP."},{"p":"In the reaction 2 H2 + O2 -> 2 H2O, a mixture contains 4.0 moles of H2 and 4.0 moles of O2. Which statement correctly identifies the limiting reactant?","a":"H2 is limiting because 4.0 mol H2 requires only 2.0 mol O2.","w":["O2 is limiting because 4.0 mol O2 requires 8.0 mol H2.","Neither is limiting because equal moles of each are present.","O2 is limiting because it has the smaller molar mass."],"h":"Use the mole ratio in the balanced equation to see how much O2 the available H2 actually needs.","e":"By the 2:1 mole ratio, 4.0 mol H2 needs only 2.0 mol O2; since 4.0 mol O2 is available, O2 is in excess and H2 is the limiting reactant."},{"p":"For the equilibrium CO(g) + 2 H2(g) <-> CH3OH(g), how is the system affected when additional H2 gas is added at constant temperature?","a":"The equilibrium shifts toward the products, producing more CH3OH.","w":["The equilibrium shifts toward the reactants, producing more CO.","The equilibrium is unaffected because H2 is a gas.","The rate of the reverse reaction increases while the forward rate decreases."],"h":"Le Chatelier's principle predicts a shift that relieves the stress of an increased reactant concentration.","e":"Adding a reactant raises its concentration, so by Le Chatelier's principle the equilibrium shifts toward the products to consume the added H2."},{"p":"In the reaction HNO3 + H2O -> H3O+ + NO3-, which species is the conjugate base of HNO3?","a":"NO3-","w":["H3O+","H2O","OH-"],"h":"A conjugate base is what remains after an acid donates (loses) a hydrogen ion.","e":"According to the Bronsted-Lowry model, HNO3 donates a proton to become NO3-, so NO3- is its conjugate base."},{"p":"What volume of 0.25 M H2SO4 is required to completely neutralize 40.0 milliliters of 0.50 M KOH? (H2SO4 + 2 KOH -> K2SO4 + 2 H2O)","a":"40.0 mL","w":["80.0 mL","20.0 mL","10.0 mL"],"h":"Find moles of KOH, then apply the 1:2 acid-to-base mole ratio before solving for volume.","e":"Moles KOH = 0.0400 L x 0.50 M = 0.020 mol; the 1:2 ratio needs 0.010 mol H2SO4, so volume = 0.010 mol / 0.25 M = 0.040 L = 40.0 mL."},{"p":"In the reaction 2 Na + Cl2 -> 2 NaCl, which substance acts as the oxidizing agent?","a":"Cl2","w":["Na","NaCl","Na+"],"h":"The oxidizing agent is the species that is reduced (gains electrons) during the reaction.","e":"Chlorine gains electrons as its oxidation number goes from 0 to -1; because it is reduced, Cl2 is the oxidizing agent."},{"p":"To which class of organic compounds does the compound with the condensed structural formula CH3COOCH3 belong?","a":"Ester","w":["Organic acid","Ether","Ketone"],"h":"Identify the characteristic functional group; look for the -COO- arrangement linking two carbon groups.","e":"The -COO- functional group joining two hydrocarbon groups identifies the compound as an ester (methyl ethanoate)."},{"p":"The reaction C2H4 + Br2 -> C2H4Br2 is best classified as which type of organic reaction?","a":"Addition","w":["Substitution","Esterification","Polymerization"],"h":"Consider whether the unsaturated reactant gains atoms across a double bond or instead exchanges an atom.","e":"Because ethene is unsaturated, the bromine atoms add across the carbon-carbon double bond, making this an addition reaction."},{"p":"Sodium-24 (atomic number 11) undergoes beta decay. What is the resulting nucleus?","a":"Magnesium-24","w":["Neon-24","Sodium-23","Magnesium-23"],"h":"In beta decay a neutron becomes a proton; track how the atomic number and mass number each change.","e":"Beta decay increases the atomic number by 1 while the mass number stays the same, converting sodium-24 (Z=11) into magnesium-24 (Z=12)."},{"p":"An archaeologist tests a wooden tool and finds it contains 25% of the carbon-14 it had when the tree was alive. If the half-life of carbon-14 is 5730 years, approximately how old is the tool?","a":"11,460 years","w":["5730 years","17,190 years","22,920 years"],"h":"Determine how many half-lives are needed to reduce a sample to 25% of its original amount.","e":"25% remaining corresponds to two half-lives (100% -> 50% -> 25%), so the age is 2 x 5730 = 11,460 years."},{"p":"A sample of gas occupies 4.0 liters at a pressure of 2.0 atmospheres. If the gas is compressed to 1.0 liter at constant temperature, what is the new pressure?","a":"8.0 atm","w":["0.50 atm","4.0 atm","16 atm"],"h":"At constant temperature, pressure and volume are inversely related (P1V1 = P2V2).","e":"By Boyle's law, P2 = (2.0 atm x 4.0 L) / 1.0 L = 8.0 atm; decreasing the volume increases the pressure proportionally."},{"p":"Metals such as copper are excellent conductors of electricity. This property is best explained by the presence of","a":"mobile valence electrons that are free to move throughout the metal.","w":["shared pairs of electrons localized between adjacent atoms.","positive and negative ions that migrate through the solid.","electrons transferred completely from one atom to another."],"h":"Consider the 'sea of electrons' model used to describe bonding in metals.","e":"Metallic bonding features a sea of delocalized (mobile) valence electrons that move freely, allowing metals to conduct electricity."},{"p":"Which of the following bonds is the most polar?","a":"H-F","w":["H-Cl","H-Br","C-H"],"h":"Bond polarity increases as the difference in electronegativity between the two bonded atoms increases.","e":"Fluorine is the most electronegative element, so the H-F bond has the greatest electronegativity difference and is the most polar."},{"p":"If 50.0 milliliters of 6.0 M hydrochloric acid is diluted with water to a final volume of 300. milliliters, what is the molarity of the diluted solution?","a":"1.0 M","w":["0.50 M","2.0 M","36 M"],"h":"The moles of solute stay constant during dilution; use M1V1 = M2V2.","e":"Using M1V1 = M2V2: M2 = (6.0 M x 50.0 mL) / 300. mL = 1.0 M; dilution lowers concentration as the volume increases."},{"p":"How many joules of heat are required to completely vaporize 10.0 grams of water at its boiling point? (heat of vaporization of water = 2260 J/g)","a":"22,600 J","w":["2260 J","3340 J","226,000 J"],"h":"During a phase change use q = mass x heat of vaporization; the temperature does not change.","e":"q = m x Hv = 10.0 g x 2260 J/g = 22,600 J; energy is absorbed to overcome intermolecular attractions during boiling."},{"p":"A reusable hand warmer contains a clear solution of sodium acetate that suddenly forms solid crystals and releases heat when a metal disk is clicked. Before it is triggered, the solution holds more dissolved solute than it could normally hold at that temperature. This type of solution is described as","a":"supersaturated","w":["saturated","unsaturated","dilute"],"h":"Compare the amount of dissolved solute to the maximum that can normally dissolve at that temperature (see a solubility curve).","e":"A solution holding more dissolved solute than the maximum it can normally contain at a given temperature is supersaturated and unstable, crystallizing when disturbed."}],"ap-calc-ab":[{"p":"Evaluate the limit: lim(x→3) (x² − 9)/(x − 3).","a":"6","w":["0","3","The limit does not exist"],"h":"The expression is 0/0 at x = 3, so try factoring the numerator before substituting.","e":"Factoring gives (x−3)(x+3)/(x−3) = x+3, and substituting x = 3 yields 6; this is removing a removable discontinuity by algebraic simplification."},{"p":"For what value of k is the function f(x) = { x², x ≤ 2 ; kx, x > 2 } continuous at x = 2?","a":"2","w":["4","1","8"],"h":"For continuity at x = 2 the two pieces must produce the same output there.","e":"Continuity requires the left value x² = 4 to equal the right value kx = 2k at x = 2, so 2k = 4 gives k = 2."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = 3x⁴ − 2x + 5.","a":"12x³ − 2","w":["12x³ − 2x","4x³ − 2","12x³ + 5"],"h":"Apply the power rule term by term; the derivative of a constant is 0.","e":"By the power rule d/dx(xⁿ) = n·xⁿ⁻¹, giving 12x³ for the first term, −2 for the linear term, and 0 for the constant."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = x² sin x.","a":"2x sin x + x² cos x","w":["2x cos x","2x cos x + x² sin x","2x sin x − x² cos x"],"h":"This is a product of two functions, so use the product rule rather than differentiating each factor separately.","e":"The product rule (uv)' = u'v + uv' gives (2x)(sin x) + (x²)(cos x)."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = sin(3x).","a":"3 cos(3x)","w":["cos(3x)","3 sin(3x)","3 cos(x)"],"h":"The argument 3x is an inside function, so account for its derivative.","e":"By the chain rule, d/dx[sin(u)] = cos(u)·u', and with u = 3x the factor u' = 3 produces 3 cos(3x)."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = e^(2x).","a":"2e^(2x)","w":["e^(2x)","2e^(x)","2x·e^(2x−1)"],"h":"The exponent 2x is a composite; multiply by the derivative of the exponent.","e":"By the chain rule, d/dx[e^u] = e^u·u', and with u = 2x the derivative of the exponent is 2, giving 2e^(2x)."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit: lim(x→∞) (3x² + 2)/(x² − 1).","a":"3","w":["2","0","The limit does not exist"],"h":"Compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator, or divide every term by the highest power of x.","e":"When numerator and denominator have equal degree, the limit at infinity equals the ratio of leading coefficients, 3/1 = 3."},{"p":"Find the equation of the line tangent to y = x² at the point (2, 4).","a":"y = 4x − 4","w":["y = 4x + 4","y = 2x − 4","y = 4x"],"h":"The slope of the tangent line is the value of the derivative at x = 2; then use point-slope form.","e":"Since y' = 2x, the slope at x = 2 is 4, and point-slope form through (2, 4) gives y − 4 = 4(x − 2), i.e., y = 4x − 4."},{"p":"Compute d/dx [ ∫₁ˣ (t² + 1) dt ].","a":"x² + 1","w":["2x","(x³/3) + x","3x²"],"h":"Apply the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (Part 1) rather than integrating first.","e":"By the FTC Part 1, differentiating an accumulation function ∫₁ˣ g(t) dt returns the integrand evaluated at x, giving x² + 1."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀² 2x dx.","a":"4","w":["8","2","x² + C"],"h":"Find an antiderivative, then evaluate it at the upper limit minus the lower limit.","e":"An antiderivative of 2x is x², so by the FTC Part 2 the value is (2)² − (0)² = 4."},{"p":"Find the general antiderivative ∫ x² dx.","a":"(x³/3) + C","w":["x³ + C","2x + C","3x³ + C"],"h":"Reverse the power rule: raise the exponent by one and divide by the new exponent.","e":"By the reverse power rule ∫xⁿ dx = xⁿ⁺¹/(n+1) + C, so ∫x² dx = x³/3 + C."},{"p":"The function f(x) = x² satisfies the hypotheses of the Mean Value Theorem on [0, 4]. Find the value c guaranteed by the theorem.","a":"c = 2","w":["c = 4","c = 1","c = 8"],"h":"Set the derivative at c equal to the average rate of change over the interval.","e":"The MVT requires f'(c) = (f(4) − f(0))/(4 − 0) = 16/4 = 4; since f'(c) = 2c, solving 2c = 4 gives c = 2."},{"p":"On what interval(s) is f(x) = x³ − 3x increasing?","a":"(−∞, −1) ∪ (1, ∞)","w":["(−1, 1)","(−∞, 0) ∪ (0, ∞)","(1, ∞) only"],"h":"A function increases where its first derivative is positive; find where f'(x) = 0 first.","e":"Since f'(x) = 3x² − 3 = 3(x−1)(x+1), the derivative is positive when x < −1 or x > 1, so f increases on (−∞, −1) ∪ (1, ∞)."},{"p":"Find the x-coordinate of the point of inflection of f(x) = x³ − 3x².","a":"x = 1","w":["x = 0","x = 2","x = −1"],"h":"Inflection points occur where the second derivative changes sign; start by computing f''(x).","e":"Here f''(x) = 6x − 6, which equals 0 at x = 1 and changes sign there, giving a point of inflection."},{"p":"The radius of a circle increases at a rate of dr/dt = 2 units/sec. How fast is the area changing when r = 3? (A = πr²)","a":"12π units²/sec","w":["6π units²/sec","4π units²/sec","36π units²/sec"],"h":"Differentiate the area formula with respect to time and substitute the given values.","e":"Differentiating A = πr² gives dA/dt = 2πr(dr/dt) = 2π(3)(2) = 12π, an application of related rates via the chain rule."},{"p":"A particle moves along a line with position s(t) = t³ − 6t² + 9t. At what times is the particle at rest?","a":"t = 1 and t = 3","w":["t = 0 and t = 3","t = 1 and t = 2","t = 2 and t = 3"],"h":"A particle is at rest when its velocity, the derivative of position, equals zero.","e":"Velocity v(t) = s'(t) = 3t² − 12t + 9 = 3(t−1)(t−3), which is zero at t = 1 and t = 3."},{"p":"Solve the differential equation dy/dx = 2y with initial condition y(0) = 3.","a":"y = 3e^(2x)","w":["y = 3e^(x)","y = e^(2x) + 3","y = 2e^(3x)"],"h":"This is a separable equation whose solutions are exponential; use the initial condition to find the constant.","e":"Separating variables gives y = Ce^(2x), and applying y(0) = 3 yields C = 3, so y = 3e^(2x)."},{"p":"Find the average value of f(x) = x² on the interval [0, 3].","a":"3","w":["9","27","6"],"h":"Use the average value formula: the integral over the interval divided by the interval's length.","e":"The average value is (1/(3−0))∫₀³ x² dx = (1/3)(9) = 3, applying the Mean Value Theorem for integrals."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit: lim(x→0) (√(x+4) − 2)/x.","a":"1/4","w":["0","1/2","The limit does not exist"],"h":"The form is 0/0; multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the numerator.","e":"Rationalizing gives 1/(√(x+4)+2), which evaluates to 1/4 at x = 0 (indeterminate-form limit via conjugate)."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = (x + 1)/(x − 1).","a":"−2/(x − 1)²","w":["2/(x − 1)²","−2/(x − 1)","−1/(x − 1)²"],"h":"Apply the quotient rule: (low·d(high) − high·d(low))/(low)².","e":"By the quotient rule, f'(x) = [(x−1)(1) − (x+1)(1)]/(x−1)² = −2/(x−1)²."},{"p":"Given the curve x² + y² = 25, find dy/dx.","a":"−x/y","w":["x/y","−y/x","−x/(2y)"],"h":"Differentiate both sides with respect to x, treating y as a function of x.","e":"Implicit differentiation gives 2x + 2y·y' = 0, so y' = −x/y."},{"p":"A 10-foot ladder leans against a wall. The base is pulled away from the wall at 2 ft/sec. How fast is the top sliding down when the base is 6 feet from the wall?","a":"−1.5 ft/sec","w":["−2.4 ft/sec","−1.33 ft/sec","−0.75 ft/sec"],"h":"Differentiate x² + y² = 100 with respect to time and solve for dy/dt.","e":"With x = 6, y = 8: 2x(dx/dt) + 2y(dy/dt) = 0 gives dy/dt = −(6·2)/8 = −1.5 ft/sec (related rates)."},{"p":"Evaluate ∫ 2x(x² + 1)³ dx.","a":"(x² + 1)⁴/4 + C","w":["(x² + 1)⁴ + C","(x² + 1)⁴/8 + C","3(x² + 1)² + C"],"h":"Use u-substitution with u = x² + 1.","e":"With u = x² + 1, du = 2x dx, so ∫u³ du = u⁴/4 + C = (x²+1)⁴/4 + C (substitution)."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₁⁴ (1/√x) dx.","a":"2","w":["4","1","3"],"h":"Rewrite 1/√x as x^(−1/2); its antiderivative is 2x^(1/2).","e":"By the FTC, [2√x] from 1 to 4 = 4 − 2 = 2."},{"p":"Find the area of the region enclosed by y = x and y = x² between x = 0 and x = 1.","a":"1/6","w":["1/2","1/3","5/6"],"h":"Integrate (top curve − bottom curve); check which curve is larger on (0, 1).","e":"On (0,1), x ≥ x², so area = ∫₀¹ (x − x²) dx = 1/2 − 1/3 = 1/6."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit: lim(x→0) sin(5x)/(2x).","a":"5/2","w":["5","1","0"],"h":"Use the standard limit lim(θ→0) sin θ/θ = 1 after matching coefficients.","e":"sin(5x)/(2x) = (5/2)·sin(5x)/(5x) → (5/2)·1 = 5/2."},{"p":"The region under y = √x from x = 0 to x = 4 is revolved about the x-axis. Find the volume of the resulting solid.","a":"8π","w":["16π","4π","64π/3"],"h":"Use the disk method: V = π∫ [f(x)]² dx.","e":"V = π∫₀⁴ (√x)² dx = π∫₀⁴ x dx = π·8 = 8π (disk method)."},{"p":"A rectangle has a perimeter of 40. What is the maximum possible area?","a":"100","w":["400","80","200"],"h":"Use the perimeter constraint to write area in one variable, then maximize.","e":"With 2x + 2y = 40, A = x(20 − x), maximized at x = 10, giving area 100 (optimization; a square is optimal)."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = ln(x² + 1).","a":"2x/(x² + 1)","w":["1/(x² + 1)","2x","2/(x² + 1)"],"h":"Use the chain rule: the derivative of ln(u) is u'/u.","e":"f'(x) = (1/(x²+1))·(2x) = 2x/(x²+1) (chain rule)."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit: lim(x→∞) (2x + 1)/(x² + 3).","a":"0","w":["2","1/3","The limit is infinite"],"h":"Compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator.","e":"The denominator's degree exceeds the numerator's, so the rational function tends to 0 (end behavior of rational functions)."},{"p":"A particle moves along a line with velocity v(t) = t − 2 (m/sec) for 0 ≤ t ≤ 3. Find the total distance traveled.","a":"2.5 m","w":["1.5 m","3.5 m","4.5 m"],"h":"Total distance integrates the absolute value of velocity; locate where v changes sign.","e":"v = 0 at t = 2, so distance = ∫₀²(2 − t) dt + ∫₂³(t − 2) dt = 2 + 0.5 = 2.5 m (distance vs. displacement)."},{"p":"Solve the differential equation dy/dx = 6x² with initial condition y(0) = 1.","a":"y = 2x³ + 1","w":["y = 2x³","y = x³ + 1","y = 12x + 1"],"h":"Antidifferentiate the right side, then apply the initial condition to determine C.","e":"∫6x² dx = 2x³ + C; using y(0) = 1 gives C = 1, so y = 2x³ + 1."},{"p":"Estimate ∫₀⁴ x² dx using a right-endpoint Riemann sum with two subintervals of equal width.","a":"40","w":["8","24","32"],"h":"With Δx = 2, evaluate x² at the right edge of each subinterval and multiply by the width.","e":"Right endpoints x = 2 and x = 4 give 2(4) + 2(16) = 40 (right Riemann sum; it overestimates here)."},{"p":"Use the second-derivative test to find the local maximum value of f(x) = x³ − 12x.","a":"16","w":["−16","8","−8"],"h":"Find the critical points, then use the sign of f'' to identify which is a maximum.","e":"f'(x) = 3x² − 12 = 0 at x = ±2; f''(x) = 6x < 0 at x = −2, so f(−2) = 16 is the local maximum."},{"p":"Use a tangent-line (linear) approximation at x = 4 to estimate √(4.1).","a":"2.025","w":["2.05","2.01","2.25"],"h":"Build the local linearization of f(x) = √x at x = 4 using f'(4).","e":"f'(x) = 1/(2√x) = 1/4 at x = 4, so L(4.1) = 2 + 0.25(0.1) = 2.025 (linear approximation)."},{"p":"The function f(x) = x³ + x − 1 is continuous. By the Intermediate Value Theorem, which interval must contain a root of f?","a":"(0, 1)","w":["(1, 2)","(−1, 0)","(2, 3)"],"h":"The IVT guarantees a root where a continuous function changes sign.","e":"f(0) = −1 < 0 and f(1) = 1 > 0, so by the Intermediate Value Theorem a root lies in (0, 1)."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit: lim(x→0) (1 − cos x)/x².","a":"1/2","w":["0","1","The limit does not exist"],"h":"Multiply numerator and denominator by (1 + cos x) to reintroduce a familiar trigonometric limit.","e":"Using (1 − cos x)(1 + cos x) = sin²x, the expression becomes sin²x /(x²(1 + cos x)) → 1²·(1/2) = 1/2. This is a standard indeterminate-form (0/0) trigonometric limit."},{"p":"Let f(x) = { x² + 1, x ≤ 1 ; ax + b, x > 1 }. For what value of a is f differentiable at x = 1?","a":"a = 2","w":["a = 1","a = 3","a = 0"],"h":"Differentiability at a point requires the one-sided derivatives to agree there.","e":"Differentiability at x = 1 forces the left-hand derivative 2x|₍ₓ₌₁₎ = 2 to equal the right-hand derivative a, so a = 2."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = eˣ / x².","a":"eˣ(x − 2)/x³","w":["eˣ(2 − x)/x³","eˣ/(2x)","eˣ(x − 2)/x⁴"],"h":"Apply the quotient rule, treating eˣ and x² as the two factors.","e":"Quotient rule gives (eˣ·x² − eˣ·2x)/x⁴ = eˣ(x − 2)/x³."},{"p":"The curve x³ + y³ = 6xy (the folium of Descartes) defines y implicitly. Find dy/dx.","a":"(2y − x²)/(y² − 2x)","w":["(x² − 2y)/(y² − 2x)","(2y − x²)/(2x − y²)","(6y − x²)/(y² − 6x)"],"h":"Differentiate both sides implicitly and use the product rule on the 6xy term.","e":"Implicit differentiation yields 3x² + 3y²y′ = 6y + 6xy′; solving for y′ gives (2y − x²)/(y² − 2x)."},{"p":"Water is poured into an inverted conical tank whose top radius is 5 ft and height is 10 ft, at a constant rate of 8 ft³/min. How fast is the water level rising when the depth is 6 ft?","a":"8/(9π) ft/min","w":["8/(36π) ft/min","2/(9π) ft/min","8/(3π) ft/min"],"h":"Use similar triangles to write the radius in terms of the depth before differentiating the volume.","e":"With r = h/2, V = πh³/12, so dV/dt = (πh²/4)(dh/dt); at h = 6, 8 = 9π(dh/dt), giving dh/dt = 8/(9π) ft/min."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = arctan(x²).","a":"2x/(1 + x⁴)","w":["1/(1 + x⁴)","2x/(1 + x²)","2x/(1 − x⁴)"],"h":"Recall that d/dx[arctan u] = u′/(1 + u²) and apply the chain rule.","e":"With u = x², d/dx[arctan u] = u′/(1 + u²) = 2x/(1 + x⁴)."},{"p":"Find the derivative of f(x) = xˣ for x > 0.","a":"xˣ(1 + ln x)","w":["x·xˣ⁻¹","xˣ·ln x","xˣ/x"],"h":"Take the natural logarithm of both sides first, then differentiate implicitly.","e":"Logarithmic differentiation: ln y = x ln x, so y′/y = 1 + ln x, giving y′ = xˣ(1 + ln x). The power rule does not apply because the exponent is variable."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀³ |x − 1| dx.","a":"5/2","w":["3/2","2","9/2"],"h":"Split the integral at the value of x where the expression inside the absolute value changes sign.","e":"Splitting at x = 1: ∫₀¹(1 − x)dx + ∫₁³(x − 1)dx = 1/2 + 2 = 5/2."},{"p":"Evaluate ∫ x/√(x² + 1) dx.","a":"√(x² + 1) + C","w":["(1/2)√(x² + 1) + C","2√(x² + 1) + C","ln√(x² + 1) + C"],"h":"Use the substitution u = x² + 1.","e":"With u = x² + 1, du = 2x dx, the integral becomes ∫(1/2)u^(−1/2) du = u^(1/2) + C = √(x² + 1) + C."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₁ᵉ (ln x)/x dx.","a":"1/2","w":["1","e − 1","2"],"h":"Let u = ln x and note how du relates to dx/x.","e":"With u = ln x, du = dx/x, the integral becomes ∫₀¹ u du = 1/2."},{"p":"The region enclosed by y = x and y = x² between x = 0 and x = 1 is revolved about the x-axis. Find the volume of the resulting solid.","a":"2π/15","w":["π/6","π/15","8π/15"],"h":"Use the washer method; the line is the outer radius and the parabola is the inner radius.","e":"V = π∫₀¹(x² − (x²)²)dx = π∫₀¹(x² − x⁴)dx = π(1/3 − 1/5) = 2π/15."},{"p":"A solid has as its base the region bounded by y = √x, the x-axis, and x = 4. Cross sections perpendicular to the x-axis are squares. Find the volume of the solid.","a":"8","w":["16","4","32/3"],"h":"The side length of each square equals the height of the base region at that x; integrate the square's area.","e":"Each cross-sectional area is (√x)² = x, so V = ∫₀⁴ x dx = 8."},{"p":"A bacteria culture grows exponentially and doubles every 3 hours. If it starts with 100 cells, how many cells are present after 9 hours?","a":"800","w":["600","900","2700"],"h":"Count how many complete doubling periods occur in the elapsed time.","e":"9 hours equals 3 doubling periods, so the population is 100·2³ = 800; exponential growth multiplies by 2 each period."},{"p":"A particle moving along a line has acceleration a(t) = 6t and velocity v(0) = −4. Find the velocity v(2).","a":"8","w":["12","4","20"],"h":"Antidifferentiate acceleration to get velocity, then use the initial condition to determine the constant.","e":"v(t) = 3t² + C; v(0) = −4 gives C = −4, so v(t) = 3t² − 4 and v(2) = 12 − 4 = 8."},{"p":"Solve the differential equation dy/dx = xy with initial condition y(0) = 1.","a":"y = e^(x²/2)","w":["y = e^(x²)","y = x²/2 + 1","y = e^(x² + 1)"],"h":"Separate the variables so that all y-terms are on one side and all x-terms on the other.","e":"Separating gives dy/y = x dx, so ln|y| = x²/2 + C; y(0) = 1 forces C = 0, yielding y = e^(x²/2)."},{"p":"A car's speed is recorded at equally spaced times. The table gives t (sec) and v (ft/sec): (0,10), (2,20), (4,25), (6,30). Use the trapezoidal rule to estimate the distance traveled over [0, 6].","a":"130 ft","w":["120 ft","150 ft","260 ft"],"h":"The trapezoidal rule weights the interior readings twice and the endpoints once, scaled by half the width.","e":"Trapezoidal estimate = (2/2)[10 + 2(20) + 2(25) + 30] = 130 ft, approximating ∫₀⁶ v dt."},{"p":"Water enters a tank at a rate of 4t gallons/hour and leaves at a rate of 3 gallons/hour, for 0 ≤ t ≤ 4. What is the net change in the amount of water over these 4 hours?","a":"20 gallons","w":["32 gallons","12 gallons","44 gallons"],"h":"Net change is the definite integral of the difference between the inflow and outflow rates.","e":"Net change = ∫₀⁴(4t − 3)dt = [2t² − 3t]₀⁴ = 32 − 12 = 20 gallons, by the net-change (accumulation) theorem."},{"p":"The function f(x) = (x² − 4)/(x − 2) is undefined at x = 2. What value should be assigned to f(2) so that the extended function is continuous there?","a":"4","w":["0","2","No value makes it continuous"],"h":"Simplify the rational expression, then evaluate the limit as x → 2.","e":"For x ≠ 2, f(x) = x + 2, so lim(x→2) f(x) = 4; defining f(2) = 4 removes this removable discontinuity."}],"regents-living":[{"p":"Which cell organelle is the primary site of aerobic respiration, where energy stored in glucose is released and used to produce ATP?","a":"Mitochondrion","w":["Ribosome","Vacuole","Cell wall"],"h":"Think about which structure is often called the \"powerhouse\" of the cell.","e":"Mitochondria carry out aerobic cellular respiration, transferring chemical energy from glucose into ATP that the cell uses for its activities."},{"p":"Ribosomes are the cell structures directly responsible for which life function?","a":"Synthesis of proteins","w":["Storage of hereditary information","Digestion of large food molecules","Regulation of materials entering the cell"],"h":"Consider which molecules are assembled from amino acids following instructions in mRNA.","e":"Ribosomes are the site of protein synthesis, linking amino acids into polypeptide chains according to the sequence carried by messenger RNA."},{"p":"The maintenance of a stable internal environment within an organism, despite changes in the external environment, is best described as","a":"homeostasis","w":["mutation","evolution","differentiation"],"h":"This term refers to a state of balance, sometimes called dynamic equilibrium.","e":"Homeostasis is the maintenance of a stable internal environment (dynamic equilibrium) through feedback mechanisms that respond to internal and external changes."},{"p":"In a molecule of DNA, adenine (A) always pairs with which nitrogenous base?","a":"Thymine (T)","w":["Guanine (G)","Cytosine (C)","Uracil (U)"],"h":"Recall the base-pairing rule and that this base is found in DNA but not RNA.","e":"According to the base-pairing rules of DNA, adenine bonds with thymine and guanine bonds with cytosine; uracil replaces thymine only in RNA."},{"p":"A change in the sequence of DNA bases in a gene is known as a","a":"mutation","w":["fertilization","replication","dominant trait"],"h":"This is an alteration in the genetic code that may be passed to offspring if it occurs in sex cells.","e":"A mutation is a change in the base sequence of DNA; it is the ultimate source of new genetic variation and may be inherited if it occurs in gametes."},{"p":"According to the theory of natural selection, which individuals in a population are most likely to pass their genes to the next generation?","a":"Those with traits best suited to the environment","w":["Those that are the largest in body size","Those that produce the fewest offspring","Those that acquire new traits during their lifetime"],"h":"Consider which organisms are most likely to survive and reproduce in a given environment.","e":"Natural selection favors individuals whose inherited variations make them better adapted to survive and reproduce, increasing the frequency of those traits over generations."},{"p":"In most ecosystems, green plants and algae are classified as producers because they","a":"make their own food through photosynthesis","w":["consume other organisms for energy","break down dead organisms for nutrients","obtain energy by eating producers"],"h":"Focus on the word \"autotroph\" and how these organisms obtain energy.","e":"Producers (autotrophs) use light energy to synthesize organic food molecules through photosynthesis, forming the base of nearly all food chains."},{"p":"In an energy pyramid, why is only a small percentage of energy available to organisms at each higher feeding level?","a":"Much of the energy is lost as heat during life processes at each level","w":["Energy is destroyed as it moves up the pyramid","Producers store all the energy and release none","Organisms at higher levels do not need much energy"],"h":"Consider what happens to energy during cellular respiration and other activities.","e":"At each trophic level, much energy is used for life processes and lost to the environment as heat, so only about 10% is stored and passed to the next level."},{"p":"Which type of blood cell is primarily responsible for defending the body against disease-causing pathogens?","a":"White blood cell","w":["Red blood cell","Platelet","Nerve cell"],"h":"Think about which cells are part of the immune response rather than oxygen transport.","e":"White blood cells are key components of the immune system, engulfing pathogens and producing antibodies to defend the body against infection."},{"p":"Human sex cells (gametes) are produced by the process of meiosis, which results in cells that contain","a":"half the number of chromosomes of a body cell","w":["twice the number of chromosomes of a body cell","the same number of chromosomes as a body cell","no chromosomes at all"],"h":"Consider what must happen to chromosome number so it stays constant after fertilization.","e":"Meiosis produces gametes with half (haploid) the chromosome number, so that fertilization restores the normal diploid number in the offspring."},{"p":"In a controlled experiment testing how fertilizer affects plant growth, all groups receive the same amount of water and sunlight. These identical conditions are best described as the","a":"constants (controlled variables)","w":["independent variable","dependent variable","hypothesis"],"h":"These are the factors deliberately kept the same so the results are valid.","e":"Constants (controlled variables) are the conditions kept the same across all groups so that any difference in results can be attributed to the independent variable being tested."},{"p":"The movement of molecules from a region of higher concentration to a region of lower concentration across a cell membrane, without the use of energy, is called","a":"diffusion","w":["active transport","protein synthesis","mitosis"],"h":"This passive process follows the concentration gradient.","e":"Diffusion is the passive movement of molecules down their concentration gradient, requiring no energy input by the cell."},{"p":"Which set correctly identifies the raw materials used by a plant during photosynthesis?","a":"Carbon dioxide and water","w":["Oxygen and glucose","Glucose and water","Carbon dioxide and oxygen"],"h":"Recall the inputs of the equation, not the products.","e":"During photosynthesis, plants use carbon dioxide and water, along with light energy, to produce glucose and release oxygen."},{"p":"Enzymes function as biological catalysts in living organisms because they","a":"speed up the rate of chemical reactions","w":["provide energy for chemical reactions","are used up completely during reactions","raise the temperature of the cell"],"h":"Think about how catalysts affect reaction rate without being consumed.","e":"Enzymes are protein catalysts that lower activation energy and speed up chemical reactions without being permanently changed or used up."},{"p":"In a food web, organisms such as bacteria and fungi that break down dead organisms and return nutrients to the environment are called","a":"decomposers","w":["producers","herbivores","predators"],"h":"These organisms recycle materials rather than making or hunting food.","e":"Decomposers break down dead organic matter, recycling nutrients back into the ecosystem so they can be reused by producers."},{"p":"When blood glucose levels rise after a meal, the pancreas releases insulin, which lowers glucose levels back toward normal. This is an example of","a":"a feedback mechanism maintaining homeostasis","w":["a genetic mutation altering the pancreas","natural selection acting on blood cells","the loss of dynamic equilibrium"],"h":"Consider how the body detects a change and responds to reverse it.","e":"This is negative feedback: a change (rising glucose) triggers a response (insulin release) that returns the internal environment to balance, maintaining homeostasis."},{"p":"The genetic information that determines an organism's inherited traits is stored in molecules of","a":"DNA","w":["ATP","glucose","water"],"h":"This molecule is found in the nucleus and is made of nucleotide subunits.","e":"DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) carries the genetic code in its sequence of bases, providing the instructions for building proteins and determining inherited traits."},{"p":"Which structure controls the movement of materials into and out of a cell, helping to maintain homeostasis?","a":"Cell (plasma) membrane","w":["Nucleus","Ribosome","Chromosome"],"h":"Think about the selectively permeable boundary of the cell.","e":"The cell membrane is selectively permeable, regulating which substances enter and leave the cell and thereby helping maintain internal balance."},{"p":"A certain plant species has 24 chromosomes in each of its body (somatic) cells. How many chromosomes will normally be present in each gamete produced by this plant?","a":"12","w":["24","48","6"],"h":"Think about how meiosis changes chromosome number from a body cell to a sex cell.","e":"Meiosis is a reduction division that produces haploid gametes with half the diploid chromosome number, so 24 halves to 12."},{"p":"A father who has type AB blood and a mother who has type O blood have several children. Based on the inheritance of ABO blood type, which statement about their children's possible blood types is correct?","a":"Only type A and type B are possible","w":["Only type AB and type O are possible","Type A, B, AB, and O are all possible","Only type AB is possible"],"h":"Write out the alleles: the AB parent contributes I^A or I^B, and the O parent contributes only i.","e":"This is codominance with multiple alleles; crossing I^A I^B with ii yields I^A i (type A) or I^B i (type B) only."},{"p":"In pea plants, tall (T) is completely dominant over short (t). Two heterozygous tall plants (Tt) are crossed. What percentage of their offspring is expected to be short?","a":"25%","w":["50%","75%","0%"],"h":"Set up a Punnett square for Tt x Tt and count how many boxes show the recessive genotype.","e":"A monohybrid cross of two heterozygotes gives a 3:1 phenotypic ratio, so 1 of 4 (25%) is homozygous recessive (short)."},{"p":"When a red-flowered snapdragon (RR) is crossed with a white-flowered snapdragon (WW), all of the offspring have pink flowers. This blending of the two parental phenotypes in the offspring best illustrates","a":"incomplete dominance","w":["codominance","complete dominance","multiple alleles"],"h":"Notice that the offspring show an intermediate color rather than one parent's color or both together.","e":"In incomplete dominance the heterozygote displays a blended, intermediate phenotype rather than either allele fully masking the other."},{"p":"During transcription, a segment of a DNA template strand has the base sequence T-A-C. What is the corresponding base sequence of the mRNA strand produced from it?","a":"A-U-G","w":["A-T-G","U-A-G","T-A-C"],"h":"Apply base-pairing rules for RNA, remembering which base RNA uses in place of thymine.","e":"In transcription, RNA pairs A-U and G-C; DNA T-A-C therefore produces mRNA A-U-G, with uracil replacing thymine."},{"p":"A population of bacteria is exposed to an antibiotic. Most die, but a few survive, reproduce, and give rise to a population that is now resistant to the drug. Which statement best explains this increase in resistance?","a":"Antibiotic-resistant variants already present in the population survived and reproduced","w":["The antibiotic caused each bacterium to purposely mutate for resistance","Individual bacteria became stronger during their own lifetimes and passed that on","The bacteria chose to develop resistance in response to the threat"],"h":"Consider whether the resistance arose because of the antibiotic or already existed as variation before exposure.","e":"This is natural selection acting on pre-existing genetic variation; the antibiotic selects for resistant individuals rather than creating the trait."},{"p":"The forelimbs of humans, whales, and bats contain the same basic arrangement of bones even though they are used for grasping, swimming, and flying. These homologous structures provide evidence that these organisms","a":"share a common ancestor","w":["evolved directly from one another","live in the same type of environment","have identical DNA sequences"],"h":"Focus on why a shared underlying bone pattern would exist despite very different uses.","e":"Homologous structures reflect descent with modification from a common ancestor, a key line of evidence for evolution."},{"p":"In an energy pyramid, the producer level contains about 10,000 units of stored energy. Assuming roughly 10% of energy is passed to each successive level, approximately how much energy is available to the secondary consumers (the third level of the pyramid)?","a":"100 units","w":["1,000 units","10 units","5,000 units"],"h":"Apply the roughly 10% rule twice as you move up two levels from the producers.","e":"About 10% of energy transfers per trophic level, so 10,000 to 1,000 (primary consumers) to 100 (secondary consumers)."},{"p":"Which statement best describes the relationship between photosynthesis and cellular respiration?","a":"The products of photosynthesis are used as reactants in cellular respiration","w":["Both processes release oxygen as a waste product","Both processes occur only in the cells of green plants","Cellular respiration produces glucose and oxygen for the cell"],"h":"Compare the inputs and outputs of each process and see how they connect.","e":"Photosynthesis produces glucose and oxygen, which are the reactants of aerobic cellular respiration, linking the two in a cycle of matter and energy."},{"p":"A vaccine helps protect a person against a specific disease. Which explanation best describes how most vaccines work?","a":"They stimulate the immune system to make antibodies and memory cells against the pathogen","w":["They introduce antibiotics that directly kill invading viruses","They replace white blood cells that were destroyed by the pathogen","They supply the body with extra red blood cells to fight infection"],"h":"Think about what the immune system 'remembers' after a vaccine so it can respond faster next time.","e":"Vaccines trigger a primary immune response, producing antibodies and memory cells that allow a rapid response upon later exposure to the real pathogen."},{"p":"Compared with the endocrine system, the nervous system generally responds to a stimulus","a":"more rapidly, by transmitting electrical impulses along neurons","w":["more slowly, by releasing hormones into the blood","at the same speed, by releasing hormones into the blood","more rapidly, by releasing hormones into the blood"],"h":"Recall which system uses chemical messengers in the bloodstream and which uses cell-to-cell signals.","e":"The nervous system uses fast electrical impulses along neurons, while the endocrine system uses slower chemical signaling by hormones in the blood."},{"p":"The enzyme amylase, found in saliva, begins the chemical digestion of which nutrient in the mouth?","a":"Starch, breaking it into simpler sugars","w":["Proteins, breaking them into amino acids","Fats, breaking them into fatty acids","Sugars, joining them into starch"],"h":"Match the enzyme's name to the type of large molecule it acts on.","e":"Amylase is a carbohydrate-digesting enzyme that hydrolyzes starch into smaller sugars, illustrating enzyme substrate specificity."},{"p":"Nearly all body cells of a person contain the same genes, yet muscle cells and nerve cells look and function very differently. Which statement best explains this difference?","a":"Different genes are expressed (turned on) in different types of cells","w":["Each type of cell contains a completely different set of genes","Muscle cells permanently lost the genes used by nerve cells","The DNA sequence physically changes as cells specialize"],"h":"The cells have identical instructions, so consider which instructions are actually being used.","e":"Cell differentiation results from differential gene expression: the same genome is present, but different genes are activated in different cell types."},{"p":"Before a cell divides by mitosis, its DNA must first be","a":"replicated, so that each new cell receives a complete copy","w":["cut in half, so each new cell receives half of the DNA","mutated, so that the new cells will show variation","converted into proteins for the new cells to use"],"h":"Both daughter cells of mitosis are genetically identical to the original, so think about what must happen to the DNA beforehand.","e":"DNA replication during interphase ensures each daughter cell of mitosis receives a full, identical set of genetic information."},{"p":"After a forest fire clears an area, grasses and small plants grow first, later replaced by shrubs and eventually trees over many years. This gradual, somewhat predictable change in the community over time is called","a":"ecological succession","w":["natural selection","biological evolution","carrying capacity"],"h":"The question is about how the whole community of species changes over time, not how one species' genes change.","e":"Ecological succession is the orderly, gradual replacement of one community by another over time following a disturbance."},{"p":"A deer population in a forest grows and then levels off, staying near the largest number the forest's resources can support. This maximum sustainable population size is called the","a":"carrying capacity","w":["biotic potential","limiting factor","population density"],"h":"Focus on the maximum number the environment can support over the long term, not what slows the growth.","e":"Carrying capacity is the maximum population size an environment can sustain given its available resources."},{"p":"A student designs an experiment to measure how the amount of light affects the rate of photosynthesis in a water plant. In this experiment, the rate of photosynthesis is the","a":"dependent variable","w":["independent variable","controlled variable","hypothesis"],"h":"Identify which factor is being measured as a response and which is being deliberately changed by the student.","e":"The dependent (responding) variable is what is measured, while the independent variable (light amount) is deliberately changed."},{"p":"Over many generations, farmers have repeatedly chosen and bred only the cows that produce the most milk. This human-directed process of selecting organisms with desired traits to reproduce is called","a":"selective breeding","w":["genetic engineering","natural selection","cloning"],"h":"Consider that humans, not the environment, are doing the choosing, and that no genes are directly altered in a lab.","e":"Selective breeding (artificial selection) is the human-directed choice of parents with desirable traits to increase those traits in offspring."},{"p":"A nerve cell maintains a higher concentration of potassium ions (K+) inside the cell and a higher concentration of sodium ions (Na+) outside the cell. Moving these ions against their concentration gradients requires the cell to use energy. This process is best described as","a":"active transport","w":["simple diffusion","osmosis","facilitated diffusion"],"h":"Notice that the ions are being moved against their concentration gradients, which does not happen spontaneously.","e":"Active transport uses ATP to move molecules against a concentration gradient, from a region of lower concentration to higher concentration, across the cell membrane."},{"p":"Red-green colorblindness is an X-linked recessive trait. A woman who is a carrier (heterozygous) has children with a man who has normal color vision. Approximately what percentage of their sons is expected to be colorblind?","a":"50%","w":["0%","25%","100%"],"h":"A son's single X chromosome always comes from his mother, who carries one normal and one recessive allele.","e":"For an X-linked recessive trait, a carrier mother passes the recessive allele to half of her sons, who are affected because they have no second X chromosome to mask it."},{"p":"During meiosis, a pair of homologous chromosomes sometimes fails to separate properly, resulting in a gamete that has one too many or one too few chromosomes. This failure of chromosomes to separate is called","a":"nondisjunction","w":["crossing-over","segregation","replication"],"h":"The key problem is that chromosomes did not move apart the way they normally should during cell division.","e":"Nondisjunction is the failure of homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids to separate during meiosis, producing gametes with an abnormal chromosome number."},{"p":"A new river cuts through a forest, splitting a single population of squirrels into two groups that can no longer interbreed. Over many generations the groups accumulate different traits and eventually can no longer produce fertile offspring together. The initial separation by the river is an example of","a":"geographic isolation","w":["artificial selection","genetic engineering","direct competition"],"h":"Think about what physically prevented the two groups from mating in the first place.","e":"Geographic isolation is a physical barrier that separates populations and prevents gene flow, often leading to speciation over time."},{"p":"Scientists compared the amino acid sequence of the protein cytochrome c in four animal species. Species that had the fewest differences in their cytochrome c sequences were interpreted as being","a":"the most closely related evolutionarily","w":["the most distantly related evolutionarily","unable to share a common ancestor","members of the same exact species"],"h":"Molecular similarities reflect how recently two species shared a common ancestor.","e":"Fewer differences in protein or DNA sequences indicate a more recent common ancestor, providing molecular evidence of close evolutionary relationships."},{"p":"A clownfish lives among the stinging tentacles of a sea anemone, gaining protection from predators. In return, the clownfish drives away animals that would eat the anemone and provides it with nutrients. Because both organisms benefit, this relationship is an example of","a":"mutualism","w":["parasitism","commensalism","predation"],"h":"Consider which organism, if any, is harmed in this partnership.","e":"Mutualism is a symbiotic relationship in which both interacting species benefit from the association."},{"p":"A person who received a vaccine against chickenpox later catches the flu. Which statement best explains why the chickenpox vaccine did not protect the person from the flu?","a":"Antibodies produced against one antigen usually recognize only that specific antigen","w":["Vaccines weaken the immune system and make people more likely to get sick","The flu is caused by bacteria, which vaccines are unable to affect","Antibodies stop working just a few days after a vaccine is given"],"h":"Think about how precisely an antibody must fit the pathogen it is made to target.","e":"Antibodies are specific: each type binds to a particular antigen, so immunity to one pathogen does not provide protection against a different pathogen."},{"p":"Early in the development of an embryo, certain unspecialized cells are capable of dividing and developing into many different specialized cell types, such as muscle, nerve, or blood cells. These unspecialized cells are called","a":"stem cells","w":["gametes","zygotes","gland cells"],"h":"The defining feature is that these cells have not yet become one particular kind of cell.","e":"Stem cells are unspecialized cells that can differentiate into a variety of specialized cell types during development."},{"p":"A student concludes that a new fertilizer increases plant growth after testing it on only two plants. Which change would most improve the reliability of the student's conclusion?","a":"Repeating the experiment with a large number of plants","w":["Using a single plant that is much larger","Measuring the plants only once at the very end","Removing the group that received no fertilizer"],"h":"Conclusions are more trustworthy when results can be shown to hold across many trials.","e":"A large sample size and repeated trials reduce the influence of chance and individual variation, making experimental conclusions more reliable."},{"p":"Hydrangea plants of the same variety produce blue flowers when grown in acidic soil and pink flowers when grown in more basic soil. This observation best illustrates that an organism's phenotype can be","a":"influenced by both its genes and its environment","w":["determined only by the genes it inherits","changed permanently in its DNA by the soil","passed to its offspring only through the soil"],"h":"The plants are the same genetic variety, yet they look different depending on where they grow.","e":"Phenotype results from the interaction of genotype and environmental factors, so the same genes can produce different traits under different conditions."},{"p":"Which process, carried out by both plants and animals, returns carbon dioxide to the atmosphere as part of the carbon cycle?","a":"cellular respiration","w":["photosynthesis","transpiration","nitrogen fixation"],"h":"Look for the process that breaks down glucose and releases carbon dioxide as a waste product.","e":"Cellular respiration releases carbon dioxide back into the atmosphere, balancing the carbon removed from the air by photosynthesis in the carbon cycle."},{"p":"On a hot day, a hiker sweats heavily and does not drink enough water. To maintain homeostasis, which response would the hiker's body most likely carry out?","a":"The kidneys reabsorb more water, and a smaller volume of urine is produced","w":["The kidneys reabsorb less water, and a larger volume of urine is produced","The sweat glands release even more sweat to cool the blood further","The intestines absorb less water from the digested food"],"h":"The body is losing water and needs to conserve it to keep internal conditions stable.","e":"When the body is dehydrated, hormonal signals cause the kidneys to reabsorb more water and produce less urine, an example of negative feedback maintaining water balance."},{"p":"During protein synthesis at the ribosome, transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules perform which function?","a":"They bring specific amino acids to the ribosome to be added to the growing protein","w":["They copy the DNA code into a strand of messenger RNA","They unwind the two strands of the DNA double helix","They break finished proteins back down into amino acids"],"h":"Consider what raw materials must be delivered so that a protein chain can be assembled.","e":"During translation, each tRNA carries a specific amino acid and matches its anticodon to an mRNA codon, adding the correct amino acid to the growing polypeptide."},{"p":"Before the Industrial Revolution, most peppered moths in England were light-colored and blended in with light tree bark, while rare dark moths were easily seen by predators. After factories darkened the tree bark with soot, dark moths became far more common than light moths. Which statement best explains this change?","a":"A change in the environment made the dark coloring more advantageous for survival and reproduction","w":["The soot caused the light moths to change their body color to dark","Individual moths chose to become darker in order to avoid being eaten","Dark moths always reproduce faster than light moths regardless of their surroundings"],"h":"Focus on how the change in the trees affected which moths predators could easily see and catch.","e":"This is natural selection: an environmental change shifted the selective pressure, so the previously disadvantageous dark trait improved survival and became more common."},{"p":"Zebra mussels, introduced into the Great Lakes from another continent, reproduce rapidly and consume large amounts of the plankton that native species depend on. Which effect is this invasive species most likely to have on the ecosystem?","a":"A decrease in the populations of native species that compete for the same food","w":["An increase in the overall biodiversity of the ecosystem over time","No change, because native species always outcompete newcomers","An immediate and lasting increase in the number of top predators"],"h":"Consider what happens to native organisms that rely on the same limited resource.","e":"Invasive species often reduce biodiversity by outcompeting native organisms for limited resources such as food and space."},{"p":"The enzyme pepsin digests protein in the stomach and works best at a very low (acidic) pH. If pepsin were placed in a solution with a high (basic) pH, its activity would most likely","a":"decrease, because the enzyme's shape would be altered","w":["increase, because a higher pH always speeds up enzymes","stay the same, because pH has no effect on enzymes","decrease, because the enzyme would be used up as a reactant"],"h":"Enzyme function depends on maintaining a specific three-dimensional shape at its optimal conditions.","e":"Each enzyme has an optimal pH; conditions far from it change the enzyme's shape (denaturation), reducing its ability to bind its substrate and catalyze the reaction."},{"p":"In a cell, many individual amino acid molecules are chemically bonded together to build a large protein, and a molecule of water is released each time a new bond forms. This type of process, which builds large molecules from smaller building blocks, is best described as","a":"synthesis, building a larger molecule from smaller subunits","w":["digestion, breaking a large molecule into subunits","diffusion, moving molecules across a membrane","replication, copying a molecule of DNA"],"h":"Focus on whether small units are being joined together or broken apart.","e":"Joining smaller subunits such as amino acids into a larger molecule is a synthesis reaction; in cells it releases water and requires energy."},{"p":"Two nearby ecosystems are compared: one contains a great variety of species, while the other contains only a few species. If an unexpected disease kills one important species, the ecosystem with greater biodiversity is more likely to","a":"remain stable, because other species can help fill the affected roles","w":["collapse much more quickly than the low-diversity ecosystem","lose all of its remaining species at the same rate","become permanently unable to recover any of its species"],"h":"Think about whether having many different species provides a kind of backup when one is lost.","e":"Greater biodiversity increases ecosystem stability because a variety of species provides resilience, helping the ecosystem withstand disturbances such as disease."}],"ap-stats":[{"p":"A distribution of household incomes for a large city is strongly skewed to the right. How does the mean of this distribution compare to the median?","a":"The mean is greater than the median.","w":["The mean is less than the median.","The mean is equal to the median.","The mean is equal to the mode."],"h":"Think about how a few very large values in the long tail pull a measure of center.","e":"In a right-skewed distribution the high-value tail pulls the (non-resistant) mean above the (resistant) median."},{"p":"On a test with mean 76 and standard deviation 4, a student earns a score of 84. What is the standardized value (z-score) of this score?","a":"2.0","w":["0.5","8.0","-2.0"],"h":"A z-score measures how many standard deviations a value lies from the mean.","e":"The z-score is (x − μ)/σ = (84 − 76)/4 = 2, standardizing a value in standard-deviation units."},{"p":"For a data set, Q1 = 20 and Q3 = 40. Using the 1.5 × IQR rule, a value is considered an outlier if it is:","a":"greater than 70 or less than −10","w":["greater than 60 or less than 0","greater than 50 or less than 10","greater than 90 or less than −30"],"h":"First find the IQR, then extend the fences 1.5 IQRs beyond each quartile.","e":"With IQR = 20, the fences are Q3 + 1.5(20) = 70 and Q1 − 1.5(20) = −10, the standard 1.5 × IQR outlier rule."},{"p":"Which statement correctly describes the correlation coefficient r?","a":"r is always between −1 and 1 and has no units of measurement.","w":["r changes if the units of the variables are changed.","r measures the strength of any association, including curved ones.","r close to 0 proves there is no relationship between the variables."],"h":"Recall what r measures and how it behaves under changes of scale.","e":"The correlation r is a unitless measure of the strength and direction of a linear relationship, always in [−1, 1]."},{"p":"A teacher decides to add 5 points to every student's raw score. What happens to the mean and the standard deviation of the scores?","a":"The mean increases by 5 and the standard deviation is unchanged.","w":["Both the mean and the standard deviation increase by 5.","The mean is unchanged and the standard deviation increases by 5.","Both the mean and the standard deviation are unchanged."],"h":"Consider how adding a constant shifts a distribution versus how it affects spread.","e":"Adding a constant shifts the center (mean) but does not change spread, so the standard deviation is unaffected."},{"p":"A principal divides students by grade level (9, 10, 11, 12) and then randomly selects 15 students from within each grade. This sampling method is best described as a:","a":"Stratified random sample","w":["Cluster sample","Systematic sample","Convenience sample"],"h":"Note that homogeneous groups are formed first and then sampling occurs within every group.","e":"Sampling within predefined groups (strata) that share a characteristic is a stratified random sample."},{"p":"Which type of study design allows a researcher to justify a cause-and-effect conclusion between the explanatory and response variables?","a":"A randomized comparative experiment with treatments assigned by chance","w":["An observational study using a large random sample","A sample survey achieving a very high response rate","A study finding a strong correlation between the variables"],"h":"Establishing causation requires controlling for lurking variables through the design.","e":"Random assignment in an experiment balances confounding variables across groups, allowing cause-and-effect conclusions."},{"p":"In a study, a variable is associated with both the explanatory variable and the response variable, making it impossible to separate their effects. This variable is called a:","a":"Confounding variable","w":["Response variable","Categorical variable","Blocking variable"],"h":"The key issue is that two influences on the response cannot be told apart.","e":"A confounding variable is linked to both the explanatory and response variables, so their effects on the response cannot be distinguished."},{"p":"Events A and B are independent with P(A) = 0.4 and P(B) = 0.5. What is P(A and B)?","a":"0.20","w":["0.90","0.10","0.45"],"h":"For independent events, use the multiplication rule for the joint probability.","e":"For independent events, P(A and B) = P(A)·P(B) = (0.4)(0.5) = 0.20."},{"p":"Events A and B are mutually exclusive with P(A) = 0.30 and P(B) = 0.25. What is P(A or B)?","a":"0.55","w":["0.075","0.475","0.85"],"h":"Mutually exclusive events cannot occur together, which simplifies the addition rule.","e":"For mutually exclusive events P(A and B) = 0, so P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) = 0.55."},{"p":"A binomial random variable X counts the number of successes in n = 20 independent trials, each with success probability p = 0.3. What is the mean (expected value) of X?","a":"6","w":["0.3","14","4.2"],"h":"The mean of a binomial distribution depends only on n and p.","e":"For a binomial distribution, the mean is μ = np = 20(0.3) = 6."},{"p":"A random variable X takes the values 0, 1, and 2 with probabilities 0.5, 0.3, and 0.2, respectively. What is the expected value of X?","a":"0.7","w":["1.0","0.5","1.5"],"h":"Weight each possible value by its probability and add.","e":"The expected value is Σ x·P(x) = 0(0.5) + 1(0.3) + 2(0.2) = 0.7."},{"p":"A population has standard deviation σ = 10. For random samples of size n = 25, what is the standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the sample mean x̄?","a":"2","w":["10","0.4","0.5"],"h":"The variability of a sample mean decreases as the sample size grows.","e":"The standard deviation of x̄ is σ/√n = 10/√25 = 2."},{"p":"A 95% confidence interval for a population mean is computed to be (48, 52). Which is the correct interpretation?","a":"We are 95% confident that the interval from 48 to 52 captures the true population mean.","w":["There is a 95% probability that the true population mean is exactly 50.","About 95% of the sample data values fall between 48 and 52.","We are 95% confident that the sample mean lies between 48 and 52."],"h":"The interval is a statement about the unknown parameter, not the sample or individual data.","e":"A confidence interval provides a plausible range for the population parameter, with confidence referring to the method's long-run capture rate."},{"p":"What does it mean to say that a confidence interval was constructed at the 95% confidence level?","a":"If the sampling were repeated many times, about 95% of the resulting intervals would contain the true parameter.","w":["There is a 95% chance the parameter falls in this particular interval.","About 95% of all possible sample values lie inside this interval.","The interval is correct in 95% of the individual observations sampled."],"h":"Confidence level describes the long-run performance of the method across many samples.","e":"The confidence level is the long-run proportion of intervals, from repeated sampling, that would capture the true parameter."},{"p":"In a significance test, which statement best describes the meaning of the p-value?","a":"The probability of obtaining a result at least as extreme as the one observed, assuming the null hypothesis is true.","w":["The probability that the null hypothesis is true.","The probability that the alternative hypothesis is true.","The probability of making a Type I error in the test."],"h":"A p-value is computed under an assumption about the null hypothesis.","e":"The p-value is the probability, computed assuming H0 is true, of getting a statistic at least as extreme as observed."},{"p":"In hypothesis testing, a Type I error occurs when a researcher:","a":"rejects the null hypothesis when it is actually true.","w":["fails to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually false.","rejects the null hypothesis when it is actually false.","fails to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually true."],"h":"Classify errors by the true state of the null hypothesis and the decision made.","e":"A Type I error is rejecting a true null hypothesis (a false positive), occurring with probability α."},{"p":"A least-squares regression line is given by ŷ = 2 + 3x, where x is hours studied and ŷ is predicted exam points. What does the slope of 3 represent?","a":"For each additional hour studied, the predicted exam score increases by 3 points.","w":["A student who studies 0 hours is predicted to score 3 points.","For each additional hour studied, the exam score is exactly 3 points higher.","The predicted exam score is 3 times the number of hours studied."],"h":"Interpret the slope as a rate of change in the predicted response per unit of x.","e":"The slope of a least-squares line gives the predicted change in y for each one-unit increase in x."},{"p":"In a survey of 500 adults, 270 said they prefer coffee over tea. Of the 200 men surveyed, 150 prefer coffee. If one person is selected at random from those who prefer coffee, what is the probability the person is a man?","a":"150/270 ≈ 0.556","w":["150/200 = 0.750","150/500 = 0.300","270/500 = 0.540"],"h":"A conditional probability restricts the sample space to a given group; identify which group is the condition here.","e":"This is conditional probability P(man | prefers coffee) = P(man and coffee)/P(coffee), so the denominator is the number who prefer coffee (270), not the total or the number of men."},{"p":"Independent random variables X and Y have standard deviations σ_X = 3 and σ_Y = 4. What is the standard deviation of the difference D = X − Y?","a":"5","w":["1","√7 ≈ 2.65","7"],"h":"Variances of independent variables add even when the variables are subtracted; work with variances before returning to standard deviation.","e":"For independent variables, Var(X − Y) = Var(X) + Var(Y) = 9 + 16 = 25, so the standard deviation is √25 = 5; standard deviations themselves never subtract."},{"p":"Scores on an exam are approximately Normal with mean 500 and standard deviation 100. A scholarship is offered to students scoring in the top 10%. Using z ≈ 1.28, what is the approximate minimum score needed to qualify?","a":"628","w":["372","590","500"],"h":"Top 10% means the value has 90% of the distribution below it; convert the appropriate z-score back to the original scale.","e":"Using x = μ + zσ with z ≈ 1.28 gives 500 + 1.28(100) = 628; a negative z would incorrectly place the cutoff in the lower tail."},{"p":"A population proportion is p = 0.4. For simple random samples of size n = 100, what is the standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the sample proportion p̂?","a":"0.049","w":["0.24","0.0024","0.006"],"h":"The formula involves p(1−p) divided by n, all under a square root.","e":"The standard deviation of p̂ is √[p(1−p)/n] = √[(0.4)(0.6)/100] = √0.0024 ≈ 0.049; forgetting the square root gives the variance instead."},{"p":"A population distribution is strongly right-skewed. According to the Central Limit Theorem, the sampling distribution of the sample mean x̄ will be approximately Normal when:","a":"the sample size n is sufficiently large","w":["the sample size n is small","the population standard deviation σ is known","the number of separate samples taken is large"],"h":"The theorem addresses the shape of the distribution of x̄ and hinges on one feature of each individual sample.","e":"The Central Limit Theorem states that the sampling distribution of x̄ becomes approximately Normal as the sample size n grows large, regardless of the population's shape; it is the size of each sample, not the count of samples, that matters."},{"p":"A 95% confidence interval for a population mean has margin of error m. Keeping the confidence level and sample standard deviation the same, by what factor must the sample size be multiplied to reduce the margin of error to m/2?","a":"4","w":["2","8","1/2"],"h":"The margin of error is inversely proportional to the square root of the sample size.","e":"Because the margin of error is proportional to 1/√n, halving it requires quadrupling n (since √4 = 2); the relationship is not linear in n."},{"p":"A least-squares regression line predicts a house's price. For a particular house, the predicted price is $22 (in ten-thousands) while the actual price is $25 (in ten-thousands). What is the residual for this house?","a":"3","w":["−3","22","25"],"h":"A residual measures how far the observed value falls from the line's prediction, keeping track of direction.","e":"Residual = observed − predicted = 25 − 22 = 3; a positive residual means the actual value lies above the regression line."},{"p":"For a linear relationship between two quantitative variables, the correlation is r = −0.7. Which is the correct interpretation of r² = 0.49?","a":"About 49% of the variation in the response variable is explained by the linear model","w":["About 70% of the variation in the response variable is explained by the linear model","About 49% of the data points fall exactly on the regression line","There is about a 49% chance that the association is truly linear"],"h":"The coefficient of determination describes explained variation, not the count of points or a probability.","e":"r² = 0.49 is the coefficient of determination: about 49% of the variability in the response variable is accounted for by the least-squares regression on the explanatory variable."},{"p":"A discrete random variable X takes values 0, 1, and 2 with probabilities 0.2, 0.3, and 0.5, respectively. What is the variance of X?","a":"0.61","w":["0.78","2.30","1.69"],"h":"First find the mean, then use Var(X) = E(X²) − [E(X)]²; the variance is not the same as the standard deviation.","e":"E(X) = 1.3 and E(X²) = 0(0.2) + 1(0.3) + 4(0.5) = 2.3, so Var(X) = 2.3 − 1.3² = 2.3 − 1.69 = 0.61; taking the square root would give the standard deviation instead."},{"p":"A binomial random variable X counts the number of successes in n = 50 independent trials, each with success probability p = 0.2. What is the standard deviation of X?","a":"2.83","w":["10","8","3.16"],"h":"For a binomial variable, the standard deviation uses np(1−p) under a square root, not np.","e":"The standard deviation of a binomial variable is √[np(1−p)] = √[50(0.2)(0.8)] = √8 ≈ 2.83; np = 10 is the mean and np(1−p) = 8 is the variance."},{"p":"In a game, each independent trial results in a success with probability 0.25. What is the probability that the first success occurs on the third trial?","a":"0.141","w":["0.250","0.422","0.016"],"h":"This is a geometric setting: the first two trials must fail before the success on the third.","e":"Using the geometric formula P(X = 3) = (1 − p)²p = (0.75)²(0.25) ≈ 0.141; the first two trials must be failures followed by a success."},{"p":"Each of 5 independent trials results in a success with probability 0.3. What is the probability of at least one success in the 5 trials?","a":"0.832","w":["0.168","1.500","0.002"],"h":"The complement of 'at least one success' is a single, easy-to-compute event.","e":"P(at least one) = 1 − P(no successes) = 1 − (0.7)⁵ ≈ 1 − 0.168 = 0.832; using the complement rule avoids adding many separate cases."},{"p":"In the context of significance testing, the power of a test is best described as the probability of:","a":"rejecting the null hypothesis when it is actually false","w":["rejecting the null hypothesis when it is actually true","failing to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually false","failing to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually true"],"h":"Power measures a test's ability to detect an effect that genuinely exists.","e":"Power is the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis (1 − P(Type II error)); rejecting a true null is a Type I error, and failing to reject a false null is a Type II error."},{"p":"A researcher tests H₀: μ = 50 against Hₐ: μ > 50. A sample of size n = 64 has mean x̄ = 52 and standard deviation s = 8. What is the value of the one-sample t test statistic?","a":"2.0","w":["0.25","16.0","2.83"],"h":"The standard error in the denominator divides s by the square root of the sample size.","e":"t = (x̄ − μ₀)/(s/√n) = (52 − 50)/(8/√64) = 2/1 = 2.0; dividing by s alone (0.25) or by n instead of √n (16) are common errors."},{"p":"Which condition must be satisfied to safely construct a one-sample t confidence interval for a population mean?","a":"The data come from a random sample and the sampling distribution of x̄ is approximately Normal","w":["The population standard deviation σ is known before computing the interval","The sample size is at least 10% of the population size","The sample data are strongly skewed with several clear outliers"],"h":"Think about the randomness of the data and the shape requirement that justifies using a t-model.","e":"A t interval requires a random sample and an approximately Normal sampling distribution of x̄ (from a Normal population or a large n); knowing σ would call for a z procedure instead."},{"p":"In a completely randomized experiment comparing fertilizers, a researcher instead groups plots by soil type before randomly assigning treatments within each group. What is the primary purpose of this blocking?","a":"To reduce variability due to soil type so treatment effects are easier to detect","w":["To guarantee a cause-and-effect conclusion that randomization alone cannot provide","To increase the sample size available for each treatment group","To eliminate the need for random assignment within the experiment"],"h":"Blocking groups similar experimental units together; consider what this does to the variability in the response.","e":"Blocking controls a known source of variability (soil type) by comparing treatments within similar groups, which reduces unexplained variation and makes real treatment differences easier to detect."},{"p":"In a clinical trial, neither the patients nor the medical staff interacting with them know who receives the real drug versus the placebo. What is the main reason for this double-blind design?","a":"To prevent expectations of patients and staff from biasing the response measurements","w":["To ensure that the treatment and control groups are exactly the same size","To remove the need for a control group in the study","To guarantee that the sample is representative of the population"],"h":"Consider how knowledge of who got the real treatment could influence how outcomes are reported or perceived.","e":"A double-blind design prevents the expectations of both subjects and those assessing them from influencing the results, controlling response and assessment bias (including the placebo effect)."},{"p":"Using the same sample data, a statistician computes both a 90% and a 95% confidence interval for a population mean. How do the two intervals compare?","a":"The 95% interval is wider than the 90% interval","w":["The 95% interval is narrower than the 90% interval","The two intervals have exactly the same width","The 95% interval is centered at a higher value than the 90% interval"],"h":"Greater confidence requires capturing the parameter more often; think about what that demands of the interval's width.","e":"Higher confidence requires a larger critical value, so the 95% interval has a larger margin of error and is wider; both intervals share the same center, x̄."},{"p":"A basketball player makes each free throw independently with probability 0.85, and she shoots free throws until she misses one. What is the expected number of free throws she takes up to and including her first miss?","a":"Approximately 6.67 free throws","w":["Approximately 1.18 free throws","Approximately 5.67 free throws","Approximately 0.15 free throws"],"h":"This is a geometric setting; the mean is 1 divided by the probability of the event you are waiting for.","e":"For a geometric random variable the mean is 1/p, where p is the probability of the outcome being waited for; here a miss has probability 0.15, so E(X) = 1/0.15 ≈ 6.67."},{"p":"A machine fills bottles independently, each with volume that is Normally distributed with mean 500 mL and standard deviation 6 mL. A case contains 4 such bottles. What is the standard deviation of the total volume of a case?","a":"12 mL","w":["24 mL","6 mL","3 mL"],"h":"Variances of independent random variables add, but standard deviations do not add directly.","e":"For a sum of independent variables the variances add: Var(total) = 4(6²) = 144, so the standard deviation is √144 = 12 mL."},{"p":"After fitting a least-squares line, a student examines the residual plot and sees a clear U-shaped (curved) pattern in the residuals. What is the best conclusion?","a":"A linear model is not appropriate; the association is likely nonlinear","w":["The two variables have a strong positive linear correlation","The residuals show constant variance, so the linear model fits well","There is at least one influential outlier distorting the fit"],"h":"A residual plot should show random scatter with no leftover pattern when a line is a good model.","e":"A systematic curved pattern in the residuals indicates the form of the model is wrong (a nonlinear relationship), not merely an issue of spread or a single outlier."},{"p":"A regression line relating age (years) to height (cm) was built from data on children aged 5 to 12. Using this line to predict the height of a 40-year-old is unreliable primarily because of:","a":"Extrapolation beyond the range of the observed data","w":["A lurking variable affecting both age and height","Influential outliers in the original data set","A low value of the correlation coefficient"],"h":"Compare the x-value being predicted to the range of x-values used to build the model.","e":"Extrapolation—predicting for x-values outside the observed range—is unreliable because the linear pattern is not guaranteed to continue beyond the data."},{"p":"A researcher measures each of 30 volunteers' blood pressure before and after a meditation program and wants to test whether the program changes blood pressure. Which inference procedure is appropriate?","a":"A paired (matched-pairs) t-test on the differences","w":["A two-sample t-test comparing two independent means","A one-proportion z-test for a single proportion","A chi-square test for independence"],"h":"Ask whether the two measurements on each person are independent of one another.","e":"Because each subject supplies two related measurements, the correct approach is a paired t-test performed on the within-subject differences."},{"p":"From a single random sample of 500 voters, each person is classified by both region (North, South, West) and preferred candidate (A, B, C). To test whether region and candidate preference are associated, which test should be used?","a":"Chi-square test for independence","w":["Chi-square goodness-of-fit test","Chi-square test for homogeneity","Two-sample z-test for proportions"],"h":"Consider whether the data come from one sample classified two ways or from several separate populations.","e":"One random sample cross-classified by two categorical variables calls for a chi-square test for independence (association)."},{"p":"Two independent samples are drawn. Sample 1 has n = 40 and s = 10; Sample 2 has n = 50 and s = 8. What is the standard error of the difference in sample means x̄₁ − x̄₂?","a":"About 1.94","w":["About 3.78","About 18.0","About 0.42"],"h":"The standard error of a difference of independent means combines the two squared standard errors.","e":"SE = √(s₁²/n₁ + s₂²/n₂) = √(100/40 + 64/50) = √3.78 ≈ 1.94, because variances of independent estimators add."},{"p":"Hospital A has a higher overall survival rate than Hospital B, yet Hospital B has a higher survival rate for both mild cases and severe cases considered separately. This reversal when severity is accounted for is an example of:","a":"Simpson's paradox","w":["Sampling variability","A Type II error","Response bias"],"h":"An association seen within every subgroup can reverse when the groups are combined.","e":"Simpson's paradox occurs when a relationship present in each subgroup reverses direction in the aggregated data because of a lurking variable (here, case severity)."},{"p":"A disease affects 1% of a population. A screening test is positive for 99% of people who have the disease and for 5% of people who do not. If a randomly chosen person tests positive, what is the probability they actually have the disease?","a":"About 0.17","w":["About 0.99","About 0.94","About 0.95"],"h":"Use a tree diagram or Bayes' rule; compare the true-positive branch to all positive results.","e":"By Bayes' rule, P(disease | positive) = (0.01·0.99)/(0.01·0.99 + 0.99·0.05) ≈ 0.17; the low prevalence makes most positive results false positives."},{"p":"All else held equal, which change would increase the power of a significance test?","a":"Increasing the sample size","w":["Decreasing the significance level α","Decreasing the true effect size","Reducing the sample size"],"h":"Power rises when it becomes easier to detect a genuine effect.","e":"A larger sample reduces the variability of the estimator, raising the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis (power)."},{"p":"An insurer sells a one-year policy for $250. It pays out $50,000 if the insured event occurs, which happens with probability 0.004. What is the insurer's expected profit per policy?","a":"$50","w":["−$200","$250","$200"],"h":"Expected profit equals the premium collected minus the expected payout.","e":"Expected payout = 50,000 × 0.004 = $200, so expected profit = 250 − 200 = $50, using the definition of expected value of a random variable."},{"p":"An estimator of a population parameter has low bias but high variability. Which description best fits this estimator?","a":"On average it centers on the true value, but individual estimates vary widely","w":["Individual estimates are consistent, but systematically off the true value","It is both systematically off the true value and highly inconsistent","It always produces exactly the true parameter value"],"h":"Bias concerns the center of the sampling distribution; variability concerns its spread.","e":"Low bias means the sampling distribution is centered at the parameter, while high variability means individual estimates are spread widely around that center."},{"p":"A telephone survey is conducted only during weekday business hours, so people who work traditional daytime jobs are far less likely to be reached and included. This is best described as:","a":"Undercoverage","w":["Nonresponse bias","Response bias","Confounding"],"h":"Consider whether some groups are systematically left out of the process that reaches potential respondents.","e":"Undercoverage occurs when part of the population is systematically excluded from being contacted or sampled, distinct from people who are reached but decline to respond."},{"p":"Computer output for a regression of exam score on hours studied gives a 95% confidence interval for the slope of (1.8, 4.6). Which interpretation is correct?","a":"We are 95% confident the true mean increase in exam score per additional hour studied is between 1.8 and 4.6 points","w":["95% of students' scores increase by between 1.8 and 4.6 points","We are 95% confident an individual student's score is between 1.8 and 4.6 points","There is a 95% probability that the true slope equals 3.2"],"h":"The slope represents the change in the mean response for each one-unit increase in the explanatory variable.","e":"A confidence interval for the slope estimates the true rate of change—the mean change in y per one-unit increase in x—with the stated level of confidence."},{"p":"A scatterplot of population size y versus time x shows an exponential growth pattern. To linearize the relationship for least-squares regression, which transformation is most appropriate?","a":"Plot log(y) versus x","w":["Plot y versus log(x)","Plot log(y) versus log(x)","Plot y² versus x"],"h":"For a model of the form y = a·bˣ, take logarithms of the response variable.","e":"An exponential model y = a·bˣ becomes linear when log(y) is plotted against x, since log(y) = log(a) + x·log(b)."},{"p":"In predicting weight (kg) from height, computer output reports s = 4.2 (the standard deviation of the residuals). What does this value represent?","a":"The typical size of a prediction error (residual) when using the line","w":["The typical distance of the x-values from their mean","The average predicted weight across all subjects","The proportion of variation in weight explained by height"],"h":"This quantity summarizes how far observed points tend to fall from the regression line, in the units of y.","e":"The standard deviation of the residuals, s, measures the typical vertical distance of observed responses from the least-squares line."},{"p":"When sampling without replacement, the standard deviation formulas for a sample proportion or sample mean rely on observations being (approximately) independent. This is considered reasonable as long as:","a":"The sample size is no more than 10% of the population size","w":["The sample size is at least 30","Both np and n(1 − p) are at least 10","The population distribution is exactly Normal"],"h":"There is a rule that limits the sample size relative to the size of the population.","e":"The 10% condition states that when n ≤ 0.10N, sampling without replacement keeps the observations close enough to independent for the usual formulas to apply."},{"p":"In a data set, a value reported at the 80th percentile means that:","a":"About 80% of the observations are less than or equal to that value","w":["About 80% of the observations are greater than that value","The value is 80% of the largest observation in the data","About 20% of the observations are equal to that value"],"h":"Percentiles describe cumulative relative position within the distribution.","e":"The pth percentile is a value at or below which about p% of the observations in the distribution fall."}],"regents-ela":[{"p":"Read: \"Coral reefs cover less than one percent of the ocean floor, yet they support roughly a quarter of all marine species. When ocean temperatures rise even slightly, corals expel the algae living in their tissues, losing both their color and their main food source. Scientists warn that without swift reductions in carbon emissions, most reefs could vanish within a century.\"\n\nWhich statement best expresses the central idea of the passage?","a":"Coral reefs are ecologically vital but highly vulnerable to warming oceans.","w":["Coral reefs cover a large portion of the ocean floor and are easy to protect.","Algae are harmful organisms that corals must expel in order to grow.","Rising ocean temperatures ultimately benefit most marine species over time."],"h":"Choose the statement that accounts for the whole passage, not a single detail.","e":"The central idea is the overarching point supported by every detail; here, both the reef's importance and its fragility to warming."},{"p":"Read: \"The senator's remarks were deliberately ambiguous; supporters and critics alike left the hall convinced she had endorsed their side.\"\n\nAs used in the sentence, the word \"ambiguous\" most nearly means","a":"open to more than one interpretation","w":["spoken in a harsh and angry tone","extremely detailed and precise","brief and quickly forgotten"],"h":"Use the clue that both sides believed she agreed with them.","e":"Context clues define a word by its surroundings; the two opposite reactions show \"ambiguous\" means having multiple possible meanings."},{"p":"Read: \"Her voice was a warm blanket, wrapping the frightened children in comfort as the storm raged outside.\"\n\nThe phrase \"Her voice was a warm blanket\" is an example of","a":"metaphor","w":["simile","hyperbole","personification"],"h":"Check whether the comparison uses the words \"like\" or \"as.\"","e":"A metaphor directly states that one thing is another without using \"like\" or \"as.\""},{"p":"Read: \"Before you toss that banana peel in the trash, consider this: food scraps in landfills release methane, a greenhouse gas far more potent than carbon dioxide. Composting at home is simple, and it keeps that waste out of the landfill entirely.\"\n\nWhat is the author's primary purpose?","a":"to persuade readers to compost food waste at home","w":["to explain the chemical structure of methane gas","to describe how landfills are constructed and managed","to entertain readers with a humorous story about gardening"],"h":"Consider what the author wants the reader to do after reading.","e":"Author's purpose is persuasive when the text urges an action; the direct address \"consider this\" signals a call to act."},{"p":"Read: \"Oh, wonderful. Another Monday, another mountain of emails I'll never finish, another meeting that could have been a single sentence. I can hardly contain my joy.\"\n\nWhich word best describes the tone of the passage?","a":"sarcastic","w":["sincerely enthusiastic","mournful and grieving","calm and reassuring"],"h":"Notice the gap between the literal words and the situation being described.","e":"Sarcasm uses ostensibly positive words to convey the opposite, negative attitude."},{"p":"Read: \"Marcus never sought praise. When the team won the championship, he slipped out before the trophy ceremony, and he mailed his prize money to the youth league that had trained him.\"\n\nWhich detail best shows that Marcus is modest and generous?","a":"He left before the ceremony and donated his prize money.","w":["He played on a team that won the championship.","He had once trained with a local youth league.","The team held a trophy ceremony after the victory."],"h":"Look for the action that demonstrates both traits at the same time.","e":"Strong textual evidence directly supports the stated inference; avoiding praise and giving away winnings show modesty and generosity."},{"p":"Read: \"I pressed my back against the cold locker and counted the seconds until the hallway emptied. My hands would not stop shaking. I told myself no one had noticed, but I wasn't sure I believed it.\"\n\nFrom which point of view is this passage told?","a":"first person","w":["third-person omniscient","third-person limited","second person"],"h":"Identify the pronouns the narrator uses to tell the story.","e":"First-person narration uses \"I\" and \"me\" and confines the reader to the narrator's own perspective."},{"p":"Read: \"We shall fight in the fields. We shall fight in the streets. We shall fight in the hills. We shall never surrender.\"\n\nWhich rhetorical device is most prominent in this passage?","a":"anaphora, the repetition of a phrase at the start of clauses","w":["hyperbole, the use of deliberate exaggeration","onomatopoeia, the use of words that imitate sounds","oxymoron, the pairing of contradictory terms"],"h":"Look closely at how each sentence begins.","e":"Anaphora repeats an opening phrase across successive clauses to build emphasis and rhythm."},{"p":"Read: \"Grandmother set only two places at the table now, though her hands still reached for the third plate each evening before she caught herself and put it back.\"\n\nWhat can most reasonably be inferred from this passage?","a":"She is grieving someone who used to eat with her.","w":["She is expecting a guest to arrive soon for dinner.","She has always eaten her evening meals entirely alone.","She dislikes the third plate and refuses to use it."],"h":"Consider why she reaches for a plate she no longer needs.","e":"An inference combines textual clues (the old habit, the self-correction) with reasoning to reach an unstated meaning."},{"p":"Read: \"First, gather your soil and seeds. Next, plant each seed about an inch deep. After a week, seedlings will appear. Finally, transplant the strongest sprouts to the garden bed.\"\n\nHow is this passage organized?","a":"chronological, or sequential, order","w":["comparison and contrast","cause and effect","problem and solution"],"h":"Notice the signal words such as \"first,\" \"next,\" and \"finally.\"","e":"Sequential structure presents steps in time order, marked by transitional signal words."},{"p":"Read: \"Though the small library had no marble columns and its shelves sagged, it was where Amara first learned that a single book could carry her farther than any airplane.\"\n\nWhich statement best expresses the theme of the passage?","a":"Modest places can open the mind to limitless possibilities.","w":["Libraries should be renovated with grander architecture.","Air travel is the fastest way to see the distant world.","Old buildings are usually unsafe and should be avoided."],"h":"Consider the lesson about the library's value beyond its appearance.","e":"Theme is the universal insight a text conveys; here, that humble settings can spark boundless imagination."},{"p":"Read: \"The reporter described the crowd not as a 'gathering' but as a 'mob.'\"\n\nThe word \"mob\" carries a connotation that is","a":"negative, suggesting disorder or menace","w":["neutral, suggesting only a number of people","positive, suggesting friendliness and warmth","technical, suggesting a scientific measurement"],"h":"Think about the feelings the word stirs beyond its dictionary meaning.","e":"Connotation is the emotional association attached to a word; \"mob\" implies unruliness and threat."},{"p":"Read: \"Dad never said 'I love you.' He said 'Drive safe,' 'Did you eat?' and 'Call me when you land.' He said it in a hundred small ways that never used the words.\"\n\nHow is the father best characterized?","a":"caring but reserved in expressing affection","w":["cold and indifferent toward his family","talkative and openly sentimental","forgetful about his child's whereabouts"],"h":"Look at what his repeated questions reveal about his feelings.","e":"Indirect characterization reveals a character through actions and speech rather than through direct statements."},{"p":"Read: \"The rejection letter sat on the desk like a stone she could not lift, heavier each time she passed it.\"\n\nThe simile \"like a stone she could not lift\" mainly emphasizes","a":"the emotional weight and burden of the rejection","w":["the literal heaviness of the folded paper letter","the smooth, polished surface of the wooden desk","the speed with which she read the letter"],"h":"Consider what feeling the comparison to a stone is meant to convey.","e":"A simile compares using \"like\" or \"as\"; its effect here conveys the emotional burden the letter represents."},{"p":"Read: \"The company did not 'fire' workers; its press release announced it would 'right-size its human capital.'\"\n\nThe phrase \"right-size its human capital\" is an example of","a":"euphemism that softens an unpleasant reality","w":["hyperbole that exaggerates for dramatic effect","allusion that references another well-known text","onomatopoeia that imitates an actual sound"],"h":"Consider why the company avoided the plainer, blunter word.","e":"A euphemism substitutes a mild or vague expression for one considered harsh or blunt."},{"p":"Read: \"As a pediatrician with thirty years of experience treating children, I can assure you this vaccine is safe.\"\n\nWhich rhetorical appeal is most prominent in this statement?","a":"ethos, an appeal based on the speaker's credibility","w":["pathos, an appeal to the audience's emotions","logos, an appeal to logic and hard evidence","kairos, an appeal to the timeliness of the moment"],"h":"Consider what the speaker emphasizes about herself before making the claim.","e":"Ethos establishes persuasive trust through the speaker's authority, expertise, or character."},{"p":"Read: \"The fire station burned to the ground while every firefighter was away attending a seminar on fire safety.\"\n\nThis situation is best described as an example of","a":"situational irony","w":["verbal irony","dramatic irony","understatement"],"h":"Consider the gap between what one would expect and what actually happens.","e":"Situational irony occurs when the outcome of a situation sharply contradicts what would be expected."},{"p":"Read: \"Some argue that homework builds discipline. However, research increasingly shows that excessive homework harms sleep and offers little academic benefit for younger students.\"\n\nIn this passage, the counterclaim the author acknowledges is that","a":"homework builds discipline in students","w":["excessive homework harms students' sleep","homework offers little measurable academic benefit","current research contradicts the value of homework"],"h":"Identify the view the author introduces in order to push back against it.","e":"A counterclaim is the opposing position an author acknowledges before refuting it, here signaled by \"Some argue.\""},{"p":"Read: \"The city's new bike-share program was praised as a triumph for the environment. Yet each bicycle must be trucked nightly to recharging depots across town, and the fleet is replaced every eighteen months as the cheap frames rust. What looks green on the surface may leave a deeper footprint than the cars it was meant to replace.\"\n\nWhich statement best expresses the central idea of the passage?","a":"A program marketed as environmentally friendly may carry hidden costs that undermine its stated benefit.","w":["Bike-share programs are more popular with city residents than automobiles are.","Rusting bicycle frames are the single greatest source of urban pollution.","Cities should abandon all efforts to reduce automobile use downtown."],"h":"The central idea must account for the contrast the author sets up between appearance and reality, not just one detail.","e":"Central idea synthesizes the whole passage; here the author's 'green on the surface' contrast frames the hidden costs, so the main point is that appearances can mask a larger footprint."},{"p":"Read: \"After the scandal broke, the mayor's once-loyal aides began to temporize, issuing statements that neither defended nor condemned him while they waited to see which way public opinion would turn.\"\n\nAs used in the sentence, the word \"temporize\" most nearly means","a":"to delay committing in order to gain time","w":["to apologize sincerely for a mistake","to grow furious and lash out","to negotiate a fair compromise"],"h":"Use the surrounding clues about aides who 'neither defended nor condemned' and 'waited to see' before deciding.","e":"Word-in-context meaning is fixed by surrounding evidence; the aides' stalling to await public opinion signals that temporize means to delay commitment to gain time."},{"p":"Read: \"The old bridge groaned under the weight of the morning traffic, and by afternoon it seemed to sigh with relief as the last car rolled off.\"\n\nWhich figurative device is used in this sentence?","a":"Personification","w":["Simile","Hyperbole","Metaphor"],"h":"Notice what human actions the bridge is described as performing.","e":"Personification gives human qualities to a nonhuman thing; the bridge 'groaned' and 'seemed to sigh with relief,' both human actions, rather than being directly compared to something else."},{"p":"Read: \"Elena arrived an hour early to every rehearsal, marked her sheet music in three colors, and stayed after to stack the folding chairs no one else remembered. When the director forgot her name at the concert, she only smiled and kept setting up for the next show.\"\n\nElena is best characterized as","a":"conscientious and unassuming","w":["ambitious and resentful","careless and forgetful","impatient and demanding"],"h":"Base the trait on the pattern of her repeated actions, including how she responds to being overlooked.","e":"Characterization is inferred from consistent behavior; her early arrivals, thorough preparation, and quiet reaction to being forgotten show her as conscientious and unassuming."},{"p":"Read: \"Nadia was sure the letter contained good news. Across the room, her brother clutched the same envelope's twin, certain it spelled disaster. Neither knew that the committee had, in fact, chosen someone else entirely.\"\n\nFrom which point of view is this passage told?","a":"Third-person omniscient","w":["Third-person limited","First-person","Second-person"],"h":"Notice whose thoughts the narrator is able to reveal within the passage.","e":"Third-person omniscient narration accesses multiple characters' inner thoughts and information they don't know; here the narrator reports Nadia's, her brother's, and the committee's knowledge."},{"p":"Read: \"Should we really wait until the river floods the school before we build the levee? Should we wait until the roof caves in before we fix the leak? How many warnings must arrive before we finally act?\"\n\nWhich rhetorical device is most prominent in this passage?","a":"Rhetorical question","w":["Hyperbole","Allusion","Personification"],"h":"Consider the form each sentence takes and whether an answer is actually expected.","e":"A rhetorical question is posed for effect rather than to elicit an answer; the repeated questions here press the audience toward action rather than seeking information."},{"p":"Read: \"The porch light stayed on every night that autumn. Mrs. Alvarez said it was for moths, but she kept it burning long after the cold had killed them all, her eyes drifting to the empty driveway.\"\n\nWhat can most reasonably be inferred from this passage?","a":"Mrs. Alvarez is waiting for someone who has not returned.","w":["Mrs. Alvarez is conducting a scientific study of moths.","Mrs. Alvarez is afraid of the dark and cannot sleep.","Mrs. Alvarez plans to sell her house and move away."],"h":"Combine the detail that the light burns after the moths are gone with where her gaze keeps drifting.","e":"An inference draws a logical conclusion from combined textual clues; the light kept on 'long after' the moths die plus her glances at the empty driveway suggest she is waiting for someone."},{"p":"Read: \"The paperback costs six dollars and slips into a coat pocket, but it yellows and tears within a year. The hardcover costs thirty and weighs down a bag, yet it survives a decade of rereading. Each edition trades durability for convenience in its own way.\"\n\nHow is this passage organized?","a":"Compare and contrast","w":["Chronological order","Problem and solution","Cause and effect"],"h":"Examine how the two editions are set side by side and what the final sentence signals.","e":"Compare-and-contrast structure examines similarities and differences between items; the passage weighs the paperback against the hardcover point by point and names the trade-off."},{"p":"Read: \"The champion runner laughed at the boy's cardboard trophy, made of foil and tape. Years later, when injury ended her career, it was that same boy—now a coach—who reminded her that the joy of running had never depended on medals at all.\"\n\nWhich statement best expresses the theme of the passage?","a":"True worth is found in the love of an activity rather than in its rewards.","w":["Injuries inevitably end the careers of competitive athletes.","Children should not be given trophies made of cheap materials.","Coaching is a more secure profession than professional running."],"h":"Look for the universal lesson the reversal between the two characters teaches.","e":"Theme is a universal message conveyed through the story; the reversal from mocking the trophy to relearning that joy outlasts medals expresses that worth lies in loving the activity itself."},{"p":"Read: \"The developer did not call the neighborhood 'crowded' or 'run-down.' In the brochure it became a 'vibrant, close-knit community brimming with character.'\"\n\nThe phrase \"vibrant, close-knit community brimming with character\" carries a connotation that is","a":"positive, casting the neighborhood in an appealing light","w":["neutral, simply reporting the facts about the area","negative, warning buyers away from the neighborhood","technical, using precise real-estate terminology"],"h":"Compare the emotional coloring of the brochure's wording against the plainer words it replaced.","e":"Connotation is the emotional association a word carries; replacing 'crowded' and 'run-down' with 'vibrant' and 'brimming with character' gives the description a favorable, positive connotation."},{"p":"Read: \"Between 2015 and 2020, the district that added free breakfast programs saw absenteeism fall by 22 percent, while test scores in reading rose across every grade level. The three neighboring districts without such programs recorded no comparable gains.\"\n\nWhich rhetorical appeal is most prominent in this statement?","a":"Logos, an appeal to logic and evidence","w":["Pathos, an appeal to emotion","Ethos, an appeal to the speaker's authority","Kairos, an appeal to timeliness"],"h":"Identify what kind of support—feelings, credentials, or data—the argument relies on.","e":"Logos persuades through logic and factual evidence; the statistics, percentages, and comparison to control districts make this primarily an appeal to reason."},{"p":"Read: \"The audience smiled as the detective assured the widow that her husband's killer would never be found. They had watched, in the opening scene, as the detective himself buried the murder weapon in his own garden.\"\n\nThis situation is best described as an example of","a":"Dramatic irony","w":["Situational irony","Verbal irony","An extended metaphor"],"h":"Consider the gap between what the audience knows and what the widow on stage knows.","e":"Dramatic irony occurs when the audience knows something a character does not; viewers know the detective is the killer while the widow trusts him, creating that gap."},{"p":"Read: \"Fog pressed against the windows of the abandoned depot. Somewhere down the corridor a door creaked, then fell silent. Dust hung in the gray light, and every footstep seemed to echo back a beat too late.\"\n\nWhich word best describes the mood of the passage?","a":"Eerie","w":["Joyful","Peaceful","Triumphant"],"h":"Focus on the feeling the sensory details create in the reader, not the narrator's attitude.","e":"Mood is the atmosphere a text evokes in the reader; the fog, creaking door, and delayed echoes build an unsettling, eerie atmosphere."},{"p":"Read: \"When her grandfather died, Priya inherited his pocket watch. It had stopped ticking years before, yet she wound it every morning and carried it everywhere, its cracked face pressed close to her heart.\"\n\nIn the passage, the broken pocket watch most likely symbolizes","a":"Priya's enduring bond with her grandfather's memory","w":["Priya's need to replace an outdated timepiece","the family's wealth and social standing","the passage of time as measured by the seasons"],"h":"Ask what larger idea the object stands for, given how and why Priya keeps it.","e":"A symbol is a concrete object representing an abstract idea; the watch, kept and wound despite being broken, stands for Priya's lasting connection to her grandfather's memory."},{"p":"Read: \"I've told you a million times to close the door. This backpack weighs a ton, and I'm so hungry I could eat a horse before we even reach the car.\"\n\nWhich figurative device appears throughout this passage?","a":"Hyperbole","w":["Understatement","Oxymoron","Allusion"],"h":"Notice the scale of the claims and whether they are meant to be taken literally.","e":"Hyperbole is deliberate exaggeration for emphasis; 'a million times,' 'weighs a ton,' and 'eat a horse' are all overstatements not meant literally."},{"p":"Read: \"Because the factory dumped its runoff upstream, the fish population collapsed within two seasons. With the fish gone, the herons abandoned their nests, and the tourists who came to watch them stopped booking the lakeside inns.\"\n\nHow is this passage organized?","a":"Cause and effect","w":["Compare and contrast","Chronological sequence of unrelated events","Order of importance"],"h":"Trace how each event triggers the next one in a chain.","e":"Cause-and-effect structure links events by showing how one produces another; the runoff causes the fish collapse, which drives off the herons, which drives away tourists."},{"p":"Read: \"The proposal promised much and delivered little; it demanded everything and returned nothing.\"\n\nWhich rhetorical device is most prominent in this sentence?","a":"Antithesis","w":["Hyperbole","Understatement","Simile"],"h":"Notice how the two halves of each clause set opposing ideas against each other in parallel form.","e":"Antithesis places contrasting ideas (much/little, everything/nothing) in balanced, parallel structure to sharpen the contrast."},{"p":"Read: \"When the surgeon told him the eight-hour operation had removed only part of the tumor, Daniel shrugged and said, 'Well, that's not the worst news I've had this week.'\"\n\nDaniel's reply is an example of","a":"Understatement","w":["Hyperbole","Personification","Allusion"],"h":"Consider whether Daniel's words make the situation sound bigger or smaller than it really is.","e":"Understatement deliberately downplays the seriousness of something, here treating grave medical news as a minor inconvenience."},{"p":"Read: \"When Coach handed the smallest player the final shot, the gym fell silent—everyone waiting to see whether this David could topple the towering champions from across the state.\"\n\nThe reference to \"this David\" is an example of","a":"Allusion","w":["Hyperbole","Metaphor","Personification"],"h":"The word 'David' points the reader toward a well-known story outside this passage.","e":"An allusion is a brief reference to a familiar person, place, or story—here the biblical David and Goliath—to add meaning through association."},{"p":"Read: \"The only constant in the newsroom, the editor liked to say, was change itself.\"\n\nThe editor's statement is best described as a","a":"Paradox","w":["Oxymoron","Hyperbole","Analogy"],"h":"The statement seems to contradict itself at first, yet points to a truth when you think it through.","e":"A paradox is a self-contradictory statement that nonetheless reveals a deeper truth; 'the only constant is change' cannot literally hold yet makes sense on reflection."},{"p":"Read: \"Critics called the band's comeback album a 'deafening silence'—polished in production yet empty of anything new to say.\"\n\nThe phrase \"deafening silence\" is an example of","a":"Oxymoron","w":["Paradox","Hyperbole","Personification"],"h":"Look closely at the two words in the phrase and whether their meanings can normally go together.","e":"An oxymoron pairs two contradictory words ('deafening' and 'silence') for effect; it is a compact contradiction rather than a full statement like a paradox."},{"p":"Read: \"The people needed a leader they could trust. The nation needed a leader they could trust. History, above all, needed a leader they could trust.\"\n\nWhich rhetorical device is most prominent in this passage?","a":"Epistrophe","w":["Anaphora","Alliteration","Assonance"],"h":"Pay attention to where the repeated wording falls within each sentence—beginning or end.","e":"Epistrophe is the repetition of the same words at the END of successive clauses; anaphora, by contrast, repeats words at the beginning."},{"p":"Read: \"You wake before the alarm, certain you have forgotten something. You check your bag twice, then a third time. You tell yourself the interview will go fine, even as your stomach twists.\"\n\nFrom which point of view is this passage told?","a":"Second-person point of view","w":["First-person point of view","Third-person limited point of view","Third-person omniscient point of view"],"h":"Identify the pronoun that the narrator uses to address whoever is experiencing the scene.","e":"Second-person point of view addresses the reader directly with 'you,' placing the reader inside the action."},{"p":"Read: \"The White House released a statement Tuesday denying any knowledge of the leaked documents.\"\n\nThe phrase \"The White House\" is an example of","a":"Metonymy","w":["Synecdoche","Personification","Hyperbole"],"h":"Consider whether the building itself issued the statement, or something closely associated with it.","e":"Metonymy substitutes something closely related for the thing meant; 'the White House' stands in for the presidential administration."},{"p":"Read: \"The rancher counted forty head grazing near the fence and figured he'd need two more hands before the spring roundup.\"\n\nThe words \"head\" and \"hands\" are examples of","a":"Synecdoche","w":["Metonymy","Metaphor","Idiom"],"h":"Think about whether each word names a part of something in order to refer to the whole thing.","e":"Synecdoche uses a part to represent the whole; 'head' stands for whole cattle and 'hands' for whole workers."},{"p":"Read: \"Sometimes I pass the old bakery, boarded up now, and I can almost smell the cinnamon my mother bought there on Sunday mornings. We never knew, back then, how quickly those mornings would run out.\"\n\nWhich word best describes the tone of the passage?","a":"Wistful","w":["Bitter","Indignant","Cheerful"],"h":"Weigh the speaker's mixture of fond memory and quiet loss.","e":"A wistful tone conveys gentle, yearning sadness about something in the past, as the speaker fondly recalls mornings now gone."},{"p":"Read: \"Mara laughed off the fortune-teller's warning about deep water and boarded the ferry in high spirits, joking to the captain that she'd never learned to swim a stroke. On the horizon, dark clouds were just beginning to gather.\"\n\nThe mention of the warning, her inability to swim, and the gathering clouds are examples of","a":"Foreshadowing","w":["Flashback","Symbolism","Verbal irony"],"h":"Consider what these early details hint about events that have not yet happened.","e":"Foreshadowing plants clues early in a text that hint at later developments, building suspense about what is to come."},{"p":"Read: \"The visitors moved slowly past the long rows of white headstones, their voices dropping to whispers. Someone laid a single flower on the nearest grave, and for a long moment no one spoke at all.\"\n\nWhich word best describes the mood of the passage?","a":"Solemn","w":["Festive","Tense","Whimsical"],"h":"Focus on the feeling the setting and the visitors' quiet behavior create in the reader.","e":"Mood is the emotional atmosphere a text evokes; the hushed voices, headstones, and stillness create a solemn, reverent mood."},{"p":"Read: \"Reporters pressed the general for details, but his replies stayed laconic—'Yes,' 'No,' 'We'll see'—and they left with little to print.\"\n\nAs used in the sentence, the word \"laconic\" most nearly means","a":"Using very few words","w":["Rude and dismissive","Cheerful and talkative","Vague and misleading"],"h":"Use the examples of his actual replies as a clue to what the word describes.","e":"In context, 'laconic' means terse or sparing with words, shown by the general's one- and two-word answers."},{"p":"Read: \"The ostensible reason for the meeting was to plan the fundraiser, but everyone knew it was really a chance for the director to lecture the staff.\"\n\nAs used in the sentence, the word \"ostensible\" most nearly means","a":"Stated or apparent, but not necessarily true","w":["Hidden and deliberately concealed","Official and legally binding","Urgent and unavoidable"],"h":"The contrast set up by 'but' signals how the stated reason relates to the real one.","e":"'Ostensible' describes what is outwardly claimed or appears to be the case, often contrasted with the actual reason, as the word 'but' signals here."},{"p":"Read: \"The manager's capricious moods kept the staff on edge; a plan praised on Monday might be scrapped on Tuesday for no reason anyone could name.\"\n\nAs used in the sentence, the word \"capricious\" most nearly means","a":"Given to sudden, unpredictable changes","w":["Cruel and calculating","Calm and steady","Generous and forgiving"],"h":"The example of praising a plan one day and scrapping it the next shows the quality being described.","e":"'Capricious' means impulsive and prone to sudden shifts of mind, illustrated by the manager's abrupt reversals."},{"p":"Read: \"Above all, wear a helmet—nothing matters more for your safety. Next, keep your brakes in good repair. Finally, a bell, though the least essential, still helps warn pedestrians.\"\n\nHow is this passage organized?","a":"Order of importance","w":["Chronological order","Cause and effect","Compare and contrast"],"h":"Ask whether the items are ranked by how much they matter or arranged by when they happen.","e":"Order-of-importance structure ranks points by significance; phrases like 'above all' and 'least essential' rank the tips rather than sequence them in time."},{"p":"Read: \"At the front of the shop stood the register and a rack of postcards. Behind it, shelves of paperbacks stretched to the back wall, where a narrow staircase climbed to the rare-books loft.\"\n\nHow is this passage organized?","a":"Spatial order","w":["Chronological order","Problem and solution","Cause and effect"],"h":"Notice the words that tell you where things are located rather than when things occur.","e":"Spatial organization arranges details by physical location, using position words such as 'front,' 'behind,' and 'back wall' to guide the reader through a space."},{"p":"Read: \"Planting a single tree is often praised as a climate fix, but a young sapling stores little carbon for decades, and many die before maturity. Protecting an existing old-growth forest, which already locks away enormous stores of carbon, does far more for the climate today.\"\n\nWhich statement best expresses the central idea of the passage?","a":"Preserving mature forests helps the climate more immediately than planting new trees.","w":["Planting trees does nothing to help fight climate change.","Young saplings store more carbon than old-growth forests do.","Most newly planted trees die before they ever reach maturity."],"h":"Look for the point the whole passage builds toward, not a single supporting detail or an overstatement.","e":"The central idea is the main point a text develops; here the contrast shows that protecting old-growth forests yields greater immediate climate benefit than planting saplings."}],"ap-physics1":[{"p":"A ball is dropped from rest and falls freely near Earth's surface. Ignoring air resistance, what is its speed after falling for 3.0 s? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"30 m/s","w":["10 m/s","15 m/s","45 m/s"],"h":"For an object starting from rest, speed increases at a steady rate equal to the acceleration each second.","e":"Using v = v0 + at with v0 = 0, v = (10 m/s²)(3.0 s) = 30 m/s. This is uniformly accelerated (free-fall) motion."},{"p":"A cart starts from rest and accelerates uniformly at 2.0 m/s² along a straight track. How far does it travel in the first 4.0 s?","a":"16 m","w":["8.0 m","32 m","4.0 m"],"h":"Distance under constant acceleration from rest depends on the square of the time.","e":"Using x = ½at² with v0 = 0, x = ½(2.0)(4.0)² = 16 m. This is the kinematic equation for constant acceleration."},{"p":"A net force of 12 N acts on an object of mass 4.0 kg. What is the magnitude of the object's acceleration?","a":"3.0 m/s²","w":["48 m/s²","0.33 m/s²","16 m/s²"],"h":"Relate net force, mass, and acceleration using Newton's second law.","e":"By Newton's second law, a = Fnet/m = 12 N / 4.0 kg = 3.0 m/s²."},{"p":"A book rests on a table. Earth pulls down on the book with a gravitational force. According to Newton's third law, which force is the reaction to this pull?","a":"The gravitational force the book exerts on Earth","w":["The normal force the table exerts on the book","The weight of the book acting downward","The force the table exerts on the floor"],"h":"A Newton's third law pair acts between the same two objects, equal in magnitude and opposite in direction, but of the same type.","e":"Third-law pairs act on different bodies and are the same type of force; the reaction to Earth pulling the book gravitationally is the book pulling Earth gravitationally."},{"p":"A 10 kg box is pushed at constant velocity across a level floor. The coefficient of kinetic friction between the box and floor is 0.30. What horizontal force is required? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"30 N","w":["3.0 N","100 N","300 N"],"h":"At constant velocity the net force is zero, so the applied force balances kinetic friction, which depends on the normal force.","e":"On a level surface the normal force equals mg, so friction f = μN = 0.30(10)(10) = 30 N, and the applied force must equal it for constant velocity."},{"p":"A car moves at constant speed around a circular track. In what direction is the car's acceleration at any instant?","a":"Toward the center of the circle","w":["Tangent to the circle, in the direction of motion","Away from the center of the circle","Zero, because the speed is constant"],"h":"Even at constant speed, the velocity vector is changing direction, and acceleration points in the direction of that change.","e":"Uniform circular motion has centripetal acceleration directed toward the center, since the velocity's direction (not magnitude) is changing."},{"p":"Two point masses attract each other gravitationally. If the distance between them is doubled while the masses are unchanged, the gravitational force becomes what fraction of its original value?","a":"1/4 as large","w":["1/2 as large","2 times as large","4 times as large"],"h":"Newton's law of universal gravitation depends on the separation distance in a nonlinear way.","e":"Because F ∝ 1/r², doubling r multiplies the force by 1/2² = 1/4 (inverse-square law)."},{"p":"A single net (total) force does work on a moving object. According to the work-energy theorem, this net work equals the change in the object's:","a":"Kinetic energy","w":["Gravitational potential energy","Momentum","Total mechanical energy"],"h":"Consider which quantity is defined by ½mv² and how force over a distance affects motion.","e":"The work-energy theorem states Wnet = ΔKE; the net work done on an object equals its change in kinetic energy."},{"p":"A pendulum bob is released from rest at a height of 0.80 m above its lowest point. Ignoring friction, what is its speed at the lowest point? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"4.0 m/s","w":["8.0 m/s","16 m/s","2.8 m/s"],"h":"With no friction, the potential energy lost equals the kinetic energy gained.","e":"By conservation of mechanical energy, mgh = ½mv², so v = √(2gh) = √(2·10·0.80) = 4.0 m/s."},{"p":"A motor does 600 J of work in 3.0 s. What is the average power output of the motor?","a":"200 W","w":["1800 W","2.0 W","0.005 W"],"h":"Power measures how quickly work is done or energy is transferred.","e":"Average power P = W/t = 600 J / 3.0 s = 200 W."},{"p":"A constant force of 5.0 N acts on an object for 4.0 s along the direction of motion. What is the magnitude of the impulse delivered to the object?","a":"20 N·s","w":["1.25 N·s","9.0 N·s","0.80 N·s"],"h":"Impulse combines the force with the time interval over which it acts.","e":"Impulse J = FΔt = (5.0 N)(4.0 s) = 20 N·s, which also equals the object's change in momentum."},{"p":"A 2.0 kg cart moving at 3.0 m/s collides with and sticks to a stationary 1.0 kg cart on a frictionless track. What is the speed of the combined carts after the collision?","a":"2.0 m/s","w":["3.0 m/s","1.5 m/s","6.0 m/s"],"h":"In a collision with no external horizontal forces, total momentum before equals total momentum after.","e":"By conservation of momentum, (2.0)(3.0) = (2.0+1.0)v, so v = 6.0/3.0 = 2.0 m/s (perfectly inelastic collision)."},{"p":"A mass oscillates on an ideal spring. If the attached mass is quadrupled while the spring constant stays the same, the period of oscillation becomes:","a":"2 times the original period","w":["4 times the original period","1/2 the original period","Unchanged"],"h":"The period of a mass-spring system depends on the square root of the mass.","e":"Since T = 2π√(m/k), quadrupling m multiplies the period by √4 = 2."},{"p":"For a simple pendulum undergoing small-amplitude oscillations, the period depends on which of the following?","a":"The length of the pendulum and the local value of g","w":["The mass of the bob and the length of the pendulum","The amplitude of the swing and the mass of the bob","The mass of the bob and the local value of g"],"h":"Recall the formula for a simple pendulum's period and which variables appear in it.","e":"Because T = 2π√(L/g), the period depends only on length L and gravitational field strength g, not on mass or (small) amplitude."},{"p":"A force of fixed magnitude is applied at a fixed distance from a pivot. The torque produced is greatest when the angle between the force and the lever arm is:","a":"90°","w":["0°","45°","180°"],"h":"Torque depends on the component of the force perpendicular to the lever arm.","e":"Torque τ = rF sinθ is maximized when sinθ = 1, i.e., when the force is perpendicular (θ = 90°) to the lever arm."},{"p":"A wrench applies a 20 N force perpendicular to its handle at a distance of 0.50 m from the bolt. What is the magnitude of the torque about the bolt?","a":"10 N·m","w":["40 N·m","20 N·m","100 N·m"],"h":"Torque is the product of the force and its perpendicular distance from the pivot.","e":"With the force perpendicular to the lever arm, τ = rF = (0.50 m)(20 N) = 10 N·m."},{"p":"A projectile is launched and follows a parabolic path, ignoring air resistance. At the highest point of its trajectory, its acceleration is:","a":"g, directed downward","w":["Zero, because vertical velocity is zero","g, directed upward","Horizontal, in the direction of motion"],"h":"Consider what force acts on the projectile throughout its entire flight.","e":"Ignoring air resistance, gravity is the only force during flight, so the acceleration is g downward everywhere, including the peak where vertical velocity is momentarily zero."},{"p":"An object moves in a straight line at constant velocity. What can be concluded about the forces acting on it?","a":"The net force on the object is zero","w":["A single constant force acts in the direction of motion","The net force is constant but nonzero","No forces at all can be acting on the object"],"h":"Relate constant velocity (zero acceleration) to Newton's first and second laws.","e":"Constant velocity means zero acceleration, so by Newton's first law the forces are balanced and the net force is zero (though individual forces may be present)."},{"p":"A car traveling at 20 m/s brakes and decelerates uniformly, coming to rest in 5.0 s. How far does the car travel while stopping?","a":"50 m","w":["100 m","25 m","40 m"],"h":"With uniform acceleration, distance equals the average of the initial and final velocities multiplied by the time.","e":"For constant acceleration, displacement = (average velocity) × time = (½)(20 m/s)(5.0 s) = 50 m; using the full 20 m/s instead of the average is the common error."},{"p":"A ball is thrown straight up with an initial speed of 15 m/s. Ignoring air resistance, how long does it take to reach its highest point? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"1.5 s","w":["3.0 s","0.67 s","1.0 s"],"h":"At the highest point the vertical velocity is momentarily zero; use v = v₀ − gt.","e":"Setting v = 0 in v = v₀ − gt gives t = v₀/g = 15/10 = 1.5 s; the 3.0 s value is the full up-and-down flight time, not the time to the top."},{"p":"A block is released from rest on a frictionless incline that makes a 30° angle with the horizontal. What is the magnitude of the block's acceleration down the incline? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"5.0 m/s²","w":["10 m/s²","8.7 m/s²","2.5 m/s²"],"h":"Only the component of gravity directed along the incline surface produces the acceleration.","e":"On a frictionless incline the acceleration is g·sin θ = 10·sin 30° = 5.0 m/s²; using g·cos θ (8.7) confuses the along-incline and perpendicular components."},{"p":"A block slides down a 37° incline at constant velocity. What is the coefficient of kinetic friction between the block and the incline? (sin 37° = 0.60, cos 37° = 0.80.)","a":"0.75","w":["0.60","0.80","1.0"],"h":"Constant velocity means the friction force up the incline exactly balances the gravity component down the incline.","e":"Setting μk·mg·cos θ = mg·sin θ gives μk = tan θ = 0.60/0.80 = 0.75; students often mistakenly report sin θ or cos θ alone."},{"p":"Two masses, 3.0 kg and 2.0 kg, hang from opposite ends of a light string over a frictionless, massless pulley (an Atwood machine). What is the magnitude of the system's acceleration? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"2.0 m/s²","w":["5.0 m/s²","10 m/s²","4.0 m/s²"],"h":"Treat the two masses as one system: the net driving force is the weight difference, and the total inertia is the sum of the masses.","e":"Applying Newton's second law to the system, a = (m₁ − m₂)g/(m₁ + m₂) = (1.0)(10)/(5.0) = 2.0 m/s²."},{"p":"A 60 kg person stands on a scale in an elevator that is accelerating upward at 2.0 m/s². What is the reading of the scale (the normal force it exerts)? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"720 N","w":["600 N","480 N","120 N"],"h":"Apply Newton's second law vertically: the net upward force equals mass times the upward acceleration.","e":"From N − mg = ma, the normal force N = m(g + a) = 60(10 + 2.0) = 720 N; this apparent-weight increase reflects the upward acceleration."},{"p":"A 0.50 kg ball attached to a 2.0 m string is whirled in a horizontal circle at a constant speed of 4.0 m/s. What is the magnitude of the net (centripetal) force on the ball?","a":"4.0 N","w":["8.0 N","2.0 N","1.0 N"],"h":"The centripetal force depends on the mass, the square of the speed, and the radius of the circular path.","e":"The centripetal force is F = mv²/r = (0.50)(4.0)²/(2.0) = 4.0 N; forgetting to square the speed is a frequent mistake."},{"p":"A ball is whirled in a horizontal circle at the end of a string. At one instant the string suddenly breaks. Ignoring gravity's vertical effect, which path does the ball follow immediately afterward?","a":"A straight line tangent to the circle at the break point","w":["A curved path continuing in the same circle","A straight line directed radially outward from the center","A straight line directed radially inward toward the center"],"h":"With no net force, Newton's first law dictates the ball moves with constant velocity in the direction it was traveling.","e":"Once the centripetal force vanishes, the ball obeys Newton's first law and travels in a straight line along its instantaneous velocity, which is tangent to the circle."},{"p":"A spring with spring constant 200 N/m is compressed by 0.10 m from its natural length. How much elastic potential energy is stored in the spring?","a":"1.0 J","w":["2.0 J","10 J","0.50 J"],"h":"The elastic potential energy depends on the spring constant and on the square of the displacement, with a factor of one-half.","e":"Elastic potential energy is U = ½kx² = ½(200)(0.10)² = 1.0 J; omitting the factor of ½ or not squaring x are common errors."},{"p":"A 4.0 kg box slides across a rough horizontal floor with an initial speed of 6.0 m/s and eventually comes to rest due to friction. How much thermal energy is generated by friction?","a":"72 J","w":["144 J","24 J","12 J"],"h":"By energy conservation, the thermal energy produced equals the kinetic energy the box loses.","e":"All the initial kinetic energy converts to thermal energy: ½mv² = ½(4.0)(6.0)² = 72 J, illustrating conservation of energy with dissipation."},{"p":"A 3.0 kg cart and a 1.0 kg cart are initially at rest and in contact on a frictionless track, held together by a compressed spring between them. When released, the 1.0 kg cart moves off at 6.0 m/s. What is the speed of the 3.0 kg cart?","a":"2.0 m/s","w":["6.0 m/s","18 m/s","3.0 m/s"],"h":"The total momentum of the system stays zero because there is no external horizontal force; the two momenta must be equal and opposite.","e":"By conservation of momentum, m₁v₁ = m₂v₂, so (3.0)v = (1.0)(6.0), giving v = 2.0 m/s in the opposite direction."},{"p":"A 0.15 kg ball strikes a wall horizontally at 20 m/s and bounces straight back at 20 m/s. What is the magnitude of the impulse delivered to the ball by the wall?","a":"6.0 kg·m/s","w":["3.0 kg·m/s","0 kg·m/s","60 kg·m/s"],"h":"Impulse equals the change in momentum, and momentum is a vector, so the reversal in direction matters.","e":"Impulse = Δp = m(v_f − v_i) = 0.15(20 − (−20)) = 6.0 kg·m/s; treating the two speeds as canceling (giving 0) ignores that momentum is a vector."},{"p":"Two carts collide and stick together in a perfectly inelastic collision on a frictionless track. Which statement correctly describes the conserved quantities?","a":"Total momentum is conserved but total kinetic energy is not","w":["Both total momentum and total kinetic energy are conserved","Total kinetic energy is conserved but total momentum is not","Neither total momentum nor total kinetic energy is conserved"],"h":"Consider which quantity is always conserved when no external force acts, versus which is lost when objects deform or stick.","e":"In any collision with no external force, momentum is conserved; in an inelastic collision some kinetic energy is converted to other forms, so kinetic energy is not conserved."},{"p":"A mass oscillates on an ideal spring with amplitude A. At what displacement from equilibrium is the kinetic energy equal to the elastic potential energy?","a":"A/√2","w":["A/2","A","A/4"],"h":"Total energy is ½kA²; set the potential energy ½kx² equal to half of the total energy.","e":"Setting ½kx² = ½(½kA²) gives x² = A²/2, so x = A/√2; this follows from conservation of energy in simple harmonic motion."},{"p":"A mass on a spring undergoes simple harmonic motion with amplitude 0.10 m and angular frequency 5.0 rad/s. What is the maximum speed of the mass?","a":"0.50 m/s","w":["2.5 m/s","0.020 m/s","0.050 m/s"],"h":"In SHM the speed is greatest at equilibrium, where it equals the amplitude times the angular frequency.","e":"Maximum speed in SHM is v_max = Aω = (0.10)(5.0) = 0.50 m/s, occurring as the mass passes through equilibrium."},{"p":"A seesaw is balanced on a central pivot. A 40 N child sits 2.0 m to the left of the pivot. At what distance to the right of the pivot must an 80 N child sit so the seesaw is in rotational equilibrium?","a":"1.0 m","w":["2.0 m","4.0 m","0.50 m"],"h":"For rotational equilibrium, the clockwise torque about the pivot must equal the counterclockwise torque.","e":"Setting torques equal, (40 N)(2.0 m) = (80 N)(d), so d = 1.0 m; the heavier child must sit closer to the pivot to balance the torques."},{"p":"A solid sphere and a thin hoop have the same mass and radius. Both are released from rest and roll without slipping down the same incline. Which reaches the bottom first?","a":"The solid sphere","w":["The hoop","They reach the bottom at the same time","It depends on the mass of the objects"],"h":"For a given mass and radius, the object with more of its mass concentrated far from the axis has a larger rotational inertia and accelerates more slowly.","e":"The solid sphere has a smaller moment of inertia (2/5 MR² versus MR² for the hoop), so a greater fraction of its energy becomes translational and it accelerates faster down the incline."},{"p":"A car of mass 1000 kg rounds a curve of radius 80 m on a frictionless roadway that is banked at an angle θ, where tan θ = 0.50. At the design speed the car needs no friction to stay on the road. What is this design speed? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"20 m/s","w":["40 m/s","28 m/s","400 m/s"],"h":"For frictionless banking, the horizontal component of the normal force alone supplies the centripetal force; set up the equations for the vertical and horizontal directions.","e":"On a frictionless banked curve, tan θ = v²/(gr), so v = √(g r tan θ) = √(10·80·0.50) = 20 m/s."},{"p":"A small ball is whirled in a vertical circle of radius 0.90 m at the end of a string. What is the minimum speed the ball can have at the very top of the circle so that the string remains taut? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"3.0 m/s","w":["4.2 m/s","6.0 m/s","9.0 m/s"],"h":"At minimum speed the string tension is zero, so gravity alone must provide exactly the centripetal force at the top.","e":"At the minimum top speed the string tension is zero, so mg = mv²/r, giving v = √(gr) = √(10·0.90) = 3.0 m/s."},{"p":"A satellite is moved from a circular orbit to a new circular orbit whose radius is 4 times larger. By what factor does its orbital period change?","a":"8","w":["4","16","2"],"h":"Kepler's third law relates the square of the period to the cube of the orbital radius.","e":"By Kepler's third law T² ∝ r³, so T ∝ r^(3/2); increasing r by a factor of 4 multiplies T by 4^(3/2) = 8."},{"p":"A spinning ice skater pulls her arms inward, reducing her rotational inertia to half its original value while she spins freely (no external torque). What happens to her rotational kinetic energy?","a":"It doubles","w":["It stays the same","It is halved","It quadruples"],"h":"Angular momentum is conserved because there is no external torque, but the skater's muscles do work as she pulls her arms in.","e":"With L = Iω conserved, halving I doubles ω; since KE = ½Iω² = ½Lω, doubling ω doubles the rotational kinetic energy (the extra energy comes from work done by the skater)."},{"p":"A uniform solid disk of mass 2.0 kg and radius 0.10 m (rotational inertia I = ½MR²) is free to rotate about its central axis. A steady 5.0 N force is applied tangentially at the rim. What is the disk's angular acceleration?","a":"50 rad/s²","w":["25 rad/s²","250 rad/s²","5.0 rad/s²"],"h":"Find the torque from the tangential force and the lever arm, then use the rotational form of Newton's second law.","e":"Torque τ = FR = 5.0·0.10 = 0.50 N·m and I = ½MR² = ½·2.0·(0.10)² = 0.010 kg·m², so α = τ/I = 0.50/0.010 = 50 rad/s²."},{"p":"A 4.0 kg rifle fires a 0.020 kg bullet with a muzzle speed of 300 m/s. Assuming the rifle is free to recoil, what is the magnitude of the rifle's recoil speed?","a":"1.5 m/s","w":["6.0 m/s","3.0 m/s","0.75 m/s"],"h":"The rifle-plus-bullet system starts at rest, so total momentum stays zero as the bullet leaves.","e":"By conservation of momentum, m_bullet·v_bullet = m_rifle·v_rifle, so v_rifle = (0.020·300)/4.0 = 1.5 m/s."},{"p":"A net force acts on a 2.0 kg object that starts from rest on a frictionless surface. The force increases linearly from 0 N to 8.0 N over a 4.0 s interval. Using the impulse-momentum theorem, what is the object's speed at the end of the 4.0 s?","a":"8.0 m/s","w":["16 m/s","4.0 m/s","32 m/s"],"h":"The impulse equals the area under the force-versus-time graph, and impulse equals the change in momentum.","e":"Impulse = area of the triangle = ½·(4.0 s)·(8.0 N) = 16 N·s; since J = Δp = mΔv, v = 16/2.0 = 8.0 m/s."},{"p":"A 1000 kg car drives up a long straight hill at a constant 20 m/s. The road rises 1.0 m of vertical height for every 20 m traveled along the road (so sin θ = 0.050). What is the minimum power the engine must deliver just to overcome gravity? (Use g = 10 m/s²; ignore friction and air resistance.)","a":"10,000 W","w":["200,000 W","5,000 W","500 W"],"h":"The power needed against gravity is the gravitational force component along the road times the speed along the road.","e":"The gravity component along the incline is mg sin θ = 1000·10·0.050 = 500 N, so P = Fv = 500·20 = 10,000 W."},{"p":"A spring with spring constant 800 N/m is compressed 0.10 m and used to launch a 0.50 kg ball horizontally along a frictionless surface. What is the ball's launch speed?","a":"4.0 m/s","w":["8.0 m/s","2.0 m/s","16 m/s"],"h":"All the stored elastic potential energy converts into the ball's kinetic energy.","e":"Setting ½kx² = ½mv² gives v = x√(k/m) = 0.10·√(800/0.50) = 0.10·40 = 4.0 m/s."},{"p":"A 0.50 kg block is attached to an ideal spring of spring constant 200 N/m and oscillates on a frictionless surface. What is the period of its simple harmonic motion?","a":"0.31 s","w":["1.3 s","3.1 s","0.05 s"],"h":"The period of a mass-spring oscillator depends on the mass and the spring constant, not the amplitude.","e":"T = 2π√(m/k) = 2π√(0.50/200) = 2π·0.050 ≈ 0.31 s."},{"p":"A mass on an ideal spring undergoes simple harmonic motion with amplitude A. At what displacement from equilibrium is the mass moving at exactly half of its maximum speed?","a":"About 0.87A","w":["0.50A","0.25A","0.71A"],"h":"Use energy conservation: total energy equals kinetic plus potential, and relate speed to displacement through v = v_max√(1 − (x/A)²).","e":"Since v = v_max√(1 − (x/A)²), setting v = ½v_max gives 1 − (x/A)² = ¼, so x/A = √3/2 ≈ 0.87."},{"p":"Two point masses lie on the x-axis: a 2.0 kg mass at x = 0 and a 6.0 kg mass at x = 4.0 m. Where is the center of mass of this two-particle system?","a":"x = 3.0 m","w":["x = 2.0 m","x = 1.0 m","x = 4.0 m"],"h":"The center of mass is the mass-weighted average position, pulled toward the heavier mass.","e":"x_cm = (Σmᵢxᵢ)/(Σmᵢ) = (2.0·0 + 6.0·4.0)/8.0 = 3.0 m, closer to the larger mass."},{"p":"A hypothetical planet has twice the mass of Earth and twice the radius of Earth. Compared with Earth's surface gravitational field strength, the field strength at this planet's surface is:","a":"one-half as large","w":["the same","twice as large","one-fourth as large"],"h":"Surface field strength scales directly with mass but inversely with the square of the radius.","e":"Since g = GM/R², doubling M and doubling R gives g' = G(2M)/(2R)² = (2/4)·(GM/R²) = ½ g_Earth."},{"p":"A boat's motor drives it directly across a river, pointing the bow perpendicular to the banks and giving it a speed of 3.0 m/s relative to the water. The river current flows at 4.0 m/s parallel to the banks. What is the boat's speed relative to the ground?","a":"5.0 m/s","w":["7.0 m/s","1.0 m/s","3.5 m/s"],"h":"The velocity relative to the water and the current velocity are perpendicular vectors that must be added as vectors.","e":"The boat's ground velocity is the vector sum of two perpendicular velocities: √(3.0² + 4.0²) = 5.0 m/s."},{"p":"A ball is launched horizontally at 15 m/s from the top of a cliff 20 m high. Ignoring air resistance, how far from the base of the cliff does the ball land? (Use g = 10 m/s².)","a":"30 m","w":["15 m","60 m","45 m"],"h":"Horizontal and vertical motions are independent; find the fall time from the vertical drop first.","e":"The fall time is t = √(2h/g) = √(2·20/10) = 2.0 s, so the horizontal range is x = v·t = 15·2.0 = 30 m."},{"p":"A block sits on a plank whose angle of inclination is slowly increased. The block first begins to slide when the plank reaches 30° above the horizontal. What is the coefficient of static friction between the block and the plank?","a":"0.58","w":["0.50","0.87","1.7"],"h":"At the angle of impending motion, the maximum static friction force just balances the gravitational component along the incline.","e":"At the verge of sliding, μ_s = tan θ = tan 30° ≈ 0.58."},{"p":"A uniform hoop rolls without slipping along a level surface. What fraction of the hoop's total kinetic energy is rotational (as opposed to translational)?","a":"1/2","w":["1/3","2/5","2/7"],"h":"For a hoop the rotational inertia is MR², and rolling without slipping links v and ω through v = ωR.","e":"For a hoop, rotational KE = ½Iω² = ½MR²(v/R)² = ½Mv², which equals the translational KE, so rotational energy is exactly half the total."},{"p":"Two blocks sit in contact on a frictionless surface: a 2.0 kg block in front of a 1.0 kg block. A constant 12 N horizontal force is applied to the 2.0 kg block, pushing both blocks so they accelerate together, with the 2.0 kg block shoving the 1.0 kg block ahead of it. What is the magnitude of the contact force the 2.0 kg block exerts on the 1.0 kg block?","a":"4.0 N","w":["12 N","8.0 N","6.0 N"],"h":"First find the common acceleration of the whole system, then isolate the 1.0 kg block to find the only horizontal force acting on it.","e":"The system accelerates at a = F/(m₁+m₂) = 12/3.0 = 4.0 m/s²; isolating the 1.0 kg block, the contact force is the net force on it: 1.0·4.0 = 4.0 N."}],"ap-bio":[{"p":"Which property of water is most directly responsible for its ability to moderate temperature, allowing large bodies of water to resist rapid temperature change?","a":"Its high specific heat, resulting from hydrogen bonds that absorb heat when broken","w":["Its low specific heat, allowing it to release heat rapidly to the surroundings","Its nonpolar covalent bonds, which prevent it from absorbing thermal energy","Its high density as a solid, which insulates the liquid water below"],"h":"Consider what must happen to the many hydrogen bonds between water molecules as temperature rises.","e":"Water's high specific heat arises because much absorbed energy goes into breaking hydrogen bonds rather than increasing molecular motion, a property central to thermal stability in organisms and ecosystems."},{"p":"A student examines four organic molecules and must identify which contains a carboxyl functional group. A carboxyl group is best described as which of the following?","a":"A carbon double-bonded to one oxygen and single-bonded to a hydroxyl (–COOH), acting as a weak acid","w":["A nitrogen atom bonded to two hydrogens (–NH2), acting as a weak base","A single carbon bonded to a hydroxyl group (–OH), making the molecule an alcohol","A carbon double-bonded to an oxygen located within a carbon chain (–C=O–)"],"h":"Focus on the group that donates a proton (H+) in solution and is found on amino acids and fatty acids.","e":"The carboxyl group (–COOH) ionizes to release H+, making it acidic; recognizing functional groups predicts a molecule's chemical behavior."},{"p":"When two monosaccharides are joined to form a disaccharide, which of the following describes what occurs?","a":"A dehydration (condensation) reaction forms a glycosidic bond and releases a water molecule","w":["A hydrolysis reaction breaks a glycosidic bond and consumes a water molecule","A dehydration reaction forms a peptide bond and releases a water molecule","A hydrolysis reaction forms a phosphodiester bond and releases a water molecule"],"h":"Monomers are linked by removing components that together make up water.","e":"Polymers are built by dehydration synthesis, in which a covalent bond forms and water is released; between sugars this covalent bond is specifically a glycosidic linkage."},{"p":"The three-dimensional folding of a single polypeptide into its functional shape, stabilized by interactions among R groups such as hydrogen bonds, disulfide bridges, and hydrophobic interactions, defines which level of protein structure?","a":"Tertiary structure","w":["Primary structure","Secondary structure","Quaternary structure"],"h":"This level describes one whole polypeptide's overall shape, not the coiling of a local region or the assembly of multiple chains.","e":"Tertiary structure is the overall 3-D shape of a single polypeptide determined by R-group interactions; quaternary structure requires two or more polypeptide subunits."},{"p":"Mitochondria and chloroplasts contain their own circular DNA, ribosomes resembling those of prokaryotes, and double membranes. These features are cited as evidence for which idea?","a":"The endosymbiotic theory, in which these organelles descended from engulfed free-living prokaryotes","w":["The fluid mosaic model, which explains the movement of membrane proteins","Spontaneous generation, in which organelles arise anew from cytoplasm","The theory of natural selection acting only on multicellular eukaryotes"],"h":"Think about why these organelles resemble bacteria more than the rest of the eukaryotic cell.","e":"The endosymbiotic theory holds that mitochondria and chloroplasts originated as prokaryotes engulfed by a host cell, explaining their bacterial-like DNA, ribosomes, and double membranes."},{"p":"A molecule of glucose moves across a cell membrane down its concentration gradient with the help of a transport protein, without the cell expending ATP. This process is best classified as which of the following?","a":"Facilitated diffusion","w":["Active transport","Simple diffusion through the phospholipid bilayer","Exocytosis via vesicle fusion"],"h":"The molecule needs help crossing but still moves from high to low concentration.","e":"Facilitated diffusion is passive transport of solutes through membrane proteins down their gradient; it requires a protein (unlike simple diffusion) but no energy (unlike active transport)."},{"p":"How does a competitive inhibitor decrease the rate of an enzyme-catalyzed reaction?","a":"It binds the active site, blocking substrate from binding there","w":["It binds a site other than the active site, changing the enzyme's shape","It permanently destroys the enzyme by breaking its peptide bonds","It lowers the activation energy so the reverse reaction dominates"],"h":"The name of the inhibitor describes what it competes with the substrate for.","e":"A competitive inhibitor resembles the substrate and occupies the active site; its effect can be overcome by increasing substrate concentration, unlike noncompetitive (allosteric) inhibition."},{"p":"In the light-dependent reactions of photosynthesis, water is split and electrons are energized by light. Which two energy-carrying products are generated to power the Calvin cycle?","a":"ATP and NADPH","w":["ATP and NADH","Glucose and oxygen","FADH2 and NADPH"],"h":"One product is the universal energy currency; the other is a reduced electron carrier specific to the chloroplast.","e":"The light reactions produce ATP (from photophosphorylation) and NADPH (from reduction of NADP+); these drive carbon fixation in the light-independent Calvin cycle."},{"p":"In eukaryotic cellular respiration, where does glycolysis take place?","a":"In the cytoplasm (cytosol)","w":["In the mitochondrial matrix","On the inner mitochondrial membrane","Within the nucleus"],"h":"This first stage occurs outside any membrane-bound organelle and does not require oxygen.","e":"Glycolysis occurs in the cytosol and splits glucose into two pyruvate molecules; only later stages (Krebs cycle and oxidative phosphorylation) occur inside the mitochondrion."},{"p":"During signal transduction, a signaling molecule binds a receptor on the cell surface and triggers a series of relay proteins inside the cell before a response occurs. This relay of molecular changes is best described as which of the following?","a":"A signal transduction pathway that transmits and amplifies the signal","w":["Simple diffusion of the ligand directly to the target gene","A negative feedback loop that halts the original signal","Passive osmosis of water into the responding cell"],"h":"Consider how a small number of signal molecules can produce a large cellular response.","e":"Signal transduction pathways convert an extracellular signal into a cellular response through a cascade of relay molecules, often amplifying the signal at each step."},{"p":"At the G1 checkpoint of the cell cycle, what critical decision does the cell make?","a":"Whether conditions are favorable to proceed and commit to DNA replication and division","w":["Whether the chromosomes are properly attached to the spindle before anaphase","Whether DNA replication has been completed correctly before mitosis begins","Whether the cell should fuse with a gamete to restore diploidy"],"h":"This checkpoint comes before S phase, so it governs entry into the replication commitment.","e":"The G1 checkpoint assesses cell size, nutrients, and DNA integrity to decide whether to enter S phase; the spindle-attachment check occurs at the later M (metaphase) checkpoint."},{"p":"Which statement correctly distinguishes meiosis from mitosis?","a":"Meiosis produces four genetically distinct haploid cells, whereas mitosis produces two genetically identical diploid cells","w":["Meiosis produces two identical diploid cells, whereas mitosis produces four haploid cells","Meiosis and mitosis both produce four haploid cells, but only mitosis involves crossing over","Meiosis produces two haploid cells, whereas mitosis produces four diploid cells"],"h":"Count the number of divisions and whether chromosome number is halved in each process.","e":"Meiosis involves two divisions yielding four haploid, genetically varied gametes (via crossing over and independent assortment); mitosis is one division yielding two diploid clones."},{"p":"In a monohybrid cross between two heterozygous pea plants (Pp x Pp) for a trait with complete dominance, what phenotypic ratio is expected in the offspring?","a":"3 dominant : 1 recessive","w":["1 dominant : 1 recessive","9 dominant : 3 : 3 : 1","1 : 2 : 1 dominant to recessive"],"h":"Use a Punnett square and remember that heterozygotes express the dominant phenotype.","e":"A monohybrid Pp x Pp cross yields a 3:1 phenotypic ratio (and 1:2:1 genotypic ratio) under complete dominance, per Mendel's law of segregation."},{"p":"Mendel's law of independent assortment states which of the following about alleles for different traits during gamete formation?","a":"Alleles of different genes segregate independently of one another (for genes on different chromosomes)","w":["Alleles of the same gene always stay together in the same gamete","Dominant alleles are always inherited more frequently than recessive alleles","Alleles of different genes always remain linked and are inherited together"],"h":"Think about how genes on separate chromosomes behave during metaphase I of meiosis.","e":"The law of independent assortment holds that alleles of genes on different chromosomes sort into gametes independently, producing new allele combinations; linked genes are an exception."},{"p":"During translation, which molecule reads the codons of an mRNA and delivers the appropriate amino acid to the growing polypeptide?","a":"Transfer RNA (tRNA), via its anticodon","w":["Messenger RNA (mRNA), via its promoter","DNA polymerase, via its proofreading site","The nuclear envelope, via its pore complexes"],"h":"This molecule has an anticodon on one end and carries a specific amino acid on the other.","e":"During translation at the ribosome, tRNA anticodons base-pair with mRNA codons to deliver the correct amino acids, linking the genetic code to protein sequence."},{"p":"A single nucleotide substitution changes a codon from one that specifies an amino acid to a stop codon. This type of mutation is best classified as which of the following?","a":"A nonsense mutation, which prematurely terminates translation","w":["A silent mutation, which does not change the amino acid sequence","A frameshift mutation, which shifts the reading frame downstream","A missense mutation, which substitutes one amino acid for another"],"h":"Consider the effect on the polypeptide's length when a stop signal appears early.","e":"A nonsense mutation converts an amino-acid codon into a stop codon, truncating the protein; missense changes one amino acid, and silent mutations leave the sequence unchanged."},{"p":"Which set of conditions must be met for a population to remain in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, meaning allele frequencies do not change over time?","a":"No mutation, no gene flow, no natural selection, random mating, and a very large population","w":["Frequent mutation, strong natural selection, and a small population","Random mating combined with strong directional selection favoring one allele","Significant gene flow between populations and nonrandom (assortative) mating"],"h":"The equilibrium describes a population in which no evolutionary forces are acting.","e":"Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium requires no mutation, no gene flow, no selection, random mating, and a large population; violation of any condition indicates evolution is occurring."},{"p":"In a typical food chain, roughly what percentage of the energy stored in one trophic level is transferred to and stored in the next higher trophic level?","a":"About 10 percent","w":["About 50 percent","About 90 percent","About 100 percent"],"h":"Most energy at each level is lost as heat through metabolism and is not passed upward.","e":"The 10 percent rule states that only about 10 percent of energy is transferred between trophic levels, with the rest lost mainly as metabolic heat, which limits food chain length."},{"p":"Cyanide blocks the final electron acceptor in the electron transport chain of mitochondria. What is the most direct consequence for ATP production by oxidative phosphorylation?","a":"ATP synthesis falls sharply because the proton gradient can no longer be maintained","w":["ATP synthesis increases because electrons flow faster through the chain","ATP synthesis is unaffected because glycolysis compensates fully in the matrix","ATP synthesis rises because oxygen is no longer consumed by the cell"],"h":"Think about what drives ATP synthase and what happens when electron flow to oxygen stops.","e":"Blocking the electron transport chain halts electron flow to oxygen, so no proton gradient is pumped, and chemiosmotic ATP synthesis by ATP synthase collapses."},{"p":"A cell's cytoplasm contains a buffer made of carbonic acid (H2CO3) and bicarbonate (HCO3-). When a small amount of strong acid is added to this solution, why does the pH change only slightly?","a":"The bicarbonate ion acts as a base and accepts the added H+ ions, minimizing the change in free H+ concentration","w":["The carbonic acid dissociates completely, releasing extra H+ that neutralizes the added acid","The water molecules absorb the added H+ ions permanently into their covalent bonds","The added acid reacts with the buffer to raise the pH back above 7 regardless of amount"],"h":"A buffer works because it contains both a species that can donate H+ and one that can accept H+.","e":"Buffers resist pH change because the conjugate base (HCO3-) accepts added H+ while the weak acid can donate H+ if base is added, keeping free H+ nearly constant."},{"p":"ATP is often called the energy currency of the cell. When ATP is hydrolyzed to ADP + inorganic phosphate, energy is released. Which statement best explains the source of this released energy?","a":"Breaking the bond releases energy because the products (ADP + Pi) are more stable and at lower free energy than ATP","w":["The phosphate bonds themselves store energy that is physically released like a compressed spring uncoiling","Energy is created during hydrolysis because a new water molecule is synthesized in the process","The energy comes from the formation of a new high-energy bond between ADP and phosphate"],"h":"Free energy change depends on comparing the stability of reactants versus products, not on energy stored inside a bond.","e":"ATP hydrolysis is exergonic because the products have lower free energy than the reactants; the phrase high-energy bond refers to this favorable free-energy change, not energy trapped within the bond."},{"p":"Phospholipids spontaneously form bilayers in water. Which structural feature of a phospholipid molecule most directly explains this behavior?","a":"It is amphipathic, having a hydrophilic phosphate head and two hydrophobic fatty acid tails","w":["It is entirely hydrophobic, so the whole molecule is repelled by the surrounding water","It is entirely hydrophilic, so both ends dissolve completely and evenly in water","It carries a strong overall positive charge that attracts it to negatively charged water"],"h":"Consider how a molecule with two chemically different ends would arrange itself relative to surrounding water.","e":"Phospholipids are amphipathic; the hydrophilic heads face the aqueous environment while the hydrophobic tails cluster inward, driving bilayer self-assembly."},{"p":"A DNA polymerase can only add nucleotides to the 3' end of a growing strand. On the lagging strand during replication, this constraint results in which of the following?","a":"Synthesis occurs discontinuously in short Okazaki fragments moving away from the replication fork","w":["Synthesis occurs continuously in one piece toward the replication fork without any interruptions","Synthesis proceeds in the 3' to 5' direction to keep pace with the opening fork","Synthesis is carried out by RNA polymerase because DNA polymerase cannot work backward"],"h":"The two template strands are antiparallel, so one new strand must be built in pieces as the fork opens.","e":"Because polymerase adds only to the 3' end (5' to 3' synthesis) and the strands are antiparallel, the lagging strand is made in discontinuous Okazaki fragments."},{"p":"As a spherical cell grows larger, its ability to exchange materials with the environment becomes limited. Which change best explains why very large cell size is disadvantageous?","a":"Volume increases faster than surface area, so there is too little membrane area to service the cell's contents","w":["Surface area increases faster than volume, leaving excess membrane the cell cannot support","Both surface area and volume increase at exactly the same rate, causing no real limitation","The nucleus grows too large to fit inside the expanding cytoplasm of the cell"],"h":"Compare how area (a squared term) and volume (a cubed term) scale as the radius increases.","e":"Volume scales with r^3 while surface area scales with r^2, so as a cell enlarges its surface-area-to-volume ratio drops, limiting exchange across the membrane."},{"p":"A red blood cell is placed in a solution, and after several minutes it shrinks and shrivels (crenates). What can be concluded about the solution relative to the cell's interior?","a":"The solution is hypertonic, so water moved out of the cell by osmosis","w":["The solution is hypotonic, so water moved out of the cell by osmosis","The solution is hypertonic, so water moved into the cell by osmosis","The solution is isotonic, so there was no net movement of water"],"h":"Water moves toward the region with higher solute concentration; the cell losing water tells you which side that is.","e":"Crenation indicates net water loss by osmosis, meaning the external solution has a higher solute concentration (hypertonic) than the cytoplasm."},{"p":"An enzyme shows maximum activity at pH 7 and 37 degrees C. When the temperature is raised to 60 degrees C, its activity drops sharply. Which explanation best accounts for this decrease?","a":"The high temperature denatures the enzyme, disrupting the interactions that maintain its active-site shape","w":["The high temperature permanently changes the enzyme's amino acid sequence, altering its primary structure","The high temperature increases substrate concentration so the enzyme becomes saturated and stops working","The high temperature converts the enzyme into a competitive inhibitor of its own reaction"],"h":"Enzyme function depends on a precise three-dimensional shape held together by weak interactions.","e":"Excess heat denatures the enzyme by disrupting hydrogen bonds and other weak interactions that hold its tertiary structure, distorting the active site without changing the amino acid sequence."},{"p":"During glycolysis, a total of 4 ATP molecules are produced by substrate-level phosphorylation, but the process also consumes ATP in its early steps. What is the net ATP gain from glycolysis of one glucose molecule?","a":"A net gain of 2 ATP, because 2 ATP are invested before 4 are produced","w":["A net gain of 4 ATP, because the ATP invested is later recovered from NADH","A net gain of 36 ATP, because glycolysis includes the electron transport chain","A net gain of 0 ATP, because glycolysis only produces NADH and pyruvate"],"h":"Account for both the energy-investment phase and the energy-payoff phase of the pathway.","e":"Glycolysis invests 2 ATP and yields 4 ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation, giving a net of 2 ATP (plus 2 NADH and 2 pyruvate)."},{"p":"In the absence of oxygen, many cells carry out fermentation following glycolysis. What is the primary role of fermentation in allowing glycolysis to continue?","a":"It regenerates NAD+ by oxidizing NADH, so glycolysis has the electron acceptor it needs","w":["It produces large amounts of ATP directly to replace the ATP made by respiration","It regenerates oxygen so that the electron transport chain can keep operating","It breaks down lactate or ethanol to release additional energized electrons for glycolysis"],"h":"Glycolysis needs a supply of a specific oxidized electron carrier to keep running.","e":"Fermentation oxidizes NADH back to NAD+, replenishing the electron acceptor required for the glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate step of glycolysis so ATP production can continue anaerobically."},{"p":"In the Calvin cycle, the enzyme RuBisCO catalyzes the first major step. Which reaction does RuBisCO carry out?","a":"It attaches CO2 to the five-carbon molecule RuBP, a process called carbon fixation","w":["It splits water molecules to release oxygen and provide electrons for the cycle","It uses light energy directly to convert ADP into ATP for sugar synthesis","It reduces G3P into glucose using electrons carried by NADPH"],"h":"The Calvin cycle begins by incorporating inorganic carbon into an existing organic molecule.","e":"RuBisCO fixes CO2 onto ribulose bisphosphate (RuBP), the carbon-fixation step that begins the Calvin cycle's light-independent reactions."},{"p":"Many hydrophilic signaling molecules bind receptors on the cell surface and trigger production of cAMP inside the cell. What is the role of cAMP in this pathway?","a":"It acts as a second messenger, relaying and amplifying the signal to activate intracellular proteins","w":["It acts as the primary signal that leaves the cell to bind neighboring receptors","It serves as the surface receptor that binds the incoming signaling molecule","It is the final target protein whose activity produces the cellular response"],"h":"Think about how a signal received at the membrane gets spread and amplified through the cytoplasm.","e":"cAMP is a second messenger: a small intracellular molecule that relays and amplifies signals from a membrane receptor, often by activating protein kinase A."},{"p":"The protein p53 normally halts the cell cycle when DNA damage is detected, allowing repair or triggering apoptosis. Why does a loss-of-function mutation in the p53 gene contribute to cancer?","a":"Cells with damaged DNA are no longer stopped at the checkpoint and continue to divide, accumulating mutations","w":["Cells lose the ability to divide entirely, so damaged tissue can never be replaced or repaired","p53 loss causes cells to permanently exit the cell cycle into a non-dividing G0 state","p53 loss speeds up DNA repair so much that harmful mutations are fixed incorrectly"],"h":"Consider what happens to a checkpoint control when its key regulatory protein no longer works.","e":"p53 is a tumor-suppressor that enforces the G1 DNA-damage checkpoint; without it, cells with damaged DNA bypass the checkpoint and proliferate, accumulating the mutations characteristic of cancer."},{"p":"A dihybrid organism (RrYy) is crossed with a fully recessive individual (rryy) in a test cross. Assuming independent assortment, what phenotypic ratio is expected in the offspring?","a":"1:1:1:1 among the four possible phenotype combinations","w":["9:3:3:1 among the four possible phenotype combinations","3:1 between dominant and recessive phenotypes","1:2:1 among three phenotype combinations"],"h":"The recessive parent contributes only recessive alleles, so offspring phenotype reflects the gametes of the dihybrid parent.","e":"A dihybrid test cross (RrYy x rryy) yields a 1:1:1:1 ratio because the RrYy parent produces four equally likely gamete types and the tester contributes only recessive alleles."},{"p":"Red-green color blindness is an X-linked recessive trait. A woman who is a carrier (X^B X^b) has children with a man who has normal color vision (X^B Y). What is the probability that any one of their sons will be color blind?","a":"1/2, because half of the sons will inherit the recessive allele on the mother's X","w":["1/4, because color blindness requires two recessive alleles in the son","0, because the father does not carry the color-blindness allele","1, because all sons inherit the mother's X chromosome carrying the allele"],"h":"A son receives his single X chromosome from his mother; focus only on which X she passes on.","e":"Because males are hemizygous, a son is color blind if he inherits the mother's X^b; the carrier mother passes X^b to half her sons, giving a 1/2 probability."},{"p":"In humans, the ABO blood group shows both codominance and multiple alleles. A person with genotype I^A I^B expresses both A and B antigens on their red blood cells. This is an example of which inheritance pattern?","a":"Codominance, because both alleles are fully and separately expressed in the phenotype","w":["Incomplete dominance, because the two alleles blend into an intermediate phenotype","Complete dominance, because one allele completely masks the other allele","Polygenic inheritance, because many genes each add a small effect on the phenotype"],"h":"Distinguish between alleles that blend versus alleles that are each fully visible at the same time.","e":"In codominance both alleles are expressed fully and independently (both A and B antigens appear), unlike incomplete dominance where heterozygotes show a blended intermediate."},{"p":"In E. coli, the lac operon genes are transcribed only when lactose is present. In the absence of lactose, a repressor protein binds the operator. What is the effect of lactose (via its isomer allolactose) on this system?","a":"It binds the repressor, causing it to release the operator so transcription can proceed","w":["It binds the operator directly, physically blocking the repressor from attaching","It activates the repressor so it binds more tightly, increasing transcription","It degrades the repressor protein permanently so the operon can never be shut off"],"h":"Think about how an inducer molecule changes the shape and binding ability of the repressor.","e":"Allolactose acts as an inducer that binds the lac repressor, changing its shape so it can no longer bind the operator, allowing RNA polymerase to transcribe the operon."},{"p":"After a eukaryotic pre-mRNA is transcribed, it undergoes processing before leaving the nucleus. During splicing, which change occurs to the transcript?","a":"Introns are removed and the remaining exons are joined together","w":["Exons are removed and the remaining introns are joined together","A poly-A tail is removed from the 3' end of the transcript","Amino acids are added according to the sequence of codons"],"h":"Recall which segments are the expressed, coding regions and which are the intervening regions.","e":"Splicing removes introns (intervening non-coding sequences) and ligates the exons (expressed sequences) together, producing a mature mRNA."},{"p":"A volcanic eruption drastically reduces a beetle population from thousands to a few dozen survivors purely by chance, unrelated to any traits. The survivors' allele frequencies differ noticeably from the original population. This scenario best illustrates which mechanism of evolution?","a":"Genetic drift through a bottleneck effect","w":["Natural selection favoring beetles with advantageous traits","Directional selection driven by an environmental pressure","Gene flow between two separate beetle populations"],"h":"Consider whether the change in allele frequency was due to fitness differences or to random chance in a small sample.","e":"A random, non-selective reduction in population size that alters allele frequencies is a bottleneck effect, a form of genetic drift most pronounced in small populations."},{"p":"A plant cell with a water potential of -0.7 MPa is placed into an open beaker of solution whose water potential is -0.4 MPa. Assuming no other factors, which direction will there be a net movement of water?","a":"Water will move into the cell, because water flows from higher (less negative) toward lower (more negative) water potential","w":["Water will move out of the cell, because water moves from lower to higher solute concentration until pressures equalize","There will be no net movement of water, because the pressure potential of the cell already balances the solution","Water will move out of the cell, because water always moves from more negative toward less negative water potential"],"h":"Compare the two water potential values numerically and recall the rule for the direction water flows.","e":"Water moves down its water potential gradient, from higher (-0.4 MPa) to lower (-0.7 MPa) potential; since the cell is more negative, water enters the cell."},{"p":"At high temperatures a cell membrane tends to become too fluid, while at low temperatures it tends to become too rigid. In animal cells, cholesterol embedded in the phospholipid bilayer helps address both problems. Which statement best describes cholesterol's role?","a":"It acts as a fluidity buffer, restraining phospholipid movement at high temperatures and preventing tight packing at low temperatures","w":["It increases membrane fluidity at all temperatures by pushing phospholipids farther apart","It decreases membrane fluidity at all temperatures by forming rigid cross-links between phospholipids","It replaces phospholipids in the bilayer, forming channels that stabilize the membrane at temperature extremes"],"h":"Consider that cholesterol has opposite effects depending on whether the membrane is too fluid or too rigid.","e":"Cholesterol is a fluidity buffer: at high temperatures it restrains phospholipid motion, and at low temperatures it prevents tight packing, moderating fluidity in both directions."},{"p":"On a hot, dry day, C4 plants such as corn outcompete C3 plants because they minimize a wasteful process that occurs when RuBisCO binds O2 instead of CO2. Which statement best explains the C4 advantage?","a":"C4 plants concentrate CO2 in bundle-sheath cells, reducing photorespiration when stomata are partly closed","w":["C4 plants keep their stomata fully open in heat, allowing more CO2 in and preventing photorespiration","C4 plants replace RuBisCO with an enzyme that cannot bind O2, eliminating the Calvin cycle's oxygen problem","C4 plants perform the Calvin cycle only at night, when cooler temperatures prevent RuBisCO from binding O2"],"h":"Think about how spatially separating initial carbon fixation from the Calvin cycle changes the CO2-to-O2 ratio around RuBisCO.","e":"C4 plants fix CO2 initially in mesophyll cells and pump it into bundle-sheath cells, raising the local CO2:O2 ratio and suppressing photorespiration when stomata close to conserve water."},{"p":"In a metabolic pathway, the final product molecule can bind to the first enzyme of the pathway at a site distinct from the active site, changing the enzyme's shape and slowing its own production. This regulatory mechanism is best described as which of the following?","a":"Allosteric feedback inhibition, in which the end product acts as a noncompetitive regulator of an early enzyme","w":["Competitive inhibition, in which the end product competes with the substrate for the active site","Cooperativity, in which binding of the product increases the enzyme's affinity for additional substrate","Denaturation, in which the end product permanently unfolds the first enzyme of the pathway"],"h":"Focus on the fact that the product binds away from the active site and regulates a step early in its own pathway.","e":"This is feedback (end-product) inhibition acting through allosteric (noncompetitive) binding, a common way cells regulate metabolic pathways."},{"p":"In oxidative phosphorylation, the energy that ultimately powers ATP synthase comes from a proton gradient. Across which structure is this H+ gradient established in a mitochondrion?","a":"The inner mitochondrial membrane, with protons accumulating in the intermembrane space","w":["The outer mitochondrial membrane, with protons accumulating outside the mitochondrion","The inner mitochondrial membrane, with protons accumulating in the mitochondrial matrix","The cristae junctions, with protons accumulating directly within the matrix"],"h":"Recall where the electron transport chain pumps protons and which compartment they build up in.","e":"The electron transport chain pumps H+ from the matrix into the intermembrane space across the inner membrane; this gradient (chemiosmosis) drives ATP synthase."},{"p":"For a chemical reaction occurring at constant temperature and pressure, which condition indicates that the reaction is spontaneous (thermodynamically favorable) as written?","a":"The change in Gibbs free energy (delta G) is negative","w":["The change in Gibbs free energy (delta G) is positive","The change in enthalpy (delta H) is positive regardless of entropy","The change in Gibbs free energy (delta G) is exactly zero"],"h":"Recall the sign of the free-energy change associated with an exergonic reaction.","e":"A reaction is spontaneous (exergonic) when delta G < 0; a positive delta G is endergonic and a delta G of zero means the reaction is at equilibrium."},{"p":"A geneticist crosses two heterozygous fruit flies and obtains offspring numbers that differ from the expected Mendelian ratio. She performs a chi-square test and calculates a p-value of 0.02, using a significance level of 0.05. What is the correct conclusion?","a":"The deviation is statistically significant, so she rejects the null hypothesis that the difference is due to chance alone","w":["The deviation is not significant, so she fails to reject the null hypothesis and accepts that chance explains the data","The deviation is statistically significant, so she accepts the null hypothesis that the data fit the expected ratio","The p-value is too small to interpret, so the chi-square test cannot be applied to these data"],"h":"Compare the p-value to the significance level and recall what happens when p is below that threshold.","e":"Because p (0.02) is less than the significance level (0.05), the deviation is significant and the null hypothesis (that observed differences are due to chance) is rejected."},{"p":"In Labrador retrievers, one gene (B/b) determines whether pigment is black or brown, but a second gene (E/e) controls whether any pigment is deposited in the fur at all; dogs that are ee are yellow regardless of their B/b genotype. The masking of the B/b gene by the ee genotype is an example of which phenomenon?","a":"Epistasis, in which one gene's alleles mask or modify the phenotypic expression of a different gene","w":["Incomplete dominance, in which heterozygotes show a blended intermediate phenotype","Codominance, in which both alleles of a single gene are fully expressed in the phenotype","Pleiotropy, in which a single gene produces multiple, seemingly unrelated phenotypic effects"],"h":"The key is that alleles at one locus hide the effect of alleles at a separate locus.","e":"When one gene (E/e) masks the expression of another gene (B/b), the interaction is epistasis, distinct from single-gene patterns like incomplete dominance or codominance."},{"p":"During meiosis, a pair of homologous chromosomes fails to separate at anaphase I. If a resulting gamete with an extra chromosome is fertilized by a normal gamete, what is the most direct outcome for the zygote?","a":"The zygote will be trisomic, having three copies of that chromosome instead of the normal two","w":["The zygote will be monosomic, having only one copy of that chromosome","The zygote will be triploid, having three complete sets of every chromosome","The zygote will be haploid, having a single copy of every chromosome"],"h":"Determine how many copies of that one chromosome the abnormal gamete carries, then add the normal gamete's contribution.","e":"Nondisjunction in meiosis I can yield a gamete with n+1 chromosomes; fertilization by a normal (n) gamete produces a trisomic zygote (2n+1) for that chromosome."},{"p":"In E. coli, the trp operon encodes enzymes for tryptophan synthesis. When tryptophan is abundant, the operon is switched off; when tryptophan is scarce, the operon is transcribed. How does tryptophan itself contribute to this regulation?","a":"Tryptophan acts as a corepressor, binding the inactive repressor and activating it to bind the operator","w":["Tryptophan acts as an inducer, binding the repressor and preventing it from binding the operator","Tryptophan binds RNA polymerase directly, blocking it from initiating transcription of the operon","Tryptophan acts as an activator, binding a regulatory site upstream to increase transcription of the operon"],"h":"The trp operon is repressible, so the small molecule turns the system off rather than on.","e":"The trp operon is repressible: tryptophan is a corepressor that activates the repressor, which then binds the operator and blocks transcription when tryptophan is plentiful."},{"p":"Two genes are located on the same chromosome. In a test cross, recombinant offspring make up 18% of the total. According to the standard convention for genetic mapping, what is the distance between these two genes?","a":"18 map units (centimorgans), since one map unit corresponds to a 1% recombination frequency","w":["82 map units, since the distance equals 100% minus the recombination frequency","36 map units, since the recombinant percentage must be doubled to account for both parents","9 map units, since the recombinant percentage must be halved to give the true distance"],"h":"Recall the direct relationship between percent recombinant offspring and map units.","e":"Map distance in centimorgans equals the recombination frequency as a percentage, so 18% recombinants corresponds to 18 map units between the genes."},{"p":"A river permanently changes course, dividing a single population of lizards into two groups that can no longer interbreed. Over many generations the two groups accumulate genetic differences and eventually become separate species. This process is best described as which mode of speciation?","a":"Allopatric speciation, in which a geographic barrier prevents gene flow between populations","w":["Sympatric speciation, in which new species arise within the same geographic area without physical separation","Adaptive radiation, in which one species rapidly diversifies to fill many available niches","Convergent evolution, in which unrelated species independently evolve similar traits"],"h":"Focus on the role of the physical barrier that stops the two groups from interbreeding.","e":"Speciation caused by a physical barrier that halts gene flow is allopatric speciation, in contrast to sympatric speciation, which occurs without geographic isolation."},{"p":"A population of deer is introduced to an island with limited food and space. As the population approaches the environment's carrying capacity (K), which change in the population's growth is expected under a logistic growth model?","a":"The per capita growth rate decreases and the population growth slows, leveling off near K","w":["The per capita growth rate stays constant, so the population continues growing exponentially past K","The per capita growth rate increases, causing the population to overshoot and stabilize well above K","The population immediately crashes to zero as soon as it reaches carrying capacity"],"h":"Consider how resource limitation affects growth rate as numbers rise toward the environment's maximum.","e":"In logistic growth, resource limits reduce the per capita growth rate as the population nears carrying capacity, producing an S-shaped curve that levels off around K."},{"p":"Read: \"When sea otters were hunted to near extinction along a coastline, their prey, sea urchins, exploded in number and devoured the kelp forests, causing many other species to disappear.\" The sea otter in this scenario is best described as which of the following?","a":"A keystone species, whose presence exerts a disproportionately large effect on community structure","w":["A primary producer, whose photosynthesis forms the base of the community's food web","An invasive species, whose introduction outcompetes and displaces native organisms","A decomposer, whose feeding recycles nutrients that support the rest of the community"],"h":"Notice that removing this one predator triggered dramatic, far-reaching changes throughout the community.","e":"A keystone species has an effect on its community out of proportion to its abundance; removing sea otters collapsed the kelp-forest community through a trophic cascade."},{"p":"A sample of double-stranded DNA is analyzed and found to contain 20% adenine among its total nitrogenous bases. Based on Chargaff's rules, what percentage of the bases in this DNA is guanine?","a":"30%","w":["20%","40%","60%"],"h":"Use complementary base pairing to find thymine first, then determine what fraction remains for the G-C pair.","e":"By Chargaff's rules, A = T = 20%, so A+T = 40%, leaving 60% for G+C; since G = C, guanine is 30%."},{"p":"The synthesis of glutamine from glutamate is endergonic and would not occur on its own. In cells this reaction proceeds because it is directly linked to ATP hydrolysis. This linking of a favorable reaction to drive an unfavorable one is called which of the following?","a":"Energy coupling, in which the free energy released by an exergonic reaction drives an endergonic reaction","w":["Feedback inhibition, in which a product shuts down the pathway that produced it","Substrate-level phosphorylation, in which a phosphate is transferred directly to ADP by an enzyme","Chemiosmosis, in which a proton gradient across a membrane powers the synthesis of ATP"],"h":"The favorable reaction supplies the energy needed to push the unfavorable one forward.","e":"Energy coupling uses the negative delta G of an exergonic reaction (ATP hydrolysis) to drive an endergonic reaction, giving the combined process an overall negative delta G."},{"p":"In a dividing plant cell, cytokinesis differs from that in an animal cell. Which structure divides the plant cytoplasm into two daughter cells?","a":"A cell plate forms at the middle of the cell and develops into a new cell wall separating the daughters","w":["A cleavage furrow pinches inward as a ring of actin filaments constricts the cell membrane","The centrioles migrate to the cell center and physically split the cytoplasm in two","The nuclear envelope elongates and pinches the cytoplasm into two separate compartments"],"h":"Recall that a rigid cell wall prevents the pinching mechanism used by animal cells.","e":"Plant cytokinesis occurs by vesicles fusing to form a cell plate that becomes a new cell wall, whereas animal cells divide by a contractile cleavage furrow."}],"ap-chem":[{"p":"Which of the following represents the ground-state electron configuration of a neutral iron atom (Z = 26)?","a":"1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s² 3d⁶","w":["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 3d⁸","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s² 3d⁸","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s¹ 3d⁷"],"h":"Fill orbitals in order of increasing energy and make sure the electrons total Z.","e":"By the Aufbau principle the 4s subshell fills before 3d, so neutral Fe is [Ar]4s²3d⁶ (26 electrons)."},{"p":"Which of these atoms has the largest atomic radius?","a":"Na","w":["Mg","Al","P"],"h":"These elements are all in the same period; think about effective nuclear charge.","e":"Atomic radius decreases left to right across a period as effective nuclear charge increases, so Na (farthest left) is largest."},{"p":"In the photoelectron spectrum (PES) of phosphorus, the peak at the highest binding energy corresponds to electrons in which subshell?","a":"1s","w":["2s","2p","3p"],"h":"Binding energy reflects how strongly electrons are attracted to the nucleus.","e":"PES binding energy is greatest for core electrons closest to the nucleus; the 1s electrons are held most tightly."},{"p":"Which of the following atoms has the highest first ionization energy?","a":"Cl","w":["S","P","Si"],"h":"First ionization energy generally increases from left to right across a period.","e":"First ionization energy increases across a period with rising effective nuclear charge; Cl is farthest right among these."},{"p":"Which of the following bonds is the most polar?","a":"H–F","w":["H–Cl","H–Br","H–I"],"h":"Bond polarity tracks the difference in electronegativity between the two bonded atoms.","e":"Polarity increases with electronegativity difference; fluorine is the most electronegative atom, so H–F is the most polar bond."},{"p":"In the Lewis structure of the ammonium ion, NH₄⁺, what is the formal charge on the nitrogen atom?","a":"+1","w":["0","−1","+2"],"h":"Formal charge = (valence electrons) − (nonbonding electrons) − ½(bonding electrons).","e":"Nitrogen has 5 valence electrons, 0 lone-pair electrons, and 4 bonds: 5 − 0 − 4 = +1."},{"p":"According to VSEPR theory, what is the molecular geometry of ammonia, NH₃?","a":"Trigonal pyramidal","w":["Trigonal planar","Tetrahedral","Bent"],"h":"Count both bonding domains and lone pairs on the central atom.","e":"NH₃ has 3 bonding pairs and 1 lone pair (tetrahedral electron geometry), giving a trigonal pyramidal molecular shape."},{"p":"Which of the following substances exhibits hydrogen bonding in the pure liquid?","a":"NH₃","w":["CH₄","PH₃","H₂S"],"h":"Hydrogen bonding requires hydrogen bonded directly to a specific set of highly electronegative atoms.","e":"Hydrogen bonding occurs only when H is bonded directly to N, O, or F; NH₃ has N–H bonds and qualifies."},{"p":"For the reaction 2 H₂(g) + O₂(g) → 2 H₂O(g), if 4.0 mol H₂ react with 3.0 mol O₂, how many moles of H₂O are produced?","a":"4.0 mol","w":["6.0 mol","3.0 mol","8.0 mol"],"h":"Identify the limiting reactant using the mole ratio from the balanced equation.","e":"H₂ is limiting (4.0 mol needs only 2.0 mol O₂); the 2:2 ratio yields 4.0 mol H₂O."},{"p":"A compound is found to be 40.0% carbon, 6.7% hydrogen, and 53.3% oxygen by mass. What is its empirical formula?","a":"CH₂O","w":["C₂H₄O₂","CHO","CH₄O"],"h":"Convert each mass percent to moles, then divide all by the smallest mole value.","e":"Moles give C 3.33 : H 6.7 : O 3.33, a 1:2:1 ratio, so the empirical formula is CH₂O."},{"p":"What volume does 2.0 mol of an ideal gas occupy at STP (0 °C and 1 atm)?","a":"44.8 L","w":["22.4 L","11.2 L","89.6 L"],"h":"Recall the molar volume of an ideal gas at STP.","e":"At STP one mole of ideal gas occupies 22.4 L, so 2.0 mol occupies 2.0 × 22.4 = 44.8 L."},{"p":"If 50.0 mL of 6.0 M HCl is diluted with water to a final volume of 300.0 mL, what is the concentration of the resulting solution?","a":"1.0 M","w":["0.50 M","2.0 M","36 M"],"h":"Use the dilution relationship M₁V₁ = M₂V₂.","e":"M₂ = (6.0 M)(50.0 mL)/(300.0 mL) = 1.0 M, since moles of solute are conserved on dilution."},{"p":"For a certain reaction, doubling the concentration of reactant A causes the reaction rate to increase by a factor of 4. What is the order of the reaction with respect to A?","a":"Second order","w":["First order","Zero order","Third order"],"h":"The rate depends on [A]ⁿ; find n from the observed factor change.","e":"Since 2ⁿ = 4, n = 2, so the reaction is second order in A."},{"p":"For an exothermic reaction, what is the sign of the enthalpy change, ΔH?","a":"Negative","w":["Positive","Zero","Equal to ΔS"],"h":"Consider whether heat is released to or absorbed from the surroundings.","e":"Exothermic reactions release heat to the surroundings, so ΔH is negative."},{"p":"A reaction is thermodynamically spontaneous at all temperatures under which combination of conditions?","a":"ΔH < 0 and ΔS > 0","w":["ΔH > 0 and ΔS < 0","ΔH < 0 and ΔS < 0","ΔH > 0 and ΔS > 0"],"h":"Examine the sign of ΔG = ΔH − TΔS for every possible temperature.","e":"ΔG = ΔH − TΔS is negative at all temperatures only when ΔH < 0 and ΔS > 0."},{"p":"Consider the exothermic equilibrium N₂(g) + 3 H₂(g) ⇌ 2 NH₃(g), ΔH < 0. What happens when the temperature is increased?","a":"The equilibrium shifts toward the reactants (left)","w":["The equilibrium shifts toward the products (right)","The equilibrium does not shift at all","The value of K increases"],"h":"Heat can be treated as a product in an exothermic reaction when applying Le Châtelier's principle.","e":"For an exothermic reaction, adding heat shifts the equilibrium toward the reactants and decreases K."},{"p":"What is the pH of a 0.010 M solution of HCl at 25 °C?","a":"2","w":["1","12","3"],"h":"HCl is a strong acid that dissociates completely; use pH = −log[H⁺].","e":"Complete dissociation gives [H⁺] = 0.010 M, so pH = −log(0.010) = 2."},{"p":"What is the oxidation number of chromium in the dichromate ion, Cr₂O₇²⁻?","a":"+6","w":["+7","+3","+2"],"h":"Assign oxygen its usual value and set the sum of oxidation numbers equal to the ion's charge.","e":"With each O at −2: 2x + 7(−2) = −2 gives x = +6 for chromium."},{"p":"Which of the following isoelectronic species has the smallest ionic radius? (All have 10 electrons.)","a":"Mg²⁺","w":["Na⁺","F⁻","O²⁻"],"h":"For an isoelectronic series, every species has the same number of electrons, so compare the nuclear charges pulling on that electron cloud.","e":"In an isoelectronic series, greater nuclear charge (Z) pulls the fixed electron cloud in more tightly; Mg²⁺ (Z = 12) has the highest Z and thus the smallest radius (Coulomb's law/Zeff)."},{"p":"In the photoelectron spectrum (PES) of magnesium (Z = 12), one peak is exactly three times as tall as the peak for the 3s electrons. This taller peak corresponds to electrons in which subshell?","a":"2p","w":["1s","2s","3s"],"h":"Peak height (intensity) is proportional to the number of electrons occupying that subshell; the 3s subshell of Mg holds 2 electrons.","e":"PES peak intensity is proportional to electron count; the 3s peak represents 2 electrons, so a peak three times as tall represents 6 electrons, which is the filled 2p subshell."},{"p":"Which of the following ionic compounds has the greatest (most negative) lattice energy?","a":"MgO","w":["NaF","NaCl","KBr"],"h":"Lattice energy depends on the product of the ionic charges and the inverse of the distance between ion centers.","e":"By Coulomb's law, lattice energy increases with larger ionic charges and smaller ionic radii; MgO combines 2+ and 2− charges with small ions, giving the largest magnitude."},{"p":"Which of the following liquids has the highest normal boiling point?","a":"CH₃OH","w":["CH₃CH₃","CH₃Cl","CH₄"],"h":"Identify which molecule can participate in the strongest type of intermolecular attraction in the pure liquid.","e":"Methanol (CH₃OH) has an O–H bond enabling hydrogen bonding, the strongest intermolecular force here, so it requires the most energy to vaporize."},{"p":"For the reaction Zn(s) + 2 HCl(aq) → ZnCl₂(aq) + H₂(g), 3.0 mol Zn is combined with 4.0 mol HCl. How many moles of H₂ gas are produced?","a":"2.0 mol","w":["3.0 mol","4.0 mol","1.5 mol"],"h":"First determine the limiting reactant using the 1:2 mole ratio of Zn to HCl, then use the ratio of that reactant to H₂.","e":"HCl is limiting: 4.0 mol HCl requires only 2.0 mol Zn, and 4.0 mol HCl × (1 mol H₂ / 2 mol HCl) = 2.0 mol H₂."},{"p":"A 25.0 mL sample of NaOH solution is exactly neutralized by 30.0 mL of 0.100 M H₂SO₄. What is the molarity of the NaOH solution?","a":"0.240 M","w":["0.120 M","0.0833 M","0.0600 M"],"h":"Sulfuric acid is diprotic, so each mole supplies two moles of H⁺ available to react with hydroxide.","e":"Moles H⁺ = 0.0300 L × 0.100 M × 2 = 0.00600 mol = moles NaOH; dividing by 0.0250 L gives 0.240 M (accounting for the diprotic acid in the stoichiometry)."},{"p":"A certain reaction is first order with a rate constant k = 0.0231 min⁻¹. How long will it take for the reactant concentration to fall to 25% of its initial value?","a":"60 minutes","w":["30 minutes","45 minutes","120 minutes"],"h":"For a first-order reaction the half-life is 0.693/k and is independent of concentration; falling to 25% means two successive halvings.","e":"The first-order half-life is t½ = 0.693/0.0231 = 30 min; reaching 25% (½ × ½) requires two half-lives, so 60 minutes."},{"p":"For the reaction A + B → products, initial-rate data give: doubling [A] (with [B] fixed) quadruples the rate, while doubling [B] (with [A] fixed) leaves the rate unchanged. What is the rate law?","a":"rate = k[A]²","w":["rate = k[A][B]","rate = k[A]²[B]","rate = k[A]"],"h":"Determine the order in each reactant separately from how the rate responds when only that concentration is changed.","e":"Rate quadrupling when [A] doubles means second order in A (2² = 4); no change when [B] doubles means zero order in B, giving rate = k[A]²."},{"p":"Given C(s) + O₂(g) → CO₂(g), ΔH = −394 kJ and CO(g) + ½ O₂(g) → CO₂(g), ΔH = −283 kJ, what is ΔH for C(s) + ½ O₂(g) → CO(g)?","a":"−111 kJ","w":["−677 kJ","+111 kJ","+677 kJ"],"h":"Add the first equation to the reverse of the second equation using Hess's law, remembering to change the sign of any reversed step.","e":"By Hess's law, ΔH = (−394 kJ) + (+283 kJ) = −111 kJ, obtained by reversing the CO combustion step and adding."},{"p":"A reaction has ΔH = +150 kJ/mol and ΔS = +300 J/(mol·K). Above what temperature does the reaction become thermodynamically spontaneous?","a":"500 K","w":["0.5 K","200 K","750 K"],"h":"Spontaneity begins when ΔG changes sign; set ΔG = ΔH − TΔS = 0 and be careful that ΔH and ΔS use consistent energy units.","e":"Setting ΔG = 0: T = ΔH/ΔS = 150,000 J / 300 J·K⁻¹ = 500 K; above this the −TΔS term overcomes the positive ΔH (unit conversion kJ → J is essential)."},{"p":"For N₂O₄(g) ⇌ 2 NO₂(g), Kc = 0.20 at a given temperature. At one instant [N₂O₄] = 0.10 M and [NO₂] = 0.10 M. In which direction does the reaction proceed to reach equilibrium?","a":"Toward products (to the right)","w":["Toward reactants (to the left)","The system is already at equilibrium","The direction cannot be determined from Kc"],"h":"Calculate the reaction quotient Q with the given concentrations and compare it to Kc.","e":"Q = (0.10)²/(0.10) = 0.10, which is less than Kc = 0.20, so the reaction shifts forward (toward products) until Q = Kc."},{"p":"For the equilibrium A(g) ⇌ B(g) + C(g), a flask is charged with 0.50 M A and no products. At equilibrium [A] = 0.30 M. What is the value of Kc?","a":"0.13","w":["0.080","0.040","0.27"],"h":"Use an ICE table: the amount of A consumed equals the amount of each product formed, then substitute equilibrium concentrations.","e":"Since 0.20 M of A reacted, [B] = [C] = 0.20 M, so Kc = (0.20)(0.20)/(0.30) = 0.13."},{"p":"What is the pH of a 0.10 M solution of acetic acid (Ka = 1.8 × 10⁻⁵) at 25 °C?","a":"2.87","w":["1.00","4.74","5.74"],"h":"Acetic acid is a weak acid, so use the equilibrium expression; the approximation [H⁺] ≈ √(Ka·C) applies when ionization is small.","e":"[H⁺] = √(1.8 × 10⁻⁵ × 0.10) = 1.3 × 10⁻³ M, so pH = 2.87; treating it as a strong acid (pH 1.00) is the common error."},{"p":"A buffer is prepared containing 0.20 M NH₃ and 0.20 M NH₄Cl. For NH₃, Kb = 1.8 × 10⁻⁵. What is the pH of the buffer at 25 °C?","a":"9.26","w":["4.74","5.26","8.72"],"h":"Use the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation with the pKa of the conjugate acid NH₄⁺; note the base and acid concentrations are equal.","e":"pKa(NH₄⁺) = 14 − pKb = 14 − 4.74 = 9.26; with equal [base] and [acid], pH = pKa = 9.26."},{"p":"A galvanic cell is built from the half-reactions Ag⁺ + e⁻ → Ag (E° = +0.80 V) and Ni²⁺ + 2 e⁻ → Ni (E° = −0.25 V). What is the standard cell potential?","a":"+1.05 V","w":["+0.55 V","−1.05 V","+0.80 V"],"h":"The species with the more positive reduction potential is reduced at the cathode; E°cell = E°cathode − E°anode.","e":"Ag⁺/Ag is the cathode (higher E°): E°cell = (+0.80) − (−0.25) = +1.05 V, a positive value confirming a spontaneous galvanic cell."},{"p":"A current of 2.0 A is passed through a solution of Cu²⁺ for 965 seconds. How many grams of copper are deposited at the cathode? (F = 96,500 C/mol e⁻, molar mass Cu = 63.5 g/mol)","a":"0.635 g","w":["1.27 g","0.318 g","0.020 g"],"h":"Find total charge (Q = It), convert to moles of electrons, then account for the 2 electrons needed per Cu²⁺ ion.","e":"Q = 2.0 × 965 = 1930 C; mol e⁻ = 1930/96,500 = 0.0200; mol Cu = 0.0200/2 = 0.0100; mass = 0.0100 × 63.5 = 0.635 g."},{"p":"A rigid container holds 2.0 mol N₂ and 3.0 mol O₂ with a total pressure of 5.0 atm. What is the partial pressure of O₂?","a":"3.0 atm","w":["2.0 atm","5.0 atm","1.5 atm"],"h":"By Dalton's law, each gas's partial pressure equals its mole fraction times the total pressure.","e":"Mole fraction of O₂ = 3.0/(2.0 + 3.0) = 0.60, so P(O₂) = 0.60 × 5.0 atm = 3.0 atm (Dalton's law of partial pressures)."},{"p":"Considering its three equivalent resonance structures, what is the nitrogen–oxygen bond order in the nitrate ion, NO₃⁻?","a":"1.33","w":["1.00","1.50","2.00"],"h":"Count the total number of bonds (single plus double) shared among the equivalent N–O positions and divide by the number of those positions.","e":"Resonance delocalizes one double bond and two single bonds (4 bonds total) over 3 equivalent N–O positions, giving an average bond order of 4/3 ≈ 1.33."},{"p":"The first four successive ionization energies (in kJ/mol) of a certain main-group element are 577, 1816, 2744, and 11,577. Based on this pattern, to which group does the element belong?","a":"Group 13 (IIIA)","w":["Group 2 (IIA)","Group 14 (IVA)","Group 3 (IIIB)"],"h":"Look for the large jump between successive ionization energies; it marks the point where a core electron is being removed.","e":"The huge jump after the third ionization energy shows the atom has exactly three valence electrons, placing it in Group 13. Core electrons require far more energy to remove than valence electrons."},{"p":"In the molecule hydrogen cyanide, H–C≡N, what is the hybridization of the central carbon atom?","a":"sp","w":["sp²","sp³","sp³d"],"h":"Count the number of sigma bonds and lone pairs (electron domains) around the carbon atom.","e":"Carbon in HCN has two sigma bonds and no lone pairs (two electron domains), giving sp hybridization. The number of hybrid orbitals equals the number of electron domains."},{"p":"A student measures the absorbance of a colored solution in a spectrophotometer. A 0.20 M standard gives an absorbance of 0.40, and an unknown sample measured in the same cuvette gives an absorbance of 0.60. Assuming Beer's law holds, what is the concentration of the unknown?","a":"0.30 M","w":["0.13 M","0.40 M","0.60 M"],"h":"According to Beer's law, absorbance is directly proportional to concentration when path length and wavelength are held constant.","e":"By the Beer–Lambert law (A = εbc), absorbance is proportional to concentration: c = 0.20 M × (0.60/0.40) = 0.30 M."},{"p":"Two identical balloons are filled, one with helium (molar mass 4.0 g/mol) and one with methane, CH₄ (molar mass 16.0 g/mol). Approximately how many times faster does the helium effuse through a small pinhole than the methane?","a":"2.0 times faster","w":["4.0 times faster","1.4 times faster","0.50 times faster"],"h":"Graham's law relates effusion rate to the square root of molar mass.","e":"By Graham's law of effusion, the rate ratio equals √(M_CH₄/M_He) = √(16.0/4.0) = 2.0. Lighter gases effuse faster."},{"p":"In the industrial Haber process, N₂(g) + 3 H₂(g) → 2 NH₃(g), a reactor is charged with 14.0 g of N₂ (0.500 mol) and 6.00 g of H₂ (3.00 mol). What is the theoretical yield of ammonia?","a":"17.0 g","w":["34.0 g","8.50 g","6.00 g"],"h":"First identify the limiting reactant by comparing the mole ratio available to the ratio required by the equation.","e":"N₂ requires 3 × 0.500 = 1.50 mol H₂ but 3.00 mol is available, so N₂ is limiting; 0.500 mol N₂ yields 1.00 mol (17.0 g) NH₃."},{"p":"When a chemist constructs an Arrhenius plot of ln k versus 1/T for a reaction, the data fall on a straight line. What does the slope of this line equal?","a":"−Eₐ/R","w":["+Eₐ/R","−Eₐ","ln A"],"h":"Start from the linear form of the Arrhenius equation, ln k = −(Eₐ/R)(1/T) + ln A, and compare it to y = mx + b.","e":"In the linearized Arrhenius equation, the slope is −Eₐ/R, allowing the activation energy to be found experimentally; the y-intercept is ln A."},{"p":"How much heat energy is required to raise the temperature of 50.0 g of liquid water from 20.0 °C to 70.0 °C? (specific heat of water = 4.18 J/(g·°C))","a":"10.5 kJ","w":["14.6 kJ","4.18 kJ","209 J"],"h":"Use q = mcΔT, and be careful to use the temperature change rather than the final temperature.","e":"Using q = mcΔT = (50.0 g)(4.18 J/g·°C)(50.0 °C) = 10,450 J ≈ 10.5 kJ. Calorimetry relates heat to mass, specific heat, and temperature change."},{"p":"Using standard enthalpies of formation ΔH°f: CH₄(g) = −75 kJ/mol, CO₂(g) = −394 kJ/mol, H₂O(l) = −286 kJ/mol, and O₂(g) = 0, calculate ΔH° for the combustion CH₄(g) + 2 O₂(g) → CO₂(g) + 2 H₂O(l).","a":"−891 kJ","w":["−605 kJ","−1047 kJ","+891 kJ"],"h":"Apply ΔH° = ΣΔH°f(products) − ΣΔH°f(reactants), remembering the coefficient of 2 on water.","e":"ΔH° = [(−394) + 2(−286)] − [(−75) + 0] = −966 + 75 = −891 kJ. This applies Hess's law through standard enthalpies of formation."},{"p":"For which of the following processes is the standard entropy change of the system, ΔS°ₛᵧₛ, negative?","a":"2 NO₂(g) → N₂O₄(g)","w":["CO₂(s) → CO₂(g)","H₂O(l) → H₂O(g)","NaCl(s) → Na⁺(aq) + Cl⁻(aq)"],"h":"Entropy increases with the number of gas-phase moles and with greater molecular freedom (solid < liquid < gas).","e":"Combining two moles of gas into one mole of gas decreases the number of gas particles and therefore decreases entropy; the other processes all increase disorder."},{"p":"The solubility product of magnesium hydroxide, Mg(OH)₂, is Ksp = 5.6 × 10⁻¹² at 25 °C. What is its molar solubility in pure water?","a":"1.1 × 10⁻⁴ M","w":["1.8 × 10⁻⁴ M","2.4 × 10⁻⁶ M","5.6 × 10⁻¹² M"],"h":"Write the dissolution equilibrium and note that each formula unit produces one Mg²⁺ and two OH⁻ ions, so Ksp = 4s³.","e":"For Mg(OH)₂ ⇌ Mg²⁺ + 2 OH⁻, Ksp = (s)(2s)² = 4s³, so s = ∛(5.6×10⁻¹²/4) ≈ 1.1×10⁻⁴ M. The 1:2 stoichiometry produces the factor of 4."},{"p":"Solid AgCl is placed in 0.10 M NaCl solution rather than in pure water. How does the molar solubility of AgCl change, and why?","a":"Lower, because the added Cl⁻ shifts the dissolution equilibrium toward solid AgCl","w":["Higher, because dissolved NaCl increases the ionic strength of the solution","Unchanged, because Ksp for AgCl is a constant at fixed temperature","Higher, because Na⁺ ions form a soluble complex with the chloride"],"h":"Consider Le Chatelier's principle applied to AgCl(s) ⇌ Ag⁺(aq) + Cl⁻(aq) when a product ion is already present.","e":"This is the common-ion effect: adding Cl⁻ (a product ion) shifts the equilibrium toward the solid, decreasing molar solubility even though Ksp is unchanged."},{"p":"For the equilibrium N₂(g) + 3 H₂(g) ⇌ 2 NH₃(g), what is the correct relationship between Kp and Kc at temperature T?","a":"Kp = Kc(RT)⁻²","w":["Kp = Kc(RT)²","Kp = Kc(RT)⁻¹","Kp = Kc"],"h":"Use Kp = Kc(RT)^Δn, where Δn is the change in the number of moles of gas (products minus reactants).","e":"Here Δn = 2 − (1 + 3) = −2, so Kp = Kc(RT)⁻². Kp and Kc differ whenever the moles of gas change during the reaction."},{"p":"A 0.10 M solution of acetic acid (a weak acid) is titrated with 0.10 M NaOH. What is the pH of the solution at the equivalence point?","a":"Greater than 7","w":["Equal to 7","Less than 7","Equal to the pKa of acetic acid"],"h":"At the equivalence point, all the weak acid has been converted to its conjugate base; consider how that ion affects water.","e":"At the equivalence point only acetate ion remains, and this conjugate base hydrolyzes water to produce OH⁻, giving a basic pH above 7 for a weak acid–strong base titration."},{"p":"For the cell Zn(s) | Zn²⁺(1.0 M) || Cu²⁺(0.010 M) | Cu(s), the standard cell potential is 1.10 V (n = 2). Using the Nernst equation at 25 °C, what is the cell potential under these conditions?","a":"1.04 V","w":["1.16 V","1.10 V","0.98 V"],"h":"Apply E = E° − (0.0592/n)log Q, and write Q as [Zn²⁺]/[Cu²⁺] for this reaction.","e":"Q = 1.0/0.010 = 100, so E = 1.10 − (0.0592/2)(log 100) = 1.10 − 0.0592 = 1.04 V. Lowering the product-side reactant concentration reduces the cell potential."},{"p":"A reaction proceeds by the mechanism: Step 1 (slow): NO₂ + NO₂ → NO₃ + NO; Step 2 (fast): NO₃ + CO → NO₂ + CO₂. What is the predicted rate law for the overall reaction NO₂ + CO → NO + CO₂?","a":"rate = k[NO₂]²","w":["rate = k[NO₂][CO]","rate = k[NO₂]²[CO]","rate = k[NO₂][NO₃]"],"h":"The rate law is determined by the reactants in the rate-determining (slowest) elementary step.","e":"The slow first step involves two NO₂ molecules, so rate = k[NO₂]². CO appears only in the fast step and does not enter the rate law."},{"p":"A scuba tank has an internal volume of 10.0 L and contains gas at 25 °C and a pressure of 3.0 atm. Approximately how many moles of gas does it hold? (R = 0.0821 L·atm/(mol·K))","a":"1.2 mol","w":["12 mol","0.82 mol","2.4 mol"],"h":"Apply the ideal gas law PV = nRT, and remember to convert the temperature to kelvin.","e":"n = PV/RT = (3.0 atm)(10.0 L)/[(0.0821)(298 K)] ≈ 1.2 mol. Temperature must be in kelvin for the ideal gas law."},{"p":"Road crews add ionic solids to water to lower its freezing point. Which of the following 0.10 m aqueous solutions has the lowest freezing point?","a":"0.10 m CaCl₂","w":["0.10 m glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆)","0.10 m NaCl","0.10 m KBr"],"h":"Freezing-point depression is a colligative property that depends on the total concentration of dissolved particles (the van't Hoff factor).","e":"CaCl₂ dissociates into three ions (i = 3), producing the greatest number of particles and thus the largest freezing-point depression among these equal-molality solutions."},{"p":"Using average bond enthalpies (H–H = 436 kJ/mol, Cl–Cl = 242 kJ/mol, H–Cl = 431 kJ/mol), estimate ΔH for the reaction H₂(g) + Cl₂(g) → 2 HCl(g).","a":"−184 kJ","w":["+184 kJ","−92 kJ","−431 kJ"],"h":"ΔH ≈ (sum of bond enthalpies of bonds broken) − (sum of bond enthalpies of bonds formed).","e":"ΔH ≈ [436 + 242] − [2(431)] = 678 − 862 = −184 kJ. Breaking bonds absorbs energy while forming bonds releases it."}],"ap-eng-lit":[{"p":"Read: \"Her patience was a slow river, wearing down the stone of his resistance day after day, never rushing, never still.\"\n\nWhich figure of speech does the sentence primarily use to characterize the woman's patience?","a":"Metaphor, equating patience directly with a river without using \"like\" or \"as\"","w":["Simile, comparing patience to a river through an explicit connective","Hyperbole, deliberately exaggerating the woman's endurance for effect","Metonymy, substituting a related object for the idea of patience"],"h":"Look at whether the comparison uses a connective such as \"like\" or \"as,\" or states the identity outright.","e":"A metaphor asserts an implicit identity between two unlike things (\"patience was a slow river\") without \"like\" or \"as,\" unlike a simile."},{"p":"Read: \"The old man moved through the crowded market like a leaf carried on a current, drifting wherever the press of bodies took him.\"\n\nWhich figure of speech is used in this sentence?","a":"Simile, comparing the man's movement to a leaf using the connective \"like\"","w":["Metaphor, directly identifying the man as a leaf on a current","Personification, giving human traits to the leaf and the current","Apostrophe, directly addressing an absent or inanimate thing"],"h":"Check whether the comparison is stated directly or signaled by a connecting word.","e":"A simile compares two unlike things using \"like\" or \"as\" (\"like a leaf carried on a current\"), keeping the two terms distinct rather than merging them."},{"p":"Read: \"The wind gossiped at the shutters all night, prying at the latches and whispering the secrets of the road.\"\n\nWhat literary device is most clearly at work in this description of the wind?","a":"Personification, giving the wind human actions such as gossiping and whispering","w":["Onomatopoeia, using words that imitate the sounds the wind makes","Hyperbole, overstating the strength of the wind for dramatic effect","Simile, comparing the wind to a person by means of a connective"],"h":"Consider what kind of behavior the wind is being credited with here.","e":"Personification attributes human qualities or actions (gossiping, prying, whispering secrets) to a nonhuman thing, the wind."},{"p":"Read: \"Oh, splendid. Another Monday, another mountain of forms to sign, each one more urgently pointless than the last.\"\n\nWhich word best describes the speaker's tone?","a":"Sardonic, expressing scorn through mock enthusiasm and bitter wit","w":["Earnest, expressing sincere eagerness to begin the week's work","Reverent, expressing deep respect for the task being described","Melancholic, expressing quiet sorrow over an unavoidable loss"],"h":"Weigh the literal cheer of \"splendid\" against phrases like \"urgently pointless.\"","e":"Tone is the speaker's attitude toward the subject; here mock-praise (\"Oh, splendid\") paired with contempt (\"urgently pointless\") produces a sardonic tone."},{"p":"Scan the following line of verse: \"Shall I compare thee to a summer's day?\"\n\nWhat is the predominant meter of this line?","a":"Iambic pentameter, five iambic feet of an unstressed then a stressed syllable","w":["Trochaic tetrameter, four feet of a stressed then an unstressed syllable","Dactylic hexameter, six feet of one stressed and two unstressed syllables","Anapestic trimeter, three feet of two unstressed and one stressed syllable"],"h":"Count the stressed syllables and note whether each foot rises or falls.","e":"Iambic pentameter consists of five iambs (da-DUM) per line, the dominant meter of the English sonnet and Shakespeare's verse."},{"p":"Read: \"I pressed my palm against the cold glass and watched my own breath bloom and vanish, wondering whether anyone below could see me at all.\"\n\nFrom what point of view is this passage told?","a":"First person, narrated by a character using \"I\" who is inside the story","w":["Third-person limited, narrated by an outside voice tied to one mind","Third-person omniscient, narrated by an all-knowing outside voice","Second person, narrated using \"you\" to address the reader directly"],"h":"Notice which pronouns the narrator uses to refer to the observing self.","e":"First-person narration is delivered by a character within the story who refers to themselves as \"I,\" limiting us to that character's perceptions."},{"p":"A student says the theme of a story about a soldier returning home is simply \"war.\" Why is this an inadequate statement of theme?","a":"\"War\" is only the subject; a theme must state an insight or claim the work makes about that subject","w":["\"War\" is too specific; a theme must always be a single abstract noun","\"War\" names the setting; a theme must instead identify the plot's climax","\"War\" is figurative; a theme must be stated only in literal language"],"h":"Distinguish what a work is about from what it says about that topic.","e":"A subject is the topic (war), while a theme is a complete statement of the work's central insight or argument about that topic."},{"p":"Read: \"Marcus said nothing when the prize was announced. He set down his fork, folded his napkin into a neat square, and asked to be excused.\"\n\nHow does the author reveal Marcus's feelings here?","a":"Through indirect characterization, letting his actions imply his emotional state","w":["Through direct characterization, explicitly naming his disappointment","Through an epiphany, a sudden revelation that changes his outlook","Through a flashback, interrupting the scene with an earlier memory"],"h":"Ask whether the narrator states the emotion outright or shows behavior we must interpret.","e":"Indirect characterization reveals a character through actions, speech, or gestures the reader must interpret, rather than stating traits directly."},{"p":"Read: \"The road was a ribbon of moonlight over the purple moor, and the highwayman came riding, riding, riding, up to the old inn-door.\"\n\nWhich type of imagery is most prominent in this excerpt?","a":"Visual imagery, appealing chiefly to the reader's sense of sight","w":["Auditory imagery, appealing chiefly to the reader's sense of hearing","Tactile imagery, appealing chiefly to the reader's sense of touch","Olfactory imagery, appealing chiefly to the reader's sense of smell"],"h":"Identify which sense the concrete details (ribbon of moonlight, purple moor) most engage.","e":"Imagery is descriptive language appealing to the senses; \"ribbon of moonlight\" and \"purple moor\" are chiefly visual, engaging sight."},{"p":"In a novel, a caged bird that the protagonist keeps and finally releases comes to represent her longing for freedom. This use of a concrete object to stand for a larger abstract idea is best called what?","a":"Symbolism, in which an object carries meaning beyond its literal self","w":["Allusion, in which a text refers to another well-known work or figure","Foreshadowing, in which early details hint at later plot events","Motif, in which a single detail appears only once for emphasis"],"h":"Consider what happens when a literal object also points to an idea larger than itself.","e":"A symbol is a concrete image that represents an abstract idea; the caged bird literally exists yet also signifies the character's yearning for freedom."},{"p":"A character stands in a pouring rainstorm without an umbrella and mutters, \"What lovely weather we're having.\" What kind of irony is this?","a":"Verbal irony, in which the speaker's words mean the opposite of what is said","w":["Dramatic irony, in which the audience knows more than the character does","Situational irony, in which an outcome contradicts what was expected","Cosmic irony, in which fate or the universe seems to mock human plans"],"h":"Focus on the gap between the words spoken and the speaker's real meaning.","e":"Verbal irony occurs when a speaker says the opposite of what they mean; praising \"lovely weather\" during a downpour signals the intended contrast."},{"p":"Read: \"The silken sad uncertain rustling of each purple curtain.\"\n\nWhich sound device is most prominent in this line?","a":"Alliteration, the repetition of initial consonant sounds in nearby words","w":["Assonance, the repetition of vowel sounds in nearby stressed syllables","Onomatopoeia, the use of words that imitate the sounds they name","Consonance, the repetition of consonant sounds at the ends of words"],"h":"Read the line aloud and notice which repeated sounds begin the stressed words.","e":"Alliteration is the repetition of initial consonant sounds in neighboring words, heard here in the repeated \"s\" of \"silken sad.\""},{"p":"In a Petrarchan (Italian) sonnet, the turn or shift in argument or emotion that typically occurs between the octave and the sestet is known by what term?","a":"The volta, the structural turn that marks a shift in thought or feeling","w":["The couplet, a pair of rhymed lines that concludes the poem","The refrain, a line or phrase repeated at regular intervals","The caesura, a strong pause falling within a single line of verse"],"h":"Think about the word for the moment the poem pivots between its two main sections.","e":"The volta is the thematic or tonal \"turn\" in a sonnet, falling between octave and sestet in the Petrarchan form."},{"p":"Read: \"I have told you a thousand times, and I would tell the mountains and the seas if they would only listen, that I will never, ever leave this house.\"\n\nWhich device drives the exaggeration in this statement?","a":"Hyperbole, deliberate overstatement not meant to be taken literally","w":["Understatement, deliberately presenting something as less than it is","Paradox, a statement that seems contradictory yet reveals a truth","Oxymoron, a compact pairing of two contradictory terms"],"h":"Ask whether the speaker means the numbers and claims literally.","e":"Hyperbole is intentional exaggeration for emphasis or effect (\"a thousand times,\" telling the mountains), not meant to be read literally."},{"p":"When analyzing a poem, why is it a mistake to assume the \"I\" of the poem is the poet expressing personal feelings?","a":"The \"I\" is a speaker or persona, a constructed voice that may differ from the poet","w":["The \"I\" is always an allegory representing an entire social class","The \"I\" is the antagonist, whose views the poem exists to refute","The \"I\" is the narrator of a subplot separate from the main poem"],"h":"Consider the difference between the author and the voice the author creates.","e":"The speaker (or persona) is the voice created to deliver the poem and should not be automatically equated with the poet's own identity or views."},{"p":"Read: \"The abandoned house sagged under a sky the color of old bruises, its windows dark, its porch swallowed by weeds that hissed in the dry wind.\"\n\nWhat mood does this description primarily create?","a":"An ominous, desolate mood of decay and unease","w":["A serene, comforting mood of rest and safety","A festive, exuberant mood of celebration and joy","A nostalgic, tender mood of fond remembrance"],"h":"Gather the connotations of details like \"old bruises,\" \"dark,\" and \"swallowed by weeds.\"","e":"Mood is the emotional atmosphere a passage evokes in the reader; images of decay, darkness, and bruise-colored sky create an ominous, desolate mood."},{"p":"An author describes a politician's residence as \"the corridors of power.\" Substituting a closely associated attribute (the corridors) for the thing itself (governmental authority) is an example of what?","a":"Metonymy, naming something by an associated word rather than its own name","w":["Synecdoche, naming a whole by one of its constituent parts","Personification, granting human qualities to an abstract concept","Allusion, referencing a famous person, place, or earlier text"],"h":"Distinguish substituting an associated thing from substituting a literal part of the thing.","e":"Metonymy replaces a thing's name with something closely associated with it (\"corridors of power\" for governmental authority), as distinct from synecdoche's part-for-whole."},{"p":"In a story, a reckless, hot-tempered brother is placed beside a cautious, mild-mannered brother so that each one's traits stand out more sharply by comparison. What is the cautious brother functioning as?","a":"A foil, a character whose contrast highlights another character's qualities","w":["A protagonist, the central character whose goals drive the plot","An archetype, a universal character pattern recurring across literature","A confidant, a character in whom the hero privately confides"],"h":"Focus on the purpose served by pairing two characters with opposite traits.","e":"A foil is a character whose contrasting traits emphasize, by comparison, the distinctive qualities of another character."},{"p":"Read: \"The trees are coming into leaf / Like something almost being said.\"\n\nThe way the grammatical sense of the first line continues into the second without any pause or punctuation at the line break is called what?","a":"Enjambment","w":["End-stopped line","Caesura","Refrain"],"h":"Focus on what happens at the boundary between the two lines rather than within either line.","e":"Enjambment occurs when a syntactic unit runs over the end of a line into the next without terminal punctuation, in contrast to an end-stopped line."},{"p":"Read: \"She was not unfamiliar with hardship, having buried two husbands and raised six children entirely on her own.\"\n\nWhich figure of speech does the phrase \"not unfamiliar with hardship\" employ?","a":"Litotes","w":["Hyperbole","Euphemism","Paradox"],"h":"Consider the effect of stating something by negating its opposite rather than asserting it directly.","e":"Litotes is a form of deliberate understatement that affirms a quality by negating its contrary (\"not unfamiliar\" = very familiar)."},{"p":"Read: \"Emma set down her teacup and smiled. Really, was there ever such an insufferable man? He would spoil the evening, as he spoiled everything, and no one would say a word.\"\n\nWhich narrative technique renders Emma's private judgments in the third person here?","a":"Free indirect discourse","w":["First-person interior monologue","Objective (dramatic) narration","Second-person address"],"h":"Notice that the narrator uses \"she\" yet the exasperated voice clearly belongs to the character, not a detached observer.","e":"Free indirect discourse merges a third-person narrator's grammar with a character's own idiom and perspective, without quotation marks or a \"she thought\" tag."},{"p":"Read: \"Parting is such sweet sorrow.\"\n\nWhich device is created by the pairing of \"sweet\" and \"sorrow\"?","a":"Oxymoron","w":["Paradox","Hyperbole","Metonymy"],"h":"The device here is a compact pairing of two contradictory words placed side by side.","e":"An oxymoron yokes two contradictory terms into a single phrase; unlike a paradox, it operates at the level of adjacent words rather than a whole statement."},{"p":"Read: \"The child is father of the man.\"\n\nThis line makes a statement that seems self-contradictory yet expresses an underlying truth. What is this device called?","a":"Paradox","w":["Oxymoron","Synecdoche","Antithesis"],"h":"The contradiction here spans an entire assertion and dissolves once you interpret it, rather than sitting in a two-word pairing.","e":"A paradox is a statement that appears logically contradictory but, on reflection, reveals a coherent truth; it works at the level of a whole proposition."},{"p":"Read: \"O eloquent, just, and mighty Death! whom none could advise, thou hast persuaded.\"\n\nBy directly addressing Death as though it could listen, the speaker primarily uses which device?","a":"Apostrophe","w":["Personification","Allusion","Invocation of the muse"],"h":"The key move is speaking to something that cannot actually answer, as if it were present and attending.","e":"Apostrophe is a direct address to an absent person, abstraction, or thing; though Death is also personified, the defining gesture is the address itself."},{"p":"Read: \"She left in a fury and a taxi.\"\n\nA single verb (\"left\") governs two grammatically parallel but semantically mismatched objects (\"a fury\" and \"a taxi\"). What is this device?","a":"Zeugma","w":["Parallelism","Antithesis","Metaphor"],"h":"Look at how one word is made to yoke together two objects that belong to different categories, one abstract and one concrete.","e":"Zeugma (syllepsis) uses one word to govern two others in different senses, producing a witty or jarring yoking of the literal and figurative."},{"p":"Read: \"The captain needed fifty able hands to crew the ship before the storm arrived.\"\n\nUsing \"hands\" to mean whole sailors is an example of which figure of speech?","a":"Synecdoche","w":["Metonymy","Personification","Metaphor"],"h":"Ask whether \"hands\" is literally a physical part of the people being referred to, or merely something associated with them.","e":"Synecdoche substitutes a part for the whole (or vice versa); it differs from metonymy, which substitutes a closely associated concept rather than a component part."},{"p":"Scan the following line of verse: \"Whose woods these are I think I know.\"\n\nWhat is the predominant meter of this line?","a":"Iambic tetrameter","w":["Iambic pentameter","Trochaic tetrameter","Anapestic trimeter"],"h":"Count the syllables and the number of stressed beats, then identify whether each foot rises or falls.","e":"The line has four unstressed-stressed (iambic) feet across eight syllables, making it iambic tetrameter rather than the five-foot pentameter."},{"p":"In an English (Shakespearean) sonnet, the turn of thought (volta) and the poem's resolution most characteristically arrive in which structural unit?","a":"The final rhyming couplet","w":["The opening quatrain","The break between octave and sestet","The third quatrain's first line"],"h":"Recall how the fourteen lines of this sonnet type are grouped and where the epigrammatic clincher tends to fall.","e":"The Shakespearean sonnet's three quatrains build an argument that the closing couplet resolves or reverses; the octave/sestet turn belongs to the Petrarchan form."},{"p":"Read: \"The rain in Spain stays mainly in the plain.\"\n\nWhich sound device is most prominent in this line?","a":"Assonance","w":["Consonance","Alliteration","Onomatopoeia"],"h":"Listen for a repeated vowel sound recurring across stressed syllables rather than repeated consonants.","e":"Assonance is the repetition of internal vowel sounds (the long \"a\" in rain, Spain, mainly, plain); consonance and alliteration concern consonant sounds."},{"p":"Read: \"Our two souls, therefore, which are one, / Though I must go, endure not yet / A breach, but an expansion, / Like gold to airy thinness beat.\"\n\nThe poet develops the comparison of the lovers' souls to beaten gold across several lines and later to a compass. What is this sustained comparison called?","a":"Extended metaphor (conceit)","w":["Simile","Allegory","Personification"],"h":"Consider that a single figurative comparison is elaborated and carried through multiple lines rather than stated once.","e":"An extended metaphor, or metaphysical conceit, elaborates a single figurative comparison at length; a simile would require \"like\" or \"as\" for each individual likeness."},{"p":"A novel's narrator reports the private thoughts, memories, and hidden motives of every major character and even comments on events none of them witnessed. This narrative stance is best described as what?","a":"Third-person omniscient","w":["Third-person limited","First-person peripheral","Objective (dramatic) point of view"],"h":"The decisive clue is how many minds the narrator can enter and whether the knowledge is confined to one figure.","e":"A third-person omniscient narrator has unrestricted access to all characters' inner lives and events; a limited narrator is confined to one character's perspective."},{"p":"Read: \"To err is human; to forgive, divine.\"\n\nThe pause created within the line at the semicolon is known by what technical term?","a":"Caesura","w":["Enjambment","End rhyme","Anaphora"],"h":"The term names a break located inside a line of verse, not at its end.","e":"A caesura is a sense pause within a metrical line, often marked by punctuation; enjambment, by contrast, describes a line running on without pause."},{"p":"Throughout a novel about mortality, the author repeatedly introduces images of stopped clocks, tolling bells, and wilting flowers. This recurring pattern of related images is best labeled as what?","a":"Motif","w":["Symbol","Theme","Allegory"],"h":"Distinguish a single object that stands for an idea from a pattern that recurs and accumulates meaning across the whole work.","e":"A motif is a recurring image, idea, or element that unifies a work and reinforces its themes; a single such object functioning representationally would be a symbol."},{"p":"Read: \"He launched the reckless scheme with the giddy confidence of a boy fitting on wings of wax and feathers.\"\n\nThe reference to wings of wax and feathers most directly functions as what device?","a":"Allusion","w":["Extended metaphor","Personification","Hyperbole"],"h":"Consider whether the phrase gains its meaning by pointing to a well-known story outside the text.","e":"An allusion is a brief, indirect reference to a familiar person, myth, or text (here the myth of Icarus) that imports its associations into the passage."},{"p":"Read: \"The town's brand-new fire station burned to the ground on the very night of its grand opening.\"\n\nThe gap between the expected outcome and what actually happens illustrates which type of irony?","a":"Situational irony","w":["Dramatic irony","Verbal irony","Sarcasm"],"h":"Determine whether the irony lies in an unexpected turn of events, a character's ignorance, or a speaker meaning the opposite of what is said.","e":"Situational irony arises when the actual result of a situation sharply contradicts the expected result; dramatic and verbal irony depend on audience knowledge or a speaker's intent."},{"p":"Read: \"We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds, we shall fight in the fields and in the streets.\"\n\nThe repetition of \"we shall fight\" at the beginning of successive clauses is called what?","a":"Anaphora","w":["Epistrophe","Chiasmus","Assonance"],"h":"Note precisely where in each clause the repeated phrase falls.","e":"Anaphora is the repetition of the same word or phrase at the start of successive clauses; epistrophe is the same device at the end of clauses."},{"p":"Read: \"The audience has just watched the servant slip poison into the goblet. Moments later, the unsuspecting king raises that very cup and toasts to his own good health.\"\n\nWhich type of irony arises here from the audience knowing what the king does not?","a":"Dramatic irony","w":["Situational irony","Verbal irony","Cosmic irony"],"h":"Focus on the gap between what the audience has witnessed and what the character on stage understands.","e":"Dramatic irony occurs when the audience possesses knowledge that a character lacks, creating tension between the character's confident words or actions and the reality the audience already sees."},{"p":"Scan the following line of verse: \"Tyger Tyger, burning bright,\"\n\nWhat is the predominant meter of this line?","a":"Trochaic tetrameter","w":["Iambic tetrameter","Trochaic pentameter","Anapestic tetrameter"],"h":"Decide whether each foot runs stressed-unstressed or unstressed-stressed, then count the feet.","e":"The line divides into four trochees (stressed-unstressed): TY-ger TY-ger BURN-ing BRIGHT, making it trochaic tetrameter, with the final foot catalectic (missing its last unstressed syllable)."},{"p":"Scan the following line of verse: \"The Assyrian came down like the wolf on the fold,\"\n\nWhat is the predominant meter of this line?","a":"Anapestic tetrameter","w":["Dactylic tetrameter","Anapestic trimeter","Iambic pentameter"],"h":"Look for a repeating pattern of two unstressed syllables followed by a stressed one, then count how many times it recurs.","e":"Byron's line is built from four anapests (unstressed-unstressed-stressed): 'the As-SYR / ian came DOWN / like the WOLF / on the FOLD,' making it anapestic tetrameter."},{"p":"Read: \"Ask not what your country can do for you; ask what you can do for your country.\"\n\nThe reversal of grammatical order in the second clause is best identified as which device?","a":"Chiasmus (antimetabole)","w":["Anaphora","Antithesis","Parallelism"],"h":"Notice how the key terms from the first half return in reversed order in the second half.","e":"Chiasmus, and specifically antimetabole, repeats words or grammatical structures in inverted order (A-B, B-A), as Kennedy inverts 'you' and 'your country.'"},{"p":"Read: \"I came, I saw, I conquered.\"\n\nThe deliberate omission of conjunctions between these parallel clauses is called what?","a":"Asyndeton","w":["Polysyndeton","Parataxis","Ellipsis"],"h":"Focus on what connecting word has been left out between the coordinated clauses.","e":"Asyndeton omits conjunctions such as 'and' between coordinated words or clauses, quickening the pace and lending Caesar's tricolon its clipped force."},{"p":"Read: \"We lived and laughed and loved and left, and never once looked back.\"\n\nThe deliberate use of more conjunctions than grammar requires is called what?","a":"Polysyndeton","w":["Asyndeton","Anaphora","Epistrophe"],"h":"Focus on the repeated connecting word inserted between each item.","e":"Polysyndeton inserts conjunctions between successive words or clauses beyond grammatical need, slowing the rhythm and giving each element added weight."},{"p":"Read: \"The trumpet's blare was a scorching orange that stung the ear and left a bitter taste on the tongue.\"\n\nDescribing a sound in terms of color, heat, and taste exemplifies which device?","a":"Synesthesia","w":["Metonymy","Onomatopoeia","Personification"],"h":"Notice how one kind of sensory experience is described using the vocabulary of entirely different senses.","e":"Synesthesia blends or transfers one sensory mode into another, here rendering an auditory experience through sight, temperature, and taste."},{"p":"Read: \"When I was a child, I spoke as a child, I understood as a child, I thought as a child.\"\n\nThe repetition of \"as a child\" at the end of successive clauses is called what?","a":"Epistrophe","w":["Anaphora","Anadiplosis","Symploce"],"h":"Identify the position within each clause where the repeated phrase falls.","e":"Epistrophe (or epiphora) repeats the same word or phrase at the end of successive clauses, functioning as the mirror image of anaphora."},{"p":"Read: \"He lay awake through another sleepless night, staring at the indifferent walls of the condemned cell.\"\n\nIn the phrase \"sleepless night,\" a modifier that logically belongs to the person is attached to a nearby noun. What is this device?","a":"Transferred epithet (hypallage)","w":["Personification","Synecdoche","Metonymy"],"h":"Ask which noun the adjective truly describes versus the noun it is grammatically attached to.","e":"A transferred epithet (hypallage) shifts a modifier from the noun it logically qualifies (the sleepless person) onto an adjacent noun (the night)."},{"p":"Read: \"It was the best of times, it was the worst of times.\"\n\nThe pairing of contrasting ideas in balanced grammatical structures is called what?","a":"Antithesis","w":["Oxymoron","Paradox","Chiasmus"],"h":"Look for opposing ideas set against each other in matching parallel form.","e":"Antithesis places contrasting ideas in parallel grammatical structures to sharpen the opposition; unlike an oxymoron, its contrasts occupy full parallel clauses rather than adjacent words."},{"p":"A poem is composed throughout in unrhymed lines of iambic pentameter. What is this verse form called?","a":"Blank verse","w":["Free verse","Heroic couplet","Terza rima"],"h":"The lines keep a fixed meter but follow no rhyme scheme.","e":"Blank verse is unrhymed iambic pentameter; it differs from free verse, which lacks a regular meter, and from rhymed forms such as the heroic couplet."},{"p":"Read: \"I heard a Fly buzz — when I died — / The Stillness in the Room / Was like the Stillness in the Air — / Between the Heaves of Storm —\"\n\nThe pairing of \"Room\" and \"Storm,\" which share consonant sounds but not vowel sounds, is an example of what?","a":"Slant rhyme","w":["Eye rhyme","Internal rhyme","Feminine rhyme"],"h":"The two words nearly rhyme, but their vowel sounds differ while their consonants echo.","e":"Slant (or near/half) rhyme uses similar but not identical sounds, often matching consonants while vowels diverge, as in Dickinson's 'Room'/'Storm.'"},{"p":"Read: \"As the funeral procession wound up the hill, the sky itself seemed to grieve, the clouds sagging low and weeping a cold, ceaseless rain.\"\n\nAttributing human emotion to nature so that the weather mirrors the mourners' grief is best termed what?","a":"Pathetic fallacy","w":["Objective correlative","Anthropomorphism","Apostrophe"],"h":"The precise term, coined by Ruskin, names nature reflecting human feeling.","e":"Pathetic fallacy (Ruskin's term) ascribes human emotions to nature, typically so the environment mirrors a character's mood; it is a specialized form of personification."},{"p":"A single fictional speaker, who is not the poet, addresses a silent listener at a charged moment and unintentionally exposes his own character, as in Browning's \"My Last Duchess.\" This poetic form is called what?","a":"Dramatic monologue","w":["Soliloquy","Interior monologue","Aside"],"h":"Note that an implied listener is present throughout, though that listener never speaks.","e":"A dramatic monologue presents a single speaker distinct from the poet addressing an implied auditor and revealing character unwittingly; a soliloquy, by contrast, is spoken by a character alone."},{"p":"Read: \"I am not mad; I have never been calmer. Listen to how carefully, how sanely I can tell you the whole story of why the old man had to die.\"\n\nThe narrator's protests, which lead the reader to distrust his account, mark him as what?","a":"An unreliable narrator","w":["An omniscient narrator","An objective narrator","A stream-of-consciousness narrator"],"h":"Consider whether the reader is meant to accept the narrator's self-assessment at face value.","e":"An unreliable narrator's account cannot be fully trusted, often owing to bias, instability, or self-deception, prompting readers to read against the narration."},{"p":"A novel opens in the midst of a raging battle and only later, through flashback, reveals how the war began. This technique of beginning in the middle of the action is called what?","a":"In medias res","w":["Frame narrative","Flashback (analepsis)","Foreshadowing"],"h":"The Latin term describes where the narrative begins relative to the chronology of events.","e":"In medias res ('into the middle of things') launches a narrative at a crucial point in the action, with earlier events supplied afterward through exposition or flashback."},{"p":"Read: \"As when a mountain lion, ranging the hills in hunger, spies a flock and, heedless of the shepherds' cries, leaps the fold to seize his prey — so Hector fell upon the trembling ranks.\"\n\nThis extended, elaborately developed comparison in the Homeric manner is best called what?","a":"An epic (Homeric) simile","w":["A metaphysical conceit","An allegory","A synecdoche"],"h":"Consider the unusual length and elaboration of the comparison and its epic pedigree.","e":"An epic (Homeric) simile is an extended simile, often running several lines, that develops the vehicle in vivid narrative detail; it differs from the metaphysical conceit, which yokes intellectually surprising ideas."},{"p":"Read: \"Fear leads to anger. Anger leads to hate. Hate leads to suffering.\"\n\nRepeating the last word of one clause at the start of the next is called what?","a":"Anadiplosis","w":["Epistrophe","Epanalepsis","Anaphora"],"h":"Trace how the word that ends one clause reappears to open the following clause.","e":"Anadiplosis repeats the final word or phrase of one clause at the beginning of the next, forging a linked chain of ideas."}],"ap-envsci":[{"p":"Which of the following best describes the role of nitrogen-fixing bacteria in the nitrogen cycle?","a":"They convert atmospheric N2 gas into ammonia (NH3/NH4+) that plants can use","w":["They convert nitrates (NO3-) back into atmospheric N2 gas","They convert ammonia (NH3) into nitrites and then nitrates","They break down dead organic matter into inorganic phosphate"],"h":"Atmospheric N2 is very stable and most organisms cannot use it directly.","e":"Nitrogen fixation converts inert atmospheric N2 into biologically available ammonia; without it, most producers could not access nitrogen despite its atmospheric abundance."},{"p":"A population of rabbits grows in an environment with unlimited resources and no predators. Which growth pattern and curve shape best describes this population?","a":"Exponential growth, producing a J-shaped curve","w":["Logistic growth, producing an S-shaped curve","Zero population growth, producing a flat line","Linear growth, producing a straight diagonal line"],"h":"Consider what happens to growth rate when nothing limits reproduction.","e":"With unlimited resources, populations grow exponentially at rate dN/dt = rN, generating a J-shaped curve; limits produce logistic S-shaped growth instead."},{"p":"In a typical food chain, roughly what percentage of energy is transferred from one trophic level to the next?","a":"About 10%","w":["About 50%","About 90%","About 1%"],"h":"Most energy at each level is lost as heat during cellular respiration.","e":"The 10% rule states that only about 10% of energy at one trophic level is stored as biomass available to the next; the rest is lost mainly as heat through respiration."},{"p":"Which of the following is a density-dependent factor limiting population growth?","a":"Competition for food among members of the population","w":["A hurricane that floods the habitat","A sudden volcanic eruption","An unusually cold winter freeze"],"h":"Ask whether the factor's effect gets stronger as more individuals crowd together.","e":"Density-dependent factors like competition, disease, and predation intensify as population density rises; density-independent factors (e.g., weather) act regardless of density."},{"p":"Which characteristics are typical of a K-selected species?","a":"Few offspring, extensive parental care, and long lifespan","w":["Many offspring, little parental care, and short lifespan","Rapid maturation and boom-and-bust population cycles","Small body size and high early mortality of young"],"h":"Think of large mammals like elephants versus insects that produce thousands of eggs.","e":"K-selected species are adapted to stable environments near carrying capacity, investing in few, well-cared-for offspring; r-selected species produce many offspring with little care."},{"p":"The primary greenhouse gas responsible for the largest share of human-caused enhanced global warming is:","a":"Carbon dioxide (CO2)","w":["Methane (CH4)","Nitrous oxide (N2O)","Ozone (O3)"],"h":"Consider which gas is released in the greatest quantity by burning fossil fuels.","e":"Although methane traps more heat per molecule, CO2's much larger emission volume from fossil fuel combustion makes it the leading contributor to enhanced warming."},{"p":"During ecological succession, which term describes the first species to colonize a bare, lifeless area such as newly cooled lava rock?","a":"Pioneer species","w":["Climax species","Keystone species","Indicator species"],"h":"These organisms, often lichens, arrive where no soil yet exists.","e":"Primary succession begins with pioneer species such as lichens and mosses that break down rock to form soil, enabling later successional stages."},{"p":"Which of the following is a renewable energy source that produces no direct CO2 emissions during electricity generation?","a":"Wind power","w":["Natural gas","Coal","Oil"],"h":"Look for the source that relies on moving air rather than combustion.","e":"Wind turbines generate electricity from moving air with no combustion and no direct CO2 emissions, unlike fossil fuels."},{"p":"A keystone species is best defined as one that:","a":"Has a disproportionately large effect on its community relative to its abundance","w":["Is always the most abundant species in the ecosystem","Occupies the highest trophic level in the food web","Was the first species to colonize the ecosystem"],"h":"The importance of this species is not measured by how many individuals there are.","e":"Keystone species, like sea otters controlling urchins, exert outsized influence on community structure; removing them causes dramatic ecosystem changes despite low abundance."},{"p":"Which soil horizon is the topmost layer richest in decomposed organic matter (humus)?","a":"The O and A horizons (topsoil)","w":["The C horizon (parent material)","The B horizon (subsoil)","The bedrock (R horizon)"],"h":"Fertile topsoil is nearest the surface where leaves and organisms accumulate.","e":"The O horizon (organic litter) and A horizon (topsoil) contain the most humus and nutrients, making them the most fertile layers for plant growth."},{"p":"The albedo effect refers to:","a":"The fraction of solar radiation reflected by a surface back into space","w":["The trapping of infrared radiation by greenhouse gases","The gradual acidification of ocean water by CO2","The depletion of stratospheric ozone by CFCs"],"h":"Think about why ice and snow appear bright compared to dark ocean water.","e":"Albedo measures reflectivity; light surfaces like ice have high albedo and reflect sunlight, while dark surfaces like oceans absorb it, influencing climate feedbacks."},{"p":"Eutrophication of a lake is most directly caused by:","a":"Excess nutrients such as nitrogen and phosphorus from fertilizer runoff","w":["Thermal pollution from power plant cooling water","Acid deposition from sulfur dioxide emissions","Introduction of an invasive fish predator"],"h":"Consider what nutrients in agricultural runoff fuel algal blooms.","e":"Cultural eutrophication results from nutrient loading that triggers algal blooms; their decomposition depletes dissolved oxygen, creating hypoxic dead zones."},{"p":"Which of the following best explains why the ozone layer in the stratosphere is important to life on Earth?","a":"It absorbs harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the Sun","w":["It traps infrared radiation and warms the planet","It provides oxygen for organisms to breathe","It reflects incoming meteors and space debris"],"h":"This layer protects living things from a specific harmful type of solar radiation.","e":"Stratospheric ozone shields organisms by absorbing high-energy UV-B radiation; its depletion by CFCs increases skin cancer and ecosystem damage."},{"p":"According to the demographic transition model, a country in Stage 2 typically experiences:","a":"Declining death rates while birth rates remain high, causing rapid population growth","w":["High and roughly equal birth and death rates, so population is stable","Low birth and death rates, so population growth slows to near zero","Birth rates falling below death rates, causing population decline"],"h":"Focus on the gap that opens between falling death rates and still-high birth rates.","e":"In Stage 2, improved medicine and sanitation lower death rates while birth rates stay high, producing the fastest population growth of the transition."},{"p":"The burning of fossil fuels contributes to acid deposition primarily by releasing which pollutants?","a":"Sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx)","w":["Carbon dioxide (CO2) and methane (CH4)","Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and halons","Carbon monoxide (CO) and lead (Pb)"],"h":"These oxides form sulfuric and nitric acids when they react with atmospheric water.","e":"SO2 and NOx react with water in the atmosphere to form sulfuric and nitric acids, lowering the pH of rain and harming aquatic and forest ecosystems."},{"p":"Which agricultural practice best reduces soil erosion on sloped farmland?","a":"Contour plowing along the natural contours of the land","w":["Plowing straight up and down the slope for efficiency","Removing all crop residue after each harvest","Applying maximum irrigation to bare soil"],"h":"Think about plowing that runs across a slope rather than up and down it.","e":"Contour plowing follows land contours to slow water runoff and reduce erosion; plowing up and down slopes accelerates soil loss."},{"p":"A biome characterized by permafrost, low precipitation, short growing seasons, and no trees is the:","a":"Tundra","w":["Taiga (boreal forest)","Temperate grassland","Desert"],"h":"Frozen subsoil year-round prevents trees from establishing deep roots.","e":"The tundra features permafrost that prevents deep root growth, so trees are absent; low temperatures and precipitation limit vegetation to lichens, mosses, and shrubs."},{"p":"Ocean acidification, driven by increasing atmospheric CO2, most directly harms marine organisms by:","a":"Reducing carbonate ions needed to build calcium carbonate shells and skeletons","w":["Raising ocean temperatures beyond thermal tolerance limits","Blocking sunlight needed for phytoplankton photosynthesis","Increasing dissolved oxygen to toxic levels for fish"],"h":"Think about what corals and shellfish need to build their hard structures.","e":"Dissolved CO2 forms carbonic acid, lowering pH and carbonate availability, which impairs shell and coral formation in calcifying organisms."},{"p":"A country's population grows at a constant 2% per year. Using the rule of 70, approximately how many years will it take for the population to double?","a":"About 35 years","w":["About 70 years","About 140 years","About 14 years"],"h":"The rule of 70 relates a percentage growth rate to a doubling time using a simple division.","e":"By the rule of 70, doubling time is approximately 70 divided by the percent growth rate, so 70/2 = 35 years."},{"p":"A persistent, fat-soluble pollutant such as DDT enters an aquatic food web. In which organisms would you expect to measure the highest tissue concentration of the pollutant?","a":"Top predators such as ospreys and eagles","w":["Primary producers such as phytoplankton","Decomposers such as fungi and bacteria","Primary consumers such as zooplankton"],"h":"Consider what happens to a non-degradable, fat-stored toxin as it moves up successive trophic levels.","e":"Biomagnification causes fat-soluble, persistent toxins to increase in concentration at each higher trophic level, peaking in top predators."},{"p":"According to the logistic growth model, the number of individuals added to a population per unit time (the growth rate) is greatest when the population size is:","a":"At about half the carrying capacity (K/2)","w":["At the carrying capacity (K)","Just above the carrying capacity","Near zero (a very small population)"],"h":"Think about the inflection point of the S-shaped logistic curve, where the slope is steepest.","e":"In logistic growth the maximum rate of increase (and maximum sustainable yield) occurs at K/2, the inflection point of the S-curve."},{"p":"A grassland has a gross primary productivity (GPP) of 10,000 kcal/m2/yr, and its plants use 4,000 kcal/m2/yr in cellular respiration. What is the net primary productivity (NPP)?","a":"6,000 kcal/m2/yr","w":["14,000 kcal/m2/yr","10,000 kcal/m2/yr","4,000 kcal/m2/yr"],"h":"NPP is the energy left for growth and storage after producers pay their own metabolic costs.","e":"NPP = GPP minus respiration, so 10,000 - 4,000 = 6,000 kcal/m2/yr represents energy available to consumers."},{"p":"A nation's age-structure diagram shows a very broad base that narrows sharply toward the top. This shape most likely indicates:","a":"A rapidly growing population with many pre-reproductive individuals","w":["A stable population with roughly equal numbers in each age class","A declining population with more elderly than young people","A population that has already reached zero population growth"],"h":"A wide base means a large share of the population has not yet reached reproductive age.","e":"A pyramid with a broad base and narrow top signals a high proportion of young (pre-reproductive) people and rapid future population growth."},{"p":"A government policy sets a firm overall limit on total emissions and issues allowances that companies may buy and sell among themselves. This market-based approach is known as:","a":"Cap-and-trade","w":["Command-and-control regulation","A green (Pigovian) tax","The tragedy of the commons"],"h":"The defining features are a fixed ceiling on emissions plus tradable permits.","e":"Cap-and-trade caps total emissions and lets firms trade allowances, using market incentives to reduce pollution where it is cheapest."},{"p":"Individual fishers, each acting in their own self-interest, collectively overharvest a shared, unregulated ocean fishery until it collapses. This scenario best illustrates:","a":"The tragedy of the commons","w":["Maximum sustainable yield","The precautionary principle","A density-independent limiting factor"],"h":"The problem arises specifically because the resource is shared and open-access with no ownership.","e":"The tragedy of the commons describes the depletion of a shared, unregulated resource by users pursuing individual short-term gain."},{"p":"Which of the following is best classified as a NONPOINT source of water pollution?","a":"Fertilizer runoff from many suburban lawns across a watershed","w":["A discharge pipe from a single factory","A leaking underground storage tank at one gas station","Effluent from a wastewater treatment plant outfall"],"h":"Nonpoint sources cannot be traced to one identifiable point of entry.","e":"Nonpoint-source pollution comes from diffuse, widespread runoff rather than a single identifiable discharge point."},{"p":"On a cold, still morning in a valley, a layer of warm air settles above cooler air near the ground, trapping vehicle exhaust and smog close to the surface. This atmospheric condition is called:","a":"A temperature (thermal) inversion","w":["The enhanced greenhouse effect","Normal atmospheric convection","A rain-shadow effect"],"h":"Normally air cools with altitude; here the usual vertical temperature pattern is reversed.","e":"A thermal inversion places warm air over cold air, preventing the vertical mixing that would otherwise disperse pollutants."},{"p":"During a strong El Nino event, which change typically occurs in the surface waters off the coast of Peru?","a":"Upwelling of cold, nutrient-rich water weakens, reducing fish populations","w":["Upwelling strengthens, boosting fish populations","Coastal surface waters become unusually cold","Trade winds intensify, pushing warm water westward"],"h":"El Nino is associated with weakened trade winds and warmer eastern Pacific surface water.","e":"During El Nino (part of ENSO), reduced trade winds suppress coastal upwelling off Peru, cutting nutrient supply and fishery productivity."},{"p":"A radioactive isotope in nuclear waste has a half-life of 30 years. After 90 years, what fraction of the original sample remains radioactive?","a":"1/8","w":["1/3","1/6","1/9"],"h":"First determine how many half-lives fit into the elapsed time, then halve repeatedly.","e":"90 years equals three half-lives (90/30 = 3), and (1/2)^3 = 1/8 of the original remains."},{"p":"Which characteristic most commonly enables an introduced species to become invasive in a new ecosystem?","a":"A lack of natural predators, parasites, or competitors in the new range","w":["A narrow tolerance range for environmental conditions","A slow reproductive rate and long generation time","A high degree of specialization on a single food source"],"h":"Think about what population controls an introduced species escapes when it arrives without its native enemies.","e":"Invasive species often thrive because they leave behind their natural predators and competitors, allowing unchecked population growth."},{"p":"A farmer plants a leguminous cover crop such as clover during the off-season instead of leaving fields bare. Which pair of benefits does this practice most directly provide?","a":"Reduced soil erosion and increased soil nitrogen","w":["Increased soil erosion and reduced soil nitrogen","Increased soil salinization and reduced infiltration","Reduced water infiltration and increased surface runoff"],"h":"Consider both the physical protection of the soil surface and the special trait of legumes.","e":"Legume cover crops shield soil from erosion and, through symbiotic nitrogen fixation, add nitrogen to the soil."},{"p":"Prolonged, excessive pumping from a groundwater well lowers the water table into a downward-sloping funnel shape immediately around the well. This feature is called a:","a":"Cone of depression","w":["Recharge zone","Confined aquifer","Zone of aeration"],"h":"The name describes the shape the water table takes right around a heavily pumped well.","e":"A cone of depression is the funnel-shaped lowering of the water table caused by withdrawing groundwater faster than it recharges."},{"p":"Among common solid fuels, which type of coal has the highest carbon content and yields the most energy per unit mass when burned?","a":"Anthracite","w":["Lignite","Peat","Bituminous coal"],"h":"Ranking follows the degree of geologic compaction and carbon concentration over time.","e":"Anthracite is the most compressed, highest-carbon coal, giving it the greatest energy content per unit mass."},{"p":"Two forest plots each contain 100 trees representing 5 species. Plot A has 96 trees of one species and 1 of each of the other four; Plot B has 20 trees of each species. Which statement is correct?","a":"Both plots have equal species richness, but Plot B has greater species evenness","w":["Plot A has both greater richness and greater evenness","Plot B has greater richness but lower evenness","The two plots are identical in every measure of biodiversity"],"h":"Separate the count of different species from how equally individuals are distributed among them.","e":"Species richness counts the number of species (5 in each), while evenness measures how equally individuals are distributed; Plot B is far more even."},{"p":"Warm air rises at the equator, cools and releases moisture, then descends as dry air near 30 degrees latitude, where many of Earth's major deserts occur. This atmospheric circulation loop is called a:","a":"Hadley cell","w":["Ferrel cell","Coriolis cell","Polar cell"],"h":"This is the tropical circulation cell whose descending dry limb sits around 30 degrees latitude.","e":"Hadley cells circulate air between the equator and about 30 degrees latitude; their descending dry air creates the subtropical desert belts."},{"p":"In a developed country with low infant mortality, the replacement-level total fertility rate is generally considered to be approximately:","a":"2.1 children per woman","w":["1.0 child per woman","3.0 children per woman","4.2 children per woman"],"h":"Replacement level slightly exceeds two because not every child survives to reproduce.","e":"Replacement-level fertility is about 2.1, the two children needed to replace the parents plus a small allowance for childhood mortality."},{"p":"Which of the following best describes the driving mechanism of the global ocean 'conveyor belt' (thermohaline circulation)?","a":"Differences in seawater density caused by variations in temperature and salinity","w":["Prevailing surface winds pushing water westward along the equator","The gravitational pull of the moon generating deep tidal currents","Freshwater river runoff delivering sediment to coastal zones"],"h":"The name itself points to the two water properties that together control seawater density.","e":"Thermohaline circulation is driven by density differences from temperature (thermo) and salinity (haline); cold, salty water sinks and powers deep-ocean flow."},{"p":"A wind farm has a rated (nameplate) capacity of 100 MW. Over one year (8,760 hours) it actually generates 262,800 MWh of electricity. What is its capacity factor?","a":"30%","w":["3%","50%","88%"],"h":"Divide the actual output by the maximum output the farm would produce running at full rated power the whole year.","e":"Capacity factor = actual output / (rated power x time) = 262,800 / (100 x 8,760) = 0.30, or 30%, a typical value for onshore wind."},{"p":"Long-term, natural cycles of glacial and interglacial periods over tens of thousands of years are best explained by:","a":"Periodic variations in Earth's orbit, axial tilt, and precession (Milankovitch cycles)","w":["Regular fluctuations in the atmospheric concentration of CFCs","Cyclic reversals of Earth's magnetic poles over time","Periodic changes in the rate of continental plate drift"],"h":"These cycles concern the geometry of Earth's path around, and spin relative to, the Sun.","e":"Milankovitch cycles—eccentricity, obliquity (tilt), and precession—alter the distribution and intensity of incoming solar radiation, pacing ice-age cycles."},{"p":"As Arctic permafrost thaws, it releases stored methane and CO2, which intensify warming and cause still more thawing. This self-reinforcing process is an example of:","a":"A positive feedback loop","w":["A negative feedback loop","A density-dependent limiting factor","A homeostatic buffering mechanism"],"h":"Consider whether the initial change is amplified or dampened by the effects it triggers.","e":"A positive feedback loop amplifies an initial change; permafrost thaw releasing greenhouse gases that drive further warming is a classic climate example."},{"p":"An oyster releases millions of eggs, most of which die as larvae, but the few that survive to adulthood live a relatively long time. Which survivorship curve does this species exhibit?","a":"Type III, with high mortality early in life","w":["Type I, with high mortality late in life","Type II, with constant mortality across all ages","Type IV, with high mortality only in middle age"],"h":"Think about which life stage accounts for the vast majority of deaths in this species.","e":"Type III survivorship curves show very high juvenile mortality with high survival among the few reaching adulthood—typical of r-selected species like oysters."},{"p":"Read: 'Five warbler species feed on insects in the same spruce trees, but each forages in a different zone—outer branches, inner branches, treetop, or lower trunk.' This division of a shared habitat most directly illustrates:","a":"Resource partitioning that reduces interspecific competition","w":["Competitive exclusion eliminating all but one species","Mutualism that benefits all five warbler species","Primary succession occurring within the tree canopy"],"h":"The species coexist by using the same general resource in slightly different ways.","e":"Resource partitioning lets species divide a shared resource (feeding zones), reducing niche overlap and enabling coexistence rather than competitive exclusion."},{"p":"A barnacle species can physiologically survive across a wide vertical range of a rocky shore, but competition with a stronger species confines it to only the upper zone. The upper zone it actually occupies represents its:","a":"Realized niche","w":["Fundamental niche","Habitat carrying capacity","Ecological footprint"],"h":"Distinguish where a species could live from where it actually ends up living once competitors are present.","e":"The fundamental niche is the full range a species can tolerate; the realized niche is the portion actually occupied after biotic interactions such as competition."},{"p":"Abandoned coal mines often leak water with very low pH that stains downstream creeks orange. This acid mine drainage forms primarily when:","a":"Sulfide minerals such as pyrite, exposed by mining, react with water and oxygen to form sulfuric acid","w":["Carbonate rocks dissolve and release carbonic acid into the groundwater","Nitrogen fertilizers from nearby farms leach downward into the mine shafts","Chlorine used to treat mine water combines with dissolved iron and metals"],"h":"The culprit is a common iron-sulfur mineral in coal seams reacting with air and water.","e":"Acid mine drainage results from oxidation of pyrite (FeS2) exposed during mining, producing sulfuric acid and dissolved iron that acidify and discolor waterways."},{"p":"In an arid region, decades of flood irrigation followed by rapid evaporation have left a white crust on the soil surface, reducing crop yields. This form of soil degradation is called:","a":"Salinization","w":["Leaching","Eutrophication","Desertification"],"h":"Evaporating irrigation water leaves behind whatever it was carrying in solution.","e":"Salinization occurs when irrigation water evaporates and deposits dissolved salts at the surface, raising soil salinity and harming plants—common on arid, irrigated farmland."},{"p":"In a conventional wastewater treatment plant, the secondary treatment stage primarily accomplishes which of the following?","a":"Uses aerobic bacteria to decompose dissolved organic matter, lowering biochemical oxygen demand","w":["Physically screens and settles out large solids and grit from the influent","Adds chlorine to disinfect and kill pathogens just before discharge","Removes dissolved nitrogen and phosphorus by chemical precipitation"],"h":"This biological stage sits between the initial physical settling step and final disinfection.","e":"Secondary treatment is a biological process in which aerobic microbes break down dissolved organic waste, reducing BOD; physical settling is primary and disinfection or nutrient removal come later."},{"p":"A naturally occurring, odorless radioactive gas that seeps from uranium-bearing bedrock into basements and is a leading cause of lung cancer among nonsmokers is:","a":"Radon","w":["Carbon monoxide","Formaldehyde","Methane"],"h":"It is a colorless decay product of uranium in rock and soil that accumulates in enclosed spaces.","e":"Radon-222, a decay product of uranium in rocks and soil, accumulates in poorly ventilated basements and is the second-leading cause of lung cancer."},{"p":"Ground-level ozone, a harmful component of photochemical smog, is best described as:","a":"A secondary pollutant formed when sunlight drives reactions among nitrogen oxides and volatile organic compounds","w":["A primary pollutant emitted directly from vehicle tailpipes","A greenhouse gas released mainly from the digestion of cattle","A stratospheric gas that shields Earth from ultraviolet radiation"],"h":"It is not emitted directly; forming it requires sunlight acting on other emitted pollutants.","e":"Tropospheric (ground-level) ozone is a secondary pollutant produced when sunlight catalyzes reactions between NOx and VOCs, distinct from protective stratospheric ozone."},{"p":"A catalytic converter in a gasoline vehicle's exhaust system reduces air pollution mainly by:","a":"Converting carbon monoxide, unburned hydrocarbons, and NOx into CO2, water, and N2","w":["Filtering out particulate soot before it exits the tailpipe","Trapping and storing CO2 to prevent its release to the atmosphere","Removing sulfur dioxide by reacting it with a limestone slurry"],"h":"It chemically transforms three regulated exhaust gases into less harmful molecules.","e":"Catalytic converters use platinum-group metals to catalyze conversion of carbon monoxide, hydrocarbons, and nitrogen oxides into carbon dioxide, water vapor, and nitrogen gas."},{"p":"The 1987 Montreal Protocol is widely regarded as a successful international agreement because it:","a":"Phased out production of chlorofluorocarbons to protect the stratospheric ozone layer","w":["Set binding limits on greenhouse gas emissions to slow global warming","Banned international trade in endangered species and their body parts","Established a network of protected marine reserves in international waters"],"h":"It targeted the specific class of chemicals responsible for the Antarctic ozone hole.","e":"The Montreal Protocol phased out ozone-depleting substances such as CFCs, allowing stratospheric ozone to recover—distinct from climate treaties like Kyoto or Paris."},{"p":"Over a 100-year period, one kilogram of methane traps far more heat than one kilogram of carbon dioxide. This comparison is captured by methane's higher:","a":"Global warming potential","w":["Albedo","Biochemical oxygen demand","Residence half-life in soil"],"h":"The metric compares a gas's heat-trapping ability to that of CO2 over a defined time frame.","e":"Global warming potential (GWP) measures how much heat a gas traps relative to CO2 over a time horizon; methane's GWP is roughly 28-36 over 100 years."},{"p":"According to the theory of island biogeography, which island would be expected to support the greatest number of species?","a":"A large island located close to the mainland","w":["A large island located far from the mainland","A small island located close to the mainland","A small island located far from the mainland"],"h":"Two factors matter: island size affects extinction rate, and distance from a source affects immigration rate.","e":"Island biogeography predicts species richness rises with island size (lower extinction) and proximity to the mainland (higher immigration), so large-and-near maximizes richness."},{"p":"Read: 'After wolves were reintroduced, elk avoided open valleys, willow and aspen recovered, and beaver and songbird populations rose.' The wolves' far-reaching influence across multiple trophic levels best illustrates:","a":"A trophic cascade initiated by a top predator","w":["Primary succession following the wolves' arrival","A density-independent limiting factor on elk","Character displacement among the elk population"],"h":"One predator's effects ripple downward through several levels of the food web.","e":"A trophic cascade occurs when a top predator indirectly affects lower trophic levels and vegetation; the Yellowstone wolf reintroduction is the classic example."},{"p":"When humanity's ecological footprint exceeds Earth's biocapacity, the planet is said to be in overshoot. Which outcome is the most direct consequence of sustained global overshoot?","a":"Renewable resources are consumed faster than natural systems can regenerate them","w":["Nonrenewable fossil fuel reserves become permanently replenished","Global biodiversity increases as ecosystems steadily expand","Carbon dioxide is removed from the atmosphere faster than it is emitted"],"h":"Overshoot means demand outpaces the rate at which nature can replace what is used.","e":"Ecological overshoot occurs when human demand (footprint) exceeds biocapacity, drawing down natural capital such as fisheries and forests faster than it regenerates."}],"honors-precalc":[{"p":"If f(x) = x^2 + 1 and g(x) = 2x - 3, evaluate the composition (f ∘ g)(2).","a":"2","w":["7","5","3"],"h":"Composition (f ∘ g)(x) means apply g first, then substitute that result into f. Work from the inside out.","e":"Function composition applies the inner function first: g(2) = 1, then f(1) = 1^2 + 1 = 2. Order matters, since (g ∘ f) generally differs from (f ∘ g)."},{"p":"Given that sin θ = 3/5 and θ lies in the first quadrant, find cos θ.","a":"4/5","w":["-4/5","3/4","5/4"],"h":"Use the Pythagorean identity relating sine and cosine, and recall the sign of cosine in the given quadrant.","e":"By the Pythagorean identity sin^2 θ + cos^2 θ = 1, cos^2 θ = 1 − 9/25 = 16/25, so cos θ = 4/5 (positive in Quadrant I)."},{"p":"Convert the polar point (r, θ) = (4, π/3) to rectangular coordinates (x, y).","a":"(2, 2√3)","w":["(2√3, 2)","(-2, 2√3)","(4, 4√3)"],"h":"Use the conversion formulas x = r cos θ and y = r sin θ, and recall the exact values of cosine and sine at π/3.","e":"With x = r cos θ = 4·(1/2) = 2 and y = r sin θ = 4·(√3/2) = 2√3, the rectangular point is (2, 2√3)."},{"p":"A curve is given parametrically by x = t + 1 and y = t^2. Eliminate the parameter to write y as a function of x.","a":"y = (x − 1)^2","w":["y = (x + 1)^2","y = x^2 − 1","y = x^2 + 1"],"h":"Solve the first equation for t, then substitute that expression into the second equation.","e":"Solving x = t + 1 gives t = x − 1; substituting into y = t^2 yields y = (x − 1)^2, the standard parameter-elimination technique."},{"p":"Find the magnitude of the vector u = ⟨3, −4⟩.","a":"5","w":["7","√7","1"],"h":"The magnitude of a vector is found using the distance formula on its components; a negative component does not make the magnitude negative.","e":"The magnitude ‖u‖ = √(3^2 + (−4)^2) = √25 = 5, applying ‖⟨a,b⟩‖ = √(a^2 + b^2)."},{"p":"Compute the dot product u · v for u = ⟨2, 3⟩ and v = ⟨−1, 4⟩.","a":"10","w":["14","⟨−2, 12⟩","2"],"h":"The dot product multiplies corresponding components and adds the results, producing a single scalar rather than a vector.","e":"The dot product is (2)(−1) + (3)(4) = −2 + 12 = 10; it yields a scalar, not a vector."},{"p":"Evaluate the determinant of the matrix [[2, 1], [3, 4]].","a":"5","w":["11","−5","8"],"h":"For a 2×2 matrix, multiply the main-diagonal entries and subtract the product of the off-diagonal entries.","e":"For [[a, b], [c, d]], the determinant is ad − bc = (2)(4) − (1)(3) = 8 − 3 = 5."},{"p":"In an arithmetic sequence with first term a₁ = 3 and common difference d = 5, find the tenth term a₁₀.","a":"48","w":["53","50","45"],"h":"Use the explicit formula for an arithmetic term; note that the number of common differences added is one less than the term's index.","e":"By aₙ = a₁ + (n − 1)d, a₁₀ = 3 + (10 − 1)(5) = 3 + 45 = 48."},{"p":"Find the sum of the infinite geometric series 8 + 4 + 2 + 1 + ⋯","a":"16","w":["8","4","12"],"h":"An infinite geometric series converges only when the common ratio has absolute value less than 1; identify r first.","e":"With a = 8 and r = 1/2, the sum is S = a/(1 − r) = 8/(1 − 1/2) = 16, valid since |r| < 1."},{"p":"Find the coordinates of the foci of the ellipse x²/25 + y²/9 = 1.","a":"(±4, 0)","w":["(0, ±4)","(±√34, 0)","(±5, 0)"],"h":"For an ellipse, the focal distance c satisfies c² = a² − b², and the foci lie along the major axis.","e":"Here a² = 25 and b² = 9, so c² = 25 − 9 = 16 and c = 4; the larger denominator is under x², so the foci are (±4, 0)."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit lim_{x→2} (x² − 4)/(x − 2).","a":"4","w":["0","Does not exist","2"],"h":"Direct substitution gives 0/0, so factor the numerator and cancel the common factor before substituting.","e":"Factoring gives (x − 2)(x + 2)/(x − 2) = x + 2 for x ≠ 2, so the limit is 2 + 2 = 4; the removable discontinuity does not prevent the limit from existing."},{"p":"Solve for x: log₂(x) = 5.","a":"32","w":["10","25","7"],"h":"Rewrite the logarithmic equation in its equivalent exponential form using the definition of a logarithm.","e":"By definition, log₂(x) = 5 means 2^5 = x, so x = 32."},{"p":"Simplify the expression e^{ln 7}.","a":"7","w":["ln 7","e^7","1"],"h":"The natural exponential and natural logarithm are inverse functions; consider what happens when one undoes the other.","e":"Since e^x and ln x are inverses, e^{ln x} = x, so e^{ln 7} = 7."},{"p":"Find the exact value of tan(π/4).","a":"1","w":["√2","√3/3","0"],"h":"Use the unit circle: tangent is the ratio of the sine to the cosine at that angle.","e":"At π/4, sin = cos = √2/2, so tan(π/4) = (√2/2)/(√2/2) = 1."},{"p":"In triangle ABC, a = 5, b = 7, and the included angle C = 60°. Find the length of side c.","a":"√39","w":["√74","√109","√24"],"h":"Use the Law of Cosines, which relates a side to the other two sides and the angle opposite that side; recall cos 60° = 1/2.","e":"By the Law of Cosines, c² = a² + b² − 2ab cos C = 25 + 49 − 2(5)(7)(1/2) = 74 − 35 = 39, so c = √39."},{"p":"Find the modulus of the complex number 5 − 12i.","a":"13","w":["17","7","√119"],"h":"The modulus of a complex number is its distance from the origin in the complex plane, computed like a vector magnitude.","e":"The modulus |a + bi| = √(a² + b²) = √(5² + (−12)²) = √169 = 13."},{"p":"Using the Binomial Theorem, find the coefficient of the x² term in the expansion of (x + 2)^4.","a":"24","w":["6","12","48"],"h":"Identify the correct binomial coefficient with C(n, k), then multiply by the appropriate power of the constant term.","e":"The term is C(4, 2)·x²·2² = 6·4·x² = 24x², so the coefficient is 24."},{"p":"Determine the domain of the function f(x) = √(x − 3).","a":"x ≥ 3","w":["x > 3","x ≤ 3","all real numbers"],"h":"The expression under an even (square) root must be nonnegative; solve the resulting inequality, including the boundary case.","e":"The radicand must satisfy x − 3 ≥ 0, giving the domain x ≥ 3; equality is allowed because √0 = 0 is defined."},{"p":"If f(x) = 3x − 7, find the inverse function f⁻¹(x).","a":"f⁻¹(x) = (x + 7)/3","w":["f⁻¹(x) = (x − 7)/3","f⁻¹(x) = 3x + 7","f⁻¹(x) = 1/(3x − 7)"],"h":"Replace f(x) with y, swap x and y, then solve the new equation for y.","e":"To invert a function you interchange x and y and solve; solving x = 3y − 7 gives y = (x + 7)/3. The reciprocal 1/(3x−7) confuses inverse function with multiplicative inverse."},{"p":"Given sin θ = 5/13 with θ in the first quadrant, find the exact value of sin(2θ).","a":"120/169","w":["119/169","60/169","10/13"],"h":"Use the double-angle identity sin(2θ) = 2 sin θ cos θ, and first find cos θ from a Pythagorean triple.","e":"With cos θ = 12/13, the identity sin(2θ) = 2 sin θ cos θ = 2(5/13)(12/13) = 120/169. The value 119/169 is cos(2θ), and 10/13 drops the cosine factor."},{"p":"Convert the rectangular point (x, y) = (−1, √3) to polar coordinates (r, θ) with r > 0 and 0 ≤ θ < 2π.","a":"(2, 2π/3)","w":["(2, π/3)","(2, 4π/3)","(4, 2π/3)"],"h":"Compute r = √(x² + y²), find the reference angle from |y/x|, then place θ in the correct quadrant based on the signs of x and y.","e":"Here r = √(1 + 3) = 2 and the reference angle is π/3; since the point lies in Quadrant II, θ = π − π/3 = 2π/3. Choosing π/3 ignores the quadrant."},{"p":"A curve is defined parametrically by x = 2 cos t and y = 3 sin t. Eliminate the parameter to obtain a rectangular equation.","a":"x²/4 + y²/9 = 1","w":["x²/2 + y²/3 = 1","x²/4 − y²/9 = 1","x²/16 + y²/81 = 1"],"h":"Solve each equation for cos t and sin t, then apply the Pythagorean identity cos²t + sin²t = 1.","e":"Since cos t = x/2 and sin t = y/3, substituting into cos²t + sin²t = 1 gives x²/4 + y²/9 = 1, an ellipse. Using a minus sign produces a hyperbola, a common sign error."},{"p":"Find the angle between the vectors u = ⟨1, √3⟩ and v = ⟨√3, 1⟩.","a":"30°","w":["60°","45°","15°"],"h":"Use cos θ = (u · v)/(‖u‖‖v‖); each vector has the same magnitude.","e":"The dot product is 2√3 and each magnitude is 2, so cos θ = 2√3/4 = √3/2, giving θ = 30°. Confusing √3/2 with the sine value leads to 60°."},{"p":"Compute the matrix product [[1, 2], [0, 3]] · [[4, 0], [1, 5]].","a":"[[6, 10], [3, 15]]","w":["[[4, 0], [0, 15]]","[[6, 3], [10, 15]]","[[5, 2], [1, 8]]"],"h":"Each entry of the product is the dot product of a row of the first matrix with a column of the second.","e":"Row-by-column multiplication gives entries 1·4+2·1 = 6, 1·0+2·5 = 10, 0·4+3·1 = 3, 0·0+3·5 = 15. The choice [[4,0],[0,15]] wrongly multiplies entrywise."},{"p":"In an arithmetic sequence with first term a₁ = 4 and common difference d = 3, find the sum of the first 20 terms.","a":"650","w":["1300","610","61"],"h":"Use Sₙ = (n/2)[2a₁ + (n − 1)d] with n = 20.","e":"The partial-sum formula gives S₂₀ = (20/2)[2·4 + 19·3] = 10·65 = 650. Omitting the factor of 1/2 yields the doubled value 1300."},{"p":"In a geometric sequence with first term a₁ = 6 and common ratio r = 1/2, find the fifth term a₅.","a":"3/8","w":["3/16","3/4","1/16"],"h":"Use aₙ = a₁ · r^(n−1); the exponent is one less than the term number.","e":"The formula gives a₅ = 6·(1/2)⁴ = 6/16 = 3/8. Using the exponent 5 instead of 4 produces the incorrect 3/16."},{"p":"Find the equations of the asymptotes of the hyperbola x²/16 − y²/9 = 1.","a":"y = ±(3/4)x","w":["y = ±(4/3)x","y = ±(9/16)x","y = ±(16/9)x"],"h":"For x²/a² − y²/b² = 1 the asymptotes are y = ±(b/a)x; identify a and b as square roots of the denominators.","e":"Here a = 4 and b = 3, so the asymptotes are y = ±(b/a)x = ±(3/4)x. Reversing the ratio to 4/3 is a frequent slip."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit lim_{x→3} (x² − 9)/(x² − 2x − 3).","a":"3/2","w":["0","does not exist","6"],"h":"Both numerator and denominator are zero at x = 3; factor each and cancel the common factor before substituting.","e":"Factoring gives (x−3)(x+3)/[(x−3)(x+1)] = (x+3)/(x+1), which at x = 3 equals 6/4 = 3/2. The removable factor makes the limit exist despite the 0/0 form."},{"p":"Write log_b(x³√y / z²) as a sum and difference of logarithms.","a":"3 log_b x + (1/2) log_b y − 2 log_b z","w":["3 log_b x + (1/2) log_b y + 2 log_b z","3 log_b x + 2 log_b y − 2 log_b z","3 log_b x − (1/2) log_b y − 2 log_b z"],"h":"Apply the product, quotient, and power rules; a square root corresponds to an exponent of 1/2, and division becomes subtraction.","e":"The laws of logarithms give 3 log_b x + (1/2) log_b y − 2 log_b z; the square root contributes the 1/2 coefficient and the denominator becomes a subtracted term."},{"p":"Solve 2 sin x = 1 for all x in the interval [0, 2π).","a":"x = π/6 and x = 5π/6","w":["x = π/6 only","x = π/6 and x = 7π/6","x = π/3 and x = 2π/3"],"h":"Isolate sin x, then find every angle in one full revolution whose sine has that value; sine is positive in two quadrants.","e":"Since sin x = 1/2, the solutions are the Quadrant I and Quadrant II angles π/6 and 5π/6. Adding π instead reaches Quadrant III, where sine is negative."},{"p":"Multiply the complex numbers (2 + 3i)(1 − 2i) and express the result in standard form a + bi.","a":"8 − i","w":["−4 − i","8 + i","2 − 7i"],"h":"Distribute using FOIL and remember that i² = −1 before combining like terms.","e":"Expanding gives 2 − 4i + 3i − 6i² = 2 − i + 6 = 8 − i. Treating i² as +1 instead of −1 yields the incorrect −4 − i."},{"p":"Using the Binomial Theorem, find the coefficient of the x³ term in the expansion of (2x − 1)⁵.","a":"80","w":["−80","40","10"],"h":"The general term is C(5, k)(2x)^(5−k)(−1)^k; choose k so the power of x is 3, then include both the binomial coefficient and the 2^(power).","e":"The x³ term uses C(5,2)(2x)³(−1)² = 10·8·1 = 80. Forgetting to raise 2 to the third power gives 10, and mishandling the sign gives −80."},{"p":"Determine the domain of the function f(x) = ln(x² − 4).","a":"(−∞, −2) ∪ (2, ∞)","w":["(2, ∞)","(−2, 2)","all real numbers except x = ±2"],"h":"The argument of a natural logarithm must be strictly positive; solve the resulting quadratic inequality.","e":"Requiring x² − 4 > 0 gives x < −2 or x > 2, so the domain is (−∞, −2) ∪ (2, ∞). The interval (−2, 2) is where the argument is negative."},{"p":"In triangle ABC, angle A = 30°, angle B = 45°, and side a = 6. Find the length of side b.","a":"6√2","w":["3√2","6√3","4√2"],"h":"Apply the Law of Sines, a/sin A = b/sin B, and solve for b using exact values of the sines.","e":"By the Law of Sines b = a·sin B / sin A = 6·(√2/2)/(1/2) = 6√2. Forgetting to divide by 1/2 (i.e., not multiplying by 2) gives 3√2."},{"p":"A bacterial population doubles every 5 hours. If the population starts at 200 cells, how many cells are present after 15 hours?","a":"1600 cells","w":["800 cells","1200 cells","3200 cells"],"h":"Find how many doubling periods fit into 15 hours, then multiply the initial amount by 2 raised to that number.","e":"Fifteen hours is 15/5 = 3 doubling periods, so the population is 200·2³ = 1600. Multiplying 200 by 6 instead of 2³ gives the incorrect 1200."},{"p":"Evaluate the finite sum Σ_{k=1}^{4} (2k + 1).","a":"24","w":["20","26","21"],"h":"Write out each term for k = 1, 2, 3, 4, then add; do not forget the constant +1 in every term.","e":"The terms are 3, 5, 7, and 9, whose sum is 24. Omitting the +1 from each term (summing only 2k) yields 20."},{"p":"Use De Moivre's Theorem to evaluate (1 + i)^8. Express the result in standard form.","a":"16","w":["16i","-16","32"],"h":"First write 1 + i in polar (trigonometric) form by finding its modulus and argument, then raise the modulus to the 8th power and multiply the argument by 8.","e":"By De Moivre's Theorem, 1 + i = √2·cis(π/4), so (1+i)^8 = (√2)^8·cis(8·π/4) = 16·cis(2π) = 16."},{"p":"A worker pushes a crate with a constant force F = ⟨40, 30⟩ newtons while the crate undergoes a displacement d = ⟨5, 12⟩ meters. The work done is the dot product F · d. Find the work done, in joules.","a":"560 J","w":["650 J","260 J","200 J"],"h":"Work equals the dot product of the force and displacement vectors: multiply corresponding components and add.","e":"Work is defined as W = F · d = (40)(5) + (30)(12) = 200 + 360 = 560 J, using the component form of the dot product."},{"p":"Two people push a cart, exerting forces F₁ = ⟨30, 40⟩ N and F₂ = ⟨−10, 20⟩ N. Find the magnitude of the resultant force.","a":"20√10 N","w":["20√13 N","100 N","80 N"],"h":"Add the two force vectors component-by-component first, then apply the distance/magnitude formula to the sum.","e":"The resultant is F₁ + F₂ = ⟨20, 60⟩, whose magnitude is √(20² + 60²) = √4000 = 20√10 N."},{"p":"Find the inverse of the matrix A = [[4, 3], [3, 2]].","a":"[[-2, 3], [3, -4]]","w":["[[2, -3], [-3, 4]]","[[-2, -3], [-3, -4]]","[[2, 3], [3, 4]]"],"h":"For a 2×2 matrix, swap the main-diagonal entries, negate the off-diagonal entries, and divide by the determinant. Check the sign of the determinant carefully.","e":"Since det(A) = (4)(2) − (3)(3) = −1, A⁻¹ = (1/−1)·[[2, −3], [−3, 4]] = [[−2, 3], [3, −4]]."},{"p":"A surveyor measures a triangular plot with side lengths a = 5 m, b = 8 m, and c = 7 m. Using the Law of Cosines, find the measure of angle C (the angle opposite the side of length 7).","a":"60°","w":["90°","45°","120°"],"h":"Solve the Law of Cosines c² = a² + b² − 2ab·cos C for cos C, then take the inverse cosine.","e":"By the Law of Cosines, cos C = (a² + b² − c²)/(2ab) = (25 + 64 − 49)/(80) = 0.5, so C = 60°."},{"p":"Identify the type of curve represented by the polar equation r = 3 + 3 cos θ.","a":"A cardioid","w":["A circle of radius 3","A limaçon with an inner loop","A four-petaled rose"],"h":"For an equation of the form r = a + b cos θ, compare the values of a and b to classify the limaçon family.","e":"When |a| = |b| in r = a + b cos θ, the graph is a cardioid; here a = b = 3, so the curve is a cardioid."},{"p":"A ball is launched so that its position (in feet) is given by the parametric equations x = 20t and y = 40t − 16t², where t is time in seconds. Find the maximum height the ball reaches.","a":"25 ft","w":["50 ft","12.5 ft","40 ft"],"h":"Maximum height occurs at the vertex of the parabolic height function y(t); find the t-value that maximizes y, then evaluate y there.","e":"The vertex of y = 40t − 16t² occurs at t = −40/(2·−16) = 1.25 s, giving y = 40(1.25) − 16(1.25)² = 25 ft."},{"p":"Use a sum or difference identity to find the exact value of cos 75°.","a":"(√6 − √2)/4","w":["(√6 + √2)/4","(√2 − √6)/4","(√6 − √2)/2"],"h":"Write 75° as 45° + 30° and apply the cosine sum identity cos(A + B) = cos A cos B − sin A sin B.","e":"cos 75° = cos(45° + 30°) = cos45°cos30° − sin45°sin30° = (√2/2)(√3/2) − (√2/2)(1/2) = (√6 − √2)/4."},{"p":"A ball is dropped from a height of 16 feet. Each time it strikes the ground it rebounds to half of its previous height. Find the total vertical distance the ball travels before coming to rest.","a":"48 ft","w":["32 ft","64 ft","24 ft"],"h":"Account for the initial drop plus each rebound, which is traveled twice (up and down). The rebound heights form an infinite geometric series.","e":"Total distance = 16 + 2(8 + 4 + 2 + ⋯) = 16 + 2·(8/(1 − ½)) = 16 + 2(16) = 48 ft, using the infinite geometric series sum."},{"p":"Evaluate the finite geometric sum Σ_{k=1}^{6} 3·2^{k−1}.","a":"189","w":["96","192","381"],"h":"Use the finite geometric series formula Sₙ = a₁(rⁿ − 1)/(r − 1) with a₁ = 3, r = 2, and n = 6.","e":"S₆ = 3(2⁶ − 1)/(2 − 1) = 3(64 − 1) = 3(63) = 189, by the finite geometric series formula."},{"p":"A satellite dish has a cross-section modeled by the parabola x² = 16y, with the vertex at the origin. The receiver should be placed at the focus. How far from the vertex, along the axis of symmetry, is the focus?","a":"4 units","w":["2 units","8 units","16 units"],"h":"Write the parabola as x² = 4py and identify p, the directed distance from the vertex to the focus.","e":"For x² = 4py, here 4p = 16 so p = 4; the focus lies 4 units from the vertex on the axis of symmetry."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit lim_{x→0} (sin 3x)/x.","a":"3","w":["1","1/3","0"],"h":"Rewrite the expression to use the special limit lim_{u→0} (sin u)/u = 1 by matching the argument of the sine to the denominator.","e":"lim_{x→0} (sin 3x)/x = 3·lim_{x→0} (sin 3x)/(3x) = 3·1 = 3, using the special trigonometric limit."},{"p":"A radioactive sample has a half-life of 8 days and an initial mass of 80 grams. How much of the sample remains after 24 days?","a":"10 g","w":["20 g","5 g","26.7 g"],"h":"Determine how many half-lives occur in 24 days, then apply A = A₀(1/2)^(number of half-lives).","e":"In 24 days there are 24/8 = 3 half-lives, so A = 80·(1/2)³ = 80/8 = 10 g by exponential decay."},{"p":"Find the exact value of tan(arccos(5/13)).","a":"12/5","w":["5/12","12/13","13/5"],"h":"Let θ = arccos(5/13) and sketch a right triangle with adjacent 5 and hypotenuse 13; find the missing side, then form the tangent ratio.","e":"If cos θ = 5/13 (θ in the first quadrant), the opposite side is √(13² − 5²) = 12, so tan θ = 12/5."},{"p":"Classify the function f(x) = 2x⁴ − 3x² + 1 as even, odd, or neither.","a":"Even","w":["Odd","Neither","Both even and odd"],"h":"Compute f(−x) and compare it to f(x) and to −f(x); even functions satisfy f(−x) = f(x).","e":"Since f(−x) = 2x⁴ − 3x² + 1 = f(x), the function is even (symmetric about the y-axis), as all exponents are even."},{"p":"Find the equation of the slant (oblique) asymptote of the rational function f(x) = (2x² + 3)/(x − 1).","a":"y = 2x + 2","w":["y = 2x","y = 2","x = 1"],"h":"A slant asymptote appears when the numerator's degree is exactly one more than the denominator's; use polynomial long division and take the quotient.","e":"Dividing 2x² + 3 by x − 1 gives quotient 2x + 2 with remainder 5, so the oblique asymptote is y = 2x + 2."},{"p":"Write the complex number −1 + √3 i in trigonometric (polar) form using degrees.","a":"2(cos 120° + i sin 120°)","w":["2(cos 60° + i sin 60°)","2(cos 240° + i sin 240°)","4(cos 120° + i sin 120°)"],"h":"Find the modulus with √(a² + b²), then determine the argument, paying attention to which quadrant the point lies in.","e":"The modulus is √((−1)² + (√3)²) = 2, and since the point is in the second quadrant the argument is 120°, giving 2(cos 120° + i sin 120°)."},{"p":"An auditorium has 15 rows of seats. The first row has 20 seats, and each subsequent row has 3 more seats than the row before it. Find the total number of seats in the auditorium.","a":"615","w":["630","600","62"],"h":"The seats per row form an arithmetic sequence; use the arithmetic series sum Sₙ = (n/2)(2a₁ + (n − 1)d).","e":"With a₁ = 20, d = 3, n = 15, S₁₅ = (15/2)(2·20 + 14·3) = (15/2)(82) = 615, by the arithmetic series formula."}],"ap-spanish":[{"p":"Completa la oración: \"Cuando yo ___ niño, ___ a la playa todos los veranos con mis abuelos.\"","a":"era / iba","w":["fui / fui","era / fui","fui / iba"],"h":"Piensa en acciones habituales y repetidas en el pasado, no en un evento único y terminado.","e":"El imperfecto expresa acciones habituales o en progreso en el pasado; la expresión \"todos los veranos\" señala repetición, no un hecho puntual."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Mi madre quiere que yo ___ la tarea antes de salir con mis amigos.\"","a":"haga","w":["hago","haré","hice"],"h":"Un verbo de deseo o voluntad seguido de \"que\" y un sujeto distinto exige un cambio de modo.","e":"Los verbos de volición como \"querer que\" con cambio de sujeto requieren el presente de subjuntivo."},{"p":"Completa: \"No te comas la sopa todavía; ___ demasiado caliente y te vas a quemar.\"","a":"está","w":["es","será","sea"],"h":"Distingue entre una cualidad inherente y un estado temporal que puede cambiar.","e":"\"Estar\" expresa condiciones o estados cambiantes (temperatura); \"ser\" describiría una característica esencial e inherente."},{"p":"Completa con la preposición correcta: \"Estudié toda la noche ___ aprobar el examen de mañana.\"","a":"para","w":["por","a","con"],"h":"Distingue entre la finalidad o el objetivo de una acción y su causa o motivo.","e":"\"Para\" expresa propósito o finalidad (\"con el fin de\"); \"por\" expresaría causa, motivo o intercambio."},{"p":"Read: \"Marta se mudó a Buenos Aires hace tres años. Al principio extrañaba mucho a su familia, pero poco a poco hizo nuevos amigos y encontró un trabajo que le encanta. Hoy dice que la ciudad se ha convertido en su segundo hogar.\" ¿Cómo se siente Marta ahora respecto a Buenos Aires?","a":"Se siente cómoda y considera la ciudad como su hogar.","w":["Todavía extraña demasiado y quiere volver pronto.","No ha logrado hacer amigos ni encontrar trabajo.","Se acaba de mudar y no conoce bien la ciudad."],"h":"Fíjate en el contraste que marca \"pero\" y en la idea de la última oración.","e":"El texto muestra una progresión de la nostalgia inicial a la pertenencia; se trata de comprender la idea principal del pasaje."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Es importante que los estudiantes ___ a tiempo a clase cada día.\"","a":"lleguen","w":["llegan","llegarán","llegaron"],"h":"Las expresiones impersonales de necesidad o importancia provocan un cambio de modo en la cláusula subordinada.","e":"Las expresiones impersonales como \"es importante que\" exigen el presente de subjuntivo en la cláusula subordinada."},{"p":"¿En qué país se celebra el Día de los Muertos con ofrendas, calaveras de azúcar y visitas al cementerio como tradición central?","a":"México","w":["Argentina","España","Perú"],"h":"Piensa en la tradición reconocida por la UNESCO que mezcla raíces indígenas mesoamericanas y católicas.","e":"El Día de los Muertos es una tradición mexicana reconocida por la UNESCO que fusiona elementos mesoamericanos y católicos."},{"p":"En el contexto \"El médico me recetó un jarabe para la tos\", ¿qué significa el verbo \"recetar\"?","a":"prescribir un medicamento","w":["preparar una comida","cobrar dinero","recibir una carta"],"h":"Relaciona el verbo con el sustantivo \"receta\" dentro de un contexto médico.","e":"\"Recetar\" significa prescribir un medicamento; ojo con la trampa del cognado \"receta\", que también significa recipe de cocina."},{"p":"Elige el mandato correcto: \"___ la puerta, por favor, que hace mucho calor aquí.\" (mandato afirmativo de \"abrir\" para tú)","a":"Abre","w":["Abra","Abres","Abrir"],"h":"El mandato afirmativo informal singular coincide con una forma del presente que ya conoces.","e":"El mandato afirmativo de tú usa la forma de tercera persona singular del presente de indicativo: \"abre\"."},{"p":"Completa: \"A mí ___ mucho los libros de historia antigua y los de mitología.\"","a":"me gustan","w":["me gusta","me gusto","yo gusto"],"h":"El verbo concuerda con la cosa que agrada, no con la persona que la disfruta.","e":"\"Gustar\" concuerda con el sujeto gramatical (los libros, plural), por lo que se usa \"me gustan\"."},{"p":"Completa la oración condicional: \"Si yo tuviera más dinero, ___ un coche nuevo este año.\"","a":"compraría","w":["compro","compraré","comprara"],"h":"Observa la cláusula con \"si\" más imperfecto de subjuntivo y piensa en qué modo pide la cláusula de resultado.","e":"En las oraciones hipotéticas con \"si\" + imperfecto de subjuntivo, la cláusula de resultado usa el condicional."},{"p":"Completa con el pronombre relativo correcto: \"El chico ___ vive al lado de mi casa es mi primo Andrés.\"","a":"que","w":["quien","cuyo","lo que"],"h":"Busca el relativo más general en una cláusula especificativa sin comas.","e":"\"Que\" es el pronombre relativo general para personas y cosas en cláusulas especificativas; \"quien\" requiere preposición o coma."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Ayer nosotros ___ una fiesta sorpresa para Ana en el jardín.\"","a":"hicimos","w":["hacíamos","hicieron","hacemos"],"h":"Necesitas la raíz irregular del pretérito para una acción terminada de \"nosotros\".","e":"\"Hacer\" tiene raíz irregular en el pretérito (hic-); la forma de nosotros es \"hicimos\"."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Te doy el dinero para que ___ el boleto de autobús mañana.\"","a":"compres","w":["compras","comprarás","compraste"],"h":"La conjunción \"para que\" siempre introduce una cláusula que exige un cambio de modo.","e":"\"Para que\" es una conjunción adverbial de finalidad que siempre exige el subjuntivo."},{"p":"Elige la opción correcta: \"Todas las mañanas Juan ___ a las seis y ___ los dientes antes de desayunar.\"","a":"se despierta / se cepilla","w":["despierta / cepilla","se despierta / cepilla","despierta / se cepilla"],"h":"Cuando el sujeto realiza la acción sobre sí mismo, hace falta cierto pronombre en ambos verbos.","e":"Los verbos reflexivos requieren el pronombre reflexivo que concuerda con el sujeto (se para la tercera persona) en ambas acciones."},{"p":"Read: \"El anuncio decía: 'Se busca voluntario para cuidar animales en el refugio los fines de semana. No se requiere experiencia, solo muchas ganas de ayudar. Comida y transporte incluidos.'\" Según el anuncio, ¿qué debe tener el candidato?","a":"Deseo y ganas de ayudar a los animales","w":["Experiencia previa cuidando animales","Un título universitario en veterinaria","Disponibilidad de lunes a viernes"],"h":"Presta atención a la estructura \"no se requiere... solo...\" del anuncio.","e":"El anuncio afirma que no se necesita experiencia, solo ganas de ayudar; se trata de comprender un detalle explícito del texto."},{"p":"¿Cuál es el baile y la música tradicional originarios de la región del Río de la Plata (Argentina y Uruguay)?","a":"El tango","w":["La salsa","El flamenco","El merengue"],"h":"Piensa en el género asociado a Buenos Aires y Montevideo, declarado Patrimonio de la Humanidad.","e":"El tango se originó en la región del Río de la Plata; la salsa es caribeña, el flamenco español y el merengue dominicano."},{"p":"En la oración \"Estoy embarazada y espero a mi bebé para diciembre\", ¿qué significa \"embarazada\"?","a":"encinta, esperando un bebé","w":["avergonzada por algo","muy cansada del trabajo","demasiado ocupada hoy"],"h":"Es un falso amigo clásico con la palabra inglesa \"embarrassed\".","e":"\"Embarazada\" significa encinta (pregnant), no avergonzada; es un cognado falso muy común con el inglés."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Es una lástima que el equipo no ___ el partido de ayer, porque jugaron muy bien.\"","a":"haya ganado","w":["ha ganado","ganó","gane"],"h":"La cláusula principal expresa emoción sobre una acción ya terminada en el pasado.","e":"La emoción o el juicio ('Es una lástima que') sobre un hecho pasado ya completado exige el pretérito perfecto de subjuntivo (haya + participio)."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Mientras nosotros ___ en el parque, de repente empezó a llover.\"","a":"caminábamos","w":["caminamos","habíamos caminado","caminaríamos"],"h":"Una acción estaba en curso de fondo cuando otra acción repentina la interrumpió.","e":"El imperfecto describe una acción de fondo en desarrollo, mientras que el evento que interrumpe ('empezó') va en pretérito."},{"p":"Completa con la preposición correcta: \"Paseamos ___ el centro histórico durante horas admirando los edificios coloniales.\"","a":"por","w":["para","a","de"],"h":"Piensa en el movimiento a través de o a lo largo de un espacio físico, no en un destino.","e":"'Por' expresa movimiento a través de o a lo largo de un espacio; 'para' indicaría destino o finalidad, que no es el sentido aquí."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"El concierto de jazz ___ en el teatro nuevo y empieza a las nueve en punto.\"","a":"es","w":["está","hay","queda"],"h":"Se pregunta dónde tiene lugar un evento, no dónde se ubica un objeto físico.","e":"La localización de un evento usa 'ser' (El concierto es en...), a diferencia de los objetos o personas, que usan 'estar'."},{"p":"Elige el mandato correcto: \"No ___ esas fotos en las redes sociales sin pedir permiso.\" (mandato negativo de \"publicar\" para tú)","a":"publiques","w":["publicas","publica","publicáis"],"h":"Los mandatos negativos informales se forman con la forma del presente de subjuntivo.","e":"Los mandatos negativos de 'tú' usan el presente de subjuntivo de la segunda persona (no publiques), nunca la forma afirmativa (publica)."},{"p":"Elige el mandato correcto: \"___, por favor; el doctor la atenderá en un momento.\" (mandato formal de \"sentarse\" para usted)","a":"Siéntese","w":["Siéntate","Se siente","Se sienta"],"h":"Los mandatos formales usan la forma del subjuntivo, y el pronombre reflexivo se une al mandato afirmativo.","e":"El mandato afirmativo de 'usted' del reflexivo 'sentarse' es 'Siéntese' (raíz del subjuntivo + -se pospuesto, con tilde escrita)."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"___ temprano mañana para evitar el tráfico de la hora punta.\" (mandato de \"nosotros\" de \"salir\")","a":"Salgamos","w":["Salimos","Salgemos","Salamos"],"h":"Un mandato de tipo 'Vamos a...' usa la forma nosotros del presente de subjuntivo.","e":"Los mandatos de nosotros ('Let's') usan el presente de subjuntivo; 'salir' tiene raíz irregular (salg-), lo que da 'Salgamos'."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Te llamaré en cuanto ___ del trabajo esta tarde.\"","a":"salga","w":["salgo","saldré","salí"],"h":"La conjunción temporal apunta a una acción que todavía no ha ocurrido.","e":"Las conjunciones temporales como 'en cuanto' o 'cuando' exigen el subjuntivo cuando la acción aún está pendiente en el futuro."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Cuando llegamos al cine, la película ya ___ y perdimos los primeros minutos.\"","a":"había empezado","w":["empezó","ha empezado","empezaba"],"h":"Una acción pasada ya se había completado antes de que ocurriera otra acción pasada.","e":"El pluscuamperfecto (había + participio) expresa una acción pasada terminada antes de otro punto en el pasado."},{"p":"Elige la forma correcta: \"Si yo ___ que venías, habría preparado una cena especial.\"","a":"hubiera sabido","w":["habría sabido","había sabido","sabría"],"h":"La cláusula 'si' de una oración pasada contraria a los hechos toma una forma específica del subjuntivo.","e":"Las condiciones irreales del pasado usan 'si' + pluscuamperfecto de subjuntivo (hubiera sabido) en la cláusula 'si' y el condicional compuesto en la principal."},{"p":"Completa: \"A nosotros ___ solo dos euros para poder comprar el regalo de cumpleaños.\"","a":"nos faltan","w":["nos falta","nos faltamos","faltamos"],"h":"Como 'gustar', el verbo concuerda con la cosa que falta, no con las personas.","e":"Verbos como 'faltar' concuerdan con el sujeto gramatical (dos euros → faltan) y usan un pronombre de objeto indirecto (nos)."},{"p":"Completa con el pronombre relativo correcto: \"Ese es el escritor ___ novela más reciente ganó el premio nacional.\"","a":"cuya","w":["que","quien","cuyo"],"h":"El hueco indica posesión y debe concordar con el sustantivo que le sigue de inmediato.","e":"'Cuyo/a' (whose) concuerda en género y número con el objeto poseído, y 'novela' es femenino, así que 'cuya'."},{"p":"En la oración \"Actualmente vivo en Madrid, pero nací en Sevilla\", ¿qué significa \"actualmente\"?","a":"en el momento presente, hoy en día","w":["en realidad, de verdad","de hecho, efectivamente","verdaderamente, sin duda"],"h":"Es un falso cognado ('falso amigo') que se parece a la palabra inglesa 'actually'.","e":"'Actualmente' significa 'currently/nowadays'; es un falso cognado y no significa 'actually' (en realidad)."},{"p":"En la oración \"Todos los alumnos deben asistir a las conferencias\", ¿qué significa \"asistir\"?","a":"estar presente, acudir a un lugar","w":["ayudar a otra persona","prestar apoyo a alguien","colaborar con un grupo"],"h":"Es un falso amigo del verbo inglés 'to assist'.","e":"'Asistir (a)' significa 'to attend', un falso cognado; la idea de ayudar se expresa con 'ayudar'."},{"p":"¿Qué arquitecto modernista catalán diseñó la basílica de la Sagrada Familia y el Park Güell en Barcelona?","a":"Antoni Gaudí","w":["Santiago Calatrava","Joan Miró","Diego Rivera"],"h":"Es célebre por sus edificios modernistas orgánicos y coloridos en Barcelona.","e":"Antoni Gaudí es el arquitecto modernista catalán de la Sagrada Familia y el Park Güell, hitos culturales clave de España."},{"p":"¿A qué civilización precolombina pertenece la ciudadela de Machu Picchu, situada en los Andes del Perú?","a":"los incas","w":["los aztecas","los mayas","los olmecas"],"h":"Este imperio tuvo su capital en Cusco, en la sierra andina.","e":"Machu Picchu fue construida por la civilización inca en los Andes peruanos; los aztecas y los mayas estaban en Mesoamérica."},{"p":"Read: \"Aunque el restaurante estaba lleno y tuvimos que esperar casi una hora, valió la pena: cada plato superó nuestras expectativas y el camarero nos trató como si fuéramos de la familia. Sin duda volveremos.\" ¿Cuál es la actitud del autor hacia el restaurante?","a":"Quedó muy satisfecho a pesar de la espera","w":["Se arrepiente de haber ido allí","Le pareció mediocre por la larga espera","No piensa regresar nunca más"],"h":"Concéntrate en la última oración y en la frase 'valió la pena'.","e":"Inferir el tono: 'valió la pena' y 'volveremos' señalan una actitud claramente positiva a pesar de la espera inicial."},{"p":"Completa: \"Para cuando cumpla treinta años, ya ___ mi propia empresa.\"","a":"habré fundado","w":["habría fundado","haya fundado","había fundado"],"h":"Se trata de una acción futura que estará terminada antes de otro momento del futuro.","e":"El futuro perfecto (habré + participio) expresa una acción que se habrá completado antes de un punto de referencia futuro."},{"p":"Completa: \"Yo en tu lugar no ___ eso; fue una decisión muy arriesgada.\"","a":"habría hecho","w":["había hecho","habré hecho","haría"],"h":"Expresa lo que uno hubiera hecho en una situación hipotética ya pasada (fíjate en 'fue').","e":"El condicional compuesto (habría + participio) indica una acción hipotética del pasado que no llegó a ocurrir; 'haría' sería presente/futuro y no encaja con 'fue'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Es estupendo que ustedes ya ___ todos los preparativos para la boda.\"","a":"hayan terminado","w":["han terminado","hubieran terminado","terminen"],"h":"Emoción expresada en presente sobre algo que ya está completado.","e":"El pretérito perfecto de subjuntivo (haya + participio) se usa tras una expresión de emoción en presente referida a una acción ya acabada."},{"p":"Completa: \"En este barrio ___ varias lenguas indígenas además del español.\"","a":"se hablan","w":["se habla","son habladas","están hablando"],"h":"El sujeto gramatical es plural y la acción es impersonal, sin agente expreso.","e":"En la pasiva refleja con 'se', el verbo concuerda con el sujeto plural ('lenguas'), de ahí 'se hablan'."},{"p":"Completa con la preposición correcta: \"Te cambio mi bocadillo ___ tu manzana, ¿trato hecho?\"","a":"por","w":["para","de","a"],"h":"Expresa el intercambio de una cosa a cambio de otra.","e":"'Por' indica intercambio o equivalencia entre dos cosas; 'para' expresaría finalidad, no intercambio."},{"p":"En la oración \"Llevo dos días muy constipado, no paro de toser y estornudar\", ¿qué significa \"constipado\"?","a":"resfriado","w":["estreñido","agotado","mareado"],"h":"Es un falso amigo del término inglés 'constipated'.","e":"Falso cognado: 'constipado' significa tener un resfriado, no estreñimiento."},{"p":"En la oración \"El equipo consiguió realizar todos sus objetivos del año\", ¿qué significa \"realizar\"?","a":"llevar a cabo","w":["darse cuenta de","imaginar","anunciar"],"h":"Es un falso amigo del verbo inglés 'to realize'.","e":"'Realizar' significa ejecutar o cumplir; 'darse cuenta de' es el equivalente de 'to realize'."},{"p":"En la oración \"Marcos es muy sensible: cualquier crítica le afecta mucho\", ¿qué significa \"sensible\"?","a":"que se emociona con facilidad","w":["que razona con prudencia","que es muy inteligente","que tiene mucha fuerza"],"h":"Es un falso amigo del adjetivo inglés 'sensible'.","e":"'Sensible' equivale a 'sensitive'; el equivalente de 'sensible' (razonable) en español es 'sensato'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Date prisa, que ya ___ listos para salir y solo faltas tú.\"","a":"estamos","w":["somos","seamos","fuimos"],"h":"El adjetivo 'listo' cambia de significado según el verbo copulativo que lo acompañe.","e":"'Estar listo' significa 'preparado', mientras que 'ser listo' significa 'inteligente'; aquí se requiere 'estar'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Aunque mañana ___ mal tiempo, la carrera se celebrará igualmente.\"","a":"haga","w":["hace","hará","hizo"],"h":"La concesión se refiere a algo futuro que todavía no es un hecho confirmado.","e":"'Aunque' rige subjuntivo cuando la información es hipotética o no confirmada, como una situación futura."},{"p":"Completa: \"A los excursionistas ___ los pies después de caminar todo el día por la montaña.\"","a":"les dolían","w":["les dolía","le dolían","le dolía"],"h":"El verbo tipo 'gustar' concuerda con la cosa que causa el dolor y usa el pronombre plural para varias personas.","e":"'Doler' funciona como 'gustar': concuerda con el sujeto plural ('los pies') y usa el pronombre plural 'les' para los excursionistas; el imperfecto describe el estado."},{"p":"¿En qué país se encuentra el salar de Uyuni, el mayor desierto de sal del mundo?","a":"Bolivia","w":["Chile","Perú","Argentina"],"h":"Está situado en el altiplano andino, en el suroeste del país.","e":"El salar de Uyuni se localiza en el suroeste de Bolivia, a gran altitud en los Andes."},{"p":"Completa: \"Anoche, en la fiesta de la empresa, ___ a la que será mi nueva jefa.\"","a":"conocí","w":["conocía","conozco","había conocido"],"h":"En pretérito, 'conocer' adquiere un matiz distinto al del imperfecto.","e":"En pretérito 'conocer' significa 'encontrar/tratar por primera vez' (acción puntual), frente al imperfecto 'conocía' (ya lo sabía de antes)."},{"p":"Completa el mandato: \"Necesito los informes urgentemente. Por favor, ___.\" (mandato afirmativo de tú de \"traer\" con los pronombres 'me' y 'los')","a":"tráemelos","w":["tráemelo","tráelosme","me los traes"],"h":"En el mandato afirmativo los pronombres se unen al verbo, primero el indirecto y luego el directo.","e":"El mandato afirmativo lleva los pronombres pospuestos con tilde: 'tráemelos' (me = indirecto, los = directo, plural por 'informes')."},{"p":"Completa con el pronombre relativo correcto: \"No comprendí ___ me explicaste sobre el proyecto.\"","a":"lo que","w":["que","el que","cual"],"h":"Se refiere a una idea o concepto global, no a un sustantivo concreto ya mencionado.","e":"'Lo que' es el relativo neutro que remite a una idea completa o a algo no especificado por un sustantivo."},{"p":"¿Qué escritor colombiano, autor de \"Cien años de soledad\", es la figura máxima del realismo mágico?","a":"Gabriel García Márquez","w":["Mario Vargas Llosa","Julio Cortázar","Jorge Luis Borges"],"h":"Recibió el Premio Nobel de Literatura en 1982.","e":"Gabriel García Márquez, colombiano, es el máximo exponente del realismo mágico latinoamericano."},{"p":"Read: \"Cuando le ofrecieron el ascenso, Lucía no dio saltos de alegría como esperaban sus colegas. Sonrió cortésmente, dio las gracias y pidió unos días para pensarlo. En el fondo, temía que el nuevo puesto la alejara del trabajo que de verdad le apasionaba.\" ¿Por qué duda Lucía en aceptar el ascenso?","a":"Teme que el nuevo cargo la aparte de lo que realmente le apasiona","w":["Está convencida de que no merece ese ascenso","Le molesta que sus colegas sientan envidia de ella","Considera que el aumento de sueldo es insuficiente"],"h":"Fíjate en la última frase, que revela su verdadero temor.","e":"Inferencia: el texto indica explícitamente que teme alejarse del trabajo que le apasiona, no las otras motivaciones."},{"p":"Read: \"El nuevo móvil promete una batería 'que dura para siempre'. La probé una semana: a media tarde ya andaba buscando un enchufe desesperadamente. Si eso es 'para siempre', prefiero no imaginar lo que dura poco.\" ¿Cuál es el tono del autor respecto al móvil?","a":"Irónico y crítico con la publicidad","w":["Entusiasta y plenamente satisfecho","Neutral y puramente informativo","Nostálgico por los móviles antiguos"],"h":"Observa el contraste entre la promesa del anuncio y la experiencia real del autor.","e":"El autor recurre a la ironía para criticar la exageración publicitaria sobre la duración de la batería."}],"ap-eng-lang":[{"p":"Read: \"As a physician who has treated over three thousand patients in this community, I can tell you that the new clinic will save lives.\" Which rhetorical appeal does the speaker PRIMARILY rely on in this sentence?","a":"Ethos, by establishing the speaker's credibility and professional authority","w":["Pathos, by stirring the audience's fear of illness","Logos, by offering statistical proof for the clinic","Kairos, by stressing the urgency of the present moment"],"h":"Consider what the phrase 'as a physician who has treated over three thousand patients' is meant to establish about the speaker.","e":"Ethos is the appeal to the speaker's credibility, character, or authority; the professional credentials here establish trustworthiness."},{"p":"Read: \"Imagine your own child, shivering and hungry, turned away from a shelter on the coldest night of the year.\" The author's appeal in this passage is best described as","a":"an appeal to pathos, evoking the audience's compassion and emotion","w":["an appeal to logos, using logical reasoning and data","an appeal to ethos, building the author's authority","an appeal to kairos, seizing the timeliness of the issue"],"h":"Notice the vivid, feeling-oriented image the author asks readers to picture.","e":"Pathos appeals to the audience's emotions; the imagined suffering child is designed to arouse sympathy."},{"p":"Read: \"Since the bridge was inspected in 2019, has carried record traffic, and now shows measurable stress fractures, it must be repaired before winter.\" This argument depends CHIEFLY on","a":"logos, reasoning from stated evidence to a logical conclusion","w":["pathos, appealing to the audience's anxieties","ethos, relying on the inspector's personal reputation","hyperbole, exaggerating the bridge's true condition"],"h":"Look at how the sentence moves from a series of facts toward a 'therefore' conclusion.","e":"Logos is the appeal to logic and evidence, arranging premises to support a reasoned conclusion."},{"p":"Read: \"How long must ordinary citizens wait before their leaders finally act?\" The primary rhetorical effect of this question is to","a":"emphasize the speaker's point and lead the audience toward the implied answer","w":["request specific information the speaker genuinely lacks","concede a weakness in the speaker's own position","introduce a statistic that will appear in the next sentence"],"h":"Consider whether the speaker actually expects a factual reply.","e":"A rhetorical question is posed for effect rather than information, steering the audience toward the speaker's implied conclusion."},{"p":"Read: \"We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds, we shall fight in the fields.\" The repeated words at the start of these clauses illustrate","a":"anaphora, the repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses","w":["epistrophe, the repetition of a word at the end of successive clauses","asyndeton, the deliberate omission of conjunctions between clauses","chiasmus, the reversal of grammatical structure across clauses"],"h":"Focus on WHERE in each clause the repeated words appear.","e":"Anaphora repeats the same words at the beginning of successive clauses to build emphasis and rhythm."},{"p":"Read: \"Ask not what your country can do for you; ask what you can do for your country.\" This sentence is constructed on","a":"antithesis, the juxtaposition of contrasting ideas in parallel grammatical structure","w":["hyperbole, deliberate exaggeration for rhetorical effect","understatement, deliberate minimizing for rhetorical effect","allusion, an indirect reference to another text or event"],"h":"Notice the two balanced halves that reverse each other's key terms.","e":"Antithesis places contrasting ideas in parallel grammatical form to sharpen the contrast between them."},{"p":"Read: \"Admittedly, the policy will cost taxpayers in the short term; nevertheless, its long-term savings justify the expense.\" The first clause functions as","a":"a concession that acknowledges an opposing point before the author counters it","w":["a thesis that states the author's central claim","a hyperbolic exaggeration of the policy's true cost","an anecdote offered as personal evidence"],"h":"Consider why a writer would admit a drawback right before the word 'nevertheless.'","e":"A concession grants a point to the opposition, boosting credibility before the author rebuts or outweighs it."},{"p":"Read: \"Oh, splendid, another two-hour meeting that could have been an email. How I treasure these precious hours.\" The tone of this passage is best described as","a":"sarcastic","w":["reverent","nostalgic","earnest"],"h":"Weigh the literal praise against the tedious situation being described.","e":"Tone is the author's attitude toward the subject; the gap between praise and a dull meeting signals sarcasm."},{"p":"Read: After the hurricane tore the roof from the house, the owner remarked, \"We may need to do a little repair work.\" This remark is an example of","a":"understatement, deliberately representing something as less significant than it is","w":["hyperbole, deliberately exaggerating something for emphasis","euphemism, substituting a mild term for a taboo one","personification, giving human traits to a nonhuman thing"],"h":"Compare the scale of the damage with the size of the described response.","e":"Understatement minimizes the magnitude of something for rhetorical effect, often producing irony."},{"p":"Read: \"This pamphlet outlines three simple steps every household can take today to cut its water use in half.\" The author's primary purpose is to","a":"persuade readers to adopt specific conservation actions","w":["narrate a personal story about a past water shortage","entertain readers with a lighthearted anecdote","analyze the chemical composition of drinking water"],"h":"Focus on what the author wants the reader to DO after reading.","e":"Author's purpose is the goal a text aims to achieve; the call to concrete steps signals a persuasive aim."},{"p":"Read: The senator did not merely 'disagree' with the plan; the reporter wrote that she 'railed against' it. The phrase 'railed against' carries a connotation of","a":"intense, vehement opposition","w":["calm, measured disagreement","cautious, tentative doubt","cheerful, playful teasing"],"h":"Consider the emotional weight the verb adds beyond plain disagreement.","e":"Connotation is the emotional association a word carries beyond its literal meaning; 'railed against' implies forceful hostility."},{"p":"Read: \"Running a national economy is like steering a massive ship: sudden turns capsize it, so change must come gradually.\" The author supports this argument PRIMARILY through","a":"an analogy comparing the economy to a ship to argue for gradual change","w":["a statistic that quantifies recent economic growth","an appeal to a recognized authority on economics","a direct rebuttal of a named opposing economist"],"h":"Identify the comparison the author draws between two unlike things.","e":"An analogy argues by comparing two different things that share a relevant similarity, here to justify gradual change."},{"p":"Read: A pediatrician writes for a magazine aimed at new parents, using plain language and reassuring examples about infant sleep. These choices are best explained as an adaptation to","a":"the audience, shaping tone and diction to suit anxious new parents","w":["the genre conventions of a scientific research paper","the formal constraints of a written legal brief","the stylistic conventions of an epic poem"],"h":"Ask who the writer expects to be reading and why the style fits them.","e":"Effective rhetoric adapts to its audience; simple, reassuring language suits non-expert, anxious new parents."},{"p":"Read: \"In the same city, a billionaire tours his private rooftop garden while a family of five shares one crowded room.\" The author's technique here is","a":"juxtaposition, placing contrasting images side by side to highlight disparity","w":["allusion, referencing a well-known text or figure","apostrophe, directly addressing an absent person","syllogism, arranging premises to reach a conclusion"],"h":"Notice the two contrasting scenes set directly next to each other.","e":"Juxtaposition positions contrasting elements together to emphasize their differences, here economic inequality."},{"p":"Read: \"Standardized tests are unfair. In our district, students from the wealthiest schools scored two hundred points higher on average.\" The second sentence functions as","a":"evidence offered to support the claim in the first sentence","w":["a counterargument raised against the first sentence","a simple restatement of the first sentence","a concession granted to the opposing side"],"h":"Consider whether the second sentence asserts an opinion or provides support for one.","e":"Evidence consists of facts or data that back a claim; the score gap supports the assertion of unfairness."},{"p":"Read: \"Leading climate scientists at NASA and the National Academy of Sciences agree that the warming trend is accelerating.\" This sentence strengthens the argument MAINLY by","a":"citing respected authorities to build ethos","w":["appealing directly to the reader's fear through pathos","presenting a step-by-step mathematical proof through logos","posing a rhetorical question directly to the reader"],"h":"Consider whose reputations the author borrows to earn the reader's trust.","e":"Referencing credible experts is an ethos strategy, lending authority and trustworthiness to a claim."},{"p":"Read: \"Through hardship, through doubt, through years of quiet labor, she finally earned the degree.\" By delaying the main clause until the end, the author creates","a":"a periodic sentence that builds suspense toward its climactic main clause","w":["a loose sentence that states its main idea first","a fragment that omits a grammatically required element","a run-on that improperly fuses two independent clauses"],"h":"Notice where the grammatical completion of the thought finally arrives.","e":"A periodic sentence withholds its main clause until the end, building anticipation and emphasis."},{"p":"Read: \"The town's fire station burned to the ground last night.\" The situation described is best identified as","a":"situational irony, an outcome strikingly contrary to what is expected","w":["verbal irony, saying the opposite of what one means","dramatic irony, when the audience knows what characters do not","metaphor, an implied comparison between two unlike things"],"h":"Consider the gap between what one expects of a fire station and what actually happened.","e":"Situational irony occurs when reality contradicts expectations; a fire station burning down subverts its very purpose."},{"p":"Read: \"My opponent's plan to fund the new library deserves no serious consideration; after all, he was twice divorced and rarely attends church.\" The reasoning in this passage is flawed because it","a":"attacks the person's character instead of addressing the merits of his plan","w":["generalizes from a single unrepresentative example to a broad claim","assumes that because one event followed another, the first caused the second","presents only two options when other alternatives clearly exist"],"h":"Consider what the speaker criticizes: the plan itself, or the man proposing it.","e":"This is an ad hominem fallacy, which attacks the arguer's character or circumstances rather than the substance of the argument."},{"p":"Read: \"Senator Ruiz says we should reduce the military budget slightly. Apparently she wants to leave our nation defenseless and invite our enemies to attack.\" The speaker's response is fallacious because it","a":"distorts the opponent's position into an extreme version that is easier to attack","w":["relies on the opinion of an expert who lacks relevant authority","concludes that a modest first step will inevitably lead to disaster","supports a claim using evidence that merely restates the claim"],"h":"Compare what Senator Ruiz actually proposed with what the speaker claims she wants.","e":"This is a straw man fallacy: misrepresenting an opponent's argument as a more extreme claim in order to refute it more easily."},{"p":"Read: \"If we allow students to redo one failed quiz, soon they will demand to retake every exam, then every course, and eventually the diploma will mean nothing.\" The reasoning here is best described as","a":"a slippery slope, assuming one small step must lead to extreme consequences","w":["a false dilemma, reducing a complex issue to only two choices","a hasty generalization, drawing a broad rule from too little evidence","a circular argument, using its conclusion as its own premise"],"h":"Trace the chain of events the speaker predicts from a single modest change.","e":"The slippery-slope fallacy assumes without justification that one action will trigger an inevitable chain of increasingly dire outcomes."},{"p":"Read: \"Running a school is exactly like running a business: since businesses fire their least productive workers, schools should simply expel their lowest-scoring students.\" The argument is weakest because it","a":"treats two fundamentally different situations as if they were equivalent","w":["appeals to the emotions of the audience rather than to reason","cites a statistic without identifying its original source","introduces a personal attack against those who disagree"],"h":"Ask whether the two things being compared are truly alike in the relevant respects.","e":"A false analogy assumes that because two things share some features, they are alike in the specific respect under debate, ignoring crucial differences."},{"p":"Read: \"I was raised in a town much like yours, where neighbors still help one another bring in the harvest, and I have never forgotten those values.\" In building credibility, the speaker relies chiefly on","a":"establishing shared values and common ground with the audience","w":["citing professional qualifications and years of formal training","presenting statistical evidence drawn from reliable studies","arousing the audience's fear of an approaching danger"],"h":"Notice that the speaker offers no credentials or data, only a shared background.","e":"This is an appeal to ethos through goodwill and identification, building trust by aligning the speaker's values with the audience's rather than by citing expertise."},{"p":"Read: \"Before we hand this untested candidate the keys to the treasury, remember that even Icarus was certain he could fly.\" The reference to Icarus functions as","a":"an allusion that warns against overconfidence by evoking a familiar story","w":["a hyperbole that exaggerates the candidate's inexperience for effect","an anecdote drawn from the speaker's own personal experience","a euphemism that softens an unpleasant truth about the candidate"],"h":"Consider what a reader must already know for the reference to carry meaning.","e":"An allusion is a brief reference to a well-known figure or story that imports its associations, here the myth of Icarus's fatal overreach."},{"p":"Read: \"Winning the national title after such a season was, needless to say, no small feat for the team.\" The phrase \"no small feat\" is an example of","a":"litotes, affirming something by negating its opposite","w":["hyperbole, overstating an achievement beyond literal truth","oxymoron, joining two contradictory terms in one phrase","metonymy, substituting a related term for the thing meant"],"h":"The writer expresses a strongly positive idea using a negative construction.","e":"Litotes is a form of understatement that affirms a point by denying its contrary, so \"no small\" conveys \"very great.\""},{"p":"Read: \"She signed the last form, the ink still wet, her hand trembling, her mind already racing toward the years of work the decision would demand.\" The structure of this sentence is best described as","a":"cumulative, beginning with the main clause and adding modifying details","w":["periodic, withholding the main clause until the very end","fragmented, omitting a grammatical subject or verb entirely","inverted, reversing the normal order of subject and predicate"],"h":"Identify where the complete main idea appears, then note what follows it.","e":"A cumulative (loose) sentence states its main clause first and then accumulates modifying phrases, creating a sense of unfolding detail."},{"p":"Read: \"Critics claim the program wastes money, but every independent audit has found that it returns three dollars in savings for every dollar spent.\" The primary function of this sentence is to","a":"rebut an opposing claim by presenting contrary evidence","w":["concede a valid point before shifting to a new topic","define a key term the audience may misunderstand","establish the writer's authority through personal experience"],"h":"Notice the sentence first names an objection, then responds to it.","e":"This is refutation (rebuttal): the writer acknowledges a counterargument and then supplies evidence to overturn it."},{"p":"Read: A columnist ends her essay on ambition with the line, \"Those who chase two rabbits catch none.\" This concluding sentence is best identified as","a":"an aphorism that compresses a general truth into a memorable saying","w":["a rhetorical question that invites the reader to reflect","an anecdote that recounts a specific personal event","a qualification that limits the scope of an earlier claim"],"h":"Consider whether the line states a broad principle in brief, quotable form.","e":"An aphorism is a concise, memorable statement of a general truth or principle, often used to close an argument with force."},{"p":"Read: \"Both proposals have merit, and reasonable people may disagree; still, on balance, the evidence tilts modestly toward the second plan.\" The tone of this passage is best described as","a":"measured and judicious","w":["indignant and accusatory","nostalgic and wistful","flippant and dismissive"],"h":"Weigh the qualifying words such as \"on balance\" and \"modestly.\"","e":"Diction like \"reasonable people may disagree\" and \"modestly\" signals a measured, judicious tone that weighs evidence carefully rather than asserting forcefully."},{"p":"Read: \"The new medication may help some patients, and preliminary data suggest it could reduce symptoms in certain cases.\" The qualifiers (\"may,\" \"some,\" \"could,\" \"certain\") primarily serve to","a":"limit the scope of the claim and acknowledge its uncertainty","w":["intensify the claim by emphasizing its wide application","appeal to the reader's emotions through vivid language","establish the writer's expertise in medical research"],"h":"Consider how the claim would change if these words were removed.","e":"Qualifiers hedge a claim, narrowing its scope and signaling appropriate caution about the strength of the evidence."},{"p":"Read: \"To show how the shortage affects real families, the author describes a single mother who waited six hours at the food bank only to be turned away.\" In the argument, this description functions as","a":"an anecdote used to illustrate a larger claim","w":["a statistic used to quantify the scope of the problem","a concession used to grant merit to the opposing side","an analogy used to compare two unlike situations"],"h":"Ask whether the author is offering a specific story or a general figure.","e":"An anecdote is a brief, specific narrative used as illustrative evidence to make an abstract claim vivid and relatable."},{"p":"Read: \"You have felt it too: the quiet dread on a Sunday evening, the sense that your own time is no longer yours.\" The author's use of the second-person \"you\" chiefly serves to","a":"draw the reader into the experience and assume a shared feeling","w":["establish the author's credentials on the subject","present objective data about workplace stress","concede a limitation in the author's argument"],"h":"Consider the relationship the pronoun creates between writer and reader.","e":"Direct second-person address positions the reader as a participant, creating intimacy and presuming a shared experience to build identification."},{"p":"Read: \"Call your representative today. Attend the hearing on Thursday. Refuse to let this ordinance pass in silence.\" The grammatical mood of these sentences primarily works to","a":"issue direct commands that urge the reader toward action","w":["pose questions that prompt quiet reflection","report events in neutral, factual terms","express doubts about the likelihood of success"],"h":"Notice that each sentence begins with a verb directed at the reader.","e":"The imperative mood gives commands; here it converts the argument into a direct call to action, urging specific behavior from the audience."},{"p":"Read: \"Traffic deaths fell 40 percent in the three years after the speed cameras were installed, while neighboring towns without cameras saw no change.\" This evidence strengthens the argument chiefly by","a":"using a comparison group to suggest the cameras caused the decline","w":["appealing to the authority of traffic-safety experts","arousing the reader's fear of dangerous drivers","conceding that other factors may explain the drop"],"h":"Consider why the writer mentions the neighboring towns at all.","e":"By contrasting towns with and without cameras, the writer uses controlled comparison (logos) to support a causal claim rather than mere correlation."},{"p":"Read: \"Either we cut every environmental regulation now, or we accept that our factories will close and thousands will lose their jobs.\" The reasoning is flawed because it","a":"presents only two options when other possibilities exist","w":["attacks the character of those who support regulation","assumes an early step must lead to an extreme outcome","draws a sweeping conclusion from a single example"],"h":"Ask whether the two outcomes named are truly the only ones available.","e":"A false dilemma (either-or fallacy) misrepresents a complex issue as having only two mutually exclusive outcomes."},{"p":"Read: \"This town deserves clean water. Our children deserve clean water. Our grandchildren deserve clean water.\" The repetition of the phrase \"deserve clean water\" at the END of each sentence is best identified as","a":"epistrophe, the repetition of words at the end of successive clauses","w":["anaphora, the repetition of words at the beginning of successive clauses","asyndeton, the omission of conjunctions between successive clauses","antithesis, the balancing of two sharply contrasting ideas"],"h":"Consider WHERE in each sentence the repeated words fall.","e":"Epistrophe is the repetition of the same word or phrase at the end of successive clauses; it is the mirror image of anaphora, which repeats words at the beginning."},{"p":"Read: \"We packed the bread and the cheese and the water and the blankets, and then we walked into the dark.\" The deliberate repetition of the conjunction \"and\" is an example of","a":"polysyndeton, which slows the rhythm and stresses accumulation","w":["asyndeton, which omits conjunctions to quicken the rhythm","anaphora, which repeats the same words at the start of clauses","parallelism, which repeats an identical grammatical structure"],"h":"Notice how many conjunctions appear where the writer could simply have used commas.","e":"Polysyndeton deliberately inserts extra coordinating conjunctions (\"and...and...and\") to slow the pace and pile up detail; asyndeton is its opposite."},{"p":"Read: \"She checked the sources, rewrote the draft, met the deadline, moved on.\" The omission of conjunctions between these parallel clauses is called","a":"asyndeton, which quickens the pace and conveys urgency","w":["polysyndeton, which multiplies conjunctions to slow the pace","epistrophe, which repeats the same words at the end of clauses","zeugma, which yokes two objects to a single verb"],"h":"Ask what small connecting words the writer chose to leave out.","e":"Asyndeton omits conjunctions between coordinate elements to create speed and momentum; it is the structural opposite of polysyndeton."},{"p":"Read: \"On that miserable morning he lost his umbrella and his patience.\" A single verb, \"lost,\" governs two objects in literal and figurative senses at once, a device known as","a":"zeugma, one word governing two others in different senses","w":["metonymy, substituting an associated term for the thing meant","oxymoron, joining two openly contradictory terms","personification, giving human traits to an inanimate thing"],"h":"Look at how one verb stretches across two very different kinds of \"loss.\"","e":"Zeugma (syllepsis) uses a single word to govern two others, applying to each in a different sense, typically pairing a literal meaning with a figurative one."},{"p":"Read: \"By noon the White House had issued a statement, and Wall Street had already begun to panic.\" The terms \"White House\" and \"Wall Street\" are best identified as","a":"metonymy, naming something by an institution or place closely associated with it","w":["synecdoche, naming a whole by one of its physical parts","personification, giving human qualities to an abstraction","hyperbole, deliberate exaggeration used for rhetorical effect"],"h":"Each name stands in for a group of people by association, not by being a literal piece of them.","e":"Metonymy substitutes a closely associated term (a place or institution) for the thing meant; synecdoche, the common distractor, specifically substitutes a part for the whole."},{"p":"Read: \"We spend our health to gain wealth, then spend our wealth to buy back health.\" The inverted mirror structure (health-wealth, wealth-health) is best identified as","a":"chiasmus, the reversal of grammatical order in two parallel phrases","w":["anaphora, the repetition of opening words in successive clauses","epistrophe, the repetition of closing words in successive clauses","hyperbole, deliberate overstatement used for emphasis"],"h":"Trace the order of the two key nouns in the first half, then in the second.","e":"Chiasmus reverses the order of corresponding words or grammatical structures in the second half of a construction (ABBA), distinguishing it from straightforward parallel repetition."},{"p":"Read: \"The proposed highway should be rejected, because it would drain and pave the last wetlands in the county.\" In Toulmin's model the claim is that the highway should be rejected and the grounds are that it would destroy the wetlands; the unstated WARRANT connecting them is the assumption that","a":"preserving the county's remaining wetlands matters more than building the highway","w":["the highway would in fact drain and pave the wetlands as described","the wetlands provide habitat for several endangered species","the county does not have enough money to complete the highway"],"h":"The warrant is the belief a reader must already accept for the stated evidence to justify the stated claim.","e":"In Toulmin analysis the warrant is the unstated assumption that licenses the move from grounds to claim; here it is the value judgment that saving the wetlands outweighs building the highway."},{"p":"Read: \"The month after the new principal arrived, test scores rose sharply; plainly, her arrival is what raised our scores.\" The reasoning is most flawed because it","a":"assumes that because the rise followed her arrival, her arrival caused it","w":["dismisses the principal's argument by attacking her character","offers only two possible explanations for the change","draws a broad conclusion from a single classroom's results"],"h":"Sequence in time is not the same thing as cause.","e":"This is the post hoc ergo propter hoc fallacy (false cause): treating mere temporal succession as proof of a causal relationship."},{"p":"Read: \"This is clearly the most trustworthy newspaper in the state, because no other paper reports the news so reliably.\" The reasoning is flawed because it","a":"assumes as already proven the very claim it is meant to establish","w":["diverts attention toward an unrelated side issue","relies on the testimony of an unqualified expert","exaggerates the paper's reach for dramatic effect"],"h":"Compare what the \"because\" clause asserts with the conclusion it supposedly supports.","e":"This is begging the question (circular reasoning): the premise (\"reports so reliably\") merely restates the conclusion (\"most trustworthy\") instead of proving it."},{"p":"Read: \"You ask whether I underreported my income, but shouldn't we be far more concerned about how my accuser has treated his own employees?\" The response is fallacious because it","a":"diverts attention to an unrelated issue instead of answering the charge","w":["assumes the truth of the very point it must prove","concludes far too much from too few cases","treats one small concession as leading to ruin"],"h":"Ask whether the reply actually addresses the question that was posed.","e":"This is a red herring: introducing an irrelevant issue to distract from the question at hand rather than engaging it directly."},{"p":"Read: \"More than two million families have already switched to SunFresh detergent, so it is obviously the right choice for your home too.\" The argument depends chiefly on","a":"an appeal to popularity, treating wide use as proof of quality","w":["an appeal to a qualified and directly relevant authority","an appeal to long-standing custom and tradition","an appeal to the audience's pity and fear"],"h":"What kind of evidence does the figure \"two million families\" actually provide?","e":"This is the bandwagon appeal (argumentum ad populum): the claim that something is good or correct simply because a large number of people accept it."},{"p":"Read: \"Our firm has always promoted from within and never hired outside managers; that history alone is reason enough to keep the practice.\" The reasoning is best described as","a":"an appeal to tradition, treating long practice as its own justification","w":["an appeal to popularity among rival firms in the field","a false dilemma between only two possible options","a slippery slope leading toward an extreme outcome"],"h":"Ask what support, other than the practice being old, is actually offered.","e":"An appeal to tradition assumes that because something has long been done a certain way, it is therefore right or best, without offering independent justification."},{"p":"Read: \"Two drivers from that city cut me off today, so people from there clearly have no manners behind the wheel.\" The reasoning is flawed because it","a":"draws a sweeping conclusion from an unrepresentative sample","w":["assumes one event caused a later, unrelated event","shifts the argument to an emotionally charged side topic","restates its conclusion as though it were its own premise"],"h":"Consider how many cases the broad claim is actually built on.","e":"This is a hasty generalization: inferring a broad conclusion about an entire group from too few or unrepresentative instances."},{"p":"Read: \"The law must treat all citizens equally, and since we are all equally unique, the law should therefore treat each of us differently.\" The reasoning goes wrong by","a":"shifting the meaning of a key word (\"equally\") between the premises","w":["appealing to the emotions of the audience rather than to reason","inferring an event's cause merely from its timing","attacking a position that no one actually holds"],"h":"The same word appears to be doing two different jobs in the two halves.","e":"This is equivocation: the argument trades on two different senses of a single term, making an invalid inference appear valid."},{"p":"Read: \"O Justice, have you abandoned this courtroom, or do you simply sleep while the guilty walk free?\" In directly addressing an abstraction as though it could hear and answer, the speaker uses","a":"apostrophe, a direct address to an absent or abstract entity","w":["allusion, a passing reference to a well-known text or figure","hyperbole, a deliberate and obvious exaggeration for effect","understatement, a deliberate minimizing of true magnitude"],"h":"Notice whom, or what, the speaker is speaking directly to.","e":"Apostrophe is the device of directly addressing an absent person, a dead person, or an abstraction (here, Justice) as if it were present and able to respond."},{"p":"Read: \"The faster he rushed to save time, the more time his careless errors ended up costing him.\" The statement is best identified as a","a":"paradox, a seemingly self-contradictory statement that reveals a truth","w":["oxymoron, two contradictory words placed directly side by side","euphemism, a mild term substituted for a harsh reality","hyperbole, an exaggeration that is not meant literally"],"h":"The whole sentence seems to contradict itself, yet it makes sense on reflection.","e":"A paradox is a statement that appears self-contradictory but expresses a genuine truth; an oxymoron, by contrast, is a compact pairing of two contradictory words."},{"p":"Read: \"In this very week, while the ash of the wildfire still hangs in our air, I urge you to pass the forest-management bill now, before the memory fades.\" The speaker's appeal rests most heavily on","a":"kairos, seizing the urgency and fitness of the present moment","w":["ethos, resting the case on the speaker's own authority","logos, resting the case on a structured chain of statistics","an appeal to long-standing tradition and established custom"],"h":"Notice how much the appeal leans on timing rather than on data or credentials.","e":"Kairos is the rhetorical appeal to the opportune moment, urging action because present circumstances make it especially timely and fitting."},{"p":"Read: \"The airline's memo explained that, following the crash, the aircraft had 'experienced an unscheduled ground-contact event' with 'no further utilization anticipated.'\" These phrases are best identified as","a":"euphemism, substituting mild or evasive wording for a harsh reality","w":["understatement, deliberately representing something as smaller than it is","verbal irony, deliberately saying the opposite of what is meant","hyperbole, deliberately exaggerating far beyond the literal truth"],"h":"Ask why the writer avoids naming plainly what actually happened.","e":"Euphemism replaces blunt or unpleasant language with softer, often evasive substitutes; here the bureaucratic phrasing disguises a fatal crash."}],"honors-spanish":[{"p":"Completa: \"Es necesario que tú ___ la tarea antes de salir de casa.\"","a":"termines","w":["terminas","terminarás","terminaste"],"h":"Fíjate en la expresión impersonal que introduce la cláusula subordinada.","e":"Las expresiones impersonales de necesidad como 'es necesario que' exigen el presente de subjuntivo en la cláusula subordinada."},{"p":"Completa: \"No creo que ellos ___ la verdad sobre lo ocurrido.\"","a":"digan","w":["dicen","dirán","decían"],"h":"Observa el verbo principal negado que expresa incredulidad.","e":"La duda o negación de la realidad ('no creer que') desencadena el presente de subjuntivo."},{"p":"Completa: \"Te explico las reglas para que ___ el concepto sin dificultad.\"","a":"entiendas","w":["entiendes","entenderás","entendías"],"h":"Piensa en qué modo requiere una conjunción de propósito o finalidad.","e":"La conjunción adverbial 'para que' siempre introduce el subjuntivo porque expresa finalidad o propósito."},{"p":"Completa: \"Ojalá que mañana ___ buen tiempo para el partido.\"","a":"haga","w":["hace","hará","hacía"],"h":"Considera qué modo acompaña a las expresiones de deseo.","e":"La partícula 'ojalá (que)' expresa deseo y exige el subjuntivo."},{"p":"Completa: \"Me alegro mucho de que tú ___ terminado el proyecto a tiempo.\"","a":"hayas","w":["has","habías","habrás"],"h":"El verbo principal expresa emoción y la acción subordinada ya está concluida.","e":"Un verbo de emoción más 'que' y una acción ya completada requieren el pretérito perfecto de subjuntivo (haya + participio)."},{"p":"Completa: \"Si yo ___ estudiado más, habría aprobado el examen final.\"","a":"hubiera","w":["había","habría","habré"],"h":"La oración plantea una situación contraria a los hechos en el pasado.","e":"En las oraciones condicionales irreales del pasado, la cláusula con 'si' usa el pluscuamperfecto de subjuntivo (hubiera + participio), correlacionado con el condicional perfecto."},{"p":"Completa: \"Este año nosotros ___ visitado tres países diferentes.\"","a":"hemos","w":["habíamos","habremos","hayamos"],"h":"El marcador 'este año' señala un periodo que aún incluye el presente.","e":"El pretérito perfecto de indicativo (haber en presente + participio) describe acciones completadas dentro de un periodo que continúa hasta ahora."},{"p":"Completa: \"Cuando llegué al cine, la película ya ___ empezado.\"","a":"había","w":["ha","habría","haya"],"h":"Se describe una acción anterior a otra acción pasada.","e":"El pluscuamperfecto de indicativo (haber en imperfecto + participio) expresa una acción pasada anterior a otro momento del pasado."},{"p":"Completa el mandato formal: \"Señor Ruiz, ___ aquí el formulario, por favor.\"","a":"firme","w":["firma","firmas","firmar"],"h":"El trato de 'usted' cambia la vocal temática del imperativo.","e":"El mandato formal afirmativo (usted) se forma con la vocal 'opuesta': los verbos en -ar toman la terminación -e."},{"p":"Completa el mandato negativo: \"No ___ tarde a clase mañana, por favor.\" (llegar, tú)","a":"llegues","w":["llegas","llega","llegar"],"h":"Los mandatos negativos informales toman la forma del subjuntivo.","e":"El mandato negativo de 'tú' usa la forma correspondiente del presente de subjuntivo (no llegues)."},{"p":"¿Cuál es la forma correcta del mandato afirmativo de 'nosotros' para decir 'let's go to the beach'?","a":"Vamos a la playa","w":["Fuimos a la playa","Iremos a la playa","Íbamos a la playa"],"h":"El verbo 'ir' tiene una forma irregular y especial en este mandato afirmativo.","e":"El mandato afirmativo de 'nosotros' de 'ir' es la excepción 'vamos'; las demás opciones son tiempos del indicativo (pretérito, futuro e imperfecto), no un mandato."},{"p":"¿Cuál es la forma correcta del mandato afirmativo (tú) con pronombres para 'give it to me'?","a":"Dámelo","w":["Me lo das","Da me lo","Dalo me"],"h":"En los mandatos afirmativos, los pronombres tienen una posición fija respecto al verbo.","e":"En los mandatos afirmativos los pronombres de objeto se unen al final del verbo y suele añadirse una tilde para mantener el acento (dá + me + lo = dámelo)."},{"p":"Completa: \"Pagué veinte dólares ___ el libro de poesía usado.\"","a":"por","w":["para","de","a"],"h":"Piensa en el uso que expresa intercambio o precio.","e":"'Por' se emplea para indicar intercambio, precio o el equivalente de algo ('a cambio de')."},{"p":"Completa: \"Todas las mañanas caminamos ___ el parque camino al trabajo.\"","a":"por","w":["para","hacia","en"],"h":"Se describe el movimiento a través de un espacio.","e":"'Por' expresa movimiento a través de o a lo largo de un lugar."},{"p":"¿Cuál es el sinónimo más apropiado del adjetivo 'sagaz'?","a":"astuto","w":["perezoso","torpe","ingenuo"],"h":"Describe a alguien perspicaz que capta las cosas con rapidez.","e":"'Sagaz' significa perspicaz o listo; su sinónimo más cercano es 'astuto'."},{"p":"¿Quién es el autor de la obra 'Don Quijote de la Mancha'?","a":"Miguel de Cervantes","w":["Lope de Vega","Francisco de Quevedo","Garcilaso de la Vega"],"h":"Se trata del máximo representante de la prosa del Siglo de Oro español.","e":"Miguel de Cervantes escribió 'Don Quijote de la Mancha', considerada la primera novela moderna."},{"p":"Lee el pasaje y responde. Read: \"Marta llevaba años soñando con estudiar en el extranjero. Cuando por fin recibió la beca, no lo podía creer. Sus padres, aunque tristes por su partida, se sentían muy orgullosos de ella.\" Según el texto, ¿cómo se sienten los padres de Marta?","a":"Orgullosos, aunque tristes por su partida","w":["Enojados y decepcionados con ella","Indiferentes ante su partida","Preocupados por perder la beca"],"h":"Localiza la oración que describe directamente la emoción de los padres.","e":"La comprensión lectora requiere identificar la información explícita: el texto dice que están 'tristes' pero 'muy orgullosos', combinación de ambos sentimientos."},{"p":"Completa: \"Iremos de excursión a menos que ___ mucho este fin de semana.\" (llover)","a":"llueva","w":["llueve","lloverá","llovió"],"h":"'A menos que' introduce una condición hipotética y siempre exige el mismo modo.","e":"Las conjunciones de condición como 'a menos que' siempre requieren el subjuntivo; aquí el presente de subjuntivo 'llueva'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Ese joven gasta el dinero como si ___ millonario.\" (ser)","a":"fuera","w":["es","era","sería"],"h":"'Como si' plantea una comparación irreal o contraria a la realidad.","e":"La expresión 'como si' siempre exige el imperfecto (o pluscuamperfecto) de subjuntivo: 'fuera'."},{"p":"Completa: \"El profesor nos pidió que ___ la composición antes del lunes.\" (entregar, nosotros)","a":"entregáramos","w":["entreguemos","entregamos","entregaríamos"],"h":"El verbo principal está en pasado; fíjate en la concordancia de tiempos.","e":"Por la correlación de tiempos, un verbo principal en pretérito ('pidió') exige imperfecto de subjuntivo en la subordinada: 'entregáramos'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Dudo que ellos ya ___ el informe esta mañana.\" (terminar)","a":"hayan terminado","w":["han terminado","hubieran terminado","habían terminado"],"h":"La duda va en presente y la acción se sitúa en un pasado reciente y acabado.","e":"'Dudar que' exige subjuntivo, y una acción pasada acabada con relación al presente requiere el pretérito perfecto de subjuntivo: 'hayan terminado'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Es evidente que ella ya ___ la solución al problema.\" (encontrar)","a":"ha encontrado","w":["haya encontrado","hubiera encontrado","encuentre"],"h":"Fíjate en si la expresión impersonal comunica certeza o duda.","e":"Las expresiones impersonales de certeza como 'es evidente que' toman indicativo, no subjuntivo; por eso el pretérito perfecto de indicativo 'ha encontrado'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Para diciembre del próximo año, yo ya ___ de la universidad.\" (graduarse)","a":"me habré graduado","w":["me habría graduado","me haya graduado","me había graduado"],"h":"La acción se completará antes de un momento futuro concreto.","e":"El futuro perfecto ('habré graduado') expresa una acción que estará acabada antes de un punto en el futuro."},{"p":"Completa: \"No es cierto que él ___ el responsable del accidente.\" (ser)","a":"sea","w":["es","será","fue"],"h":"La expresión niega la certeza de la información.","e":"Al negar una expresión de certeza ('no es cierto que'), se introduce duda y se exige el subjuntivo: 'sea'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Necesito contratar a un asistente que ___ tres idiomas con fluidez.\" (hablar)","a":"hable","w":["habla","hablará","hablaba"],"h":"El antecedente del que se habla todavía no se conoce ni existe con certeza.","e":"En cláusulas adjetivas con antecedente indefinido o desconocido se usa el subjuntivo: 'hable'."},{"p":"Completa el mandato negativo de 'nosotros': \"Es muy temprano; no ___ todavía.\" (levantarse)","a":"nos levantemos","w":["levantémonos","nos levantamos","os levantéis"],"h":"En los mandatos negativos el pronombre reflexivo cambia de posición respecto al afirmativo.","e":"El mandato negativo de 'nosotros' usa el presente de subjuntivo con el pronombre delante del verbo: 'no nos levantemos'."},{"p":"Completa el mandato formal plural: \"Señores, ___ la verdad, por favor.\" (decirme)","a":"Díganme","w":["Dígenme","Díjanme","Dígame"],"h":"Es un mandato de 'ustedes' con un pronombre de objeto añadido al final.","e":"El mandato afirmativo de 'ustedes' de 'decir' es 'digan', y el pronombre se une al verbo con tilde: 'Díganme'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Muchas gracias ___ toda tu ayuda con la mudanza.\"","a":"por","w":["para","porque","para que"],"h":"Se agradece el motivo o la causa de algo recibido.","e":"'Por' expresa la causa, el motivo o la razón de una acción, como al dar las gracias por algo."},{"p":"Completa: \"Mi hermana estudia día y noche ___ llegar a ser cirujana.\"","a":"para","w":["por","porque","para que"],"h":"Piensa si se expresa una meta futura o una causa pasada.","e":"'Para' introduce la finalidad, el propósito o el objetivo de una acción: estudiar con el fin de ser cirujana."},{"p":"Completa: \"___, tras dos horas de retraso, apareció el autobús.\"","a":"Por fin","w":["Para fin","Por final","Para siempre"],"h":"Es una locución fija que expresa que algo esperado ocurre al cabo del tiempo.","e":"'Por fin' es una expresión idiomática con 'por' que significa 'finalmente' o 'al cabo'."},{"p":"¿Cuál es el sinónimo más apropiado del adjetivo 'terco'?","a":"obstinado","w":["generoso","cobarde","perezoso"],"h":"Describe a quien no cambia de opinión ni cede fácilmente.","e":"'Terco' significa que insiste con firmeza en algo; su sinónimo es 'obstinado'."},{"p":"¿Cuál es el antónimo más apropiado del adjetivo 'escaso'?","a":"abundante","w":["raro","breve","ausente"],"h":"Piensa en lo contrario de algo que hay en poca cantidad.","e":"'Escaso' indica poca cantidad; su antónimo es 'abundante', que indica gran cantidad."},{"p":"¿Quién es el autor de la novela 'Cien años de soledad'?","a":"Gabriel García Márquez","w":["Mario Vargas Llosa","Jorge Luis Borges","Pablo Neruda"],"h":"Es un novelista colombiano ligado al realismo mágico y ganador del Premio Nobel.","e":"'Cien años de soledad' (1967) es la obra cumbre del colombiano Gabriel García Márquez, máximo exponente del realismo mágico."},{"p":"¿De qué país era el poeta Pablo Neruda, autor de 'Veinte poemas de amor y una canción desesperada'?","a":"Chile","w":["Argentina","España","México"],"h":"Es un país de la costa del Pacífico en el sur de Sudamérica.","e":"Pablo Neruda fue un poeta chileno galardonado con el Premio Nobel de Literatura en 1971."},{"p":"Lee el pasaje y responde. Read: \"Cuando Andrés abrió la puerta de la vieja casa abandonada, lo recibió un olor a polvo y a madera húmeda. Nadie había vivido allí en años; sin embargo, sobre la mesa de la cocina había una taza de café todavía tibia.\" ¿Qué se puede inferir del texto?","a":"Alguien estuvo en la casa hace muy poco tiempo.","w":["Andrés había vivido en esa casa de niño.","La casa acababa de ser construida.","Andrés preparó el café antes de entrar."],"h":"Fíjate en el detalle que contrasta con la idea de abandono.","e":"La inferencia se apoya en un detalle clave: una taza 'todavía tibia' implica presencia reciente, pese a que la casa parece abandonada."},{"p":"Completa: \"Aunque ___ rico, jamás compraría una mansión tan ostentosa como esa.\" (ser)","a":"fuera","w":["era","sería","es"],"h":"'Aunque' aquí introduce una situación hipotética o contraria a la realidad, no un hecho concreto.","e":"Cuando 'aunque' expresa una hipótesis irreal, se usa el imperfecto de subjuntivo ('fuera'), correlacionado con el condicional en la cláusula principal."},{"p":"Completa: \"Me sorprendió mucho que ellos no ___ a la reunión de ayer.\" (venir)","a":"vinieran","w":["vengan","vinieron","hayan venido"],"h":"Fíjate en el tiempo del verbo principal 'sorprendió' y aplica la concordancia de tiempos.","e":"La secuencia de tiempos exige que un verbo principal en pasado ('sorprendió') que expresa emoción rija el imperfecto de subjuntivo ('vinieran') en la subordinada."},{"p":"Completa: \"En esta oficina no hay nadie que ___ resolver un problema tan complejo.\" (poder)","a":"pueda","w":["puede","pudo","podría"],"h":"El antecedente 'nadie' es un ente negado o inexistente; observa cómo afecta al modo del verbo.","e":"En las cláusulas adjetivas cuyo antecedente es negativo o inexistente ('no hay nadie que...') se emplea el subjuntivo ('pueda')."},{"p":"Completa: \"—¿Dónde está Juan? —No lo sé; ___ al gimnasio, como suele hacer a esta hora.\" (ir)","a":"habrá ido","w":["ha ido","había ido","iría"],"h":"El hablante no afirma un hecho, sino que hace una conjetura o suposición sobre algo ya sucedido.","e":"El futuro perfecto ('habrá ido') se usa para expresar probabilidad o conjetura sobre una acción pasada reciente con relación al presente."},{"p":"Completa: \"Si hubieras llegado media hora antes, ___ personalmente al conferenciante.\" (conocer, tú)","a":"habrías conocido","w":["conocerías","conociste","habías conocido"],"h":"La cláusula 'si' está en pluscuamperfecto de subjuntivo; identifica qué tiempo corresponde en la cláusula principal.","e":"En las oraciones condicionales irreales del pasado (tercer condicional), a la prótasis en pluscuamperfecto de subjuntivo le corresponde el condicional perfecto ('habrías conocido')."},{"p":"Completa: \"Como el jefe estaba enfermo, yo firmé todos los documentos ___ él.\" (en su representación)","a":"por","w":["para","de","con"],"h":"Piensa en cuál preposición expresa la idea de actuar en nombre o en lugar de otra persona.","e":"'Por' expresa sustitución o acción realizada en nombre de alguien ('en lugar de él'), un uso que se contrasta clásicamente con 'para'."},{"p":"Completa: \"Este informe es ___ mañana a primera hora; no hay más prórroga posible.\" (fecha límite)","a":"para","w":["por","a","en"],"h":"Se trata de un plazo o fecha límite en el futuro, no de una duración.","e":"'Para' indica un plazo o fecha límite ('para mañana'), mientras que 'por' señalaría duración o tiempo aproximado."},{"p":"Completa el mandato negativo con pronombres: \"El pastel es una sorpresa; no ___ a Marta todavía.\" (decírselo, tú)","a":"se lo digas","w":["se lo dices","se lo diga","díselo"],"h":"En los mandatos negativos los pronombres van antes del verbo, que debe ir en subjuntivo.","e":"El mandato negativo informal usa el presente de subjuntivo con los pronombres antepuestos y separados ('no se lo digas')."},{"p":"Completa el mandato afirmativo con pronombres: \"Si te gusta ese abrigo, ___ antes de comprarlo.\" (probárselo, tú)","a":"pruébatelo","w":["te lo pruebas","próbatelo","pruébateló"],"h":"En los mandatos afirmativos los pronombres se adjuntan al verbo; cuenta las sílabas para colocar la tilde.","e":"En el mandato afirmativo, los pronombres se posponen y se unen al verbo, y se añade tilde para conservar el acento original ('pruébatelo')."},{"p":"¿Cuál es el sinónimo más apropiado del adjetivo 'efímero'?","a":"pasajero","w":["eterno","abundante","sólido"],"h":"Piensa en algo que dura muy poco tiempo, como el rocío de la mañana.","e":"'Efímero' significa de corta duración, por lo que su sinónimo es 'pasajero' (lo contrario sería 'eterno')."},{"p":"¿Cuál es el antónimo más apropiado del adjetivo 'prudente'?","a":"temerario","w":["cauteloso","sensato","moderado"],"h":"Busca la palabra que describa a alguien que actúa sin medir los riesgos.","e":"'Temerario' (imprudente, arriesgado) es el antónimo de 'prudente'; los demás son sinónimos, un distractor típico."},{"p":"¿Cuál palabra significa 'en el momento presente, hoy en día'?","a":"actualmente","w":["en realidad","de hecho","realmente"],"h":"Cuidado con el falso amigo: no confundas esta palabra con el inglés 'actually'.","e":"'Actualmente' significa 'en el presente' y es un falso cognado de 'actually' (que se traduce como 'en realidad')."},{"p":"¿Quién es la autora de la novela 'La casa de los espíritus'?","a":"Isabel Allende","w":["Laura Esquivel","Gabriel García Márquez","Julio Cortázar"],"h":"Se trata de una destacada escritora chilena, sobrina de un expresidente de su país.","e":"'La casa de los espíritus' (1982) es la novela más célebre de la chilena Isabel Allende, exponente del realismo mágico."},{"p":"¿A qué generación literaria pertenecía el poeta y dramaturgo Federico García Lorca?","a":"la Generación del 27","w":["la Generación del 98","el Modernismo","el Boom latinoamericano"],"h":"Este grupo de poetas españoles se reunió en 1927 para homenajear a Luis de Góngora.","e":"García Lorca formó parte de la Generación del 27, grupo que conjugó la tradición clásica con la vanguardia."},{"p":"¿Quién escribió las 'Rimas y leyendas', obra cumbre del Romanticismo tardío español?","a":"Gustavo Adolfo Bécquer","w":["Rubén Darío","Antonio Machado","José Martí"],"h":"Este poeta sevillano es célebre por versos como 'Volverán las oscuras golondrinas'.","e":"Gustavo Adolfo Bécquer escribió las 'Rimas y leyendas', obra clave del posromanticismo español."},{"p":"¿Quién es el autor de la novela experimental 'Rayuela', hito del Boom latinoamericano?","a":"Julio Cortázar","w":["Jorge Luis Borges","Mario Vargas Llosa","Carlos Fuentes"],"h":"Este autor argentino propuso leer su novela en un orden no lineal de los capítulos.","e":"'Rayuela' (1963) es la obra maestra del argentino Julio Cortázar, célebre por su estructura de lectura múltiple."},{"p":"Lee el pasaje y responde. Read: \"A pesar de la lluvia torrencial, Don Ernesto salió a regar su jardín como todas las tardes. Los vecinos lo observaban con extrañeza desde sus ventanas, pero él, sonriente, seguía su rutina de siempre sin prestarles atención.\" ¿Qué se puede inferir sobre Don Ernesto?","a":"Es un hombre muy apegado a sus costumbres.","w":["Le preocupa mucho la opinión de sus vecinos.","Siente un profundo desagrado por la jardinería.","Está convencido de que dejará de llover pronto."],"h":"Fíjate en que mantiene su rutina 'de siempre' aunque las circunstancias sean absurdas.","e":"La inferencia se apoya en detalles del texto: regar bajo la lluvia 'como todas las tardes' revela un fuerte apego a la rutina."},{"p":"Lee el pasaje y responde. Read: \"El nuevo gerente resultó ser sumamente mezquino: se negaba a compartir hasta el más mínimo recurso con su equipo y guardaba para sí cualquier beneficio.\" Según el contexto, la palabra 'mezquino' significa:","a":"avaro","w":["generoso","distraído","trabajador"],"h":"Usa las pistas del texto: 'se negaba a compartir' y 'guardaba para sí'.","e":"El significado por contexto se deduce de las acciones descritas; 'mezquino' equivale aquí a 'avaro' o tacaño."}]};
